(6, 'DR RITU GUPTA', 'rituguptasaraf@gmail.com', 'RHIN000034', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Chronic rhino sinusitis (CRS) is a common disease. Maxillary sinusitis not cured by the medicines was addressed by the open surgical procedure namely Caldwell Luc operation. Thereafter introduction of nasal endoscopes in 1970’s led to the minimally invasive surgery FESS which preserved the physiology of the nose and sinuses. In the year 2002 balloon sinuplasty\r\nwas introduced in the western world and subsequently in India. Due to various logistics it was not performed and reintroduced in the year 2015 in India. It can be termed as micro minimally invasive surgery wherein anatomy as well as physiology of the nose and sinuses were preserved in cases of medically non responsive mild to moderate sinusitis. \r\nBalloon sinuplasty is a relatively new procedure which can be termed as micro minimally invasive surgery addressing the CRS without the traditional forms for surgery like incision, cutting or microdebriding. The principle is causing microfractures by inflating the sinus opening and thus facilitating the drainage of the sinus contents. No immediate or late post operative complications were noted. Sinus patency 6 months later was present in 90% of the cases. Balloon sinuplasty is an excellent procedure for medically nonresponsive CRS without polyposis. The success rate is spectacular matching the FESS with almost no immediate post operative and late complication. The recurrence rate of sinusitis is low. We conclude that balloon sinuplasty is a micro invasive procedure which saves operating time, time of hospital stay of the patient and delivers excellent result with almost no complications. We hope it could be incorporated as a routine surgery for mild to moderate sinusitis not responding to medicines.', '/public/upload/abstract/41585bc679c434a5c2a5d6732515bde2.docx', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 1, 1, '2025-07-04 10:12:39', '2025-07-04 10:12:39'),
(43, 'Dr Ayaz Rehman', 'drayazrehmanent@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000112', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Abstract\r\nBackground:\r\nSeptorhinoplasty remains the cornerstone procedure for addressing both structural nasal airway compromise and aesthetic deformities. This study aims to evaluate the functional and aesthetic outcomes of septorhinoplasty in patients with crooked nose deformities, using validated patient-reported outcome measures and comprehensive analysis of deformity-specific surgical techniques.\r\nMethods:\r\nA prospective study was conducted on 130 patients undergoing septorhinoplasty between 2019 and 2024. Patients were categorized based on nasal axis deviation into four deformity patterns: I-shaped, C-shaped, reverse C-shaped, and S-shaped. Functional outcomes were assessed using the NOSE (Nasal Obstruction Symptom Evaluation) scale, while aesthetic satisfaction was measured using the ROE (Rhinoplasty Outcome Evaluation) scale. Surgical approach was tailored per case, with the open approach used in 85.3% and the closed approach in 14.6%, primarily for isolated dorsal corrections. Osteotomies were performed in 100% of patients, with each case involving paramedian, lateral, and transverse osteotomies; intermediate osteotomies were employed in 8.4% for additional refinement. Structural cartilage grafting was performed as indicated: spreader grafts (49.2%), columellar struts (54.6%), tip grafts (32.3%), and alar batten grafts (13.8%).\r\nResults:\r\nOf the 130 patients, 48 (36.9%) had I-shaped, 30 (23.1%) C-shaped, 28 (21.5%) reverse C-shaped, and 24 (18.5%) S-shaped deformities. Significant functional improvement was observed, with mean NOSE scores decreasing from 75.3 ± 12.1 to 18.6 ± 8.9 (p < 0.001). Aesthetic outcomes demonstrated a corresponding increase in ROE scores from 38.4 ± 10.5 to 82.1 ± 9.7 (p < 0.001). Objective aesthetic refinement was achieved across multiple parameters: dorsal profile regularization (90%), nasal symmetry restoration (88%), tip projection and definition (85%), nasofrontal and nasolabial angle harmonization (86%), and radix leveling or augmentation (42%). Complications were minimal and self-limited, with transient edema in 22% and ecchymosis in 18%. No infections, septal perforations, or revision surgeries were recorded during the follow-up period.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSeptorhinoplasty, when tailored to the specific nasal deviation pattern and supported by a structured osteotomy and grafting protocol, achieves significant functional recovery and aesthetic restoration. The combination of a deformity-specific approach, precise osteotomy execution, and comprehensive grafting techniques ensures high patient satisfaction and low morbidity. These findings underscore the importance of integrating anatomical classification with outcome-based metrics for optimizing results in modern rhinoplasty.', '/public/upload/abstract/d0415bb00ba9d396c1299bfbfe2f06bd.docx', 'Septorhinoplasty: Balancing Functional Restoration and Aesthetic Refinement', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 1, 1, '2025-07-24 17:56:56', '2025-07-24 17:56:56'),
(45, 'Dr. Ritu Gupta', 'rituguptasaraf@gmail.com', 'RHIN00006', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Background: Chronic rhinosinusitis without nasal polyposis (CRSsNP) significantly\r\naffects quality of life. This study aimed to compare the efficacy of Balloon\r\nSinuplasty (BSP) and Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (ESS) in managing CRSsNP.\r\nMethods: A non-randomized controlled trial was conducted including patients\r\ndiagnosed with CRSsNP. Participants underwent either BSP or ESS based on\r\nclinical suitability. Demographic data, symptom severity (SNOT-22), radiological\r\nscores (Lund-Mackay), endoscopic findings (Lund-Kennedy), and postoperative\r\ncomplications were evaluated at baseline, 1, 3, and 6 months postoperatively.\r\nResults: The BSP and ESS groups were demographically similar (mean age: 25.41\r\nvs. 24.61 years; p = 0.684; gender distribution p = 0.522). Both groups showed\r\nsignificant improvement in SNOT-22 scores. BSP provided better early symptom\r\nrelief at 1 month (p = 0.027), whereas ESS was more effective at 3 months (p &lt;\r\n0.001), with comparable outcomes at 6 months (p = 0.914). Preoperative Lund-\r\nMackay scores were higher in the ESS group (6.35 vs. 4.89; p = 0.001), indicating\r\nmore extensive disease. Postoperative scores improved significantly in both\r\ngroups, with BSP showing lower final scores (0.70 vs. 1.24; p = 0.001). Endoscopic\r\nscores improved in both groups, with BSP demonstrating superior early and\r\nsustained mucosal healing (p &lt; 0.001 and p = 0.009). Complications were fewer in\r\nBSP (21.74%) than ESS (32.61%), though not statistically significant (p = 0.349).\r\nConclusion: Both BSP and ESS are effective for CRSsNP. BSP offers faster\r\nrecovery, fewer complications, and comparable long-term outcomes, making it a\r\nviable minimally invasive alternative, particularly in cases with less extensive\r\ndisease.', '/public/upload/abstract/b4f1b59a80b66a80f7d90f7b0397d97d.docx', 'EFFICACY OF BALLOON SINUPLASTY VERSUS ENDOSCOPIC SINUS SURGERY FOR CHRONIC RHINOSINUSITIS WITHOUT NA', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 1, 1, '2025-07-28 08:57:41', '2025-07-28 08:57:41'),
(59, 'Dr JITENDRA PRATAP SINGH CHAUHAN', 'chauhanbhavya36@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000116', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Title: Posterior Nasal Nerve Neurectomy: A Game changer in chronic Rhinitis management \'\r\nPresenting Author: Dr Jitendra pratap singh chauhan\r\nAim: To evaluate the effectiveness of posterior nasal nerve neurectomy [PNNN] in reducing refractory symptoms of allergic and non -allergic rhinitis.\r\nMETHODOLOGY: Patients of intractable chronic rhinitis recruited from ENT OPD .written Consent taken for PNNN procedure along with RQLQ ,VAS, TNSS and peak nasal inflow noted . NCCT PNS and baseline investigations done \r\nPNNN done under General anaesthesia and followup done at 1 month. ,3month ,six month and 1 year and subjective and objective parameters noted.\r\nRESULTS: Significant improvement in TNSS , VAS AND RQLQ MEAN SCORES  . Improvement in chronic Rhinitis symptoms.\r\nCONCLUSIONS: PNNN is a promising alternative for refractory rhinitis. Effective in Rural and low income settings due to its cost effectiveness.. Long term relief and reduced need for medications make it an ideal solution.', '/public/upload/abstract/642d42c4ec193064bc9bb079366f4097.docx', 'POSTERIOR NASAL NERVE NEURECTOMY : A GAME CHANGER IN CHRONIC RHINITIS MANAGEMENT.', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-08-13 07:30:09', '2025-08-13 07:30:13'),
(60, 'Dr Jobanpreet Singh', 'jobanpreetsingh007@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000130', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: The Effect of Jalneti on Patients of Allergic Rhinitis Undergoing Medical Management with Intranasal Corticosteroids and Antihistaminics: A Randomized Controlled Trial\r\nPresenter: Dr. Jobanpreet Singh, Resident, ENT, AFMC Pune\r\nBackground:\r\nAllergic rhinitis (AR) is a common disorder caused by an exaggerated immune response to allergens, leading to sneezing, nasal blockage, and poor sleep. Though intranasal corticosteroids and antihistaminics remain standard therapy, many patients have persistent symptoms. Jalneti, a yogic saline nasal irrigation technique, is believed to improve nasal clearance and reduce inflammation, but evidence from randomized trials is limited.\r\nAim:\r\nTo assess the role of Jalneti as an adjunct to standard treatment in patients with AR.\r\nMethods:\r\nIn this randomized controlled trial, 60 patients (18–60 years) with mild-to-moderate (ARIA) AR  were divided into two groups. One received standard therapy, while the other performed Jalneti twice daily for three months along with medication. Outcomes were measured using SNOT-22 scores, nasal endoscopy, and eosinophil counts.\r\nResults:\r\nThe Jalneti group demonstrated greater symptom relief, lower eosinophil counts, and improved nasal findings compared to controls.\r\nConclusion:\r\nJalneti appears to be a safe, simple, and low-cost adjunct that can improve outcomes, reduce drug dependence, and enhance quality of life in allergic rhinitis.', '/public/upload/abstract/9cd3acac50f28b7f8ca2107d759b77df.docx', 'The Effect of Jalneti on Patients of Allergic Rhinitis Undergoing Medical Management with Intranasal', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-08-22 22:47:23', '2025-09-17 14:21:43'),
(61, 'DR B GANESH RAJA', 'ganeshrajastanley@gmail.com', 'RHIN000013', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Unveiling the Rare Sinonasal Entity: A Case Report and Review\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ganesh Raja B, Senior Resident, Department of ENT, Government Medical College Hospital, Kallakurichi\r\nObjective:\r\nTo highlight the diagnostic complexity and management of a rare sinonasal mass in a young adult female.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 22-year-old female presented to our department with complaints of left-sided nasal obstruction and intermittent episodes of epistaxis for a duration of two months. On nasal endoscopy, a polypoidal mass was visualized in the left nasal cavity. To further delineate the lesion, contrast-enhanced CT and MRI were performed, which revealed a well-defined expansile lesion occupying the left nasal cavity with extension into the left maxillary sinus. Based on these findings, the patient underwent endoscopic sinus surgery, during which the lesion was completely excised. The specimen was subsequently sent for histopathological evaluation.\r\nResults:\r\nHistopathology revealed the lesion to be a **nasal cholesteatoma**, a rare and unusual finding in this anatomical location. The postoperative period was uneventful, and the patient recovered well. She was kept under regular follow-up for six months, during which there was no evidence of recurrence either clinically or radiologically.\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasal cholesteatoma is an exceedingly rare condition, particularly when it involves the maxillary sinus. Its presentation often overlaps with that of more common benign sinonasal pathologies, such as nasal polyps or antrochoanal polyps, thereby posing diagnostic challenges. Cross-sectional imaging and histopathological confirmation remain crucial for accurate diagnosis. Complete surgical excision through endoscopic sinus surgery ensures optimal outcomes and reduces the risk of recurrence. This case emphasizes the need for clinicians to maintain a high index of suspicion for rare entities like cholesteatoma in the differential diagnosis of unilateral sinonasal masses, especially in young patients, to facilitate timely and appropriate management.', '/public/upload/abstract/5e7d598760b3d724f5da15e579a95159.docx', 'Unveiling the Rare Sinonasal Entity: A Case Report and Review', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-01 15:11:00', '2025-09-01 15:11:05'),
(63, 'PRASANTH L', 'ragavprash28@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000118', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, '-	Aim:\r\nUnilateral sinonasal masses include a wide spectrum of benign and malignant lesions with overlapping features. This study aimed to assess the diagnostic accuracy of integrating clinical, radiological, histopathological, and immunohistochemical (IHC) assessments in their evaluation and management.\r\n-	Methodology:\r\nA retrospective review was conducted on 84 patients with unilateral sinonasal masses between January 2022 and June 2025 at a tertiary care center. Demographics, clinical presentations, and nasal endoscopic findings were collected. CT and MRI were analysed for site, extent, and bony involvement. Provisional clinico-radiological diagnoses were compared with histopathology from biopsy or surgical specimens, considered the gold standard. IHC was performed in selected malignant or diagnostically challenging cases to confirm lineage and subtype tumors.\r\n-	Results:\r\nOf 84 patients (52 males, 32 females; mean age 42 years), nasal obstruction (82%) was the commonest presentation, followed by epistaxis (35%) and facial swelling (22%).Clinico-radiological impressions correlated with histopathology in 86%. Inflammatory polyps (41%) and fungal sinusitis (18%) were the most common benign pathologies, while squamous cell carcinoma (21%) was the predominant malignancy. IHC proved vital in differentiating poorly differentiated carcinomas, lymphomas, and olfactory neuroblastomas, ensuring accurate diagnosis and guiding therapy.\r\n-	Conclusion:\r\nHistopathology remains central in diagnosing sinonasal masses, while IHC adds precision in challenging cases. An integrated clinical, radiological, histopathological, and IHC approach improves diagnostic accuracy and optimizes management.', '/public/upload/abstract/53d2b1697637268355b82003b6003115.docx', 'Integrating Clinical, Radiological, and Histopathological Assessments in the Diagnosis of Unilateral', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-11 12:29:51', '2025-09-11 12:29:55'),
(65, 'P Praveen Kumar', 'praveen19061992@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000191', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Sino-nasal malignancies are extremely rare accounting < 1% of all malignancies and < 3% of aero-digestive tract tumors. Their surgical pathology is extremely challenging due to the enormous heterogeneity. Few of these sino-nasal tumors may possibly present histologically as clear cell neoplasm. This mechanism is described as ‘histological mimicry’. Renal cell like adenocarcinoma (RCLA) is amongst the top contenders in that list of tumors including squamous cell carcinoma and mucoepidermoid carcinoma. RCLA affecting the nasal cavity is an extremely rare malignancy to have been reported in the literature. It was first described by Zuhr et al. in 2002 and till as recent as 2017 only 15 such cases had been reported worldwide. We present a rare case report of a 45 years old female who presented with unilateral nasal obstruction but was found harboring a histopathological surprise. We wish to highlight the diagnostic and therapeutic challenge faced in the management of this case and create awareness amongst the ORLs, pathologists and medical oncologists about this unaccustomed entity.', '/public/upload/abstract/fef1c007ffee619a650d88ebd8a4a38c.docx', 'Renal Cell-Like Adenocarcinoma of Nasal Cavity: A Rare Entity Deserving Elucidation', 2, 1, '2025-09-13 16:06:12', '2025-09-13 16:06:16'),
(66, 'MAROOF SHAMUSHIHABUDHEEN', 'maroofsham5@gmail.com', 'RHIN000084', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'We report a 10-year-old male presenting with progressive headache and visual loss. Imaging revealed a lytic lesion involving the sphenoid sinus with skull base extension. Initial biopsy demonstrated granulomatous inflammation, while CBNAAT confirmed Mycobacterium tuberculosis. The patient underwent endoscopic surgical debridement followed by standard anti-tubercular therapy, leading to clinical and visual improvement.', '/public/upload/abstract/8240b2e9750ca38a68848957688f2501.docx', 'Tuberculosis of the Sphenoid Sinus: A Rare and Elusive Diagnosis – A Case Report', 2, 1, '2025-09-13 22:29:04', '2025-09-13 22:29:08'),
(69, 'THAVAMANI', 'sewoj77250@ishense.com', 'Rhino0000537678', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'ytfymhj.l[:\"plkjgfxdcghjkl;jhgfcxghj', '/public/upload/abstract/6d84b1ee8526bcdf13466dd0132edf51.docx', '765 video', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-09-15 11:03:51', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(72, 'prasath l', 'ragavprash28@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000118', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Test', '/public/upload/abstract/1e5b3d6a998eb2d67b8a71f09240d47b.docx', 'Test', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-15 11:18:41', '2025-09-15 11:18:45'),
(81, 'LEKHYA V', 'Lekhs1990@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000119', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting author – Dr Lekhya v Assistant Professor \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nObjective: To evaluate long-term patient-reported outcomes following functional endoscopic sinus surgery (FESS) using structured telephonic assessment.\r\n\r\nMethodology:  A retrospective audit of 72 patients (mean age 34.47±13.56 years, 68.1% male) who underwent FESS was conducted using validated telephonic questionnaires( modified SNOT 22, assessing five domains: nasal/sinus symptoms, sleep quality, psychological health, social/occupational functioning, and self-care management.\r\n\r\nResults:The questionnaire demonstrated acceptable internal consistency (Cronbach\'s alpha=0.793). Highest improvement was observed in nasal symptom relief (24.90±4.34) and self-care management (23.79±2.52). Composite overall score averaged 5.51±0.92, indicating favorable outcomes. Ordered logistic regression revealed nasal symptom relief (β=0.289, p=0.002) and sleep quality (β=0.532, p=0.028) as significant predictors of overall improvement. Patients aged 61-70 years showed significantly better outcomes compared to younger cohorts (β=3.427, p=0.027).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConclusion:Telephonic assessment effectively captures long-term post-FESS outcomes, with nasal symptom relief and sleep improvement being primary determinants of patient-reported success.', '', 'Telephonic assessment of patient – reported outcomes following functional endoscopic sinus surgery: ', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-19 11:58:47', '2025-09-19 11:58:51'),
(82, 'VADEPPALLY BALA KRISHNA', 'BALAKRISHNA221@GMAIL.COM', 'RHIN0000193', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE\r\nCrossed Nerve Palsies in Sinonasal Mucormycosis: A Diabetic’s Facial-Hypoglossal Puzzle\r\nABSTRACT\r\nINTRODUCTION\r\nSinonasal mucormycosis is an acute invasive fungal infection of the nose and paranasal sinuses, which is rare, opportunistic and potentially fatal, occurring in both normal and immunocompromised individuals. Uncontrolled diabetics and immunocompromised patients are more prone to this invasive fungal infection. Sinonasal mucormycosis is approximately 1.7 cases per 1,000,000 inhabitants per year. Incidence of VII Cranial nerve palsy is 11% in these cases, and coexistence of ipsilateral Facial nerve and contralateral hypoglossal nerve is not documented in existing literature. \r\nCASE REPORT\r\n A 53-year-old woman was diagnosed with Sinonasal Mucormycosis with extension to the skull base and Infratemporal fossa with involvement of ipsilateral facial nerve palsy and contralateral hypoglossal nerve palsy, in the setting of newly diagnosed and uncontrolled diabetes mellitus. She was promptly started on Liposomal Amphotericin-B and underwent “Endoscopic trans-nasal trans-maxillary trans-pterygoid debridement”.\r\nCONCLUSION\r\nMucormycosis is a rare condition that is still fatal in the era of medical and surgical advancements. A combination of endoscopic surgical debridement followed by intravenous Amphotericin B therapy is quintessential in the management of such patients and has less morbidity compared with conventional treatment. Rare presentations like multiple cranial nerve palsy, which would otherwise raise the suspicion onwards granulomatous disease, need to be scrutinised and aspects ruled out in effective treatment of patients.\r\nKEYWORDS: \r\nSinonasal mucormycosis, Cranial nerve palsy, Amphotericin B, Transpterygoid debridement', '', 'Crossed Nerve Palsies in Sinonasal Mucormycosis: A Diabetic’s Facial-Hypoglossal Puzzle', 2, 1, '2025-09-19 13:50:12', '2025-09-19 13:50:16'),
(83, 'Dr Jobanpreet Singh', 'jobanpreetsingh007@gmail.com', 'RHINO000130', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract\r\nTitle: Choanal Atresia Unplugged: A Journey from Blockage to Breathing\r\nAuthor: Dr Jobanpreet Singh, Resident ENT,AFMC Pune\r\nBackground:\r\nChoanal atresia is a rare congenital malformation characterized by complete or partial obstruction of the posterior nasal aperture, occurring in approximately 1 in 5,000–8,000 live births. It may be unilateral, typically presenting later with nasal obstruction and rhinorrhea, or bilateral, which manifests in neonates as respiratory distress relieved by crying. Nearly half of all cases are associated with other congenital anomalies, emphasizing the need for comprehensive evaluation.\r\nObjective:\r\nThis poster highlights a case series of congenital choanal atresia managed at a tertiary care center, emphasizing diagnostic approaches, surgical techniques, outcomes, and challenges in long-term follow-up.\r\nMethods:\r\nDiagnosis was initially suspected clinically by failure to pass a 6 Fr catheter through the nasal cavity and confirmed via nasal endoscopy and computed tomography (CT). All patients underwent surgical correction via an endoscopic transnasal approach, with postoperative stenting for seven days to maintain patency.\r\nResults:\r\nChoanal patency was successfully achieved in all patients. One case was complicated by mortality secondary to a severe atrioventricular septal defect (AVSD). Another patient developed postoperative restenosis on follow-up, requiring evaluation for revision atresiaplasty. Early diagnosis, airway stabilization, and timely intervention proved vital for favorable outcomes.\r\nConclusion:\r\nChoanal atresia, though rare, is a critical neonatal airway emergency, particularly in bilateral cases. A combination of high clinical suspicion, prompt imaging confirmation, and a multidisciplinary approach is essential. The endoscopic transnasal repair remains the gold standard for surgical management, offering excellent visualization and minimal morbidity. Long-term follow-up is imperative to monitor for restenosis and optimize patient outcomes.', '', 'Choanal Atresia Unplugged: A Journey from Blockage to Breathing', 2, 1, '2025-09-19 23:26:46', '2025-09-19 23:26:50'),
(84, 'Kaaviya J', 'kaaviyaj24@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000103', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract\r\nAuthor: Dr.J.Kaaviya ,postgraduate M.S.ENT\r\nBackground:\r\nChronic Granulomatous Disease (CGD) is a rare primary immunodeficiency resulting from defective phagocyte NADPH oxidase activity. Patients are predisposed to recurrent, severe bacterial and fungal infections. Sinonasal involvement is uncommon and may clinically and radiologically mimic neoplasms.\r\nCase Presentation:\r\nWe report a young patient with a history of recurrent respiratory tract infections who presented with progressive nasal obstruction and purulent discharge. Endoscopic examination revealed a firm sinonasal mass. CT imaging demonstrated soft tissue opacification with bony remodeling, raising differential diagnoses of fungal sinusitis or malignancy. Histopathological evaluation of the mass showed chronic granulomatous inflammation with necrosis and fungal elements. Microbiological cultures supported fungal infection, and subsequent immunological testing confirmed the diagnosis of CGD.\r\nDiscussion:\r\nSinonasal manifestations of CGD are rare but clinically significant. Their presentation as mass-like lesions often leads to misdiagnosis. Early recognition is vital, as management differs from neoplastic conditions. Treatment requires a combination of surgical debridement, targeted antimicrobial therapy, and long-term prophylaxis to prevent recurrence.\r\nConclusion:\r\nCGD should be considered in the differential diagnosis of sinonasal masses in patients with recurrent infections. Prompt diagnosis and multidisciplinary management can significantly reduce morbidity and improve patient outcomes.', '', 'Chronic Granulomatous disease presenting as sinonasal mass', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 20:44:27', '2025-09-23 20:44:31'),
(85, 'M Praveena', 'praveena2198@gmail.com', 'RHIN000099', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\n\r\nTitle\r\nInferior Rectus Entrapment with Successful Reduction and Orbital Floor Reconstruction Using Bone Graft: A Case Report\r\n\r\nAuthor  Dr.M Praveena  MS ENT postgraduate\r\n\r\nAim\r\nTo present a case of inferior rectus muscle entrapment following trauma and its successful management through reduction and orbital floor reconstruction using a bone graft, resulting in complete resolution of diplopia.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nA patient presented with complaints of double vision after orbital trauma. Clinical evaluation and imaging confirmed entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle. The patient underwent surgical intervention involving careful reduction of the entrapped muscle and reconstruction of the orbital floor defect with a bone graft. Postoperative care included close ophthalmologic monitoring to assess ocular alignment and function.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nThe patient had an uneventful recovery with complete resolution of diplopia. Postoperative ophthalmology review confirmed restoration of normal ocular movements without residual diplopia or visual impairment. The bone graft provided adequate support for orbital floor reconstruction with satisfactory cosmetic and functional outcomes.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nEntrapment of the inferior rectus muscle, though a serious complication, can be effectively managed with timely surgical intervention. Orbital floor reconstruction using a bone graft offers structural support and promotes optimal functional recovery, resulting in significant improvement in patient symptoms.', '', 'Inferior Rectus Entrapment with Successful Reduction and Orbital Floor Reconstruction Using Bone Gra', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 20:47:03', '2025-09-23 20:47:06'),
(86, 'Kaaviya J', 'kaaviyaj24@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000103', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Endoscopic Endonasal Excision of Esthesioneuroblastoma – A Minimally Invasive Approach\r\nAuthor:Dr.J.Kaaviya M.S.ENT postgraduate \r\nAbstract\r\nAim: To assess the role of endoscopic endonasal excision in the management of esthesioneuroblastoma with respect to surgical clearance, morbidity, and recovery.\r\n\r\nMethodology: Patients with histologically proven esthesioneuroblastoma (Kadish stage A–C) underwent endoscopic endonasal removal under general anesthesia. A binostril, four-handed technique with image guidance was employed. Tumor dissection from the nasal cavity, cribriform plate, and paranasal sinuses was performed with attention to preservation of critical structures. Postoperative follow-up included nasal endoscopy and imaging to detect residual or recurrent disease.\r\n\r\nDiscussion: Endoscopic surgery offers direct and magnified visualization, enabling precise tumor clearance with reduced morbidity compared to craniofacial resection. Benefits include minimal external scars, less blood loss, shorter hospital stay, and faster recovery. Limitations include technical challenges, requirement of surgical expertise, and relative difficulty in tumors with extensive orbital or intracranial spread. Long-term follow-up is crucial due to the potential for delayed recurrence.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Endoscopic endonasal excision is a safe and effective alternative for selected cases of esthesioneuroblastoma. It achieves comparable oncological outcomes to open approaches while reducing morbidity, thus representing a valuable minimally invasive strategy in modern skull base surgery', '', 'Endoscopic removal of esthenioneuroblastoma- a minimally Invasive procedure', NULL, '', NULL, 'Endoscopic Endonasal Excision of Esthesioneuroblastoma – A Minimally Invasive Approach\r\nAuthor:Dr.J.Kaaviya M.S.ENT postgraduate \r\nAbstract\r\nAim: To assess the role of endoscopic endonasal excision in the management of esthesioneuroblastoma with respect to surgical clearance, morbidity, and recovery.\r\n\r\nMethodology: Patients with histologically proven esthesioneuroblastoma (Kadish stage A–C) underwent endoscopic endonasal removal under general anesthesia. A binostril, four-handed technique with image guidance was employed. Tumor dissection from the nasal cavity, cribriform plate, and paranasal sinuses was performed with attention to preservation of critical structures. Postoperative follow-up included nasal endoscopy and imaging to detect residual or recurrent disease.\r\n\r\nDiscussion: Endoscopic surgery offers direct and magnified visualization, enabling precise tumor clearance with reduced morbidity compared to craniofacial resection. Benefits include minimal external scars, less blood loss, shorter hospital stay, and faster recovery. Limitations include technical challenges, requirement of surgical expertise, and relative difficulty in tumors with extensive orbital or intracranial spread. Long-term follow-up is crucial due to the potential for delayed recurrence.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Endoscopic endonasal excision is a safe and effective alternative for selected cases of esthesioneuroblastoma. It achieves comparable oncological outcomes to open approaches while reducing morbidity, thus representing a valuable minimally invasive strategy in modern skull base surgery', '', 'Endoscopic Endonasal Excision of Esthesioneuroblastoma – A Minimally Invasive Approach Author:Dr.J.K', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 20:47:12', '2025-09-23 20:47:17'),
(87, 'M Praveena', 'praveena2198@gmail.com', 'RHIN000099', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\n\r\nFibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series\r\n\r\nAuthor - Dr.M Praveena  MS ENT postgraduate\r\n\r\nAim\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this case series is to present and analyze three cases of fibrous dysplasia affecting the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, with emphasis on clinical features, diagnostic challenges, imaging findings, and surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\n\r\nThree patients presented with symptoms including  nasal obstruction, facial swelling, and intermittent epistaxis. Diagnostic evaluation with computed tomography  revealed the typical “ground-glass”  appearance consistent with fibrous dysplasia. Each case was managed uniquely based on the site and extent of involvement, with individualized treatment strategies. Preoperative planning relied on imaging to assess the anatomical extent and guide the management approach.\r\n\r\nResults\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent successful  management and had uneventful recoveries. Follow-up evaluations showed no recurrence in any case. One patient had involvement of the inferior turbinate, which added complexity to the diagnosis and management, requiring careful planning and execution.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nFibrous dysplasia involving the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses is rare but should be considered in patients presenting with osseous masses and nasal symptoms. Timely diagnosis and appropriately planned surgical intervention lead to favorable functional  outcomes.', '', 'Fibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series', NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\n\r\nFibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series\r\n\r\nAuthor - Dr.M Praveena  MS ENT postgraduate\r\n\r\nAim\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this case series is to present and analyze three cases of fibrous dysplasia affecting the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, with emphasis on clinical features, diagnostic challenges, imaging findings, and surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\n\r\nThree patients presented with symptoms including  nasal obstruction, facial swelling, and intermittent epistaxis. Diagnostic evaluation with computed tomography  revealed the typical “ground-glass”  appearance consistent with fibrous dysplasia. Each case was managed uniquely based on the site and extent of involvement, with individualized treatment strategies. Preoperative planning relied on imaging to assess the anatomical extent and guide the management approach.\r\n\r\nResults\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent successful  management and had uneventful recoveries. Follow-up evaluations showed no recurrence in any case. One patient had involvement of the inferior turbinate, which added complexity to the diagnosis and management, requiring careful planning and execution.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nFibrous dysplasia involving the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses is rare but should be considered in patients presenting with osseous masses and nasal symptoms. Timely diagnosis and appropriately planned surgical intervention lead to favorable functional  outcomes.', '', 'Fibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 20:50:07', '2025-09-23 20:50:11'),
(88, 'Shreya Deshpande', 'docsharoo@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000327', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'A Case of Frontal Mucocele \r\n\r\nAuthor : Dr Shreya Deshpande ( Junior resident, Dept of ENT, SKNMC Pune) \r\nGuide : Dr Sanjana Nemade ( HOD, Dept of ENT, SKNMC Pune ) \r\n\r\nCase: A 70 years old female, presented to ENT OPD with complaints of protrusion of left eye and decrease in vision of left eye since 15 days.\r\nExamination of Orbits - Left eye : Vision CF <1 m, Extraocular movements restricted, eyeball protruding. \r\nDiagnostic Nasal endoscopy and Anterior Rhinoscopy - Polypoidal left middle turbinate, smooth bulge above and lateral to left middle turbinate, \r\nCT PNS + Orbits  - Widening of frontal sinus, thinning of sinus wall with minimal erosion of posterior wall of the frontal sinus, extension into orbital roof with erosion of orbital roof.\r\nManagement - Left FESS under GA. Under endoscopic evaluation, inferior turbinate was infractured and lateralised; Uncinectomy done; Bulge noted in the middle meatus, mucosa removed, whitish cystic growth noted in the frontal recess region. On opening, cheesy non foul smelling material suctioned out. Protrusion of left eye resolved on table.\r\nHistopathology report - left frontal sinus mucocele.\r\nStatus on discharge- Complete subsidence of left eye protrusion.\r\nOn follow up - Left eye extra ocular movements improved in all directions, vision improved.\r\nConclusion: Mucocele is epithelium lined mucus filled sac within paranasal sinuses which causes expansion and remodeling of sinus walls. Site: Frontal > Ethmoid > Maxillary > Sphenoid. Most common etiology- Sinus surgery ( 66-86%). Other causes can be post surgery(50%),  trauma ( 10-14%), spontaneously (15-17%). Two essential factors - 1.Obstructed sinus outflow tract & 2. Inflammatory process within the sinus which include cytokine IL1 and TNF causing bony erosions and thinning of sinus walls. Surgical management is wide marsupialization of sac.', '', 'A Case of Frontal Mucocele', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 22:13:32', '2025-09-23 22:13:37'),
(89, 'THAIEBA  A', 'thaieba777@gmail.com', 'RHINO000100', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Background:\r\nInternal nasal valve (INV) collapse and alar weakness are important but often underdiagnosed causes of nasal obstruction. Surgical correction aims to restore both airway function and nasal contour.\r\nCase Presentation:\r\nA 25-year-old male, presented with persistent nasal obstruction, worsened on deep inspiration, with visible alar collapse on right side. Clinical examination revealed a narrowed Internal Nasal Valve angle and a positive modified  Cottle’s test on right side.\r\nSurgical Management:\r\nThe patient underwent external rhinoplasty with placement of batten graft between lower edge of upper lateral cartilage  and superior edge of lower lateral cartilage on right lateral nasal wall. Alar rim graft  placed bilaterally and septoplasty for associated deviation. Septal cartilage and tragal cartilage was used for grafting.\r\nOutcome:\r\nPost-operatively, the patient experienced significant symptomatic relief with improved nasal airflow and NOSE score reduction. The nasal sidewall remained stable without inspiratory collapse, and cosmetic outcome was satisfactory. Two month follow-up showed no recurrence of symptoms.\r\nConclusion:\r\nINV and alar collapse should be considered in young patients with nasal obstruction. Surgical management offers durable improvement in both function and aesthetics.', '', '“”AIRWAY UNLOCKED “” – FUNCTIONAL AND AESTHETIC CORRECTION OF INTERNAL NASAL VALVE AND ALAR COLLAPSE', 2, 1, '2025-09-24 20:27:46', '2025-09-24 20:27:50'),
(90, 'VIKAS SHARMA', 'vicky251983@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000345', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Choanal atresia is a rare but the most common congenital anomaly of the nasal cavity. Bilateral choanal atresia in an elderly person is extremely rare. This condition occurs due to the persistence of the nasobuccal membrane, which should normally rupture around the 7th week of embryonic development. The only way the patient survives is if there is partial atresia in one of the sides as was present in our patient. Here, we present a case of a 69-year-old woman with bilateral choanal atresia, with the right choana being completely atretic and the left choana partially atretic, the patient underwent transnasal endoscope-guided bilateral choanoplasty and reconstruction using the crossover nasoseptal flap technique and stenting. Transnasal endoscopic choanoplasty is generally considered the treatment of choice for this condition. Restenosis is a common postoperative complication, but proper nasal douching and regular follow-up can help reduce the likelihood of restenosis.', '', 'CHOANAL ATRESIA IN ADULT- ENDOSCOPIC SURGERY AND RECONSTRUCTION', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-25 10:59:38', '2025-09-25 10:59:42'),
(91, 'RADHIKA DEVI S', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title \r\nInvasive Fungal Sinusitis in Immunocompromised Patient – Case Report\r\nAuthor \r\nDr. Radhika Devi. S\r\nSecond Year ENT PG\r\nMadras Medical College \r\nAim\r\nTo highlight the clinical presentation, diagnostic approach and management of single case of invasive fungal sinusitis with importance of early intervention.\r\nMethodology \r\nA  35 year old male occupant as driver referred from RIOGH Egmore with C/O swelling in the left eye × 1week, Nasal obstruction and discharge ×1 week.\r\nClinical examination reveals DNS to left and secretions present in left nasal cavity. Examination of eye shows, blurring of vision,  elevation, abduction and adduction restricted on left eye. MRI brain shows invasive fungal sinusitis with left eye proptosis with intra cranial extensions. Patient underwent full house FESS with endoscopic left medial orbital wall decompression with septal correction followed by systemic antifungal therapy.\r\nResults: \r\nPost operatively left eye proptosis decreased and  vision also improved . \r\nPatient restricted eye movements increased . \r\nConclusion :\r\n      \"This case emphasizes the critical role of early diagnosis and prompt combined surgical and medical management \"\r\n        \"in invasive fungal sinusitis. In high-risk patients such as those with uncontrolled diabetes, a high index of \"\r\n        \"suspicion is essential to reduce morbidity and prevent mortality.\"', '', 'Invasive Fungal Sinusitis in Immunocompromised Patient- Case Report', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-25 22:56:28', '2025-09-25 22:56:32'),
(92, 'RADHIKA DEVI S', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nExtra nasopharyngeal Angio fibroma: A Rare Case Presentation \r\nAuthor\r\nDr. Radhika Devi. S\r\nSecond Year Postgraduate, Department of ENT\r\nMadras Medical College, Chennai\r\nAim\r\nTo present a rare case of extranasopharyngeal angiofibroma (ENA), highlight its clinical presentation, diagnostic approach, and management, and to compare it with classical juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA).\r\nMethodology\r\nA single case report was documented involving a 16-year-old patient who presented with swelling in the right nasal cavity for past 2 weeks and epistaxis on and off for past 2 weeks. Detailed history, clinical examination, and CT were performed to assess the site, and  extent, of the lesion followed by surgical excision under general anesthesia. Histopathological examination confirmed the diagnosis. Relevant literature was reviewed to compare epidemiology, sites of origin, and treatment strategies of ENA versus JNA.\r\nResults\r\nThe patient underwent complete surgical excision without obvious blood loss. Postoperative recovery was uneventful, and no recurrence was observed during a follow-up period of six months. Histopathology correlated with a diagnosis of extranasopharyngeal angiofibroma. A review of literature revealed that ENA is extremely rare, tends to occur in older age groups, shows less aggressive behavior than JNA, and has a better surgical outcome.\r\nConclusion\r\nExtranasopharyngeal angiofibroma should be considered in the differential diagnosis of vascular nasal and paranasal masses, especially in cases not fitting the classical profile of JNA. Early imaging, preoperative planning, and surgical excision provide excellent outcomes with minimal recurrence.', '', 'Extra nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma- A Rare Case Presentation', 2, 1, '2025-09-25 23:33:49', '2025-09-25 23:33:53'),
(93, 'Dr Malathi M', 'malathim91@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000115', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical presentation, diagnostic modalities, management, and outcomes of patients with inverted papilloma in a tertiary care setting.\r\nMethods:\r\nThis observational study analyzed patients diagnosed with inverted papilloma over a specified period. Clinical data regarding presenting symptoms, endoscopic and radiological findings (CT/MRI), surgical approaches, histopathological confirmation, and postoperative follow-up were reviewed.\r\nResults:\r\nThe majority of patients presented with unilateral nasal obstruction, nasal discharge, and epistaxis. Endoscopy revealed polypoidal mass lesions, predominantly arising from the lateral nasal wall and maxillary sinus. Imaging showed characteristic features aiding in the delineation of the extent and planning of surgical excision. All cases underwent endoscopic surgical resection. Histopathology confirmed inverted papilloma in all specimens. No malignant transformation was observed in this series.\r\nConclusion:\r\nInverted papilloma, though benign, poses significant diagnostic and therapeutic challenges due to its tendency for recurrence and malignant potential. Endoscopic surgical techniques provide excellent visualization and access, reducing recurrence rates compared to traditional approaches. Early diagnosis, meticulous surgical excision, and vigilant follow-up are critical to achieving favorable outcomes.', '', 'WHEN BENIGN BEHAVES BADLY: CASE SERIES OF INVERTED PAPILLOMA', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:12:12', '2025-09-26 19:12:16'),
(94, 'Dr Malathi M', 'malathim91@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000115', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical presentation, diagnostic modalities, management, and outcomes of patients with inverted papilloma in a tertiary care setting.\r\nMethods:\r\nThis observational study analyzed patients diagnosed with inverted papilloma over a specified period. Clinical data regarding presenting symptoms, endoscopic and radiological findings (CT/MRI), surgical approaches, histopathological confirmation, and postoperative follow-up were reviewed.\r\nResults:\r\nThe majority of patients presented with unilateral nasal obstruction, nasal discharge, and epistaxis. Endoscopy revealed polypoidal mass lesions, predominantly arising from the lateral nasal wall and maxillary sinus. Imaging showed characteristic features aiding in the delineation of the extent and planning of surgical excision. All cases underwent endoscopic surgical resection. Histopathology confirmed inverted papilloma in all specimens. No malignant transformation was observed in this series.\r\nConclusion:\r\nInverted papilloma, though benign, poses significant diagnostic and therapeutic challenges due to its tendency for recurrence and malignant potential. Endoscopic surgical techniques provide excellent visualization and access, reducing recurrence rates compared to traditional approaches. Early diagnosis, meticulous surgical excision, and vigilant follow-up are critical to achieving favorable outcomes.', '', 'WHEN BENIGN BEHAVES BADLY: CASE SERIES OF INVERTED PAPILLOMA', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:12:13', '2025-09-26 19:12:17'),
(95, 'Dr Malathi M', 'malathim91@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000115', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical presentation, diagnostic modalities, management, and outcomes of patients with inverted papilloma in a tertiary care setting.\r\nMethods:\r\nThis observational study analyzed patients diagnosed with inverted papilloma over a specified period. Clinical data regarding presenting symptoms, endoscopic and radiological findings (CT/MRI), surgical approaches, histopathological confirmation, and postoperative follow-up were reviewed.\r\nResults:\r\nThe majority of patients presented with unilateral nasal obstruction, nasal discharge, and epistaxis. Endoscopy revealed polypoidal mass lesions, predominantly arising from the lateral nasal wall and maxillary sinus. Imaging showed characteristic features aiding in the delineation of the extent and planning of surgical excision. All cases underwent endoscopic surgical resection. Histopathology confirmed inverted papilloma in all specimens. No malignant transformation was observed in this series.\r\nConclusion:\r\nInverted papilloma, though benign, poses significant diagnostic and therapeutic challenges due to its tendency for recurrence and malignant potential. Endoscopic surgical techniques provide excellent visualization and access, reducing recurrence rates compared to traditional approaches. Early diagnosis, meticulous surgical excision, and vigilant follow-up are critical to achieving favorable outcomes.', '', 'WHEN BENIGN BEHAVES BADLY: CASE SERIES OF INVERTED PAPILLOMA', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:12:15', '2025-09-26 19:12:19');
