(96, 'Dr Malathi M', 'malathim91@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000115', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE:“NASOPHARYNGEAL CARCINOMA: DIAGNOSING THE SILENT INTRUDER”\r\nPresenting author: Dr. Malathi M\r\nAim:\r\nTo study the clinical presentation, diagnostic methods, and treatment response of nasopharyngeal carcinoma.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective observational study was conducted on patients diagnosed with nasopharyngeal carcinoma in a tertiary care hospital. Detailed history, ENT examination, imaging, and histopathological confirmation were done. Patients were treated with radiotherapy and concurrent chemotherapy and followed up for outcome assessment.\r\nResults:\r\nMajority of patients presented with painless cervical lymph node enlargement, nasal obstruction, and epistaxis. Histopathology revealed undifferentiated carcinoma in most patients. Radiotherapy with chemotherapy was effective in early-stage disease, with good local control.\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasopharyngeal carcinoma often presents late due to its silent location and vague symptoms. Early diagnosis with imaging and biopsy, along with combined modality treatment, improves survival. Multidisciplinary care is vital for better outcomes.', '', 'NASOPHARYNGEAL CARCINOMA: DIAGNOSING THE SILENT INTRUDER', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:34:23', '2025-09-26 19:34:28'),
(97, 'Dr Malathi M', 'malathim91@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000115', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE:“NASOPHARYNGEAL CARCINOMA: DIAGNOSING THE SILENT INTRUDER”\r\nPresenting author: Dr. Malathi M\r\nAim:\r\nTo study the clinical presentation, diagnostic methods, and treatment response of nasopharyngeal carcinoma.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective observational study was conducted on patients diagnosed with nasopharyngeal carcinoma in a tertiary care hospital. Detailed history, ENT examination, imaging, and histopathological confirmation were done. Patients were treated with radiotherapy and concurrent chemotherapy and followed up for outcome assessment.\r\nResults:\r\nMajority of patients presented with painless cervical lymph node enlargement, nasal obstruction, and epistaxis. Histopathology revealed undifferentiated carcinoma in most patients. Radiotherapy with chemotherapy was effective in early-stage disease, with good local control.\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasopharyngeal carcinoma often presents late due to its silent location and vague symptoms. Early diagnosis with imaging and biopsy, along with combined modality treatment, improves survival. Multidisciplinary care is vital for better outcomes.', '', 'NASOPHARYNGEAL CARCINOMA: DIAGNOSING THE SILENT INTRUDER', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:34:27', '2025-09-26 19:34:32'),
(98, 'Imon DasGupta', 'imon.crazy@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000194', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR\r\nDr. Imon DasGupta\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION / BACKGROUND\r\nOral cancer is one of the three commonest types of cancer in India. 5- 12% of oral cavity cancers are found in the hard palate. They are usually seen in tobacco users and may be preceded by luekoplakia or erythroplakia. Surgical excision is the mainstay of the treatment, often followed by adjuvant radiotherapy.\r\nAIM		\r\nWe present an interesting case of Squamous carcinoma of the hard palate where, in spite of margin involvement in the original excision, no residual tumour was found in the final specimen.\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY\r\nA 42 year old male patient presented with an erythroplakic lesion of the right hard palate; the initial biopsy obtained elsewhere suggested dysplasia. A wide local excision was performed with local flap reconstruction. Surprisingly the specimen was reported as well differentiated squamous carcinoma involving all margins. The patient then underwent an infrastructure maxillectomy.\r\n\r\nRESULT\r\nThe final histopathology report showed no sign of any tumour. Both biopsy and final specimen slides were reviewed.\r\nCONCLUSION \r\nLocal immunity and anti tumour activity possibly cleared the remaining tumour cells resulting in a vanishing tumour.', '', 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:44:10', '2025-09-26 19:44:14'),
(99, 'Imon DasGupta', 'imon.crazy@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000194', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR\r\nDr. Imon DasGupta\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION / BACKGROUND\r\nOral cancer is one of the three commonest types of cancer in India. 5- 12% of oral cavity cancers are found in the hard palate. They are usually seen in tobacco users and may be preceded by luekoplakia or erythroplakia. Surgical excision is the mainstay of the treatment, often followed by adjuvant radiotherapy.\r\nAIM		\r\nWe present an interesting case of Squamous carcinoma of the hard palate where, in spite of margin involvement in the original excision, no residual tumour was found in the final specimen.\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY\r\nA 42 year old male patient presented with an erythroplakic lesion of the right hard palate; the initial biopsy obtained elsewhere suggested dysplasia. A wide local excision was performed with local flap reconstruction. Surprisingly the specimen was reported as well differentiated squamous carcinoma involving all margins. The patient then underwent an infrastructure maxillectomy.\r\n\r\nRESULT\r\nThe final histopathology report showed no sign of any tumour. Both biopsy and final specimen slides were reviewed.\r\nCONCLUSION \r\nLocal immunity and anti tumour activity possibly cleared the remaining tumour cells resulting in a vanishing tumour.', '', 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:44:10', '2025-09-26 19:44:14'),
(100, 'Imon DasGupta', 'imon.crazy@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000194', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR\r\nDr. Imon DasGupta\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION / BACKGROUND\r\nOral cancer is one of the three commonest types of cancer in India. 5- 12% of oral cavity cancers are found in the hard palate. They are usually seen in tobacco users and may be preceded by luekoplakia or erythroplakia. Surgical excision is the mainstay of the treatment, often followed by adjuvant radiotherapy.\r\nAIM		\r\nWe present an interesting case of Squamous carcinoma of the hard palate where, in spite of margin involvement in the original excision, no residual tumour was found in the final specimen.\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY\r\nA 42 year old male patient presented with an erythroplakic lesion of the right hard palate; the initial biopsy obtained elsewhere suggested dysplasia. A wide local excision was performed with local flap reconstruction. Surprisingly the specimen was reported as well differentiated squamous carcinoma involving all margins. The patient then underwent an infrastructure maxillectomy.\r\n\r\nRESULT\r\nThe final histopathology report showed no sign of any tumour. Both biopsy and final specimen slides were reviewed.\r\nCONCLUSION \r\nLocal immunity and anti tumour activity possibly cleared the remaining tumour cells resulting in a vanishing tumour.', '', 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:44:10', '2025-09-26 19:44:13'),
(101, 'PRASANTH L', 'ragavprash28@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000118', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, '-	Aim:\r\nUnilateral sinonasal masses include a wide spectrum of benign and malignant lesions with overlapping features. This study aimed to assess the diagnostic accuracy of integrating clinical, radiological, histopathological, and immunohistochemical (IHC) assessments in their evaluation and management.\r\n-	Methodology:\r\nA retrospective review was conducted on 84 patients with unilateral sinonasal masses between January 2022 and June 2025 at a tertiary care center. Demographics, clinical presentations, and nasal endoscopic findings were collected. CT and MRI were analysed for site, extent, and bony involvement. Provisional clinico-radiological diagnoses were compared with histopathology from biopsy or surgical specimens, considered the gold standard. IHC was performed in selected malignant or diagnostically challenging cases to confirm lineage and subtype tumors.\r\n-	Results:\r\nOf 84 patients (52 males, 32 females; mean age 42 years), nasal obstruction (82%) was the commonest presentation, followed by epistaxis (35%) and facial swelling (22%).Clinico-radiological impressions correlated with histopathology in 86%. Inflammatory polyps (41%) and fungal sinusitis (18%) were the most common benign pathologies, while squamous cell carcinoma (21%) was the predominant malignancy. IHC proved vital in differentiating poorly differentiated carcinomas, lymphomas, and olfactory neuroblastomas, ensuring accurate diagnosis and guiding therapy.\r\n-	Conclusion:\r\nHistopathology remains central in diagnosing sinonasal masses, while IHC adds precision in challenging cases. An integrated clinical, radiological, histopathological, and IHC approach improves diagnostic accuracy and optimizes management.\r\n-	Word count: 200', '', 'Integrating Clinical, Radiological, and Histopathological Assessments in the Diagnosis of Unilateral', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 21:55:06', '2025-09-26 21:55:10'),
(102, 'PRASANTH L', 'ragavprash28@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000118', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, '-	Aim:\r\nTo highlight the role of image-guided navigation using the Medtronic-Stealth Station FlexENT™ system in improving surgical safety, accuracy, and outcomes in endoscopic sinonasal surgeries.\r\n-	Methodology:\r\nThe video shows series of patients who underwent navigation-assisted endoscopic sinonasal surgery and includes Intraoperative parameters assessed included accuracy of anatomical localization, facilitation of dissection near vital structures, completeness of lesion clearance, and surgeon confidence. \r\n-	Results:\r\nThe image-guided navigation system provided real-time anatomical guidance with high precision, enabling safe dissection around critical areas such as the orbit, skull base, and optic nerve. Navigation proved particularly valuable in revision cases and advanced disease with distorted anatomy. Surgeons reported increased confidence, better intraoperative decision-making, and improved efficiency. Complete disease clearance was achieved in the majority of cases, with no major intraoperative complications and minimal postoperative morbidity.\r\n-	Conclusion:\r\nImage-guided navigation significantly enhances the safety and precision of endoscopic sinonasal surgeries. This system improves surgeon confidence, reduces complication risk, and ensures optimal surgical outcomes, making it a valuable adjunct in modern rhinological and skull base practice.\r\n-	Word count – 199', '', 'The Role of image-guided navigation in enhancing safety and surgical precision in Endoscopic sinonas', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-26 21:57:25', '2025-09-26 21:57:29'),
(103, 'Dr. Mohamed Farook', 'mohammedfarooqa@yahoo.com', 'RHIN00087', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nThe reported case of an 8-year-old female underscores the significant diagnostic challenges arising when common infections, such as Acute Bacterial Rhinosinusitis (ABRS), mimic rare, aggressive neoplastic conditions. While ABRS is typically straightforward, its imaging features can occasionally overlap with tumours like Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma (JNA), a benign, highly vascular tumour predominantly affecting adolescent males.\r\nCase history: \r\nThe patient presented with a 7-day history of left periorbital pain, swelling, redness, and watering of the left eye. \r\nGeneral examination: showed mild left eye proptosis. \r\nLocal examination and Diagnostic Nasal Endoscopy (DNE):  were highly suggestive of infection, revealing congested nasal mucosa, mucopurulent discharge in the left middle meatus, and an oedematous middle turbinate. Grade 4 adenoid hypertrophy was also noted.\r\nMRI Findings:  an external MRI complicated the diagnosis, suggesting a nasopharyngeal mass, likely angiofibroma, with osseous erosion of the sphenoid sinus and extension into surrounding structures, including the maxillary and frontal sinuses and the masticator space.\r\nCECT Findings: The definitive CECT provided clarity, demonstrating complete opacification of four left-sided sinuses (maxillary, ethmoid, frontal, and sphenoid) and extra-conal orbital involvement. Crucially, the CECT showed an intact left lamina papyracea. Based on clinical and CECT findings, the final diagnosis was ABRS with orbital complications (stage 2 orbital cellulitis/post septal cellulitis).\r\nManagement and Conclusion:  required a careful assessment of vision, fundus, and colour vision, followed by an aggressive 11-day course of IV Meropenem (700 mg) and Vancomycin (400 mg) thrice daily. Marked clinical improvement occurred within 48 hours, critically obviating the need for surgery. The patient was discharged with proptosis resolved, continuing oral Linezolid and Cefuroxime. This case confirms that prompt, aggressive IV antibiotics are paramount in managing stage 1 and 2 orbital cellulitis and can prevent unnecessary invasive procedures.', '', 'ACUTE BACTERIAL RHINOSINUSITIS MASQUERADING AS ANGIOFIBROMA :  A CASE REPORT', 2, 1, '2025-09-27 11:44:51', '2025-09-27 11:44:56'),
