(133, 'Devanand K', 'devanand.kannabiran92@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000334', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction: Surgical management of brainstem cavernous malformations is challenging due to their delicate location and complex accessibility. To date, advances in endoscopic techniques have enabled the reporting of ten cases of endoscopic transnasal resection of cavernous malformations in the literature. We introduce a groundbreaking technique for resecting these lesions. \r\nCase Summary: A one-year-nine-month-old infant presented with a 3-day history of difficulty walking, difficulty swallowing, and difficulty holding objects with her right hand. She was diagnosed with acute onset right hemiparesis with involvement of cranial nerves 6, 7, 9, and 10. Three months later, she returned to the emergency room with Cheyne-stokes breathing, drowsiness and was intubated. She underwent extended endoscopic transnasal transclival excision of the pontine cavernoma. Postoperative evaluation revealed significant neurological improvement with minimal morbidity.\r\nConclusion: We selected an anteromedial endoscopic endonasal approach because the lesion had displaced white matter tracts laterally rendering an anteromedial corridor the least traumatic pathway.', '', 'PEDIATRIC PONS, TARGETED PATHWAY: ENDOSCOPIC APPROACH FOR INFANTILE PONTINE CAVERNOMA', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-09-30 21:27:56', '2025-09-30 21:27:59'),
