(145, 'Dr EKTA', 'ekta301097@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000357', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Background\r\nPituitary apoplexy is a rare but life-threatening condition characterized by sudden neurological and endocrine deterioration due to hemorrhage or infarction of a pituitary adenoma. Timely surgical intervention can significantly influence outcomes.\r\nObjective\r\nTo evaluate the outcomes of emergency endoscopic endonasal transsphenoidal hypophysectomy performed within 24 hours in patients presenting with acute pituitary apoplexy.\r\nMethods\r\nThis retrospective case series includes three patients with radiologically confirmed pituitary apoplexy who underwent emergency endoscopic transnasal resection at our center. All patients presented with acute neurological symptoms and were operated on within 24 hours of onset. Preoperative and postoperative neurological and endocrine statuses were assessed.\r\nResults\r\nNeurological Deficits (Pre-op): 100% had visual impairment and/or cranial nerve palsy\r\nEndocrinopathy: Present in 1 patient (33.3%)\r\nSurgical Timing: All patients operated within 24 hours\r\nOutcomes: Visual improvement in all patients\r\nComplete visual recovery in 66.6%\r\nResolution of oculomotor palsy in 66.6%\r\nImprovement in endocrine function noted\r\nConclusion\r\nEmergency endoscopic transsphenoidal decompression is effective in reversing acute neurological deficits and stabilizing endocrine function in pituitary apoplexy. Early intervention (within 24 hours) is crucial for optimal recovery.', '', 'Emergency Hypophysectomy in Pituitary Apoplexy: A Case Series from a Tertiary Center', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 23:41:49', '2025-09-30 23:41:53'),
(146, 'Dr EKTA', 'ekta301097@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000357', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Impact of Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery on Sinonasal and Pulmonary Outcomes in Chronic Rhinosinusitis With and Without Nasal Polyposis\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ekta\r\nAim\r\nTo evaluate the effect of Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (FESS) on sinonasal symptoms and pulmonary function in patients with chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS), with and without nasal polyposis.\r\nMethodology\r\nA prospective study was conducted on 50 CRS patients at SPMC Medical College, Bikaner. Pre- and postoperative assessments included sinonasal outcome scores, visual analogue scales (VAS), and objective tests (rhinomanometry, acoustic rhinometry, nasal spirometry). Pulmonary function parameters (FEV₁, FVC, FEV₁/FVC) were recorded preoperatively, and at 1 and 3 months postoperatively.\r\nResults\r\nNasal obstruction was reported in 83–100% of patients. Following FESS, mean VAS and Likert scores decreased by over 50%. Objective measures showed significant improvement in nasal airflow and cavity volume. Pulmonary function demonstrated significant increases in FEV₁ and FVC at 1 and 3 months (p < 0.05). Improvements in pulmonary function paralleled symptomatic relief across both CRS subtypes.\r\nConclusions\r\nFESS significantly improves sinonasal and pulmonary outcomes in CRS patients, irrespective of nasal polyposis, reinforcing its role in integrated airway management.', '', 'Impact of Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery on Sinonasal and Pulmonary Outcomes in Chronic Rhinosi', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-01 00:06:55', '2025-10-01 00:06:59'),
(147, 'Akshaya V', 'dr.ak.venkat@gmail.com', 'ME0025062', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction\r\nCerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhea results from an abnormal communication between the subarachnoid space and nasal cavity and predisposes patients to meningitis if untreated. Endoscopic endonasal repair is now the standard of care, with success relying on secure closure and effective adjuncts. Platelet-rich plasma (PRP), when activated with calcium chloride to form a gel, provides concentrated growth factors that accelerate healing and create an immediate watertight seal, making it a promising autologous alternative to fibrin glue.\r\n\r\nObjective:\r\nTo assess the efficacy of autologous PRP gel as an adjunct in endoscopic repair of spontaneous anterior skull base CSF leaks.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA retrospective case series was conducted at a tertiary care center in Pondicherry. Five female patients, aged 43–50 years, presented with spontaneous CSF rhinorrhea without trauma or prior surgery. CT cisternography and MRI localized the leaks, and two patients had empty sella, suggestive of idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH). Endoscopic multilayer closure with fat and fascia lata was performed, and PRP gel was made by activating with calcium chloride and was applied between graft layers and over the repair site. Postoperative care included antibiotics, acetazolamide, and lumbar drainage for IIH patients.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll five patients had successful closure with no recurrence over 6 months of follow-up. No postoperative complications such as meningitis or graft failure occurred. PRP gel provided rapid sealing and mucosal healing while avoiding the cost of commercial sealants.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nAutologous PRP gel is a safe, effective, and economical adjunct in endoscopic CSF leak repair. Larger studies are warranted to validate long-term outcomes.', '', 'Autologous platelet-rich plasma gel as a sole adjunct in endoscopic repair of spontaneous CSF rhinor', 2, 1, '2025-10-01 06:36:57', '2025-10-01 06:37:00'),
(148, 'Abarna C', 'abarnachandrasamy@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000255', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nOptic Nerve Decompression in a Case of Orbital Apex Syndrome Following Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery\r\nAuthor\r\nAbarna\r\nObjective\r\nTo highlight the rare complication of orbital apex syndrome following functional endoscopic sinus surgery (FESS) for sinonasal polyposis and to discuss the role of timely surgical intervention in preserving vision.\r\nMethodology\r\nA 37-year-old male presented with right-sided nasal obstruction for 5 years. Clinical examination revealed bilateral polypoidal masses. CT paranasal sinuses showed sinonasal polyposis with pansinusitis. The patient underwent FESS with polypectomy. Postoperatively, he developed right medial rectus palsy with second, third and sixth cranial nerve involvement. Endoscopic re-exploration showed clots in the right nasal cavity, which were cleared. MRI brain and orbit revealed features suggestive of right orbital apex syndrome.\r\nResult\r\nThe patient was started on intravenous voriconazole, methylprednisolone and piperacillin–tazobactam. On postoperative day 5, optic nerve decompression was performed. Intraoperatively, fungal-like mucosal debris was seen in the sphenoid sinus, along with cystic material filling the sinus. The peri-orbital area was traced posteriorly up to the orbital apex, and 180° of bone covering the optic nerve was removed. Optic nerve decompression was successfully achieved.\r\nDiscussion\r\nOrbital apex syndrome is a rare but serious complication of sinonasal disease and its surgical management. Early diagnosis with radiological imaging and prompt medical and surgical management are crucial to prevent irreversible visual loss. The use of antifungal therapy, corticosteroids, and timely optic nerve decompression can improve outcomes in select cases.\r\nConclusion\r\nOrbital apex syndrome following FESS is an uncommon but vision-threatening complication. A high index of suspicion, rapid evaluation, and timely surgical decompression of the optic nerve play a key role in patient recovery and visual prognosis.', '', 'Optic Nerve Decompression in a Case of Orbital Apex Syndrome Following Functional Endoscopic Sinus S', 2, 1, '2025-10-02 08:29:11', '2025-10-02 08:29:14'),
(149, 'Dr.Meenu PS', 'psmeenu9122@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000407', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'ABSTRACT \r\nTITLE : RETROSPECTIVE  STUDY ON ETIOLOGY AND MANAGEMENT OF EPISTAXIS IN A TERTIARY CARE HOSPITAL \r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:DR. MEENU PS\r\nAIM: To analyze the etiological factors and evaluate the effectiveness of various management strategies for epistaxis in patients presenting to a tertiary care hospital.\r\nMETHODOLOGY: A retrospective observational study was conducted on patients diagnosed with epistaxis who presented to our hospital. Data regarding age, sex, site of bleeding, predisposing factors, clinical presentation, and treatment modalities were collected. Management approaches included conservative measures, anterior and posterior nasal packing, cauterization, medical therapy, and surgical interventions. Analysis of various etiological factors giving rise to epistaxis and effectiveness  of each modality of treatment were assessed. \r\nRESULTS: A total of 384 patients with epistaxis were included in the study. Males constituted the majority, accounting for 76.3 % (293) of cases. Trauma was the most common cause of epistaxis(60%), followed by hypertension(20%). The majority of patients (60%) were managed with anterior nasal packing. Conservative management  was effective in 26.7% of patients, while posterior nasal packing was required in 13.3%  of cases. 3 patients required blood transfusion during the course of treatment.\r\nCONCLUSIONS: Epistaxis is a multifactorial ENT emergency with trauma and hypertension as predominant causes. Most cases respond well to conservative management, while a small subset requires surgical intervention. A structured approach to etiology and stepwise management ensures effective outcomes and reduced recurrence.', '', 'RETROSPECTIVE STUDY ON ETIOLOGY AND MANAGEMENT OF EPISTAXIS IN A TERTIARY CARE HOSPITAL', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-05 12:45:04', '2025-10-05 12:45:07');
INSERT INTO `rh_abstract` (`id`, `name`, `email`, `reg_id`, `catergory_id`, `note`, `file`, `title_0`, `note_1`, `file_1`, `title_1`, `note_2`, `file_2`, `title_2`, `note_3`, `file_3`, `title_3`, `note_4`, `file_4`, `title_4`, `mail_send`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(150, 'Amandeep Singh', 'amandsingh001@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000330', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of Poster: Association of Body Mass Index with Severity of Allergic Rhinitis: A Prospective Observational Study\r\n\r\nPresenting Author: Dr Amandeep Singh\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n\r\nAim: To evaluate the association between body mass index (BMI) and the occurrence and severity of allergic rhinitis.\r\n\r\nMethods: A prospective observational study was conducted in the Department of Otorhinolaryngology over one year (May 2024–April 2025) on a total of 133 clinically diagnosed cases of persistent AR (as per ARIA guidelines) and 133 age- and sex-matched healthy controls. Severity of AR was assessed using the Total Nasal Symptom Score (TNSS). BMI was calculated and categorized into underweight (<18.5), normal (18.5–24.9), overweight (25–29.9), and obese (≥30).\r\n\r\nResults: In the AR group, 37.6% had mild, 38.3% moderate, and 24.1% severe symptoms. A significant difference in BMI distribution was observed between study and control groups (p = 0.0205). Among AR patients, obesity was strongly associated with increased disease severity (p < 0.001). Notably, 56.2% of severe AR patients were obese compared to only 20% in the mild category.\r\n\r\nConclusion: This study demonstrates the importance of lifestyle modifications and weight management as adjunct strategies in the prevention and management of AR.', '', 'Association of Body Mass Index with Severity of Allergic Rhinitis: A Prospective Observational Study', 2, 1, '2025-10-05 22:10:13', '2025-10-05 22:10:17'),
(151, 'Amandeep Singh', 'amandsingh001@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000330', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of Paper:  Effect of Adenoidectomy on Quality of Life in Children with Long Standing Snoring and Apnea using OSD-6 Questionnaire- A Tertiary Care Centre Study\r\n\r\nPresenting Author: Dr Amandeep Singh\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n \r\nAim:  To evaluate the effectiveness of adenoidectomy alone in treating pediatric snoring and apnea using OSD-6 questionnaire.\r\n\r\nMethods: A prospective observational study was conducted in the Department of Otorhinolaryngology over one year (August 2024–August 2025) on a total of  90 children between the age group of 5–10 years, who underwent adenoidectomy, satisfying the inclusion and exclusion criteria adapted from the the CHAT trial. Parents/guardians of the selected children were requested to fill up the OSD-6 questionnaire preoperatively and postoperatively at third month\r\n \r\nResults: 90 patients were evaluated with a mean age of 6.20± 2.33 years with male preponderance. There was statistically significant improvement in all six parameters of OSD-6 questionnaire (physical distress, sleep and swallowing disorders, emotional stress, limitation of physical activities and caregiver’s concerns) postoperatively at 3rd month (p<0.05)\r\n\r\nConclusion: This study concludes that in carefully selected candidates, adenoidectomy in isolation can be a recommended surgical option to improve the symptoms of pediatric apnea and snoring.', '', 'Effect of Adenoidectomy on Quality of Life in Children with Long Standing Snoring and Apnea using OS', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-05 22:12:45', '2025-10-05 22:12:49'),
(152, 'Niharika Gupta', 'niharika.g2609@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000332', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of Paper : CT-Based Assessment of Columella to Nasofrontal Beak and Anterior Skull Base Distances: Anatomical Landmarks for Frontal Sinus Surgery\r\n\r\nPresenting author: Dr. Niharika Gupta\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n\r\nAim: To determine the distances from the columella to the nasofrontal beak (NFB) and anterior skull base (ASB) using computed tomography (CT) in adults.\r\n\r\nMethods: An observational study was conducted in the Department of ENT, over a period of 9 months from January 2025 to July 2025. A total of 264 subjects (18–65 years) who underwent MDCT of paranasal sinuses for sinonasal symptoms were enrolled after approval from the Ethical committee. Distances from columella to NFB and ASB were measured on sagittal reconstructions.\r\n\r\nResults: The mean columella–NFB distance was 54.39 ± 3.49 mm (males: 55.49 mm; females: 53.23 mm), and mean columella–ASB distance was 62.75 ± 4.37 mm (males: 63.89 mm; females: 61.56 mm). Both parameters showed statistically significant sex-related differences. No correlation with age was observed.\r\n\r\nConclusion: CT-derived distances from columella to NFB and ASB provide reliable and consistent anatomical landmarks during frontal sinus surgery and can aid intraoperative orientation, particularly in complex or distorted anatomy.', '', 'CT-Based Assessment of Columella to Nasofrontal Beak and Anterior Skull Base Distances: Anatomical L', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-05 22:26:20', '2025-10-05 22:26:23'),
(153, 'Niharika Gupta', 'niharika.g2609@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000332', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of Poster: Association of ABO Blood Groups with Susceptibility and Severity of Allergic Rhinitis: A Case–Control Study\r\n\r\nPresenting author: Dr. Niharika Gupta\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu \r\n\r\n\r\nAim: To explore the association of ABO and Rh blood groups with AR susceptibility and severity.\r\n\r\nMethods: A prospective study was conducted in the Department of ENT from January 2025 to August 2025 on 133 clinically diagnosed persistent AR patients (per ARIA guidelines, aged 18–55 years) and 133 age- and sex-matched healthy controls. Disease severity was assessed using the Total Nasal Symptom Score (TNSS). ABO and Rh blood groups were determined via standard serological typing.\r\n\r\nResults: The mean age of AR cases was 38.5 ± 11 years, with a female predominance. Based on TNSS, 38.3% had moderate AR, 37.6% mild, and 24.1% severe. Blood group O⁺ was significantly more frequent in AR patients compared to controls (43.6% vs. 28.6%), while AB⁺ was notably less common (3.7% vs. 15.0%) (p = 0.035).\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nBlood group O, particularly O⁺, was significantly associated with both susceptibility and severity of AR, whereas AB appeared protective. ABO typing may serve as an additional risk stratification tool for early identification and preventive strategies in allergic rhinitis.', '', 'Association of ABO Blood Groups with Susceptibility and Severity of Allergic Rhinitis: A Case–Contro', 2, 1, '2025-10-05 22:29:54', '2025-10-05 22:29:58'),
(154, 'Pooja Suryawanshi', 'pooja.suryawanshi.ps@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000259', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title- Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma(ACC)  of Maxillary Sinus masquerading as Chronic Dacryocystitis(CDC): a rare case report\r\nPresenting author- Dr. Pooja Suryawanshi, Dr. Archan Naik, Dr. Vathsalya Vijay\r\nAim- To present a rare case of maxillary sinus ACC masquerading as CDC.\r\nMethodology- 36year female presented with history of watering from left eye since 2021 and left eye protrusion with left sided facial swelling for 3 months since May 2024.\r\nO/E - Left eye proptosis + vision Normal\r\nDNE- Mass in left middle meatus\r\nMRI of PNS which showed irregular heterogeneously enhancing mass causing destruction of it’s walls suggestive of neoplastic etiology \r\nBiopsy/ IHC- suggestive of ACC of left maxillary sinus\r\nPatient underwent left total maxillectomy + R1 excision of tumor extension in left orbit + temporalis flap reconstruction + insertion of palatal prosthesis under GA in oct 2024.\r\nNegative consent for orbital exenteration.\r\n\r\nResult- Histopathological diagnosis ACC with predominant cribriform pattern with perineural invasion, all margins not free.\r\nPatient underwent adjuvant radiotherapy post operatively and tolerated well.\r\nAt 11 month follow up, the patient was alive and well with no evidence of local recurrence and distant metastasis\r\n\r\nConclusion- This case highlights that ACC of the maxillary sinus can present with non-specific slow onset symptoms. The combination of surgical resection and adjuvant radiotherapy is the standard of care and vigilant follow up is essential.\r\nSecondary causes of CDC (paranasal/lacrimal sac tumors) to be kept in mind while treating cases of CDC.', '', 'Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma of Maxillary Sinus masquerading as Chronic Dacryocystitis: a rare case repo', 2, 1, '2025-10-07 21:54:36', '2025-10-07 21:54:39'),
(159, 'RAMNEET KOUR', 'Ramneetkour2000@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000250', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of poster: Fibro osseous lesion left frontoethmoid recess  and left nasal cavity\r\n\r\nType of article :Case report\r\n\r\nPresenting author:Dr.Ramneet kour\r\n\r\nAffliation: Department of ENT,GMC Jammu\r\n\r\nIntroduction :Fibro-osseous lesion characterized by the replacement of normal bone with fibrous tissue containing varying amounts of mineralized material. It mostly  involve the craniofacial skeleton. In sinonasal region it is   uncommon, with the frontal and ethmoid sinuses being rare sites of involvement. Patients typically present with nasal obstruction, headache, facial swelling, or proptosis.\r\n\r\nDetails :14 year old male patient presented to ENT OPD with complain of protrusion of left eyeball since 3 months which was insidious in onset and gradually progressive .\r\n\r\nOn examination there was increase in interpupillary distance \r\n(84mm).The interpalpebral fissure height was more on left side than the right.No inflammatory changes were seen in adjacent areas  .visual acuity was 6/6 on right side and 6/18 on left side .\r\n\r\nNCCT ORBIT : \r\nill defined  heterogeneous ,predominately,hyperdense lesion measuring approximately 4.5 *2.8*2.6 cm (AP*TR*CC) seen involving left maxillary sinus, left ethmoid air cells ,left frontoethmoid recess and left nasal cavity including left middle turbinate and causing thinning and erosion of adjacent bones .\r\n\r\nLaterally, the lesion is seen bulging into left orbit causing abutment and displacement of left medial rectus, inferior rectus and superior oblique muscle. Lateral displacement of optic nerve is seen.\r\nMild proptosis of left globe is seen.\r\n\r\nMedially, it is seen abutting nasal septum and causing effacement and blockage of left osteomeatal complex.\r\n\r\nInferomedially, the lesion is seen abutting inferior orbital fissure.\r\nAnteriorly,  it is seen involving  left nasolacrimal duct with opacification of  left frontal, ethmoid,maxillary and sphenoid sinus is seen.\r\n\r\nLikely suggestive of fibre osseous lesion.\r\n\r\n Endoscopic excision  and left orbital decompression done under GA . Histopathology revealed features of benign fibro osseous lesion suggestive of ossifying fibroma.', '', 'Fibro osseous lesion left frontoethmoid recess and left nasal cavity', 1, 1, '2025-10-08 21:14:38', '2025-10-08 21:14:38'),
(160, 'PRIYA', 'priyaclassxii@gmail.com', 'priyaclassxii@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of poster: Rhinosporidiosis of nasal cavity.\r\nType of article: Case Report\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Priya\r\nAffiliation: Department of ENT &HNS , GMC Jammu.\r\nIntroduction: Rhinosporidiosis is an infectious disease caused by an aquatic protozoan , Rhinosporidium seeberi previously considered to be a fungus . Mode of infection is transepithelial by inoculation of traumatized epithelium ( mucosa  & submucosa ) and  and with sporangiospores  on exposure to infected water (ponds, lakes) and soil.\r\n Rhinosporidiosis is an endemic disease found in tropical regions, prevalent in India (South and Central India) , Sri Lanka, and Argentina. The present report of rhinopsoridiosis constitutes the very few reported cases of rhinosporidiosis in a resident of Jammu and Kashmir , India, who has no history of travel to any of the endemic areas. \r\n Case Details: A 37 year old male presented to  ENT & HNS OPD  with complaints of  right side nasal obstruction which was gradual in onset , slowly progressive and associated with nasal discharge .\r\nLOCAL EXAMINATION  :\r\n Anterior Rhinoscopy - ‘S’ shaped deviated nasal septum. Mucopurulent discharge present in right nasal cavity . No polyp /mass visualised.\r\nOral cavity / oropharynx - WNL\r\nCECT NOSE & PNS: \r\nHeterogenously enhancing soft tissue density mass lesion measuring 22.3mm*16mm*22mm (AP*TR*CC)  is seen centred in nasopharynx more towards right side .This mass is causing obliteration of right side fossa of rossenmuller .\r\n\r\nDigital Nasal Endoscopy - A friable polypoidal mass arising from right side of choana in nasopharynx with white spots on the under surface .\r\nBiopsy was taken from the mass and sent for hpe.\r\nHISTOPATHOLOGY  EXAMINATION : Multiple sections from the submitted biopsy showed respiratory lining epithelium. Sub epithelium shows thick walled sporangia containing spores. Features were consistent with RHINOSPORIDIOSIS.\r\n \r\n Patient was planned for excision of mass using coblation under general anaesthesia  . Histopathological examination of the excised mass revealed findings consistent with rhinosporidiosis.', '', 'Rhinosporidiosis of nasal cavity', 2, 1, '2025-10-08 22:02:07', '2025-10-08 22:02:11'),
(161, 'Ramneet kour', 'Ramneetkour2000@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000250', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of poster: Fibro osseous lesion left frontoethmoid recess  and left nasal cavity\r\n \r\nType of article :Case report\r\n \r\nPresenting author:Dr.Ramneet kour\r\n \r\nAffliation: Department of ENT,GMC Jammu\r\n \r\nIntroduction :Fibro-osseous lesion characterized by the replacement of normal bone with fibrous tissue containing varying amounts of mineralized material. It mostly  involve the craniofacial skeleton. In sinonasal region it is   uncommon, with the frontal and ethmoid sinuses being rare sites of involvement. Patients typically present with nasal obstruction, headache, facial swelling, or proptosis.\r\n \r\nDetails :14 year old male patient presented to ENT OPD with complain of protrusion of left eyeball since 3 months which was insidious in onset and gradually progressive .\r\n \r\nOn examination there was increase in interpupillary distance\r\n(84mm).The interpalpebral fissure height was more on left side than the right.No inflammatory changes were seen in adjacent areas  .visual acuity was 6/6 on right side and 6/18 on left side .\r\n \r\nNCCT ORBIT :\r\nill defined  heterogeneous ,predominately,hyperdense lesion measuring approximately 4.5 *2.8*2.6 cm (AP*TR*CC) seen involving left maxillary sinus, left ethmoid air cells ,left frontoethmoid recess and left nasal cavity including left middle turbinate and causing thinning and erosion of adjacent bones .\r\n \r\n• Laterally, the lesion is seen bulging into left orbit causing abutment and displacement of left medial rectus, inferior rectus and superior oblique muscle. Lateral displacement of optic nerve is seen.\r\nMild proptosis of left globe is seen.\r\n \r\n• Medially, it is seen abutting nasal septum and causing effacement and blockage of left osteomeatal complex.\r\n \r\n• Inferomedially, the lesion is seen abutting inferior orbital fissure.\r\n• Anteriorly,  it is seen involving  left nasolacrimal duct with opacification of  left frontal, ethmoid,maxillary and sphenoid sinus is seen.\r\n \r\nLikely suggestive of fibre osseous lesion.\r\n \r\nEndoscopic excision  and left orbital decompression done under GA . Histopathology revealed features of benign fibro osseous lesion suggestive of ossifying fibroma.', '', 'Fibro osseous lesion left frontoethmoid recess  and left nasal cavity', 2, 1, '2025-10-08 22:08:59', '2025-10-08 22:09:03'),
(162, 'Dr.Shaileja S. Chopdekar', 'chopdekarshaileja1996@gmail.com', 'chopdekarshaileja1996@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title \r\nIndications for open approach septorhinoplasty: case series\r\n\r\nPresenting Authors\r\nDr. Shaileja S. Chopdekar , Dr.Markandeya Tiwari.\r\n\r\nAim\r\nTo identify and analyze the functional and aesthetic indications for selecting the open approach in septorhinoplasty at a tertiary care center.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nThis was a prospective observational study conducted over 18 months in the Department of ENT , Goa Medical College .\r\nPatients undergoing open approach septorhinoplasty were included regardless of age or gender .\r\nDemographic data ,preoperative diagnosis and surgical indications were recorded.\r\nSurgical indications were categorised into \r\n•	Post traumatic nasal deformity\r\n•	Severe septal deviation or S- shaped deformity\r\n•	Tip deformity\r\n•	Saddle nose\r\n•	Combined functional and aesthetic corrections\r\n•	Binders nose\r\nFunctional outcomes were assessed using the NOSE SCORE, and patient satisfaction was measured with a VISUAL ANALOG SCALE (VAS) .\r\nResults\r\nAmong 20 patients ( 12 males and 8 females, mean age 28.4 ± 6.7 years), the leading indication was post traumatic deformity followed by severe septal deviation, tip deformity, saddle nose correction .\r\n\r\nConclusion \r\nOpen approach septorhinoplasty is predominantly indicated for post traumatic deformities and severe septal deviations. It provides superior anatomical exposure , enabling precise correction and high patient satisfaction , making it the preferred technique for complex functional and aesthetic nasal reconstructions.', '', 'Indications for open approach septorhinoplasty: case series', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-11 23:38:23', '2025-10-11 23:38:27'),
(163, 'Thomas George', 'thomasgk97@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000415', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author:\r\nDr Thomas George\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nEndoscopic skull base surgery has shown promise as a minimally invasive alternative to traditional open approaches. This presentation highlights the safety, efficacy, and surgical advantages of the expanded endoscopic approach in extradural lesions.\r\n\r\nMethods:\r\nThis presentation includes 12 challenging cases of extradural anterior skull base lesions managed at our department in a tertiary care hospital. Each patient underwent detailed prospective clinical and radiological evaluation followed by endoscopic resection/repair using expanded endonasal approaches. The focus was on demonstrating surgical feasibility, expanding the margins of possible endoscopic resection, intraoperative safety, and postoperative outcomes.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll patients underwent successful endoscopic resection of their respective lesions with no major intraoperative or postoperative complications. The procedures had minimal blood loss, excellent visualization of anatomical structures, and satisfactory clearance of disease. All patients are currently under regular follow-up and remain asymptomatic, with no evidence of recurrence or postoperative morbidity.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nExpanded endoscopic approaches to the anterior skull base provide a safe and effective alternative for managing extradural pathologies. The enhanced visualization, reduced morbidity, and good cosmetic outcomes (owing to the lack of external incisions) make it a valuable tool in the skull base surgeon’s armamentarium. With growing experience and refinement of techniques, surgeons are pushing the envelope and expanding the surgical corridors of extradural endoscopic endonasal surgery, and these techniques are poised to become the new standard of care for the management of extradural pathologies of the anterior skull base.', '', 'Expanded Endoscopic Anterior Skull Base Surgeries for Extradural Pathologies', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-12 09:55:17', '2025-10-12 09:55:20'),
(164, 'Thomas George', 'thomasgk97@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000415', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author:\r\nDr Thomas George\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nEndoscopic skull base surgery has shown promise as a minimally invasive alternative to traditional open approaches. This presentation highlights the safety, efficacy, and surgical advantages of the expanded endoscopic approach in extradural lesions.\r\n\r\nMethods:\r\nThis presentation includes 12 challenging cases of extradural anterior skull base lesions managed at our department in a tertiary care hospital. Each patient underwent detailed prospective clinical and radiological evaluation followed by endoscopic resection/repair using expanded endonasal approaches. The focus was on demonstrating surgical feasibility, expanding the margins of possible endoscopic resection, intraoperative safety, and postoperative outcomes.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll patients underwent successful endoscopic resection of their respective lesions with no major intraoperative or postoperative complications. The procedures had minimal blood loss, excellent visualization of anatomical structures, and satisfactory clearance of disease. All patients are currently under regular follow-up and remain asymptomatic, with no evidence of recurrence or postoperative morbidity.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nExpanded endoscopic approaches to the anterior skull base provide a safe and effective alternative for managing extradural pathologies. The enhanced visualization, reduced morbidity, and good cosmetic outcomes (owing to the lack of external incisions) make it a valuable tool in the skull base surgeon’s armamentarium. With growing experience and refinement of techniques, surgeons are pushing the envelope and expanding the surgical corridors of extradural endoscopic endonasal surgery, and these techniques are poised to become the new standard of care for the management of extradural pathologies of the anterior skull base.', '', 'Expanded Endoscopic Anterior Skull Base Surgeries for Extradural Pathologies', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-12 09:55:20', '2025-10-12 09:55:23'),
(165, 'DR ARYA V', 'aryaachutham@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000417', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Dr.Arya V,aryaachutham@gmail.com,Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session,Registration Number : RHIN0000417\r\nTITLE : “POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE\r\nBACKGROUND: Oncocytic papilloma is a rare, benign tumor originating from the Schneiderian membrane (lining) of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses.This is rarest form of sinonasal papilloma with an incidence of 0.5 to 1.5 cases per 100,000 people per year.\r\nCASE REPORT:A 63 year old male with no relevant past medical history presented to otorhinolaryngology clinic with 5 years history of  bilateral nasal obstruction and snoring and 2 months history of recurrent episodes of nasal bleeds. Anterior rhinoscopy showed multiple pale polypoidal glistening masses with probe passed all around, non tender, not bleed on touch in right nasal cavity and posterior rhinoscopy showed -Pale glistening polypoidal mass noted covering both choana posteriorly extending upto the oropharynx.NCCT PNS was showing diffuse extensive mucosal thickening and near total soft tissue opacification of the right maxillary sinus and the ethmoid complexes on both sides ,that appears merging with the nasal turbinates with near total obliteration of the nasal cavity ,widening the right maxillary ostium ,the soft tissue density is also seen extending to the left choana ,obliteration of right osteomeatal complex -features suggestive of sino-nasal polyposis.Under General anesthesia FESS + Septoplasty was done and specimen was send for Histopathological evaluation.HPE shown features suggestive of sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type (ICD 10 CODE D14.0)\r\nCONCLUSION: Sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type extremely rare condition. Accurate diagnosis and appropriate surgical management are crucial for favorable outcome in such cases. Complete surgical excision through endoscopic surgery or open radical procedure is the treatment of choice; lateral rhinotomy and medial maxillectomy may be required.  Histopathological investigations play a pivotal role to arrive at the final diagnosis and exclude malignancy.', '', '“POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE', 2, 1, '2025-10-12 10:43:42', '2025-10-12 10:43:45'),
(166, 'KIRUBAKARAN K', 'kkirubakaran93@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000418', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title:\r\nEndoscopic Management of Lateral Sphenoid Recess CSF Leak: Technical Considerations and Clinical Insights from a Complex Case\r\nAuthors: Dr Kirubakaran K, Dr Mainak Dutta, Dr Henna M, Dr Vijay Sankar\r\nBackground:\r\nSpontaneous cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhea originating from the lateral recess of the sphenoid sinus is rare and challenging to manage due to the lateral location and complex anatomy. It is frequently associated with elevated intracranial pressure and idiopathic intracranial hypertension. Traditional transsphenoidal approaches offer limited instrumentation access, making the endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid route an important alternative.\r\nObjectives:\r\nTo present a complex case of spontaneous type IV lateral recess CSF leak managed by the endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach, emphasizing technical challenges, surgical strategies, and lessons from a revision procedure.\r\nCase Report\r\nA 40-year-old male with spontaneous CSF rhinorrhea confirmed by beta-2 transferrin assay underwent endoscopic repair via a transpterygoid approach. Imaging showed a 7mm x 5mm bony defect with meningoencephalocele in the postero-superior lateral recess. Multilayer repair was performed with fat, cartilage, fascia, and fibrin glue. Recurrence prompted revision surgery with widened exposure, further drilling for access, and lumbar drain placement.\r\nDiscussion points:\r\nInitial repair was complicated by mucosalization between fascia and bone causing a recurrent CSF tract. Revision surgery facilitated improved access and successful multilayer closure. The patient had no CSF leak on long-term follow-up and was managed medically for elevated intracranial pressure. This case highlights the importance of addressing CSF pressure and achieving optimal surgical exposure before attempting to repair\r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach enables direct access and effective repair of lateral recess CSF leaks. Adequate exposure, multilayer closure, and consideration of CSF dynamics are critical for success. Multidisciplinary management including ICP control is essential to prevent recurrence in this complex anatomical region.', '', 'Endoscopic Management of Lateral Sphenoid Recess CSF Leak: Technical Considerations and Clinical Ins', 2, 0, '2025-10-12 20:19:55', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(167, 'KIRUBAKARAN K', 'kkirubakaran93@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000418', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title:\r\nEndoscopic Management of Lateral Sphenoid Recess CSF Leak: Technical Considerations and Clinical Insights from a Complex Case\r\nAuthors: Dr Kirubakaran K, Dr Mainak Dutta, Dr Henna M, Dr Vijay Sankar\r\nBackground:\r\nSpontaneous cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhea originating from the lateral recess of the sphenoid sinus is rare and challenging to manage due to the lateral location and complex anatomy. It is frequently associated with elevated intracranial pressure and idiopathic intracranial hypertension. Traditional transsphenoidal approaches offer limited instrumentation access, making the endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid route an important alternative.\r\nObjectives:\r\nTo present a complex case of spontaneous type IV lateral recess CSF leak managed by the endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach, emphasizing technical challenges, surgical strategies, and lessons from a revision procedure.\r\nCase Report\r\nA 40-year-old male with spontaneous CSF rhinorrhea confirmed by beta-2 transferrin assay underwent endoscopic repair via a transpterygoid approach. Imaging showed a 7mm x 5mm bony defect with meningoencephalocele in the postero-superior lateral recess. Multilayer repair was performed with fat, cartilage, fascia, and fibrin glue. Recurrence prompted revision surgery with widened exposure, further drilling for access, and lumbar drain placement.\r\nDiscussion points:\r\nInitial repair was complicated by mucosalization between fascia and bone causing a recurrent CSF tract. Revision surgery facilitated improved access and successful multilayer closure. The patient had no CSF leak on long-term follow-up and was managed medically for elevated intracranial pressure. This case highlights the importance of addressing CSF pressure and achieving optimal surgical exposure before attempting to repair\r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach enables direct access and effective repair of lateral recess CSF leaks. Adequate exposure, multilayer closure, and consideration of CSF dynamics are critical for success. Multidisciplinary management including ICP control is essential to prevent recurrence in this complex anatomical region.', '', 'Endoscopic Management of Lateral Sphenoid Recess CSF Leak: Technical Considerations and Clinical Ins', 2, 0, '2025-10-12 20:19:58', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(168, 'Dr Rajendran Dinesh Kumar', 'dinuraj1186@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000419', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\",\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nEfficacy of Customized vs Commercial Tissue Adhesive for CSF Leak Repair: A Prospective Comparative Study in ENT Surgery.\r\n\r\nBackground\r\nCerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leaks present a serious risk in ENT surgery and require timely and secure closure to prevent complications. Commercially available tissue adhesives, though reliable, are costly. This study evaluates a cost-effective, self-prepared tissue adhesive compared to standard commercial glue in endoscopic CSF leak repair.\r\n\r\nMaterials & Methods\r\nA prospective comparative study was conducted over 2 years and 3 months amongst patients with CSF leaks undergoing endoscopic repair. Patients were divided into three groups:\r\n•	Group A  (n=15): Commercial tissue adhesive used.\r\n•	Group B  (n=15): Customized in-house tissue adhesive used.\r\n•	Group C  (n=15): Control Group -No tissue adhesive used.\r\n\r\nAll groups were matched for age, leak site, and aetiology. Post-operative outcomes such as CSF leak recurrence, infection, healing time, and cost-effectiveness were monitored over a 6-month to 1 year follow-up.\r\nResults\r\n•	Leak Closure Success: Achieved in 94% (Group A), 100% (Group B), 73% (Group C).\r\n•	Post-operative Infection: 6% (Group A), 0% (Group B), 27% (Group C)\r\n•	Mucosal Healing Time: Comparable between groups A (93%) , B (93%) , C (87%)\r\n•	Cost: Customized adhesive was approximately 90% cheaper than commercial glue.\r\n•	Patient Satisfaction: High in both groups A and B; slightly higher in Group B due to affordability.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nThe customized tissue adhesive is a safe and effective alternative to commercial glue for CSF leak repair, with comparable outcomes and significant cost savings. It offers a promising solution for resource-limited healthcare settings without compromising surgical success.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Customized adhesive, CSF leak, Endoscopic repair, ENT surgery, Biocompatible, Cost-effectiveness, Surgical innovation.', '', 'Efficacy of Customized vs Commercial Tissue Adhesive for CSF Leak Repair: A Prospective Comparative ', NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nEndoscopic Management of Stage III Sphenoid Sinus Inverted Papilloma: A Video Presentation.\r\n\r\nBackground.\r\nInverted papilloma is a rare benign tumour of the nasal cavity, with isolated sphenoid sinus involvement being extremely uncommon. Its locally aggressive behaviour and risk of recurrence pose significant surgical challenges. Sphenoid sinus inverted papilloma (IP) is rare, with isolated sphenoid involvement making up a small fraction of all IPs, which themselves account for only 0.5%–4% of nasal tumors. While the exact prevalence is not precisely defined, one study noted only 50 reported cases in the scientific literature, and involvement of the sphenoid is significantly less common than maxillary or ethmoid sinuses. This video presents a rare case and illustrates the technical nuances of endoscopic management in Stage III disease.\r\n\r\nCase Report.\r\n\r\nA 30-year-old male presented with bilateral nasal obstruction for 1 year and snoring for 3 months. Imaging revealed an isolated left sphenoid sinus lesion. Surgery was performed under general anaesthesia using an endonasal endoscopic approach to sphenoid sinus with posterior septectomy. The inverted papilloma was excised completely, along with removal of sphenoid sinus mucosa and probable bony attachment sites. Intraoperatively, the tumour was seen extending across the intersphenoid septum into the contralateral sinus, necessitating meticulous bilateral clearance.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nIsolated sphenoid inverted papilloma demands precise endoscopic excision. This video highlights surgical strategies ensuring safe and complete removal while minimizing recurrence.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Inverted papilloma, Nasal cavity, Sphenoid sinus.', '', 'Endoscopic Management of Stage III Sphenoid Sinus Inverted Papilloma: A Video Presentation.', 'Title: “Sealing the Gap: Customized Tissue Adhesive Revolutionizing CSF leak Repairs in ENT Surgeries. “\r\n\r\n\r\nBackground\r\nCerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leaks present a serious risk in ENT surgery and require timely and secure closure to prevent complications. Commercially available tissue adhesives, though reliable, are costly. This study evaluates a cost-effective, self-prepared tissue adhesive compared to standard commercial glue in endoscopic CSF leak repair.\r\n\r\nMaterials & Methods\r\nA prospective comparative study was conducted over 2 years and 3 months amongst patients with CSF leaks undergoing endoscopic repair. Patients were divided into three groups:\r\n•	Group A  (n=15): Commercial tissue adhesive used.\r\n•	Group B  (n=15): Customized in-house tissue adhesive used.\r\n•	Group C  (n=15): Control Group -No tissue adhesive used.\r\n\r\nAll groups were matched for age, leak site, and aetiology. Post-operative outcomes such as CSF leak recurrence, infection, healing time, and cost-effectiveness were monitored over a 6-month to 1 year follow-up.\r\n\r\nResults\r\n•	Leak Closure Success: Achieved in 94% (Group A), 100% (Group B), 73% (Group C).\r\n•	Post-operative Infection: 6% (Group A), 0% (Group B), 27% (Group C)\r\n•	Mucosal Healing Time: Comparable between groups A (93%) , B (93%) , C (87%)\r\n•	Cost: Customized adhesive was approximately 90% cheaper than commercial glue.\r\n•	Patient Satisfaction: High in both groups A and B; slightly higher in Group B due to affordability.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nThe customized tissue adhesive is a safe and effective alternative to commercial glue for CSF leak repair, with comparable outcomes and significant cost savings. It offers a promising solution for resource-limited healthcare settings without compromising surgical success.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Customized adhesive, CSF leak, Endoscopic repair, ENT surgery, Biocompatible, Cost-effectiveness, Surgical innovation.', '', 'Sealing the Gap: Customized Tissue Adhesive Revolutionizing CSF leak Repairs in ENT Surgeries.', 2, 1, '2025-10-13 00:02:50', '2025-10-13 00:02:54'),
(169, 'Dr Rajendran Dinesh Kumar', 'dinuraj1186@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000419', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nEndoscopic Management of Stage III Sphenoid Sinus Inverted Papilloma- A Rare Case Presentation.\r\n\r\nBackground.\r\nInverted papilloma is a rare benign tumour of the nasal cavity, with isolated sphenoid sinus involvement being extremely uncommon. Its locally aggressive behaviour and risk of recurrence pose significant surgical challenges. Sphenoid sinus inverted papilloma (IP) is rare, with isolated sphenoid involvement making up a small fraction of all IPs, which themselves account for only 0.5%–4% of nasal tumors. While the exact prevalence is not precisely defined, one study noted only 50 reported cases in the scientific literature, and involvement of the sphenoid is significantly less common than maxillary or ethmoid sinuses. \r\n\r\nCase Report.\r\n\r\nA 30-year-old male presented with bilateral nasal obstruction for 1 year and snoring for 3 months. Imaging revealed an isolated left sphenoid sinus lesion. Surgery was performed under general anaesthesia using an endonasal endoscopic approach to sphenoid sinus with posterior septectomy. The inverted papilloma was excised completely, along with removal of sphenoid sinus mucosa and probable bony attachment sites. Intraoperatively, the tumour was seen extending across the intersphenoid septum into the contralateral sinus, necessitating meticulous bilateral clearance.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nIsolated sphenoid inverted papilloma demands precise endoscopic excision. This video highlights surgical strategies ensuring safe and complete removal while minimizing recurrence.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Inverted papilloma, Nasal cavity, Sphenoid sinus.', '', 'Endoscopic Management of Stage III Sphenoid Sinus Inverted Papilloma- A Rare Case Presentation.', 2, 1, '2025-10-13 00:05:12', '2025-10-13 00:05:15'),
(170, 'JAIMANTI BAKSHI', 'drjayabakshi@ymail.com', 'drjayabakshi@ymail.com', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Aim\r\nTo evaluate the spectrum, surgical outcomes, and role of adjuvant therapy in sinonasal cancers managed endoscopically at a tertiary care hospital.\r\nMethodology\r\nA retrospective review conducted on 21 patients with sinonasal tumors treated by endoscopic surgery. Demographic details, surgical outcomes, recurrence and use of adjuvant modalities were analyzed. Patients previously managed by open surgery were excluded.\r\nResults\r\nThe cohort comprised 21 patients (mean age 45 years; 11 females, 10 males).\r\nThe histology was as follows-\r\n•	Adenocarcinoma – 7\r\n•	Adenoid cystic carcinoma – 2\r\n•	Glomangiopericytoma/Hemangiopericytoma – 3\r\n•	Solitary fibrous tumor – 1\r\n•	Plasmacytoma – 1\r\n•	Osteosarcoma – 1\r\n•	Others/Inflammatory (Rosai-Dorfman, GPA, inverted papilloma ) – 6\r\n Complete endoscopic excision was feasible in most patients with minimal complications. Adjuvant radiotherapy was administered in high-risk cases with aggressive histologies and positive or close margins. Selected patients also received chemoradiation. Early follow-up indicates favorable disease control, though recurrences were noted in a few adenocarcinoma and hemangiopericytoma cases.\r\nConclusions\r\nEndoscopic surgery is effective primary modality for sinonasal cancers, with reduced morbidity. Integration of adjuvant radiotherapy and multimodal therapy is essential for optimizing oncological outcomes . Careful selection and multidisciplinary management remain key.', '', 'Endoscopic Management of Sinonasal Tumors: Experience from a Tertiary Care Hospital', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-10-13 09:16:58', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(171, 'Dr Lekhaa Mohanraj', 'lekhaamraj@gmail.com', 'RHIN000073', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim and Background: Spontaneous cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhoea is a rare entity often associated with middle-age, female gender and obesity. Endoscopic closure of CSF leaks is a well-established procedure with successful outcomes. However, there is a risk of recurrence if the underlying intracranial hypertension (ICH) is not adequately treated. Our study aimed to evaluate the safety, efficacy and outcomes of combined endoscopic CSF Leak repair with simultaneous Theco-Peritoneal Shunt (TPS).  \r\nCase Descriptions and Methods: Patients who underwent endoscopic repair of CSF rhinorrhoea with TPS between June 2009 and June 2024 were recruited into the study. Endoscopic, multi-layered closure was done with autologous grafts and simultaneous TPS was performed by the neurosurgical team. The patient’s demographics, clinical data, comorbidities, body mass index (BMI), duration of the leak, post-operative complications, their management and success rates were retrieved and analysed. \r\nResults: A total of 82 patients with spontaneous CSF leaks were surgically treated. Most of the patients were female (84.14%). The average age was 42 ± 6.5 years and average Body Mass Index (BMI) was 32.8 ± 4.8 kg/m2. The most common presenting symptoms were rhinorrhoea and headache. The most common site of leak was the cribriform plate (50%). Three patients developed shunt related complications which resulted in recurrence of CSF leak (3.7%). The overall success rate of the combined approach was 96.34%. \r\nConclusion : Based on our institutional experience, combined endoscopic CSF leak repair with simultaneous TPS leads to successful outcomes with a low complication rate.  \r\nClinical Significance : Endoscopic spontaneous CSF rhinorrhea repair can be associated with recurrence. To prevent this, we propose a combined endoscopic repair with TPS, wherein the primary cause (ICH) and the effect (CSF leak) is managed in tandem.', '', 'Combined Endoscopic CSF Leak Repair with Simultaneous Theco-Peritoneal Shunting for Spontaneous CSF ', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-13 10:32:40', '2025-10-13 10:32:44'),
(172, 'Dr Lekhaa Mohanraj', 'lekhaamraj@gmail.com', 'RHIN000073', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim and Background\r\nMucoceles are benign expansive cystic formations, composed of a mucus-secreting epithelium. Dacryocystocele or congenital mucocele of nasolacrimal duct is a relatively rare variant of NLDO, representing 0.1% of children with congenital obstruction, and results from the coexistence of a distal and a proximal obstruction. Nasolacrimal duct mucocele typically presents as a bulging in the lower medial canthus of the eye and epiphora. \r\nCase Description \r\nThe patient was a 8-year-old boy a history of watering of right eye for 4 months. Computed tomography (CT) showed a cystic expansion in the right lacrimal sac topography and dilatation of the bony canal of the nasolacrimal duct. Nasal endoscopy showed medialization of lateral wall. He had endoscopic dacryocystorhinostomy. The lacrimal sac was opened with drainage of thick purulent secretion. \r\nResults\r\nThe patient remains asymptomatic and without clinical signs 1 year and 8 months after surgery.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nNasolacrimal duct mucocele is a rare occurrence; however, it carries a risk of complications such as local infection and cellulitis. Dacrocystorhinostomy is considered as the definitive treatment  having good outcomes.', '', 'A Rare Case of Congenital Nasolacrimal Sac Mucocele', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-13 15:35:48', '2025-10-13 15:35:52'),
(173, 'Nikhil Solomon Sundara Raj', 'nikhilssr@hotmail.com', 'RHIN0000261', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Background\r\nSkull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is a severe infection primarily affecting individuals with compromised immune systems, complicated by the rise of pan-resistant organisms. Effective management relies on prolonged, culture-directed, broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy tailored to microbiological results. The increasing prevalence of pan-resistant pathogens necessitates exploring alternative treatment options.\r\nTimely diagnosis, culture-directed therapy, and an interdisciplinary approach are crucial to reducing morbidity and mortality associated with SBO.\r\n\r\nAim\r\nThe study aimed to assess resistance patterns in central and lateral skull base osteomyelitis due to specific pathogens and to explore the importance of antibiotic stewardship in effectively managing these conditions.\r\n\r\nObjectives\r\nWe aim to explore the prevalent pathogens associated with central and lateral skull base osteomyelitis, focusing on their resistance patterns and the antibiotics utilised for effective treatment.\r\n\r\nMaterials and Methods\r\nThis comprehensive study thoughtfully evaluates 139 patients who visited the ENT outpatient department with symptoms indicative of skull base osteomyelitis. The demographic data and the diabetic status were assessed. Clinical and radiological findings made the diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nIn our comprehensive study of 139 patients, 46 % were diagnosed with central skull base osteomyelitis (CSBO) 13% with lateral skull base osteomyelitis (LSBO), 59% demonstrated maixed-type skull base osteomyelitis. The mean age was 59.8 years. There was a male preponderance, 112 patients accounting for 82.4% of the total skull base osteomyelitis patients. Diabetes Mellitus was a common factor for most patients. The mean HbA1C was 9.8.\r\nMonomicrobial infections constitute approximately 57.25% of the cases, and polymicrobial infections constitute 42.75%. The most common isolated organisms are Pseudomonas (52 cases), CONS (Coagulase-Negative Staphylococci, 27 cases), Staphylococcus Aureus (22 cases), and Aspergillus Flavus (21 cases), among others.\r\nRegarding antibiotic therapy, about 22.57% of cases are susceptible to treatment, while 77.43% show resistance to antibiotic therapy based on the susceptibility data.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nSkull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is a severe infection primarily affecting individuals with compromised immune systems, complicated by the rise of pan-resistant organisms. Effective management relies on culture-directed, broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy tailored to microbiological results. The increasing prevalence of pan-resistant pathogens necessitates exploring antibiotic stewardship and alternative treatment options.', '', 'The sensitvity and resistance pattern of pathogens isolated from Skull Base Osteomyelitis (SBO).', 2, 1, '2025-10-13 21:22:37', '2025-10-13 21:22:41');
