(174, 'Nikhil Solomon Sundara Raj', 'nikhilssr@hotmail.com', 'RHIN0000261', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Background\r\nSkull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is a severe infection primarily affecting individuals with compromised immune systems, complicated by the rise of pan-resistant organisms. Effective management relies on prolonged, culture-directed, broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy tailored to microbiological results. The increasing prevalence of pan-resistant pathogens necessitates exploring alternative treatment options.\r\nTimely diagnosis, culture-directed therapy, and an interdisciplinary approach are crucial to reducing morbidity and mortality associated with SBO.\r\n\r\nAim\r\nThe study aimed to assess resistance patterns in central and lateral skull base osteomyelitis due to specific pathogens and to explore the importance of antibiotic stewardship in effectively managing these conditions.\r\n\r\nObjectives\r\nWe aim to explore the prevalent pathogens associated with central and lateral skull base osteomyelitis, focusing on their resistance patterns and the antibiotics utilised for effective treatment.\r\n\r\nMaterials and Methods\r\nThis comprehensive study thoughtfully evaluates 139 patients who visited the ENT outpatient department with symptoms indicative of skull base osteomyelitis. The demographic data and the diabetic status were assessed. Clinical and radiological findings made the diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nIn our comprehensive study of 139 patients, 46 % were diagnosed with central skull base osteomyelitis (CSBO) 13% with lateral skull base osteomyelitis (LSBO), 59% demonstrated maixed-type skull base osteomyelitis. The mean age was 59.8 years. There was a male preponderance, 112 patients accounting for 82.4% of the total skull base osteomyelitis patients. Diabetes Mellitus was a common factor for most patients. The mean HbA1C was 9.8.\r\nMonomicrobial infections constitute approximately 57.25% of the cases, and polymicrobial infections constitute 42.75%. The most common isolated organisms are Pseudomonas (52 cases), CONS (Coagulase-Negative Staphylococci, 27 cases), Staphylococcus Aureus (22 cases), and Aspergillus Flavus (21 cases), among others.\r\nRegarding antibiotic therapy, about 22.57% of cases are susceptible to treatment, while 77.43% show resistance to antibiotic therapy based on the susceptibility data.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nSkull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is a severe infection primarily affecting individuals with compromised immune systems, complicated by the rise of pan-resistant organisms. Effective management relies on culture-directed, broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy tailored to microbiological results. The increasing prevalence of pan-resistant pathogens necessitates exploring antibiotic stewardship and alternative treatment options.', '', 'The sensitvity and resistance pattern of pathogens isolated from Skull Base Osteomyelitis (SBO).', 2, 1, '2025-10-13 21:22:39', '2025-10-13 21:22:42'),
(175, 'Dr J. JANANI', 'jjanani25395@gmail.com', 'RHIN000047', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim- To report an unusual case of midline nasal swelling in adulthood and to highlight the clinical, radiological and surgical aspects of its management\r\nMethodology: A 25year old male presented with history of slowly progressive painless swelling over the nasal bridge for one year. There was no history of trauma, discharge or nasal obstruction. Clinical examination revealed firm, non-tender, non-fluctuant midline swelling with a sinus opening. Radiological evaluation with CT Sinogram and MRI was suggestive of nasal dermoid with sinus tract with no intracranial extension. Patient was planned for surgical excision under general anesthesia. Complete excision of the lesion was done via external rhinoplasty approach. The specimen was sent for histopathological examination. \r\nResults: Intraoperatively Methylene blue dye was used to delineate the sinus tract. A firm lesion seen extending from nasal dorsum was excised and sent for HPE. Post operative period was uneventful and HPE was suggestive of Nevus Sebaceous of Jadassohn, rather than a dermoid cyst. Follow up for 6 months showed no recurrence.\r\nConclusion – Nevus sebaceous of Jadassohn is a rare hamartomatous lesion commonly seen on the scalp and face but is extremely uncommon in nasal region. Its presentation mimicked a nasal dermoid. Careful clinical assessment, complete surgical excision and thorough histopathological examination were crucial to ensure accurate diagnosis and appropriate management. Post operative follow up is essential to monitor recurrence as well as to detect any malignant transformation.\r\nKey words- Nasal dermoid, Nevus Sebaceous, Histopathology', '', 'Title: A diagnostic surprise: Nevus sebaceous presenting as nasal dermoid.', 2, 1, '2025-10-14 10:24:58', '2025-10-14 10:25:02'),
(176, 'Dr Kune Saphi Pybot', 'drkunesaphi@gmail.com', 'RHIN000083', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Background:\r\nFungal sphenoidal sinusitis complicated by central skull base osteomyelitis is a rare but serious condition, especially in immunocompromised patients. Its diagnosis is challenging as it can masquerade as a primary sellar lesion, particularly when bony erosion is present.\r\nCase Presentation:\r\nA 45-year-old male with type 2 diabetes and hypertension presented with a one-month history of progressive occipital headache, without sinonasal or neurological symptoms. MRI and CT revealed sphenoidal sinus opacification with erosion of the posterior wall and extension toward the sella. The floor of the sella was eroded, obscuring the boundary between the pituitary gland and sphenoid contents—raising suspicion for either a primary sellar lesion or invasive sphenoidal pathology.\r\nGiven the patient’s comorbidities and imaging findings, invasive fungal sinusitis with central skull base osteomyelitis was suspected. Endoscopic transnasal trans-sphenoidal debridement revealed necrotic material in the sphenoid sinus. Histopathology showed chronic nonspecific sinusitis with extensive lymphoid hyperplasia in bone and lymphoplasmacytic infiltrates in mucosa. KOH-Calcofluor staining demonstrated septate fungal filaments and rounded spores. Fungal culture confirmed Aspergillus flavus from both bone and mucosa.\r\nTreatment:\r\nThe patient received oral Posaconazole 200 mg once daily for 3 months, along with Amphotericin B nasal douching for local antifungal effect. Strict glycemic control was concurrently achieved.\r\nFollow-Up:\r\nAt 3-month follow-up, the patient remains asymptomatic with no clinical or endoscopic signs of recurrence. Sphenoidal mucosa appears healthy on examination.\r\nConclusion:\r\nThis case highlights the diagnostic difficulty of invasive fungal sphenoiditis with central skull base osteomyelitis, particularly in diabetic patients where imaging may mimic a sellar lesion. Early clinical suspicion, appropriate imaging, surgical intervention, targeted antifungal therapy followed by stringent long term follow up are essential for successful outcomes.\r\nKeywords: Sphenoidal sinusitis, central skull base osteomyelitis, Aspergillus flavus, invasive fungal sinusitis.', '', 'When Sinusitis Turns Severe: Central Skull Base Osteomyelitis with Fungal Sphenoiditis', 2, 1, '2025-10-14 12:11:07', '2025-10-14 12:11:10'),
(177, 'Akshay Singh', 'akshaysinghheer@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000120', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Central compartment atopic disease (CCAD): Prevalence of atopic manifestations in this phenotype of chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRSwNP)\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Akshay Singh\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical characteristics, atopic profile, histopathological endotypes, and treatment outcomes of CCAD and other CRSwNP subtypes in an Indian tertiary care setting, and to compare these findings with existing literature.\r\nMethods:\r\nIn this prospective observational study, 127 patients with CRSwNP were enrolled between November 2023 and June 2025. Subgroup classification was based on clinical, radiologic, endoscopic, and histologic criteria into CRSwNP (NOS), CRSwNP with central compartment involvement (CRSwNP/CC), Allergic Fungal Rhinosinusitis (AFRS), Aspirin-Exacerbated Respiratory Disease (AERD), and CCAD. Allergen sensitization was assessed using skin prick or specific IgE testing. Eosinophilic infiltration was quantified on histopathology, and symptom severity was measured using the SNOT-22 score pre- and postoperatively.\r\nResults:\r\nMean patient age was 45.2 years, with 56.7% males. CCAD (15.75%) and CRSwNP/CC (37.8%) showed the highest allergy prevalence (100% and 91.7%), with lower asthma rates in CCAD (15%). Mean eosinophil count was 36/HPF. Postoperative SNOT-22 scores improved significantly (mean 54 to 8). No recurrence occurred in CCAD or CRSwNP/CC after targeted therapy, while 20% recurred in the CRSwNP (NOS) group.\r\nConclusion:\r\nCCAD and CRSwNP/CC are distinct, allergy-driven eosinophilic phenotypes of CRSwNP with excellent outcomes following allergen-directed management and surgery. Accurate phenotyping enables individualized treatment and improved prognosis in Indian CRS patients.', '', 'Central compartment atopic disease (CCAD): Prevalence of atopic manifestations in this phenotype of ', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-14 20:08:57', '2025-10-14 20:09:01'),
(178, 'Akshay Singh', 'akshaysinghheer@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000120', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Central compartment atopic disease (CCAD): Prevalence of atopic manifestations in this phenotype of chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRSwNP)\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Akshay Singh\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical characteristics, atopic profile, histopathological endotypes, and treatment outcomes of CCAD and other CRSwNP subtypes in an Indian tertiary care setting, and to compare these findings with existing literature.\r\nMethods:\r\nIn this prospective observational study, 127 patients with CRSwNP were enrolled between November 2023 and June 2025. Subgroup classification was based on clinical, radiologic, endoscopic, and histologic criteria into CRSwNP (NOS), CRSwNP with central compartment involvement (CRSwNP/CC), Allergic Fungal Rhinosinusitis (AFRS), Aspirin-Exacerbated Respiratory Disease (AERD), and CCAD. Allergen sensitization was assessed using skin prick or specific IgE testing. Eosinophilic infiltration was quantified on histopathology, and symptom severity was measured using the SNOT-22 score pre- and postoperatively.\r\nResults:\r\nMean patient age was 45.2 years, with 56.7% males. CCAD (15.75%) and CRSwNP/CC (37.8%) showed the highest allergy prevalence (100% and 91.7%), with lower asthma rates in CCAD (15%). Mean eosinophil count was 36/HPF. Postoperative SNOT-22 scores improved significantly (mean 54 to 8). No recurrence occurred in CCAD or CRSwNP/CC after targeted therapy, while 20% recurred in the CRSwNP (NOS) group.\r\nConclusion:\r\nCCAD and CRSwNP/CC are distinct, allergy-driven eosinophilic phenotypes of CRSwNP with excellent outcomes following allergen-directed management and surgery. Accurate phenotyping enables individualized treatment and improved prognosis in Indian CRS patients.', '', 'Central compartment atopic disease (CCAD): Prevalence of atopic manifestations in this phenotype of ', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-14 20:19:37', '2025-10-14 20:19:40'),
(179, 'SUSHMA SAMPATHKUMAR', 'dr.sushmasampathkumar.2025@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000422', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE :\r\n“Endoscopic Management of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Retrospective Cross-Sectional Study”\r\n\r\nPresenting Author – Dr Sushma Sampathkumar \r\n\r\n Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical presentation, surgical approach, intraoperative techniques, and outcomes of patients with Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma (JNA) managed by endoscopic excision at a tertiary care centre. \r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nThis retrospective cross-sectional study analysed hospital records of patients diagnosed with JNA from 2015 to 2025. Data were collected on demographic details, presenting complaints, radiological and endoscopic findings, surgical methods ,   arterial involvement and postoperative outcomes. \r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll patients were males aged 12–21 years (mean age 19.1 years). The most common presenting complaints were nasal obstruction   and recurrent epistaxis. Radiological evaluation commonly demonstrated vascular masses arising from the sphenopalatine region with extension.. All patients underwent endoscopic JNA excision using   cautery or ligaclip  for hemostasis. The vascular supply was universal  by sphenopalatine artery; internal maxillary contributed in 57% of the cases . Complete excision was achieved in 60% of cases, while 40% required piecemeal removal due to bleeding or extension. Only one case (14%) showed recurrence at 1 year follow-up. \r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic management of JNA provides excellent visualization, effective hemostasis, and favourable postoperative outcomes. Early diagnosis and meticulous endoscopic excision significantly reduce morbidity and recurrence rates.', '', '“Endoscopic Management of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Retrospective Cross-Sectional Stud', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-14 21:38:36', '2025-10-14 21:38:40'),
(180, 'SUSHMA SAMPATHKUMAR', 'dr.sushmasampathkumar.2025@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000422', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE :\r\n“Endoscopic Management of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Retrospective Cross-Sectional Study”\r\n\r\nPresenting Author – Dr Sushma Sampathkumar \r\n\r\n Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical presentation, surgical approach, intraoperative techniques, and outcomes of patients with Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma (JNA) managed by endoscopic excision at a tertiary care centre. \r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nThis retrospective cross-sectional study analysed hospital records of patients diagnosed with JNA from 2015 to 2025. Data were collected on demographic details, presenting complaints, radiological and endoscopic findings, surgical methods ,   arterial involvement and postoperative outcomes. \r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll patients were males aged 12–21 years (mean age 19.1 years). The most common presenting complaints were nasal obstruction   and recurrent epistaxis. Radiological evaluation commonly demonstrated vascular masses arising from the sphenopalatine region with extension.. All patients underwent endoscopic JNA excision using   cautery or ligaclip  for hemostasis. The vascular supply was universal  by sphenopalatine artery; internal maxillary contributed in 57% of the cases . Complete excision was achieved in 60% of cases, while 40% required piecemeal removal due to bleeding or extension. Only one case (14%) showed recurrence at 1 year follow-up. \r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic management of JNA provides excellent visualization, effective hemostasis, and favourable postoperative outcomes. Early diagnosis and meticulous endoscopic excision significantly reduce morbidity and recurrence rates.', '', '“Endoscopic Management of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Retrospective Cross-Sectional Stud', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-14 21:38:38', '2025-10-14 21:38:42'),
(181, 'P. Naga Vikasini', 'vikasini1996@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000421', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'The Hidden Malignancy Behind a Chronic Nasal Discharge: A Rare Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma\r\nAim:\r\nTo report a rare case of sinonasal adenocarcinoma of the intestinal type (ITAC) managed successfully with endoscopic resection and skull base reconstruction, highlighting its clinical presentation, surgical approach, and outcome.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 51-year-old male with a 20-year history of intermittent left-sided nasal discharge, recently blood-stained, was evaluated. Clinical examination and contrast-enhanced MRI revealed a heterogeneously enhancing lobulated mass over the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone with cribriform plate erosion (T3). Endoscopic biopsy confirmed sinonasal adenocarcinoma of the intestinal type. The patient underwent coblator and microdebrider-assisted endoscopic excision of the tumor with bilayered anterior skull base reconstruction using fascia lata, Surgicel, and fibrin glue to prevent CSF leak.\r\nResults:\r\nThe postoperative course was uneventful with good symptomatic improvement. Histopathology confirmed intestinal-type sinonasal adenocarcinoma with chronic inflammation. The patient was advised nasal care and regular follow-up to monitor recurrence. No postoperative complications or CSF leak were observed.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSinonasal adenocarcinoma, though uncommon, should be considered in patients with chronic unilateral nasal symptoms. Early diagnosis and complete endoscopic excision with meticulous skull base reconstruction can provide favorable functional and oncological outcomes.', '', 'The Hidden Malignancy Behind a Chronic Nasal Discharge: A Rare Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma', NULL, '', NULL, 'Hard as Stone – Unveiling the Cemento-Ossifying Fibroma of the Nose (A Rare Case Report)\r\nAim:\r\nTo report a rare case of cemento-ossifying fibroma arising from the nasal septum and to emphasize the importance of early diagnosis and management.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 61-year-old female presented with progressive bilateral nasal obstruction for one year. Nasal endoscopy revealed a hard, pinkish mass arising from the septum. CT scan showed a high-attenuation lesion involving the nasal septum with extension to the ethmoid sinuses. The patient underwent transnasal endoscopic excision, and the specimen was subjected to histopathological evaluation.\r\nResults:\r\nIntraoperatively, a firm, well-defined mass was excised completely. Histopathology demonstrated lamellar bone with cementum-like calcifications and acellular lobulated areas, confirming cemento-ossifying fibroma. Postoperative recovery was uneventful with no recurrence noted on follow-up.\r\nConclusions:\r\nCemento-ossifying fibroma, though benign, can present aggressively when involving the sinonasal tract. Accurate diagnosis and complete surgical excision are crucial to prevent recurrence and ensure favorable outcomes.', '', 'Hard as Stone – Unveiling the Cemento-Ossifying Fibroma of the Nose (A Rare Case Report)', 2, 1, '2025-10-14 21:54:59', '2025-10-14 21:55:03'),
(182, 'Varun Gupta', 'varungupta815@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000423', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'ORBITAL COMPLICATIONS OF SINUSITIS – A REVIEW OF 10 YEARS IN TERTIARY CARE CENTRE\r\n\r\nIntroduction - Orbital complications of sinusitis are serious vision threatening infections that spread from the sinuses into the eye socket that can lead to orbital cellulitis, subperiosteal abscess and orbital abscess. \r\n\r\nAim – To analyze patients who were treated for these complications in the last decade.\r\n\r\nMethodology – Retrospective analysis of 27 patients treated with orbital complications of  sinusitis, between the years 2015 to 2025. The diagnosis was determined based on clinical examination, DNE, CT scans and MRI scans. In all cases, intensive treatment was initiated with FESS with or without Orbital abscess drainage / orbital decompression / optic nerve decompression with IV antibiotics\r\n\r\nResults – In our study, we had 27 cases of orbital complications with an average patients age of 35 years (28days – 70 years). The most common complications were palpebral inflammatory oedema, orbital cellulitis, orbital abscess, optic nerve compression. The average time patient stayed in hospital was 5-7 days.  \r\n\r\nConclusion – Orbital complications of acute rhinosinusitis are common in pediatric age group and in adult its rare. Surgical intervention and aggressive medical management remain the standard to achieve a good prognosis and visual outcome. \r\n\r\nDr. Varun Gupta\r\nRHIN0000423', '', 'ORBITAL COMPLICATIONS OF SINUSITIS – A REVIEW OF 10 YEARS IN TERTIARY CARE CENTRE', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-14 22:05:09', '2025-10-14 22:05:13'),
(183, 'KARTHIKA G', 'karthig1994@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000424', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the efficacy and outcomes of endoscopic repair in patients with cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhoea of various aetiologies.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA retrospective review was conducted on 22 patients who underwent endoscopic repair for CSF rhinorrhoea. The study analysed demographic distribution, aetiology, site, and size of the leak. Conservative management was attempted in selected cases prior to surgical intervention. All patients underwent defect closure using multi-layered grafting techniques, with postoperative management focused on reducing intracranial pressure and preventing recurrence.\r\nResults:\r\nAmong 22 patients studied, traumatic and iatrogenic aetiologies accounted for most cases, while idiopathic leaks were less common. The ethmoid and sphenoid regions were frequent sites of leakage. Endoscopic multilayer repair achieved a primary success rate of 90%, with no major postoperative complications or recurrence. The middle turbinate was preserved intact in all cases, maintaining normal nasal anatomy and function. Use of cartilage, fat, fascia, tissue glue, vascularized flaps, including the Hadad flap, provided robust closure in larger defects.\r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic repair is a safe, minimally invasive with intact middle turbinate, and highly effective technique for managing CSF rhinorrhoea. It offers superior visualization, reduced morbidity, and high success rates, making it the preferred method for most skull base leaks.', '', 'Endoscopic Repair of CSF Rhinorrhoea – A Review of Its Efficacy and Success Rate', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 00:21:10', '2025-10-15 00:21:14'),
(184, 'Dr Monica J', 'mons.jawa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000254', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'OCULAR MANIFESTATIONS AS KEY TO SINUS DIAGNOSIS\r\n \r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:\r\nDR. MONICA. J\r\nPOST GRADUATE\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nGUIDE:\r\nPROF. DR. M.K. RAJASEKAR  \r\nPROFESSOR AND HEAD OF DEPARTMENT OF ENT\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nAIM:\r\nTo highlight the importance of early recognition and prompt management of sinusitis in uncontrolled diabetic patients, emphasizing the risk of silent orbital complications and potential progression to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\n \r\nMETHODOLOGY:\r\nStudy Design: Descriptive case-based presentation of two diabetic patients with sinusitis and orbital complications.\r\nPatient Selection: Uncontrolled diabetic patients presenting with orbital signs and minimal or no nasal symptoms.\r\nClinical Evaluation: Detailed history taking and ophthalmological/ENT examination.\r\nInvestigations: Imaging with CT and MRI of paranasal sinuses and orbit to identify extent of disease.\r\nManagement Approach: Referral from ophthalmology to ENT, medical optimization of diabetes, and appropriate antifungal/antibacterial therapy with surgical intervention where indicated.\r\nOutcome Assessment: Observation of clinical response and complications during hospital stay and follow-up.\r\nRESULTS:  \r\nEarly ENT intervention and glycemic control led to stabilization of orbital findings and prevention of acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nUncontrolled diabetic patients with sinusitis, when not treated promptly, often develop orbital complications despite having no nasal symptoms. Diagnosis is usually established only after CT or MRI imaging. Both patients were referred to the ENT department from ophthalmology based on CT and MRI findings.\r\nThe underlying cause is typically sinusitis affecting the posterior group of sinuses. It is not always invasive fungal sinusitis; non-invasive fungal or bacterial sinusitis can also be responsible. In diabetic patients, even a minor orbital syndrome can rapidly progress to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.', '', 'Ocular manifestations as key to sinus diagnosis', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 06:22:02', '2025-10-15 06:22:06'),
