rior group of sinuses. It is not always invasive fungal sinusitis; non-invasive fungal or bacterial sinusitis can also be responsible. In diabetic patients, even a minor orbital syndrome can rapidly progress to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.', '', 'Ocular manifestations as key to sinus diagnosis', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 06:22:03', '2025-10-15 06:22:07'),
(186, 'Dr Monica J', 'mons.jawa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000254', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'OCULAR MANIFESTATIONS AS KEY TO SINUS DIAGNOSIS\r\n \r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:\r\nDR. MONICA. J\r\nPOST GRADUATE\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nGUIDE:\r\nPROF. DR. M.K. RAJASEKAR  \r\nPROFESSOR AND HEAD OF DEPARTMENT OF ENT\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nAIM:\r\nTo highlight the importance of early recognition and prompt management of sinusitis in uncontrolled diabetic patients, emphasizing the risk of silent orbital complications and potential progression to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\n \r\nMETHODOLOGY:\r\nStudy Design: Descriptive case-based presentation of two diabetic patients with sinusitis and orbital complications.\r\nPatient Selection: Uncontrolled diabetic patients presenting with orbital signs and minimal or no nasal symptoms.\r\nClinical Evaluation: Detailed history taking and ophthalmological/ENT examination.\r\nInvestigations: Imaging with CT and MRI of paranasal sinuses and orbit to identify extent of disease.\r\nManagement Approach: Referral from ophthalmology to ENT, medical optimization of diabetes, and appropriate antifungal/antibacterial therapy with surgical intervention where indicated.\r\nOutcome Assessment: Observation of clinical response and complications during hospital stay and follow-up.\r\nRESULTS:  \r\nEarly ENT intervention and glycemic control led to stabilization of orbital findings and prevention of acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nUncontrolled diabetic patients with sinusitis, when not treated promptly, often develop orbital complications despite having no nasal symptoms. Diagnosis is usually established only after CT or MRI imaging. Both patients were referred to the ENT department from ophthalmology based on CT and MRI findings.\r\nThe underlying cause is typically sinusitis affecting the poste