(187, 'Dr Monica J', 'mons.jawa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000254', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'OCULAR MANIFESTATIONS AS KEY TO SINUS DIAGNOSIS\r\n \r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:\r\nDR. MONICA. J\r\nPOST GRADUATE\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nGUIDE:\r\nPROF. DR. M.K. RAJASEKAR  \r\nPROFESSOR AND HEAD OF DEPARTMENT OF ENT\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nAIM:\r\nTo highlight the importance of early recognition and prompt management of sinusitis in uncontrolled diabetic patients, emphasizing the risk of silent orbital complications and potential progression to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\n \r\nMETHODOLOGY:\r\nStudy Design: Descriptive case-based presentation of two diabetic patients with sinusitis and orbital complications.\r\nPatient Selection: Uncontrolled diabetic patients presenting with orbital signs and minimal or no nasal symptoms.\r\nClinical Evaluation: Detailed history taking and ophthalmological/ENT examination.\r\nInvestigations: Imaging with CT and MRI of paranasal sinuses and orbit to identify extent of disease.\r\nManagement Approach: Referral from ophthalmology to ENT, medical optimization of diabetes, and appropriate antifungal/antibacterial therapy with surgical intervention where indicated.\r\nOutcome Assessment: Observation of clinical response and complications during hospital stay and follow-up.\r\nRESULTS:  \r\nEarly ENT intervention and glycemic control led to stabilization of orbital findings and prevention of acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nUncontrolled diabetic patients with sinusitis, when not treated promptly, often develop orbital complications despite having no nasal symptoms. Diagnosis is usually established only after CT or MRI imaging. Both patients were referred to the ENT department from ophthalmology based on CT and MRI findings.\r\nThe underlying cause is typically sinusitis affecting the posterior group of sinuses. It is not always invasive fungal sinusitis; non-invasive fungal or bacterial sinusitis can also be responsible. In diabetic patients, even a minor orbital syndrome can rapidly progress to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.', '', 'Ocular manifestations as key to sinus diagnosis', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 06:22:06', '2025-10-15 06:22:09'),
(188, 'DR ARYA V', 'aryaachutham@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000417', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE :A STUDY TO COMPARE THE EFFICACY OF BUDESONIDE NASAL SPRAY  MOMETASONE NASAL SPRAY IN ALLERGIC RHINTIS\r\nPresenting Author : Dr Arya V \r\nAim: \r\n1.To  compare the efficacy of intranasal budesonide and intranasal mometasone furoate in patients diagnosed with allergic rhinitis. \r\n2.To compare the safety of intranasal budesonide and intranasal mometasone furoate in patients diagnosed with allergic rhinitis.\r\nMethodology :\r\n Patients diagnosed with allergic rhinitis who reported to the ENT department at MVJ Medical College and Hospital were randomly assigned to two groups. Group A (n=50) received budesonide nasal spray at a dosage of 400 μg twice daily, while Group B (n=50) was administered 200 μg of mometasone furoate nasal spray twice daily. Symptom severity was evaluated using the Total Nasal Symptom Score (TNSS) at the 2nd, 4th, and 6th weeks.\r\nResult :\r\nBoth groups showed a marked decrease in TNSS scores; however, the budesonide group exhibited a significantly greater reduction than the mometasone furoate group starting from the fourth week, which continued through the sixth week.\r\nConclusion : \r\nBudesonide nasal spray demonstrated greater effectiveness than mometasone furoate in controlling nasal symptoms associated with allergic rhinitis.', '', 'A STUDY TO COMPARE THE EFFICACY OF BUDESONIDE NASAL SPRAY  MOMETASONE NASAL SPRAY IN ALLERGIC RHINTI', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 09:41:10', '2025-10-15 09:41:13'),
(189, 'AJJAI A', 'ajjaiamudhan@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000245', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim To highlight a rare presentation of nasopharyngeal carcinoma (NPC) as isolated otologic symptoms, emphasizing the necessity of complete nasopharyngeal evaluation in adults with persistent unilateral ear complaints.\r\n\r\nMethodology A 50-year-old male presented with six months of right ear pain and fullness. Previous evaluations at multiple centers revealed only a minimal bulge in the tympanic membrane, and mastoidectomy was planned. At our institute, CT imaging identified a soft-tissue mass in the right fossa of Rosenmüller. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy confirmed a bulge in the nasopharynx. The patient underwent coblation-assisted biopsy under general anesthesia, along with grommet insertion for middle ear ventilation.\r\n\r\nResults Histopathology revealed non-keratinizing nasopharyngeal carcinoma. The patient received postoperative chemoradiotherapy. At follow-up, otologic symptoms resolved, and the patient remains clinically well.\r\n\r\nConclusion Persistent unilateral otalgia or middle ear effusion in adults, even without nasal symptoms, should prompt thorough nasopharyngeal evaluation. Early detection of occult NPC prevents misdiagnosis, avoids unnecessary surgery, and ensures timely oncological management. This case reinforces the principle: in ENT, the ear may be the first sign of a hidden nasopharyngeal malignancy.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Nasopharyngeal carcinoma, Otalgia, Fossa of Rosenmüller, Middle ear effusion, Diagnostic nasal endoscopy', '', 'Missed the Bus: An Unexpected Turnaround in a Case of Hidden Nasopharyngeal Malignancy', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 10:42:18', '2025-10-15 10:42:21'),
(190, 'AJJAI A', 'ajjaiamudhan@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000245', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim To highlight a rare presentation of nasopharyngeal carcinoma (NPC) as isolated otologic symptoms, emphasizing the necessity of complete nasopharyngeal evaluation in adults with persistent unilateral ear complaints.\r\n\r\nMethodology A 50-year-old male presented with six months of right ear pain and fullness. Previous evaluations at multiple centers revealed only a minimal bulge in the tympanic membrane, and mastoidectomy was planned. At our institute, CT imaging identified a soft-tissue mass in the right fossa of Rosenmüller. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy confirmed a bulge in the nasopharynx. The patient underwent coblation-assisted biopsy under general anesthesia, along with grommet insertion for middle ear ventilation.\r\n\r\nResults Histopathology revealed non-keratinizing nasopharyngeal carcinoma. The patient received postoperative chemoradiotherapy. At follow-up, otologic symptoms resolved, and the patient remains clinically well.\r\n\r\nConclusion Persistent unilateral otalgia or middle ear effusion in adults, even without nasal symptoms, should prompt thorough nasopharyngeal evaluation. Early detection of occult NPC prevents misdiagnosis, avoids unnecessary surgery, and ensures timely oncological management. This case reinforces the principle: in ENT, the ear may be the first sign of a hidden nasopharyngeal malignancy.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Nasopharyngeal carcinoma, Otalgia, Fossa of Rosenmüller, Middle ear effusion, Diagnostic nasal endoscopy', '', 'Missed the Bus: An Unexpected Turnaround in a Case of Hidden Nasopharyngeal Malignancy', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 10:42:21', '2025-10-15 10:42:24'),
(191, 'GAYATHRI BHASKARAN', 'gayathri.tilapu@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000206', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction:Angiofibroma is a benign yet highly vascular tumor that predominantly affects adolescent males. Its occurrence in the elderly is exceptionally rare and often presents a formidable diagnostic challenge, particularly when clinical manifestations overlap with more common sinonasal pathologies. We present an unusual case of maxillary sinus angiofibroma (NA) in an elderly male following facial trauma, with clinical features mimicking both fungal rhinosinusitis and post-traumatic sequelae.\r\nCase Presentation:A 70-year-old male with a history of blunt facial trauma two months prior presented with progressive right-sided nasal obstruction and recurrent, severe epistaxis of two months’ duration. He also developed right cheek swelling over the preceding two days. Computed Tomography (CT) of the paranasal sinuses demonstrated an enhancing soft-tissue mass occupying the right maxillary sinus and extending into the nasal cavity, with evidence of intrasinus hyperattenuation and bony remodeling—initially suggestive of chronic fungal rhinosinusitis. However, the patient\'s advanced age, persistent bleeding, and antecedent trauma created a diagnostic dilemma.\r\nDiagnosis and Management:Given the lesion’s hemorrhagic nature and discordant clinical–radiological features, surgical exploration was undertaken. Intraoperatively, a highly vascular, friable mass with extensive organized clots filled the right maxillary sinus and nasal cavity. A right medial maxillectomy was performed, and histopathological examination revealed a fibrous stroma containing numerous, irregularly arranged blood vessels—findings consistent with angiofibroma. The postoperative course was uneventful, with only minor episodes of epistaxis managed conservatively. No recurrence was noted on follow-up.\r\nConclusion:This case underscores the exceptional rarity of angiofibroma in the elderly and illustrates how antecedent trauma and overlapping clinical features can obscure diagnosis. It emphasizes the necessity of maintaining a broad differential for sinonasal masses, even when imaging mimics more common entities such as fungal disease. In atypical presentations, intraoperative tissue diagnosis remains indispensable for establishing a definitive diagnosis.', '', 'Rhino Rara Avis -Seep…..A Case Report', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 11:09:18', '2025-10-15 11:09:21'),
(192, 'GAYATHRI BHASKARAN', 'gayathri.tilapu@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000206', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction:Angiofibroma is a benign yet highly vascular tumor that predominantly affects adolescent males. Its occurrence in the elderly is exceptionally rare and often presents a formidable diagnostic challenge, particularly when clinical manifestations overlap with more common sinonasal pathologies. We present an unusual case of maxillary sinus angiofibroma (NA) in an elderly male following facial trauma, with clinical features mimicking both fungal rhinosinusitis and post-traumatic sequelae.\r\nCase Presentation:A 70-year-old male with a history of blunt facial trauma two months prior presented with progressive right-sided nasal obstruction and recurrent, severe epistaxis of two months’ duration. He also developed right cheek swelling over the preceding two days. Computed Tomography (CT) of the paranasal sinuses demonstrated an enhancing soft-tissue mass occupying the right maxillary sinus and extending into the nasal cavity, with evidence of intrasinus hyperattenuation and bony remodeling—initially suggestive of chronic fungal rhinosinusitis. However, the patient\'s advanced age, persistent bleeding, and antecedent trauma created a diagnostic dilemma.\r\nDiagnosis and Management:Given the lesion’s hemorrhagic nature and discordant clinical–radiological features, surgical exploration was undertaken. Intraoperatively, a highly vascular, friable mass with extensive organized clots filled the right maxillary sinus and nasal cavity. A right medial maxillectomy was performed, and histopathological examination revealed a fibrous stroma containing numerous, irregularly arranged blood vessels—findings consistent with angiofibroma. The postoperative course was uneventful, with only minor episodes of epistaxis managed conservatively. No recurrence was noted on follow-up.\r\nConclusion:This case underscores the exceptional rarity of angiofibroma in the elderly and illustrates how antecedent trauma and overlapping clinical features can obscure diagnosis. It emphasizes the necessity of maintaining a broad differential for sinonasal masses, even when imaging mimics more common entities such as fungal disease. In atypical presentations, intraoperative tissue diagnosis remains indispensable for establishing a definitive diagnosis.', '', 'Rhino Rara Avis -Seep…..A Case Report', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 11:09:19', '2025-10-15 11:09:23'),
(193, 'DR ARYA V', 'aryaachutham@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000417', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE :BEYOND THE USUAL EPISTAXIS: SEPTAL LOBULAR CAPILLARY HEMANGIOMA IN A CHILD\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR : DR ARYA V\r\nABSTRACT\r\nAIM: Lobular capillary hemangioma (LCH) is a benign proliferative vascular tumor originating from the skin and mucosal membranes with the tendency to bleed. In head and neck region LCH is commonly located in oral cavity but rarely found in the nasal cavity. The study is aimed to know in detail the rare case presentation \r\nMETHODOLOGY :We present a case of 7 year old girl with LCH of the nasal cavity presenting with nasal obstruction and epistaxis. Examination through anterior rhinoscopy revealed polypoidal mass occupying the left side of nasal cavity on the septum which was red in colour. The patient successfully underwent surgical excision without pre-operative embolization \r\nRESULT : Child underwent endonasal endoscopic excision of polypoidal mass under short general anesthesia. The entire mass was resected and the apparent pedicle was cauterised with bipolar diathermy (figure 3a and 3b). Mass was later sent for histopathological examination. Anterior nasal packing was done for 24 hours and later removed and discharged the child.Histological examination revealed findings typical of LCH\r\nCONCLUSION: Lobular capillary hemangioma (LCH) of the nasal cavity is a rare, benign vascular lesion that should be considered in the differential diagnosis of intranasal masses, especially in children. In literature, only nine cases of hemangioma of nasal cavities have been reported in children since 1985.', '', 'BEYOND THE USUAL EPISTAXIS: SEPTAL LOBULAR CAPILLARY HEMANGIOMA IN A CHILD', NULL, '', NULL, 'Dr.Arya V,aryaachutham@gmail.com,Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session,Registration Number : RHIN0000417\r\nTITLE : “POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE\r\nBACKGROUND: Oncocytic papilloma is a rare, benign tumor originating from the Schneiderian membrane (lining) of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses.This is rarest form of sinonasal papilloma with an incidence of 0.5 to 1.5 cases per 100,000 people per year.\r\nCASE REPORT:A 63 year old male with no relevant past medical history presented to otorhinolaryngology clinic with 5 years history of  bilateral nasal obstruction and snoring and 2 months history of recurrent episodes of nasal bleeds. Anterior rhinoscopy showed multiple pale polypoidal glistening masses with probe passed all around, non tender, not bleed on touch in right nasal cavity and posterior rhinoscopy showed -Pale glistening polypoidal mass noted covering both choana posteriorly extending upto the oropharynx.NCCT PNS was showing diffuse extensive mucosal thickening and near total soft tissue opacification of the right maxillary sinus and the ethmoid complexes on both sides ,that appears merging with the nasal turbinates with near total obliteration of the nasal cavity ,widening the right maxillary ostium ,the soft tissue density is also seen extending to the left choana ,obliteration of right osteomeatal complex -features suggestive of sino-nasal polyposis.Under General anesthesia FESS + Septoplasty was done and specimen was send for Histopathological evaluation.HPE shown features suggestive of sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type (ICD 10 CODE D14.0)\r\nCONCLUSION: Sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type extremely rare condition. Accurate diagnosis and appropriate surgical management are crucial for favorable outcome in such cases. Complete surgical excision through endoscopic surgery or open radical procedure is the treatment of choice; lateral rhinotomy and medial maxillectomy may be required.  Histopathological investigations play a pivotal role to arrive at the final diagnosis and exclude malignancy.', '', 'TITLE : “POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 11:39:05', '2025-10-15 11:39:08');
