(194, 'DR ARYA V', 'aryaachutham@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000417', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE :BEYOND THE USUAL EPISTAXIS: SEPTAL LOBULAR CAPILLARY HEMANGIOMA IN A CHILD\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR : DR ARYA V\r\nABSTRACT\r\nAIM: Lobular capillary hemangioma (LCH) is a benign proliferative vascular tumor originating from the skin and mucosal membranes with the tendency to bleed. In head and neck region LCH is commonly located in oral cavity but rarely found in the nasal cavity. The study is aimed to know in detail the rare case presentation \r\nMETHODOLOGY :We present a case of 7 year old girl with LCH of the nasal cavity presenting with nasal obstruction and epistaxis. Examination through anterior rhinoscopy revealed polypoidal mass occupying the left side of nasal cavity on the septum which was red in colour. The patient successfully underwent surgical excision without pre-operative embolization \r\nRESULT : Child underwent endonasal endoscopic excision of polypoidal mass under short general anesthesia. The entire mass was resected and the apparent pedicle was cauterised with bipolar diathermy (figure 3a and 3b). Mass was later sent for histopathological examination. Anterior nasal packing was done for 24 hours and later removed and discharged the child.Histological examination revealed findings typical of LCH\r\nCONCLUSION: Lobular capillary hemangioma (LCH) of the nasal cavity is a rare, benign vascular lesion that should be considered in the differential diagnosis of intranasal masses, especially in children. In literature, only nine cases of hemangioma of nasal cavities have been reported in children since 1985.', '', 'BEYOND THE USUAL EPISTAXIS: SEPTAL LOBULAR CAPILLARY HEMANGIOMA IN A CHILD', NULL, '', NULL, 'Dr.Arya V,aryaachutham@gmail.com,Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session,Registration Number : RHIN0000417\r\nTITLE : “POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE\r\nBACKGROUND: Oncocytic papilloma is a rare, benign tumor originating from the Schneiderian membrane (lining) of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses.This is rarest form of sinonasal papilloma with an incidence of 0.5 to 1.5 cases per 100,000 people per year.\r\nCASE REPORT:A 63 year old male with no relevant past medical history presented to otorhinolaryngology clinic with 5 years history of  bilateral nasal obstruction and snoring and 2 months history of recurrent episodes of nasal bleeds. Anterior rhinoscopy showed multiple pale polypoidal glistening masses with probe passed all around, non tender, not bleed on touch in right nasal cavity and posterior rhinoscopy showed -Pale glistening polypoidal mass noted covering both choana posteriorly extending upto the oropharynx.NCCT PNS was showing diffuse extensive mucosal thickening and near total soft tissue opacification of the right maxillary sinus and the ethmoid complexes on both sides ,that appears merging with the nasal turbinates with near total obliteration of the nasal cavity ,widening the right maxillary ostium ,the soft tissue density is also seen extending to the left choana ,obliteration of right osteomeatal complex -features suggestive of sino-nasal polyposis.Under General anesthesia FESS + Septoplasty was done and specimen was send for Histopathological evaluation.HPE shown features suggestive of sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type (ICD 10 CODE D14.0)\r\nCONCLUSION: Sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type extremely rare condition. Accurate diagnosis and appropriate surgical management are crucial for favorable outcome in such cases. Complete surgical excision through endoscopic surgery or open radical procedure is the treatment of choice; lateral rhinotomy and medial maxillectomy may be required.  Histopathological investigations play a pivotal role to arrive at the final diagnosis and exclude malignancy.', '', 'TITLE : “POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 11:39:07', '2025-10-15 11:39:10'),
(195, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr Rimjhim Sharma \r\n\r\nAim: The present study aimed to evaluate the clinical outcomes of endonasal endoscopic DCR in patients with nasolacrimal duct obstruction (NLDO) treated at a peripheral health centre.\r\n\r\nMethodology: A total of 98 patients with symptomatic nasolacrimal duct obstruction, confirmed by syringing, were included in this prospective study after obtaining informed consent. Patients with a history of trauma, canalicular obstruction, nasal polyps, or previously failed DCR were excluded. Postoperative follow-ups were conducted on day 1, at 1 week, 3 weeks, and 3 months. Surgical success was defined as the absence of symptoms and freely patent syringing at the final follow-up, while persistent symptoms with regurgitation on syringing were considered indicative of failure.\r\n\r\nResults: Of the 98 operated cases, lacrimal patency was maintained in 93.88% (n=92) on day 1, 90.82% (n=89) at 1 week, 94.90% (n=93) at 3 weeks, and 96.94% (n=95) at 3 months. Hence, success rate in our study was found to be 96.94%. Only three patients (3.06% of 98) remained symptomatic at the end of the 3-month follow-up period and were classified as failures. The most common postoperative complications were granuloma formation in 9 patients (9.18%), localized infection in 6 patients (6.12%), and intranasal synechiae in 5 patients 5.10% of cases. Notably, no instances of wound dehiscence, orbital fat prolapse, cerebrospinal fluid leak, or delayed hemorrhage were observed.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Endonasal endoscopic DCR offers a highly effective, minimally invasive alternative to conventional external DCR. It provides superior cosmetic outcomes, reduced surgical morbidity, shorter operative time, and faster postoperative recovery. The high success rate and low incidence of complications in this study highlight that, even in a peripheral healthcare setting, endonasal endoscopic DCR can be performed safely and efficiently, yielding outcomes comparable to those achieved in tertiary care centres.', '', 'Title: Outcomes of Endonasal Endoscopic Dacryocystorhinostomy in a Peripheral Health Centre: Our Exp', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 12:15:22', '2025-10-15 12:15:26'),
(196, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr Rimjhim Sharma \r\n\r\nAim: The present study aimed to evaluate the clinical outcomes of endonasal endoscopic DCR in patients with nasolacrimal duct obstruction (NLDO) treated at a peripheral health centre.\r\n\r\nMethodology: A total of 98 patients with symptomatic nasolacrimal duct obstruction, confirmed by syringing, were included in this prospective study after obtaining informed consent. Patients with a history of trauma, canalicular obstruction, nasal polyps, or previously failed DCR were excluded. Postoperative follow-ups were conducted on day 1, at 1 week, 3 weeks, and 3 months. Surgical success was defined as the absence of symptoms and freely patent syringing at the final follow-up, while persistent symptoms with regurgitation on syringing were considered indicative of failure.\r\n\r\nResults: Of the 98 operated cases, lacrimal patency was maintained in 93.88% (n=92) on day 1, 90.82% (n=89) at 1 week, 94.90% (n=93) at 3 weeks, and 96.94% (n=95) at 3 months. Hence, success rate in our study was found to be 96.94%. Only three patients (3.06% of 98) remained symptomatic at the end of the 3-month follow-up period and were classified as failures. The most common postoperative complications were granuloma formation in 9 patients (9.18%), localized infection in 6 patients (6.12%), and intranasal synechiae in 5 patients 5.10% of cases. Notably, no instances of wound dehiscence, orbital fat prolapse, cerebrospinal fluid leak, or delayed hemorrhage were observed.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Endonasal endoscopic DCR offers a highly effective, minimally invasive alternative to conventional external DCR. It provides superior cosmetic outcomes, reduced surgical morbidity, shorter operative time, and faster postoperative recovery. The high success rate and low incidence of complications in this study highlight that, even in a peripheral healthcare setting, endonasal endoscopic DCR can be performed safely and efficiently, yielding outcomes comparable to those achieved in tertiary care centres.', '', 'Title: Outcomes of Endonasal Endoscopic Dacryocystorhinostomy in a Peripheral Health Centre: Our Exp', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 12:15:25', '2025-10-15 12:15:28'),
(197, 'Akshay Singh', 'akshaysinghheer@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000120', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space\r\n\r\nPresenting author : Dr. Akshay Singh\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe a rare case of sinonasal myxoma in an adult male, outlining the clinical features, radiological findings, histopathological confirmation, and management, while emphasizing the importance of early recognition and complete excision in such uncommon lesions.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 46-year-old male farmer presented with complaints of nasal obstruction and reduced sense of smell for seven months, which began on the right side and gradually involved the left. He also reported foul-smelling, nasal discharge, loss of taste, and bilateral aural fullness. On examination, there was a left-sided deviated nasal septum and a right-sided nasal mass. CECT of the paranasal sinuses showed a heterogeneously enhancing soft tissue lesion measuring 60 × 27 × 45 mm in the right nasal cavity, extending into the nasopharynx. The mass caused erosion of the nasal septum and medial wall of the right maxillary sinus with mild invasion, while the cribriform plate remained intact and no intracranial extension was seen. The lesion was completely excised endoscopically. Histopathological examination revealed abundant myxoid stroma containing scattered spindle-shaped cells without atypia, confirming the diagnosis of sinonasal myxoma. The postoperative course was uneventful, and no recurrence was noted on follow-up. \r\nResults:\r\nA 46-year-old male presented with progressive nasal obstruction and hyposmia. Imaging revealed a right nasal cavity mass with septal and turbinate erosion. Endoscopic excision confirmed sinonasal myxoma; management and recovery was uneventful.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSinonasal myxoma is an extremely rare benign tumor that can mimic other nasal masses. Despite its benign nature, it may be locally invasive. Accurate diagnosis and complete surgical removal are essential for preventing recurrence and ensuring good long-term outcomes.', '', 'Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 12:19:11', '2025-10-15 12:19:15'),
(198, 'Akshay Singh', 'akshaysinghheer@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000120', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space\r\n\r\nPresenting author : Dr. Akshay Singh\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe a rare case of sinonasal myxoma in an adult male, outlining the clinical features, radiological findings, histopathological confirmation, and management, while emphasizing the importance of early recognition and complete excision in such uncommon lesions.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 46-year-old male farmer presented with complaints of nasal obstruction and reduced sense of smell for seven months, which began on the right side and gradually involved the left. He also reported foul-smelling, nasal discharge, loss of taste, and bilateral aural fullness. On examination, there was a left-sided deviated nasal septum and a right-sided nasal mass. CECT of the paranasal sinuses showed a heterogeneously enhancing soft tissue lesion measuring 60 × 27 × 45 mm in the right nasal cavity, extending into the nasopharynx. The mass caused erosion of the nasal septum and medial wall of the right maxillary sinus with mild invasion, while the cribriform plate remained intact and no intracranial extension was seen. The lesion was completely excised endoscopically. Histopathological examination revealed abundant myxoid stroma containing scattered spindle-shaped cells without atypia, confirming the diagnosis of sinonasal myxoma. The postoperative course was uneventful, and no recurrence was noted on follow-up. \r\nResults:\r\nA 46-year-old male presented with progressive nasal obstruction and hyposmia. Imaging revealed a right nasal cavity mass with septal and turbinate erosion. Endoscopic excision confirmed sinonasal myxoma; management and recovery was uneventful.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSinonasal myxoma is an extremely rare benign tumor that can mimic other nasal masses. Despite its benign nature, it may be locally invasive. Accurate diagnosis and complete surgical removal are essential for preventing recurrence and ensuring good long-term outcomes.', '', 'Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 12:19:14', '2025-10-15 12:19:17'),
(199, 'Akshay Singh', 'akshaysinghheer@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000120', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space\r\n\r\nPresenting author : Dr. Akshay Singh\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe a rare case of sinonasal myxoma in an adult male, outlining the clinical features, radiological findings, histopathological confirmation, and management, while emphasizing the importance of early recognition and complete excision in such uncommon lesions.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 46-year-old male farmer presented with complaints of nasal obstruction and reduced sense of smell for seven months, which began on the right side and gradually involved the left. He also reported foul-smelling, nasal discharge, loss of taste, and bilateral aural fullness. On examination, there was a left-sided deviated nasal septum and a right-sided nasal mass. CECT of the paranasal sinuses showed a heterogeneously enhancing soft tissue lesion measuring 60 × 27 × 45 mm in the right nasal cavity, extending into the nasopharynx. The mass caused erosion of the nasal septum and medial wall of the right maxillary sinus with mild invasion, while the cribriform plate remained intact and no intracranial extension was seen. The lesion was completely excised endoscopically. Histopathological examination revealed abundant myxoid stroma containing scattered spindle-shaped cells without atypia, confirming the diagnosis of sinonasal myxoma. The postoperative course was uneventful, and no recurrence was noted on follow-up. \r\nResults:\r\nA 46-year-old male presented with progressive nasal obstruction and hyposmia. Imaging revealed a right nasal cavity mass with septal and turbinate erosion. Endoscopic excision confirmed sinonasal myxoma; management and recovery was uneventful.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSinonasal myxoma is an extremely rare benign tumor that can mimic other nasal masses. Despite its benign nature, it may be locally invasive. Accurate diagnosis and complete surgical removal are essential for preventing recurrence and ensuring good long-term outcomes.', '', 'Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 12:19:15', '2025-10-15 12:19:18'),
(200, 'Dr RIMJHIM SHARMA', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim: To identify the predominant allergens responsible for sensitization in patients with allergic rhinitis in our region.\r\n\r\nMethodology: A prospective 12-month study was conducted among patients with clinical features of allergic rhinitis at Shri Mata Vaishno Devi institute of medical excellence, kakryal. Proper informed consent was taken from all the participants. Participants received counselling on allergic rhinitis and the skin prick test (SPT) procedure. Standardized allergen extracts were applied at 2 cm intervals using a 1 mm lancet. A positive response was defined as a wheal at least 3 mm larger than the saline control.\r\n\r\nResults: A total of 215 patients underwent skin prick testing, comprising 64.65%(n=139) males and 35.35%(n=76) females. Patients mostly belonged to age group between 20 and 40 years of age. Sensitization was most frequently observed to dust mites (78.6%, n=169), followed by pollens (49.77%, n=107), insects (46.05%, n=99), moulds (40%, n=86), food allergens (6.51%, n=14), and animal dander (2.32%, n=5).\r\n\r\nConclusion: The distribution of allergen sensitization varies across regions. In our study, dust mite sensitization was predominant, likely due to local climatic conditions that promote the use of carpets and room heaters, creating an environment conducive to dust mite proliferation.', '', 'Trends in Allergen Sensitization Among Patients with Allergic Rhinitis in Our Region', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 13:00:24', '2025-10-15 13:00:28'),
(201, 'Dr RIMJHIM SHARMA', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim: To identify the predominant allergens responsible for sensitization in patients with allergic rhinitis in our region.\r\n\r\nMethodology: A prospective 12-month study was conducted among patients with clinical features of allergic rhinitis at Shri Mata Vaishno Devi institute of medical excellence, kakryal. Proper informed consent was taken from all the participants. Participants received counselling on allergic rhinitis and the skin prick test (SPT) procedure. Standardized allergen extracts were applied at 2 cm intervals using a 1 mm lancet. A positive response was defined as a wheal at least 3 mm larger than the saline control.\r\n\r\nResults: A total of 215 patients underwent skin prick testing, comprising 64.65%(n=139) males and 35.35%(n=76) females. Patients mostly belonged to age group between 20 and 40 years of age. Sensitization was most frequently observed to dust mites (78.6%, n=169), followed by pollens (49.77%, n=107), insects (46.05%, n=99), moulds (40%, n=86), food allergens (6.51%, n=14), and animal dander (2.32%, n=5).\r\n\r\nConclusion: The distribution of allergen sensitization varies across regions. In our study, dust mite sensitization was predominant, likely due to local climatic conditions that promote the use of carpets and room heaters, creating an environment conducive to dust mite proliferation.', '', 'Trends in Allergen Sensitization Among Patients with Allergic Rhinitis in Our Region', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 13:04:41', '2025-10-15 13:04:44'),
(204, 'DR.AYUSHI', 'ayushiashu655@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000128', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of paper: Effectiveness of Oral Saline Gargling in Postnasal Drip Syndrome ( upper airway cough syndrome).\r\n\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ayushi\r\n\r\nAffiliation: Department of ENT, GMC, Jammu\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the correlation between endoscopic findings and symptom severity in patients with postnasal drip syndrome (PNDS) without cough, and to assess the effectiveness of oral saline gargling as a therapeutic option.\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION: \r\nPostnasal drip syndrome (PNDS) is among the most common yet often misunderstood rhinological complaints. It presents as a persistent sensation of mucus trickling into the throat, sometimes causing irritation or globus feeling without any cough or evident sinonasal disease. Although traditionally linked to rhinosinus disorders and upper airway cough syndrome, PNDS can occur independently when symptom severity does not correlate with endoscopic findings. Abnormal mucus viscosity, altered mucociliary clearance, and sensory hypersensitivity may contribute to this condition. This study aimed to evaluate the association between endoscopic findings and symptom scores and to assess the role of oral saline gargling as a simple therapeutic option.\r\n\r\nMethods:\r\nA retrospective observational study was conducted on patients presenting with isolated postnasal discharge and no associated cough or sinonasal disease. All participants performed isotonic saline oral gargling for twelve weeks. The Sino-Nasal Outcome Test-22 (SNOT-22) and Postnasal Drip Symptom Score (PNDSS) were recorded pre- and post-treatment to assess improvement. Endoscopic examination was also done. \r\nResults:\r\nBoth SNOT-22 and PNDSS scores showed significant reduction following twelve weeks of therapy (p < 0.001). Endoscopic findings demonstrated mild improvement, though no consistent correlation was observed between mucosal appearance and symptom severity.\r\nConclusion:\r\nOral saline gargling is a safe, inexpensive, and effective measure for symptomatic relief in PNDS. The study supports redefining PNDS as a distinct clinical entity characterized by postnasal discharge without cough or active sinonasal pathology.', '', 'Effectiveness of oral saline gargling in postnasal drip syndrome (upper airway cough syndrome).', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 14:10:37', '2025-10-15 14:10:40'),
(205, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'rimjhimsharma360@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nThe present study aimed to assess the therapeutic benefits of adding the leukotriene receptor antagonist, montelukast, to conventional corticosteroid therapy in patients with chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRSwNP).\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective, randomized controlled study was conducted on 60 adult patients diagnosed with bilateral nasal polyps. Participants were randomly allocated into two equal groups. Group A received oral prednisolone for two weeks and budesonide nasal spray for eight weeks, while Group B received the same regimen with the addition of oral montelukast for eight weeks. Symptom severity was evaluated using a modified nasal ICSD symptom score at baseline, and subsequently at 8 and 12 weeks after treatment initiation.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nBoth groups demonstrated clinical improvement following therapy. However, patients in Group B exhibited greater and more sustained symptom relief. At 8 weeks, significant improvement was observed in sense of smell (p = 0.0005), nasal blockage (p = 0.009), and total symptom score (p = 0.001) compared to Group A. At 12 weeks, four weeks post-treatment, Group B maintained statistically significant improvement in sense of smell (p = 0.0007), headache (p = 0.035), and overall symptom score (p = 0.004). No major adverse effects were reported in either group.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nMontelukast, when administered as an adjunct to oral and topical corticosteroids, offers additional clinical benefit in the management of CRSwNP. Its use enhances symptom control—particularly in olfactory improvement and nasal patency—and may improve patient outcomes when integrated into standard medical therapy.', '', 'Montelukast as a supplementary therapy to Oral and inhaled steroids in the Management of Chronic Rhi', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-10-15 14:54:02', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(206, 'PRASHANTH.N', 'prasi39@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000426', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nChandler et al was instrumental in describing the pathogenesis of complications occurring secondary to acute sinusitis. In the elaborate account, he divided the complications into five following groups – Inflammatory edema, orbital cellulitis, sub periosteal abscess, orbital abscess, and cavernous sinus thrombosis. We present to you a series of  6 patients ( 5 pediatric and 1 adult ) presenting with different orbital complications following sinusitis in our tertiary care medical college and hospital.\r\nMethodology, Procedure and Results :\r\nWe have had 6 patients of which 5 patients were Pediatric age group and 1 elderly male with Type 2 Diabetes. Of which 4 patients of pediatric age group had stage 3-4 chandlers ( orbital and pre septal abscess), 1 child had only orbital cellulitis (pre septal –stage 2), and 1 adult patient presented with bilateral vision loss and stage 5 (cavernous sinus thrombosis). . \r\nIn our series, conservative management with IV antibiotic and supportive management was initiated but a final call for surgery was taken after no improvement was observed. On the other hand, in cases where vision is threatened, frank abscess is apparent clinically or radiologically, a wait and watch policy is strongly discouraged.\r\nAll the patients have undergone Endoscopic sinus surgery, Chandlers stage 3,4 patients required additional external Incision and drainage. Cavernous thrombosis patient required anticoagulants, high end antibiotics after surgery. All the patients successfully discharged within 4-5 days except cavernous thrombosis patient where he had to stay for 10 days for his recovery.\r\nConclusion:\r\nOrbital complications resulting secondary to sinus pathology have serious implications and therefore, require prompt intervention. The decision for conservative or surgical management should be based on the symptomatology at the time of presentation and stage of complication assessed after complete clinic-radiological investigations. Early diagnosis and swift treatment is needed in these cases to prevent complete loss of vision and even death of a patient.', '', 'Orbital complications ignited by propagating Sinusitis – a clinical case series.', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 15:27:26', '2025-10-15 15:27:29'),
(207, 'Dr Hamsini Sudhakar', 'hams2000.ms@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000244', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'PRESENTOR ; \r\nDr Hamsini Sudhakar \r\nJunior Resident , Sree balaji medical college and hospital \r\nPhone no : 9677011701 \r\nEmail :hams2000.ms@gmail.com \r\n\r\nGuide :\r\nDr MK Rajasekar \r\nProfessor and head of department \r\nSree balaji medical college and hospital \r\n\r\nTitle: Coblation-Assisted Excision of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Case Report\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe the surgical management of a case of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA) using coblation-assisted excision and highlight its effectiveness in reducing intraoperative bleeding and improving surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA male adolescent patient presented with recurrent nasal obstruction and epistaxis. Clinical examination, nasal endoscopy, and imaging confirmed the diagnosis of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. The patient underwent coblation-assisted excision of the tumor under general anesthesia. Intraoperative technique involved careful dissection of the tumor with coblation technology to minimize blood loss and preserve surrounding structures.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe coblation-assisted approach allowed precise removal of the tumor with significantly reduced intraoperative bleeding compared to conventional techniques. The postoperative course was uneventful, with no major complications or residual disease noted on follow-up endoscopic evaluation. The patient experienced rapid recovery, minimal postoperative pain, and no recurrence during the follow-up period.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted excision of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is a safe and effective technique. It provides excellent hemostasis, enhances surgical precision, and reduces morbidity. This method can be considered a valuable alternative to conventional surgical approaches in the management of JNA.', '', 'Title: Coblation-Assisted Excision of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Case Report', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 15:41:36', '2025-10-15 15:41:40'),
(208, 'Vishwanath Sivasubramanian', 'Vishwanathsiva@yahoo.com', 'RHIN0000253', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'PRESENTOR: \r\nDr Vishwanath Sivasubramanian \r\nJUNIOR RESIDENT, SREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\nPHONE-9677258642, \r\nEMAIL- Vishwanathsiva@yahoo.com\r\nGUIDE: \r\nProf Dr. M.K.Rajasekar\r\nProfessor and Head of Department\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n\r\n\r\nBackground: Pituitary macroadenomas are benign adenohypophyseal tumors larger than 10 mm, often presenting with visual disturbances, endocrine dysfunction, or features of raised intracranial pressure. Surgical management, primarily via hypophysectomy, remains the cornerstone of treatment for symptomatic lesions.\r\n\r\nObjective: To evaluate the clinical presentation, surgical management, and postoperative outcomes of a patient with pituitary macroadenoma treated with hypophysectomy.\r\n\r\nMethods: A patient diagnosed with pituitary macroadenoma based on clinical, radiological, and endocrine evaluation underwent hypophysectomy. Detailed assessment of presenting symptoms, imaging characteristics, operative findings, and perioperative management was carried out. Postoperative follow-up included clinical evaluation, visual field assessment, hormonal profile, and neuroimaging.\r\n\r\nResults: The patient presented with progressive headache, visual field defects, and features suggestive of hypopituitarism. MRI revealed a sellar-suprasellar mass consistent with pituitary macroadenoma. Hypophysectomy was performed via a trans-sphenoidal approach, achieving near-total excision. Postoperatively, there was significant improvement in visual symptoms, with normalization of intracranial pressure-related features. Hormonal replacement therapy was initiated as required.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Hypophysectomy remains an effective and safe procedure for pituitary macroadenomas, offering significant relief of compressive symptoms and improved quality of life. Early diagnosis, meticulous surgical technique, and vigilant postoperative endocrine monitoring are crucial for optimal outcomes.', '', 'Hypoohysectomy in Pituitary macroadenomas', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 15:42:05', '2025-10-15 15:42:09'),
(209, 'Dr RIMJHIM SHARMA', 'rimjhimsharma360@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nThe present study aimed to assess the therapeutic benefits of adding the leukotriene receptor antagonist, montelukast, to conventional corticosteroid therapy in patients with chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRSwNP).\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective, randomized controlled study was conducted on 60 adult patients diagnosed with bilateral nasal polyps. Participants were randomly allocated into two equal groups. Group A received oral prednisolone for two weeks and budesonide nasal spray for eight weeks, while Group B received the same regimen with the addition of oral montelukast for eight weeks. Symptom severity was evaluated using a modified nasal ICSD symptom score at baseline, and subsequently at 8 and 12 weeks after treatment initiation.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nBoth groups demonstrated clinical improvement following therapy. However, patients in Group B exhibited greater and more sustained symptom relief. At 8 weeks, significant improvement was observed in sense of smell (p = 0.0005), nasal blockage (p = 0.009), and total symptom score (p = 0.001) compared to Group A. At 12 weeks, four weeks post-treatment, Group B maintained statistically significant improvement in sense of smell (p = 0.0007), headache (p = 0.035), and overall symptom score (p = 0.004). No major adverse effects were reported in either group.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nMontelukast, when administered as an adjunct to oral and topical corticosteroids, offers additional clinical benefit in the management of CRSwNP. Its use enhances symptom control—particularly in olfactory improvement and nasal patency—and may improve patient outcomes when integrated into standard medical therapy.', '', 'Montelukast as a supplementary therapy to Oral and inhaled steroids in the Management of Chronic Rhi', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-10-15 15:55:41', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(210, 'Dr RIMJHIM SHARMA', 'rimjhimsharma360@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nThe present study aimed to assess the therapeutic benefits of adding the leukotriene receptor antagonist, montelukast, to conventional corticosteroid therapy in patients with chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRSwNP).\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective, randomized controlled study was conducted on 60 adult patients diagnosed with bilateral nasal polyps. Participants were randomly allocated into two equal groups. Group A received oral prednisolone for two weeks and budesonide nasal spray for eight weeks, while Group B received the same regimen with the addition of oral montelukast for eight weeks. Symptom severity was evaluated using a modified nasal ICSD symptom score at baseline, and subsequently at 8 and 12 weeks after treatment initiation.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nBoth groups demonstrated clinical improvement following therapy. However, patients in Group B exhibited greater and more sustained symptom relief. At 8 weeks, significant improvement was observed in sense of smell (p = 0.0005), nasal blockage (p = 0.009), and total symptom score (p = 0.001) compared to Group A. At 12 weeks, four weeks post-treatment, Group B maintained statistically significant improvement in sense of smell (p = 0.0007), headache (p = 0.035), and overall symptom score (p = 0.004). No major adverse effects were reported in either group.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nMontelukast, when administered as an adjunct to oral and topical corticosteroids, offers additional clinical benefit in the management of CRSwNP. Its use enhances symptom control—particularly in olfactory improvement and nasal patency—and may improve patient outcomes when integrated into standard medical therapy.', '', 'Montelukast as a supplementary therapy to Oral and inhaled steroids in the Management of Chronic Rhi', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-10-15 15:55:43', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(211, 'GAYATHRI BHASKARAN', 'gayathri.tilapu@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000206', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Background:Skull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is an uncommon yet potentially fatal infection, commonly affecting immunocompromised individuals, particularly those with diabetes mellitus. Mucormycosis, an equally dangerous infection, affects a similar patient population. Despite advances in antimicrobial therapy and surgical techniques, management of both conditions remain complex, and life-threatening complications can ensue. Among these, hemorrhagic events secondary to vascular involvement are exceedingly rare. We  present a case of a diabetic patient who developed a catastrophic hemorrhage, likely due to a ruptured pseudoaneurysm, following surgical debridement for Rhino-orbital mucormycosis and Left SBO.\r\nCase Presentation:A 55-year-old male with Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus presented with clinical and radiological features consistent with Rhino-orbital mucormycosis . He underwent surgical exploration with Denkers’s approach with globe sparing left orbital debridement. He was on long-term antifungal treatment. After disease stabilisation, he was discharged and was on regular followup with disease control. After 6 months, he presented with intractable headache and left ear pain and was diagnosed with left skull base osteomyelitis. He underwent comprehensive medical management with prolonged intravenous antibiotics and multidisciplinary care and surgical intervention including a left subtotal petrosectomy. Postoperatively patient recovery was good. On POD 17, he experienced two minor episodes of nasal bleeding before developing a sudden, massive nasal and oral hemorrhage associated with a precipitous drop in oxygen saturation to 86%, profuse diaphoresis, and altered consciousness, necessitating emergency intensive care support. The clinical course and background strongly suggested rupture of a pseudoaneurysm—an uncommon but devastating vascular complication of SBO.\r\nConclusion:This case highlights the critical need for vigilance regarding vascular complications, particularly pseudoaneurysm formation, in patients with Rhinoorbital mucormycosis and skull base osteomyelitis, especially those with diabetes mellitus. The dual insult of angioinvasive infection, potentially of fungal etiology and surgical manipulation may predispose to vessel wall compromise and subsequent hemorrhage. Early recognition of sentinel bleeding as a possible harbinger of vascular injury, coupled with prompt vascular imaging and intervention, is paramount to preventing fatal outcomes in such high-risk patients.', '', 'Carotid Quell…..A Case Report', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 16:00:15', '2025-10-15 16:00:19'),
(212, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim: To evaluate modified denker’s approach for inverted papilloma.\r\n\r\nMethodology: The endoscopic modified Denker’s approach (EMDA) represents a significant advancement in the management of sinonasal inverted papilloma, allowing for wide exposure of the maxillary sinus while minimizing morbidity associated with traditional external procedures. This approach offers excellent visualization of the anterolateral and inferomedial walls of the maxillary sinus, where residual disease often persists following limited endoscopic resections. The procedure begins with infiltration of local anesthetic and adrenaline along the lateral nasal wall, followed by elevation of the mucoperiosteum to expose the pyriform aperture and anterior maxillary wall. A partial inferior turbinectomy and uncinectomy are performed to create adequate access. The medial maxillectomy is initiated by resecting the medial wall of the maxilla from the inferior turbinate attachment up to the nasolacrimal duct, which is carefully identified and preserved or transected as indicated by disease extent. The anterior bony window is widened using powered instruments to achieve communication with the anterior maxillary wall, enabling direct visualization of the anterior and lateral recesses. The posterior wall, infraorbital canal, and alveolar recess are inspected, and the tumor is meticulously excised with wide mucosal margins to ensure complete removal.\r\n\r\nResults: Reconstruction involves mucosal preservation and the creation of a wide middle meatal antrostomy for postoperative surveillance. The EMDA minimizes facial scarring, preserves nasal function, and reduces recurrence rates through improved access and visualization. \r\n\r\nConclusion: Mastery of the stepwise technique ensures safe and effective management of inverted papilloma with superior outcomes compared to traditional Denker’s or Caldwell–Luc approaches.', '', 'Title: Steps of Endoscopic Modified Denker’s Approach for Inverted Papilloma Surgery', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 17:46:58', '2025-10-15 17:47:02'),
(213, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nJuvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA) is a rare, histologically benign but locally aggressive vascular tumor that predominantly affects adolescent males. Typical symptoms include nasal obstruction and recurrent epistaxis. Presentation with stridor and respiratory distress is exceedingly uncommon.\r\n\r\nCase Presentation:\r\nA 14-year-old boy presented to the ENT Department of SMVDIME, with progressive respiratory distress and noisy breathing for two months, nasal obstruction and intermittent nasal bleeding for two years, and mild dysphagia with voice change for six months. Examination revealed stridor with suprasternal and intercostal retractions, drooling of saliva, pallor, and adenoid facies. A reddish-white fleshy mass was visible in the oropharynx, and anterior rhinoscopy showed a large lobulated mass occupying the left nasal cavity and nasopharynx.\r\n\r\nInvestigations and Management:\r\nCECT of the paranasal sinuses and neck demonstrated a heterogeneous enhancing mass arising from the left sphenopalatine fossa, extending into the posterior nasal cavity, oropharynx, and infratemporal fossa, causing near-complete airway obstruction. After securing the airway with an emergency tracheostomy, the tumor was excised completely via a modified transpalatal and sublabial approach. Blood loss was minimal, and the postoperative recovery was uneventful. The patient was decannulated on postoperative day five and remained asymptomatic during follow-up.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nAlthough JNA commonly presents with nasal obstruction and epistaxis, presentation with stridor is extremely rare. This case highlights the importance of early recognition, prompt airway management, and complete surgical excision to achieve optimal outcomes in such potentially life-threatening presentations.', '', 'Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma Presenting with Stridor: A Rare Case Report', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 17:52:55', '2025-10-15 17:52:59'),
(214, 'Tanisha Goel', 'tanisha287@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000427', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Comparative Study of the Role of Oral Steroids with Itraconazole and Antibiotics in Allergic Fungal Rhinosinusitis\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Tanisha Goel\r\nAim: To compare the efficacy of oral itraconazole plus steroids versus oral antibiotics plus steroids in AFRS, using objective and subjective outcome measures.\r\nMethodology: A prospective randomized clinical trial was conducted on 100 AFRS patients diagnosed via NCCT of the nose and paranasal sinuses. Participants were divided into two groups: Group A received oral prednisolone (tapering dose) with antibiotics, and Group B received oral prednisolone with itraconazole for two weeks. Pre- and post-treatment assessments included Lund-Mackay CT scores, Kupferberg and modified Lund-Kennedy endoscopic scores, serum total IgE, SNOT-22, and VAS scores.\r\nResults: Both groups showed significant improvement in all parameters post-treatment. The mean SNOT-22 scores decreased from 41.96 to 23.08 in Group A and from 48.62 to 26.86 in Group B. VAS scores improved by 3.36 and 3.74 points, respectively. Endoscopic and CT scores also demonstrated comparable reductions. However, no statistically significant differences were observed.\r\nConclusion: Both treatment regimens—oral steroids with itraconazole and oral steroids with antibiotics—are equally effective for preoperative disease control in AFRS. Further studies are needed to validate these findings and explore long-term outcomes.', '', 'Comparative Study of the Role of Oral Steroids with Itraconazole and Antibiotics in Allergic Fungal ', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 19:42:40', '2025-10-15 19:42:44'),
(215, 'KUNE SAPHI PYRBOT', 'drkunesaphi@gmail.com', 'RHIN000083', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Background: Sinonasal masses include benign and malignant lesions of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, presenting commonly with nasal obstruction, epistaxis and facial swelling. Early diagnosis and management are crucial to reduce complications and recurrence.\r\nObjective: To evaluate the clinical features, pathology, treatment, and outcomes of sinonasal masses over five years.\r\nMethods: A retrospective study from 2019 to 2024 included 33 patients (15 males, 18 females; age 10–86 years, mean 48 years). Patients with nasal polyposis, allergic fungal rhinosinusitis and granulomatous diseases were excluded. Data on presentation, histology, treatment and follow-up were analysed.\r\nResults: Of 33 cases, 27 (82%) were benign and 6 (18%) malignant. Benign lesions included rhinosporidiosis (11), inverted papilloma (7), juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (6), fibromatosis(1), dermoid cyst(1), and schwannoma (1). Malignant tumors included squamous cell carcinoma (2), esthesioneuroblastoma (2), lymphoma(1), and hyalinising clear cell carcinoma (1).\r\nAll benign cases had complete surgical excision; malignant cases received surgery followed by radiotherapy. Recurrence occurred in 12 patients (36%), with 2 malignant (33%) and 10 benign (37%). Mean follow-up was 48 months.\r\nConclusion: Sinonasal masses show varied pathology and age distribution. Surgery is key for benign tumours; while malignant tumours require multimodal management. The notable recurrence rate, particularly in benign lesions, emphasizes the importance of long-term follow-up.\r\nKeywords: Sinonasal mass, Rhinosporidiosis, Inverted papilloma, Esthesioneuroblastoma, Demographics, Tamil Nadu, Surgical outcomes, Recurrence.', '', 'Clinicopathological Spectrum and Long-Term Outcomes of Sinonasal Masses at a Tertiary Care Centre in', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 20:25:19', '2025-10-15 20:25:23'),
(216, 'Rachit Pahwa', 'drrachitpahwa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000126', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title:Association Between Biomarkers, Cough, and Asthma in Chronic Rhinosinusitis Patients\r\nPresenting Author:Dr.RachitPahwa, Department of ENT, SMGS Hospital, Government Medical College, Jammu\r\nAim:To assess the relationship between inflammatory biomarkers and lower airway involvement among patients diagnosed with chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS), in the context of the unified airway hypothesis.\r\nMethodology:A prospective observational study was conducted in the ENT department of SMGS Hospital over 18 months. 121 adult patients with CRS underwent spirometry (FEV₁, FEV₁/FVC), fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO), absolute eosinophil count (AEC), serum IgE evaluation, and SNOT-22 scoring. Patients meeting ≥2 of the following thresholds—AEC ≥0.3×10³/µL, IgE ≥150 kU/L, FeNO>25 ppb, or FEV₁ <2.0 L—were analyzed for airway inflammation patterns. Statistical analysis included correlation and multivariate regression.\r\nResults:FeNO was positively associated with SNOT-22 scores (ρ=0.23). FEV₁ showed significant associations with AEC (p=0.048) and SNOT-22 (p=0.009). FeNO levels were significantly predicted by AEC (p=0.038), IgE (p=0.041), SNOT-22 (p=0.027), and age (p=0.015).\r\nConclusions:CRS patients frequently exhibited biomarker patterns suggestive of subclinical lower airway involvement. Inflammatory markers such as AEC, FeNO, and IgE may offer useful insights into unified airway pathology.', '', 'Association Between Biomarkers, Cough, and Asthma in Chronic Rhinosinusitis Patients', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 20:43:40', '2025-10-15 20:43:43'),
(217, 'Rachit Pahwa', 'drrachitpahwa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000126', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title:Association Between Biomarkers, Cough, and Asthma in Chronic Rhinosinusitis Patients\r\nPresenting Author:Dr.RachitPahwa, Department of ENT, SMGS Hospital, Government Medical College, Jammu\r\nAim:To assess the relationship between inflammatory biomarkers and lower airway involvement among patients diagnosed with chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS), in the context of the unified airway hypothesis.\r\nMethodology:A prospective observational study was conducted in the ENT department of SMGS Hospital over 18 months. 121 adult patients with CRS underwent spirometry (FEV₁, FEV₁/FVC), fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO), absolute eosinophil count (AEC), serum IgE evaluation, and SNOT-22 scoring. Patients meeting ≥2 of the following thresholds—AEC ≥0.3×10³/µL, IgE ≥150 kU/L, FeNO>25 ppb, or FEV₁ <2.0 L—were analyzed for airway inflammation patterns. Statistical analysis included correlation and multivariate regression.\r\nResults:FeNO was positively associated with SNOT-22 scores (ρ=0.23). FEV₁ showed significant associations with AEC (p=0.048) and SNOT-22 (p=0.009). FeNO levels were significantly predicted by AEC (p=0.038), IgE (p=0.041), SNOT-22 (p=0.027), and age (p=0.015).\r\nConclusions:CRS patients frequently exhibited biomarker patterns suggestive of subclinical lower airway involvement. Inflammatory markers such as AEC, FeNO, and IgE may offer useful insights into unified airway pathology.', '', 'Association Between Biomarkers, Cough, and Asthma in Chronic Rhinosinusitis Patients', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 20:48:16', '2025-10-15 20:48:20');
