(238, 'SHARMILA S', 'drssharmilambbs@gmail.com', 'RHINO000350', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim\r\nTo highlight the clinical presentation, diagnostic approach and management of single case of Left Sino nasal inverted papilloma with importance of early diagnosis and effective surgical intervention.\r\nMethodology \r\nA  52 year old male, farmer by occupation presented with C/O left side Nasal obstruction and left side nasal discharge ×1 week. C/O 1 episode of nose bleed.\r\nClinical examination reveals DNS to right. Left nasal cavity – proliferative pinkish friable mass extending from inferior turbinate to middle turbinate. CT PNS shows large polypoidal mucosal thickening noted in left maxillary sinus with complete opacification of the left maxillary sinus extending into the left sided nasal cavity involving middle and inferior turbinate. DNE and biopsy done.  Histopathological examination shows sinonasal papilloma (oncocytic type). Patient underwent endoscopic debridement with left medial maxillectomy.\r\nResults: \r\nPost operatively patient improved symptomatically and good surgical outcome\r\nConclusion :\r\n      This case emphasizes the role of early diagnosis and effective surgical approach to remove the tumor origin completely, to achieve low recurrence rate, minimizing morbidity, preserving anatomy and maintaining normal nasal function. It also provides excellent access for followup.', '', 'Left Sinonasal inverted papilloma', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 21:48:37', '2025-10-15 21:48:45'),
(239, 'Nicole Stephen', 'nicolestephen99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000260', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nUse of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypertension\r\n\r\nPresenting Author\r\nDr Nicole Stephen\r\n\r\nAim\r\nTo assess the specific changes in Optical coherence tomography in patients with spontaneous CSF leak\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nThis retrospective study includes 20 patients including male and female between the age 18-65years. A thorough history, including history of headache, tinnitus, rhinorrhea, nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances. OCT was taken at the time of diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nAmong the 20 patients included in the study, 18 were females. The most common clinical presentation is watery nasal discharge, followed by headache, seen in 10 patients. Two patients had history of recurrent meningitis. The average retinal nerve fibre layer thickness in right eye is 106.2m and left eye is 105.9m with symmetry of 85%.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nIdiopathic intracranial hypertension is predominantly seen in females with a history of long-standing headache and visual disturbances in the form of scotoma, diplopia and reduced visual acuity. They can present as CSF leak in patients with a long-standing history, as chronic elevation of CSF pressure can erode the skull base. Once CSF leak ensues, the intracranial pressure normalises, hence showing near-normal or higher end of normal range of RNFL thickness', '', 'Use of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypert', NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nUse of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypertension\r\n\r\nPresenting Author\r\nDr Nicole Stephen\r\n\r\nAim\r\nTo assess the specific changes in Optical coherence tomography in patients with spontaneous CSF leak\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nThis retrospective study includes 20 patients including male and female between the age 18-65years. A thorough history, including history of headache, tinnitus, rhinorrhea, nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances. OCT was taken at the time of diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nAmong the 20 patients included in the study, 18 were females. The most common clinical presentation is watery nasal discharge, followed by headache, seen in 10 patients. Two patients had history of recurrent meningitis. The average retinal nerve fibre layer thickness in right eye is 106.2m and left eye is 105.9m with symmetry of 85%.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nIdiopathic intracranial hypertension is predominantly seen in females with a history of long-standing headache and visual disturbances in the form of scotoma, diplopia and reduced visual acuity. They can present as CSF leak in patients with a long-standing history, as chronic elevation of CSF pressure can erode the skull base. Once CSF leak ensues, the intracranial pressure normalises, hence showing near-normal or higher end of normal range of RNFL thickness', '', 'Use of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypert', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 22:27:59', '2025-10-15 22:28:02'),
