h spontaneous CSF leak\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nThis retrospective study includes 20 patients including male and female between the age 18-65years. A thorough history, including history of headache, tinnitus, rhinorrhea, nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances. OCT was taken at the time of diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nAmong the 20 patients included in the study, 18 were females. The most common clinical presentation is watery nasal discharge, followed by headache, seen in 10 patients. Two patients had history of recurrent meningitis. The average retinal nerve fibre layer thickness in right eye is 106.2m and left eye is 105.9m with symmetry of 85%.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nIdiopathic intracranial hypertension is predominantly seen in females with a history of long-standing headache and visual disturbances in the form of scotoma, diplopia and reduced visual acuity. They can present as CSF leak in patients with a long-standing history, as chronic elevation of CSF pressure can erode the skull base. Once CSF leak ensues, the intracranial pressure normalises, hence showing near-normal or higher end of normal range of RNFL thickness', '', 'Use of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypert', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 22:28:01', '2025-10-15 22:28:05'),
