(246, 'Dr J. JANANI', 'jjanani25395@gmail.com', 'RHIN000047', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'AIM- To compare the surgical outcomes, complications and recurrence rates in patients undergoing endoscopic trans-nasal trans-sphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas with and without intraoperative navigation guidance.\r\nMETHODOLOGY- A retrospective comparative study was conducted on 45 patients who underwent endoscopic trans-nasal transsphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas over a 5year period. The patients were divided into two groups: Group A underwent conventional endoscopic excision without navigation and Group B underwent navigation guided excision. Pre operative MRI and hormonal evaluation were done. Parameters assessed included demographics, extent of resection, complications, and recurrence in follow op imaging. \r\nRESULTS- Among the 45 patients, 57.7 were female with a mean age of 48.8 years. Most had Macroadenoma with headache and visual symptoms. 42% underwent navigation guided excision while 57.7 underwent convention excision. Navigation guided surgery had better result with fewer recurrences and complications.\r\nCONCLUSION- Navigation guided endoscopic trans-nasal transsphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas significantly improves surgical accuracy, lowers recurrence rates compared to conventional surgery. The use of intraoperative navigation is recommended as a standard adjunct for safe and effective tumour excision.\r\nKey Words- Pituitary adenoma, Navigation guided', '', 'Comparative study between Navigation guided and conventional Endoscopic Trans-nasal trans-sphenoidal', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 22:56:14', '2025-10-15 22:56:18'),
(247, 'Dr J. JANANI', 'jjanani25395@gmail.com', 'RHIN000047', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'AIM- To compare the surgical outcomes, complications and recurrence rates in patients undergoing endoscopic trans-nasal trans-sphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas with and without intraoperative navigation guidance.\r\nMETHODOLOGY- A retrospective comparative study was conducted on 45 patients who underwent endoscopic trans-nasal transsphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas over a 5year period. The patients were divided into two groups: Group A underwent conventional endoscopic excision without navigation and Group B underwent navigation guided excision. Pre operative MRI and hormonal evaluation were done. Parameters assessed included demographics, extent of resection, complications, and recurrence in follow op imaging. \r\nRESULTS- Among the 45 patients, 57.7 were female with a mean age of 48.8 years. Most had Macroadenoma with headache and visual symptoms. 42% underwent navigation guided excision while 57.7 underwent convention excision. Navigation guided surgery had better result with fewer recurrences and complications.\r\nCONCLUSION- Navigation guided endoscopic trans-nasal transsphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas significantly improves surgical accuracy, lowers recurrence rates compared to conventional surgery. The use of intraoperative navigation is recommended as a standard adjunct for safe and effective tumour excision.\r\nKey Words- Pituitary adenoma, Navigation guided', '', 'Comparative study between Navigation guided and conventional Endoscopic Trans-nasal trans-sphenoidal', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 22:56:18', '2025-10-15 22:56:21'),
(248, 'Dheeneshwar S', 'dheeneshwar98@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000429', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Pott’s Puffy Tumor Without Sinus Symptoms: A Rare Presentation and Multimodal Management\r\nPott’s puffy tumor is a rare complication of frontal sinusitis involving subperiosteal abscess and frontal bone osteomyelitis. We report an unusual case presenting with history of vague headache without any other sinus symptoms.\r\nA 27-year-old female with no comorbidities presented with a rapidly progressive, tender forehead swelling (4×3 cm) over 15 days, preceded by intermittent headache for one year. NCCT revealed complete frontal sinus opacification with anterior wall defect and subgaleal extension, with bilateral maxillary sinus involvement. Multiple aspirations and intravenous antibiotics were initially attempted, but recurrence occurred. Definitive management was performed via a combined endoscopic and bicoronal flap frontal osteoplastic surgery and Draf III (modified Lothrop) procedure. Intraoperatively, inflamed tissue and fungal mucin were identified; histopathology showed chronic inflammation without fungal elements.\r\nPostoperative recovery was uneventful. Minimal recurrence in the form a mild swelling at two months resolved with antibiotics and topical therapy. Follow-up computed tomography at three months showed expected healing changes without cosmetic deformity.\r\nEarly recognition and multidisciplinary surgical management are key to preventing intracranial complications and achieving excellent functional and cosmetic outcomes in atypical pott’s puffy tumor presentations.', '', 'Pott’s Puffy Tumor Without Sinus Symptoms: A Rare Presentation and Multimodal Management', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 23:26:00', '2025-10-15 23:26:04'),
(249, 'Dr Sonam Snehil', 'sonam522544@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000430', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'A Tale of Two Sides: Synchronous Nasal and Contralateral Infraorbital Neurofibromas in a Young Male\r\n\r\nBackground\r\nNeurofibromas are benign peripheral nerve sheath tumors that usually occur in the context of neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1). Solitary or localized neurofibromas involving the nasal cavity or orbit are extremely rare, and synchronous lesions in distinct craniofacial sites without systemic NF1 features are uncommon.\r\n\r\nCase Presentation\r\nA 19-year-old male presented with progressive right-sided nasal obstruction and a lobulated mass protruding externally from the right nasal vestibule for last 5yrs , accompanied by a gradually enlarging, painless swelling over the left infraorbital (lower-lid) region. There was no history of epistaxis, visual disturbance, or hearing loss.\r\n\r\nInvestigations\r\nMRI face (CEMRI) demonstrated a heterogeneously enhancing lesion involving the right lateral nasal wall measuring 29 × 26 × 29 mm and another soft-tissue lesion in the left infraorbital region, both showing T2 hyperintensity and T1 hypointensity, suggestive of neurogenic origin. \r\nSections examined from right nasal cavity shows epidermis and dermis with an ill-circumscribed spindle cell tumor arranged in vague fascicles with collagen deposits resembling shredded carrots and myxoidy changes in the background. No significant atypia, mitosis or necrosis noted,suggestive of Neurofibroma. Biopsy from the infraorbital swelling confirmed neurofibroma. \r\nManagement\r\nThe patient underwent complete excision of the nasal mass , with preservation of nasal architecture. Vision and cranial nerve function remained normal post-operatively.\r\n\r\nDiscussion\r\nMultiple neurofibromas occurring without features of neurofibromatosis type 1 are rare and usually appear as isolated, slow-growing swellings. Because their imaging features can resemble other benign nasal tumors and they can affect facial appearance, careful evaluation and planned surgery are essential.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nSynchronous neurofibromas of the nasal and infraorbital regions are exceedingly uncommon. High suspicion, imaging correlation, and histopathological confirmation are essential for diagnosis, and complete excision ensures favorable functional and cosmetic outcomes.', '', 'A Tale of Two Sides: Synchronous Nasal and Contralateral Infraorbital Neurofibromas in a Young Male', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 23:45:59', '2025-10-15 23:46:03'),
(250, 'SIVASUBRAMANIAM NAGARAJAN', 'sivan020393@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000428', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE\r\nCSF Leak unmasking the forgotten Trauma\r\n\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR\r\nSivasubramaniam Nagarajan\r\n\r\nAIM\r\nTailoring the management of Traumatic CSF Leaks based on its clinical presentation\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY\r\nCross sectional study\r\nCase series of patients with Cerebrospinal Fluid Leak with past history of trauma.\r\n\r\nRESULTS\r\nAscertaining the cause for every patient with subsequent surgical repair of the CSF leak is necessary for successful management of this condition.\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION\r\nSurgical management of Traumatic CSF Leaks should be considered. Timely intervention is essential wherever necessary.', '', 'CSF Leak unmasking the forgotten Trauma', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-15 23:50:29', '2025-10-15 23:50:32'),
(251, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the functional and aesthetic outcomes of extracorporeal septoplasty in patients with severe septal deviation and nasal obstruction.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is performed under general anaesthesia for severe septal deviation. The mucoperichondrial flaps are elevated through an open or hemitransfixation incision, and the deviated septal cartilage is completely removed. The cartilage is reshaped extracorporeally on a flat surface by scoring, trimming, and suturing to achieve a straight and stable framework. The reconstructed septum is reimplanted in the midline, with the caudal end fixed to the anterior nasal spine and dorsal support reattached to the upper lateral cartilages. Mucosal flaps are repositioned and sutured, followed by nasal splints or packing to maintain alignment and ensure optimal postoperative airway function.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe mean age of the patients was 31.7 ± 8.2 years. The mean preoperative NOSE score significantly decreased at three months post-surgery (p < 0.001). Marked improvement in nasal airflow and patient-reported satisfaction was observed. Postoperative complications were minimal, including mild dorsal irregularity and transient nasal tip edema, both of which resolved with conservative management. No cases of septal perforation or saddle nose deformity were reported.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is a highly effective surgical technique for correcting complex septal deformities. It provides excellent functional and aesthetic outcomes by restoring nasal symmetry and airway patency. The procedure ensures stable septal support with minimal complications, making it a preferred approach in cases of severe deviation or post-traumatic nasal deformity.', '', 'Title: Outcomes of Extracorporeal Septoplasty', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 10:00:48', '2025-10-16 10:00:51'),
(252, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe the surgical steps of the Endoscopic Modified Denker’s Approach (EMDA) in the management of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA).\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective study was conducted on fifteen patients diagnosed with JNA (Radkowski stages IIB–IIIB) between January 2022 and December 2024. All patients underwent EMDA under general anaesthesia. Following lateral nasal wall infiltration with a vasoconstrictor, a mucosal incision was made along the pyriform aperture, and the mucoperiosteum was elevated to expose the anterior maxillary wall. After partial inferior turbinectomy, the medial maxillectomy was extended anteriorly and inferiorly, preserving or transacting the nasolacrimal duct as required. The posterior maxillary wall was removed to access the pterygopalatine and infratemporal fossae. The tumour was devascularized, dissected, and excised completely under endoscopic visualization. Intraoperative blood loss, complications, and recurrence were recorded during a one-year follow-up period.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe mean operative time was 145 ± 25 minutes, with mean intraoperative blood loss of 410 ± 90 mL. Complete tumour excision was achieved in all patients. No major complications such as cerebrospinal fluid leak or vision loss were encountered. Two patients experienced mild postoperative epistaxis, managed conservatively. At one-year follow-up, no recurrence was observed clinically or radiologically, and nasal patency was well maintained.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nThe Endoscopic Modified Denker’s Approach provides excellent access to the anterior maxilla, pterygopalatine, and infratemporal fossae, allowing complete and safe excision of JNA with minimal morbidity. It is a valuable, minimally invasive alternative to traditional open approaches for advanced but localized angiofibromas.', '', 'Surgical Steps and Outcomes of Endoscopic Modified Denker’s Approach for Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Ang', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 10:21:49', '2025-10-16 10:21:52'),
(253, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the functional and aesthetic outcomes of extracorporeal septorhinoplasty in patients with severe septal deviation and nasal obstruction.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is performed under general anaesthesia for severe septal deviation. The mucoperichondrial flaps are elevated through an open or hemitransfixation incision, and the deviated septal cartilage is completely removed. The cartilage is reshaped extracorporeally on a flat surface by scoring, trimming, and suturing to achieve a straight and stable framework. The reconstructed septum is reimplanted in the midline, with the caudal end fixed to the anterior nasal spine and dorsal support reattached to the upper lateral cartilages. Mucosal flaps are repositioned and sutured, followed by nasal splints or packing to maintain alignment and ensure optimal postoperative airway function.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe mean age of the patients was 31.7 ± 8.2 years. The mean preoperative NOSE score significantly decreased at three months post-surgery (p < 0.001). Marked improvement in nasal airflow and patient-reported satisfaction was observed. Postoperative complications were minimal, including mild dorsal irregularity and transient nasal tip edema, both of which resolved with conservative management. No cases of septal perforation or saddle nose deformity were reported.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is a highly effective surgical technique for correcting complex septal deformities. It provides excellent functional and aesthetic outcomes by restoring nasal symmetry and airway patency. The procedure ensures stable septal support with minimal complications, making it a preferred approach in cases of severe deviation or post-traumatic nasal deformity.', '', 'Outcomes of Extracorporeal Septorhinoplasty', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 11:03:34', '2025-10-16 11:03:38'),
(254, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the functional and aesthetic outcomes of extracorporeal septorhinoplasty in patients with severe septal deviation and nasal obstruction.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is performed under general anaesthesia for severe septal deviation. The mucoperichondrial flaps are elevated through an open or hemitransfixation incision, and the deviated septal cartilage is completely removed. The cartilage is reshaped extracorporeally on a flat surface by scoring, trimming, and suturing to achieve a straight and stable framework. The reconstructed septum is reimplanted in the midline, with the caudal end fixed to the anterior nasal spine and dorsal support reattached to the upper lateral cartilages. Mucosal flaps are repositioned and sutured, followed by nasal splints or packing to maintain alignment and ensure optimal postoperative airway function.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe mean age of the patients was 31.7 ± 8.2 years. The mean preoperative NOSE score significantly decreased at three months post-surgery (p < 0.001). Marked improvement in nasal airflow and patient-reported satisfaction was observed. Postoperative complications were minimal, including mild dorsal irregularity and transient nasal tip edema, both of which resolved with conservative management. No cases of septal perforation or saddle nose deformity were reported.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is a highly effective surgical technique for correcting complex septal deformities. It provides excellent functional and aesthetic outcomes by restoring nasal symmetry and airway patency. The procedure ensures stable septal support with minimal complications, making it a preferred approach in cases of severe deviation or post-traumatic nasal deformity.', '', 'Outcomes of Extracorporeal Septorhinoplasty', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 11:03:37', '2025-10-16 11:03:40'),
(255, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the surgical technique and clinical outcomes of endoscopic repair of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhea.\r\n\r\nMethodology: Endoscopic repair of CSF rhinorrhea is performed under general anaesthesia using image guidance. The leak site was localized by CT cistenography. Surrounding mucosa was elevated, and bony margins were freshened. Endoscopic repair was done in layers. Autologous graft i.e. fat, fascia lata, and vascularized pedicled nasoseptal flap were harvested and placed using underlay or overlay techniques. Each layer was reinforced using fibrin glue. Nasal packing was done to support the repair, and postoperative care included head elevation, avoidance of straining, and selective lumbar drainage. \r\n\r\nResults: Endoscopic repair of CSF rhinorrhea offers a minimally invasive, safe, and highly effective alternative to traditional transcranial approaches. It provides excellent visualization of the defect, allows precise localization and targeted repair, and minimizes brain retraction and postoperative morbidity. \r\n\r\nConclusion: This technique ensures faster recovery, reduced hospital stay, superior cosmetic outcomes, and high long-term success rates with minimal recurrence.', '', 'Outcomes of Endoscopic Repair of Cerebrospinal Fluid Rhinorrhea', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 11:35:04', '2025-10-16 11:35:08'),
(256, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo assess the efficacy and safety of intratympanic dexamethasone injections in improving hearing thresholds and reducing vertigo/tinnitus in patients unresponsive to conventional therapy.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective observational study was carried out on 35 patients between January 2022 and December 2023. Conditions included idiopathic sudden sensorineural hearing loss (ISSNHL) (n=20), refractory Menière’s disease (n=10), and persistent tinnitus (n=5) after at least four weeks of standard medical management. Intratympanic dexamethasone (4 mg/mL, 0.5 mL) was administered weekly for three consecutive weeks. Pure tone audiometry, vertigo frequency, and tinnitus handicap inventory scores were recorded pre-treatment, at one month, and at three months post-treatment.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nIn ISSNHL patients, 65% (13/20) demonstrated ≥25 dB improvement in pure tone average (PTA) at three months (mean gain 28 ± 7 dB). Among those with Menière’s disease, 8 out of 10 patients (80%) reported a >50% reduction in monthly vertigo attacks (average from 6.4 to 2.1 episodes/month). Tinnitus scores improved significantly in 3 of 5 patients (60%) at one month, though partial relapse was seen by three months. No major adverse effects occurred; transient ear discomfort was most common.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nIntratympanic dexamethasone is a safe and effective adjunct treatment for patients with ISSNHL, refractory Menière’s disease, and chronic tinnitus who have not responded to standard therapy. It yields significant improvements in hearing outcomes and vertigo control, with moderate benefit for tinnitus. Controlled trials with larger samples are recommended to optimize dose, frequency, and patient selection.', '', 'Clinical Experience with Intratympanic Dexamethasone in Sensorineural Hearing and Vestibular Disorde', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 11:51:09', '2025-10-16 11:51:12'),
(257, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo assess the efficacy and safety of intratympanic dexamethasone injections in improving hearing thresholds and reducing vertigo/tinnitus in patients unresponsive to conventional therapy.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective observational study was carried out on 35 patients between January 2022 and December 2023. Conditions included idiopathic sudden sensorineural hearing loss (ISSNHL) (n=20), refractory Menière’s disease (n=10), and persistent tinnitus (n=5) after at least four weeks of standard medical management. Intratympanic dexamethasone (4 mg/mL, 0.5 mL) was administered weekly for three consecutive weeks. Pure tone audiometry, vertigo frequency, and tinnitus handicap inventory scores were recorded pre-treatment, at one month, and at three months post-treatment.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nIn ISSNHL patients, 65% (13/20) demonstrated ≥25 dB improvement in pure tone average (PTA) at three months (mean gain 28 ± 7 dB). Among those with Menière’s disease, 8 out of 10 patients (80%) reported a >50% reduction in monthly vertigo attacks (average from 6.4 to 2.1 episodes/month). Tinnitus scores improved significantly in 3 of 5 patients (60%) at one month, though partial relapse was seen by three months. No major adverse effects occurred; transient ear discomfort was most common.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nIntratympanic dexamethasone is a safe and effective adjunct treatment for patients with ISSNHL, refractory Menière’s disease, and chronic tinnitus who have not responded to standard therapy. It yields significant improvements in hearing outcomes and vertigo control, with moderate benefit for tinnitus. Controlled trials with larger samples are recommended to optimize dose, frequency, and patient selection.', '', 'Clinical Experience with Intratympanic Dexamethasone in Sensorineural Hearing and Vestibular Disorde', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 11:51:11', '2025-10-16 11:51:14'),
(258, 'Pritansh Kumar Nikhar', 'pritanshkumar@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000124', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'AIM- To find the outcome of rare nasal tumor presented as nasal obstruction.\r\n\r\nMethodology – 40 years old female presented with nasal obstruction only without any other associated symptoms. Not resolving on medication . Zero degree endoscopy was done and a mass was seen in side the right nasal cavity . CECT and MRI was done to find out the extent of the mass. Mass was originating from sphenoid sinus and having compressive effects over sellar region. Surgical excision was done. And mass sent for the biopsy. Biopsy suggestive of Chordoma.\r\n\r\nResult – Surgical excision was the treatment of Choice for the rare nasal mass “Chordoma”.\r\n\r\nConclusion – unilateral nasal obstruction not responding to medication can rarely be presented as a uncommon tumor i.e. Chordoma, for which surgical excision is the treatment of Choice.', '', 'Rare presentation of Nasal obstruction: A case report.', 2, 1, '2025-10-19 19:39:42', '2025-10-19 19:39:46'),
(259, 'Dr Suji P.S', 'ps.sujips.suji@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000435', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\",\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim: To present our surgical experience in the management of various intracranial lesions using ETNTS approach.\r\nMethodology: This retrospective review analyzed patients who underwent the ETNTS approach for sellar or parasellar lesions at our center. Preoperative imaging, surgical technique, intraoperative navigation, and postoperative management were assessed, with focus on resection extent, hospital stay, recovery, and complications. Special attention was given to preventing cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leaks and preserving neurovascular structures.\r\nResults: Six patients (aged 27-60) underwent ETNTS, primarily for pituitary adenomas. Complete resection was achieved in all cases. The average hospital stay was 7 days, and most patients reported mild postoperative discomfort. Complications included CSF leaks and sinus issues in 33% of cases each, managed conservatively or with minor interventions. Patients showed significant improvement in neurological symptoms.\r\nConclusion: The ETNTS approach provided effective tumor resection with minimal complications, shorter recovery, and reduced discomfort. While CSF leakage remains a challenge, the ETNTS technique proves valuable for selected intracranial lesions. A multidisciplinary approach is essential for maximizing patient safety and outcomes.', '', '“Minimally Invasive Mastery: Our Experience with the Endoscopic Transnasal Transsphenoidal Approach ', NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract: Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\r\nTitle: Combined Supraorbital and Endoscopic Approach for Lateral Fronto-orbital Mucocele Excision.\r\n                                                                                  Presenting Author: Dr Suji P.S\r\nLateral frontoorbital mucoceles are rare entities that present a surgical challenge due to their deep, lateral location and proximity to the orbit and anterior cranial fossa. While endoscopic sinus surgery has become the preferred approach for most frontal mucoceles, access to the lateral recess remains limited. We present a case of a lateral frontoorbital mucocele successfully excised using a combined supraorbital and endoscopic approach.\r\nA middle-aged patient presented with progressive right supraorbital swelling and dull frontal headache. CT and MRI scans revealed a well-defined, expansile lesion occupying the lateral frontal sinus and extending toward the orbital roof. A limited supraorbital incision provided direct access to the lateral component, while endoscopic transnasal access facilitated drainage and marsupialization of the medial extension. The mucocele was completely excised with preservation of orbital and neurovascular structures.\r\nThe combined approach offered excellent visualization and complete clearance of the lesion with minimal morbidity and a superior cosmetic outcome. This hybrid technique effectively overcomes the limitations of purely endoscopic or external approaches and represents a safe and cosmetically acceptable option for the management of laterally placed frontoorbital mucoceles.', '', '“Combined Supraorbital and Endoscopic Approach for Lateral Frontoorbital Mucocele Excision.”', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-21 06:41:07', '2025-10-21 06:41:10'),
(260, 'Pritansh Kumar Nikhar', 'pritanshkumar@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000124', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'AIM- To present outcome of excision of Juvenile nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma via endoscopic approach.\r\nMETHODOLOGY- Retrospective case series review of five cases of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma who presented to Department of ENT, IPGMER and SSKM Hospital, Kolkata. All patients underwent endoscopic excision preceded by embolization.\r\nRESULTS- All patients were Indian males, presenting with chief complaints of progressive unilateral nasal obstruction, spontaneous profuse epistaxsis, hyopsmia, sleep disturbance and unilateral heaviness in ear. The patient presentation comprised of Radkowski Ib to IIc stages, with one recurrence case. Internal Maxillary artery and Ascending Pharyngeal artery were the main blood supply to the lesion. surgical approach applied was endoscopic four- handed technique of excision. All patients were discharged well with no major complications nor cases of recurrence.\r\nCONCLUSION- Endoscopic approach is possible for various stages of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma. Preoperative angiographic embolization has minimalized blood loss intraoperatively. The endoscopic approach is a better and advanced treatment modality for excision of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma which has reduced post operative morbidity.', '', 'ENDOSCOPE IS MIGHTIER THAN SCALPEL: A PARADIGM SHIFT IN MANAGEMENT OF JUVENILE NASOPHARYNGEAL ANGIOF', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-21 19:17:29', '2025-10-21 19:17:32'),
(268, 'Apoorv Srivastava', 'apoorvsrivastava85@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000347', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'INTRODUCTION-Ewing\'s sarcoma are small round cell tumors belonging to Ewing\'s family of tumors and the second most common bone tumour seen in children. Primary arising in head and neck region is uncommon and maxillary Ewing\'s sarcoma is rarely seen. Histologically it is one of many small round cell tumors found in children and therefore immunohistochemical and occasionally molecular studies are required to establish the diagnosis. CASE REPORT-A 22‐year‐old female patient reported with a chief complaint of swelling on right side of face, gradually increasing in size. Swelling was insidious in onset. On physical appearance there was gross facial asymmetry with a well-circumscribed swelling measuring about 5 × 5 cm, on the right cheek. Movements of the eye was present. Acuity of vision was not altered. On palpation the swelling was non tender, bony hard in consistency. It was non-pulsatile and noncompressible. Anterior rhinoscopy reveals pinkish mass in right nasal cavity. INVESTIGATION AND MANAGEMENT-MRI shows large circumscribed mixed signal intensity soft tissue mass epicentre in right maxillary sinus, extending into right nasal cavity, right orbit, ethmoid sinus and premaxillary sinus, causing destruction of all walls of right maxillary sinus, right maxillary bone, inferomedial wall and floor of right orbit. A maxillectomy was performed including hard palate till midline.  Three weeks, postoperatively, the patient was referred for radiation and chemotherapy. Where 24 cycles of radiotherapy were done.  DISCUSSION- After osteosarcoma, Ewing’s Sarcoma is the second most frequent primary malignant tumor occurring in bone. However, it is rare for Ewing Sarcoma to be found in the head and neck region. Approximately 4% of Ewing’s sarcoma cases have arisen in the bones of head and neck with 1% occurring in the jaws. When the jaws are involved it frequently involves the mandible than maxilla. A painful swelling was the most common presentation. The majority of patients had a average tumour size of 6 × 4 cm. The lesion is predominantly seen in children and young adults. Ewing’s sarcoma is a radiosensitive tumour. Multimodality therapy consisting of an initial biopsy, aggressive combination of surgery, chemotherapy and localized radiotherapy is the treatment of choice for Ewing’s sarcoma of the head andneck region and may result in long-term survival.', '/public/upload/abstract/371d63a45a97e92b13dd0e30857cf8ed.docx', 'RARE PRESENTATION OF EWING’S SARCOMA IN MAXILLA', 2, 1, '2025-10-28 00:39:25', '2025-10-28 00:39:28'),
(269, 'Dr Swati Tewari', 'swatitwr4@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000472', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE: Outcomes of septal perforation repair using an Anterior ethmoidal artery flap and Collagen Matrix \r\nPresenting Author: Dr Swati Tewari,\r\nCo-authors Prof Satyawati Mohindra, Prof Ramandeep Singh Virk \r\nAIM: -To evaluate the efficacy and safety of endoscopic nasal septal perforation (NSP) repair using an anterior ethmoidal artery (AEA) flap combined with a collagen matrix inlay and assess its impact on quality of life.\r\nMETHODOLOGY: - This prospective case series included five patients with symptomatic anterior NSPs who underwent endoscopic repair using an AEA pedicled flap reinforced with a collagen matrix graft. Patients were followed postoperatively on day 21 and day 90. Primary outcomes assessed were anatomical closure and mucosalization, while secondary outcomes included complication rates and quality-of-life improvements using the Septal Perforation Quality of Life (SEPEQOL) questionnaire.\r\nRESULTS: - Complete closure of the perforation was achieved in 60% of patients, with contralateral mucosalization in 80% at postoperative day (POD) 21 and 60% at POD 90. Only one patient (20%) experienced postoperative crusting. SEPEQOL scores showed statistically significant improvement in nasal congestion (2.6→0.4, p=0.01), nasal blockage (1.8→0.2, p=0.01), and air hunger (1.6→0.1, p=0.009). No major complications or graft failures were observed.\r\nCONCLUSION: - Endoscopic NSP repair using an anterior ethmoidal artery flap with a collagen matrix is a safe, effective technique for small to medium-sized anterior perforations. It provides high closure rates, promotes mucosal healing, and significantly enhances patient quality of life. Further large-scale studies are recommended to validate these findings.', '/public/upload/abstract/ba3abb00d7779cd98891f677b8cca8b8.docx', 'Outcomes of septal perforation repair using an Anterior ethmoidal artery flap and Collagen Matrix', NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nEntomophthoromycosis is a rare, chronic fungal infection predominantly affecting immunocompetent individuals in tropical and subtropical regions. Caused by Conidiobolus and Basidiobolus species, it primarily involves nasal and facial subcutaneous tissues, often mimicking other granulomatous\r\n Aim:\r\nTo present a short case series highlighting the clinical spectrum, diagnostic approach, and successful management of rhino-facial Entomophthoromycosis in immunocompetent patients.\r\nCase Report:\r\nFour male patients aged 2–19 years presented with nasal obstruction and facial swelling of 3–9 months duration. Diagnosis was confirmed through clinico-histopathological correlation demonstrating granulomatous inflammation with the Splendore-Hoeppli phenomenon. All cases were managed surgically through biopsy followed by medical therapy using liposomal amphotericin B, supersaturated potassium iodide (SSKI), and itraconazole. Patients showed complete recovery and remained disease-free during 1–13 years of follow-up.\r\nDiscussion:\r\nDue to its indolent course and clinical resemblance to other granulomatous diseases, Entomophthoromycosis often faces delayed diagnosis. Histopathology remains crucial, while combination antifungal therapy offers optimal results.\r\nConclusion:\r\nEarly recognition, prompt histological confirmation, and combined antifungal therapy ensure favorable outcomes in rhino-facial Entomophthoromycosis. Heightened clinician awareness in endemic areas can prevent morbidity and facial disfigurement.', '/public/upload/abstract/7c8ef469ef063c7bdb807ba2fff122f0.docx', 'ENTOMOPHTHOROMYCOSIS – THE TROPICAL FUNGAL INFILTRATOR', 2, 1, '2025-10-29 22:17:32', '2025-10-29 22:17:35'),
(270, 'MOHANRAJ S', 'mohanraj1757@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000488', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo present a rare case of an ectopic maxillary tooth presenting as chronic sinusitis and to emphasize the value of a combined surgical approach for successful management.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 30-year-old male presented with unilateral nasal obstruction, purulent nasal discharge, and facial heaviness unresponsive to medical therapy. Nasal endoscopy showed mucopurulent discharge from the right middle meatus. CT paranasal sinuses revealed a radiodense tooth-like structure within the right maxillary sinus. The patient underwent a combined Caldwell-Luc and endoscopic middle meatal antrostomy for removal of the ectopic tooth and sinus clearance.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe tooth was removed completely without complications. Postoperatively, the patient had complete relief of symptoms, and follow-up imaging showed a healthy, aerated maxillary sinus. Histopathology confirmed chronic inflammatory changes consistent with sinusitis.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nEctopic tooth in the maxillary sinus, though rare, should be considered in unilateral, refractory sinusitis. A combined Caldwell-Luc and endoscopic approach offers excellent visualization, complete removal, and long-term disease resolution with minimal morbidity.', '/public/upload/abstract/4d787e372f3b725195d795900b7a3e99.docx', 'An Anomalous Tooth Masquerading as Chronic Maxillary Sinusitis: A Rare Case Report', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-10-30 12:17:03', '2025-10-30 12:17:08');
