(271, 'Balakumar Y', 'bala2343@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000499', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Objective\r\nTo highlight an uncommon presentation of isolated third cranial nerve palsy as a complication of allergic fungal rhinosinusitis (AFRS), and to emphasize the importance of early recognition and management to prevent long-term neurological deficits.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nA 64-year-old female presented with gradual-onset right-sided ptosis and diplopia over 3 weeks, associated with nasal obstruction and intermittent headache. On examination, there was complete right-sided ptosis with impaired ocular movements consistent with isolated third cranial nerve palsy. Pupillary reaction was sluggish. Nasal endoscopy was completely normal. CT paranasal sinuses showed hyperdense areas within the right sphenoid sinus suggestive of allergic fungal rhinosinusitis with extension to cavernous sinus and orbit. \r\n\r\nResult\r\nThe patient underwent functional endoscopic sinus surgery (FESS) with debridement of allergic mucin and fungal debris. Histopathological examination confirmed allergic fungal rhinosinusitis. Postoperatively, the patient was managed with systemic corticosteroids. At 4-week follow-up, there was partial improvement in ptosis and ocular motility, indicating early recovery of third nerve function.\r\n\r\nDiscussion\r\nIsolated third cranial nerve palsy as a manifestation of allergic fungal rhinosinusitis is extremely rare. The mechanism involves compressive or inflammatory neuropathy due to fungal-induced sinus expansion or inflammation extending to the orbital apex. Early surgical intervention combined with medical management can result in favorable outcomes. Radiological evaluation plays a crucial role in detecting disease extension and differentiating it from other causes such as neoplasms or vascular lesions.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nAFRS can rarely present with isolated third cranial nerve palsy due to involvement of the orbital apex. Prompt recognition, imaging, and combined medical-surgical management are essential to prevent irreversible neurological damage and optimize recovery.', '/public/upload/abstract/f60a7db3df20752f022616f4bc43dba5.docx', 'Isolated Third Cranial Nerve Palsy Secondary to Allergic Fungal Rhinosinusitis (AFRS)', 2, 1, '2025-10-31 16:50:01', '2025-10-31 16:50:05'),
(272, 'Dr Hafees Abdullah Perumbally', 'drhafeesabdullah@gmail.com', 'ME002501203', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Endoscopic Draf III for a Fronto-orbital Mucocele Presenting with Isolated Ptosis in an adolescent female: Case Description and Video Demonstration.\r\nCase Report: A 16-year-old female with no comorbidities presented with progressive left-eye ptosis of 15 days duration. Clinical examination showed isolated partial ptosis without ophthalmoplegia or vision loss. CT imaging revealed a left frontal sinus mucocele with erosive bony changes of the frontal sinus posterior wall and floor. After multidisciplinary discussion she underwent endoscopic frontal sinus drainage via a Draf III (endoscopic modified Lothrop) approach. The procedure was video-recorded for demonstration. Intra-operative findings included frank mucocele contents and sclerotic frontal sinus walls. The postoperative course was uneventful; ptosis improved over days to weeks and the patient remains well on follow up with a patent frontal neo-ostium on endoscopic inspection.\r\nDiscussion & Conclusion: Endoscopic Draf III provided safe, definitive drainage and decompression of the frontal mucocele causing orbital symptoms in this adolescent patient, avoiding open external approaches. Early endoscopic management can result in rapid symptomatic recovery and good ostial patency. This case is accompanied by an intra-operative video illustrating key technical steps when frontal sinus walls are eroded and orbit is at risk.', '/public/upload/abstract/d505b94e4e851fea883ad4b8c730c789.docx', 'Endoscopic Draf III for a Fronto-orbital Mucocele Presenting with Isolated Ptosis in an adolescent f', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-02 22:57:24', '2025-11-02 22:57:27'),
(273, 'Nikhil Jacob', 'n3niks1@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000198', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'A 46-year-old male, a tea maker by profession, presented with right eye pain, proptosis, headache, and nasal obstruction. He was referred from Ophthalmology after MRI orbit revealed an inflammatory sinonasal lesion. CT and MRI of paranasal sinuses suggested invasive fungal sinusitis. Initial inpatient biopsy was non-diagnostic. A repeat biopsy and lavage during FESS revealed granulomatous inflammation. The patient was managed with surgery, antifungal, and anti-tubercular therapy, achieving complete recovery.', '/public/upload/abstract/c2d40e9c7b94dea7dd968f1524ad86ca.docx', 'Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery for Chronic Granulomatous Fungal Rhinosinusitis with Tuberculoid', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-05 11:58:28', '2025-11-05 11:58:32'),
(274, 'Dr SETHU MADHAVAN S', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract\r\n\r\nBackground:\r\nChronic Suppurative Otitis Media (CSOM) is a persistent infection of the middle ear and mastoid cavity, characterized by ear discharge and tympanic membrane perforation. It continues to be a significant cause of morbidity, especially in developing countries. Complications may arise due to bone erosion or venous thrombophlebitis, leading to extracranial or intracranial spread.\r\n\r\nAims and Objectives:\r\n\r\n1. To assess and analyze patients presenting with complications of CSOM.\r\n\r\n\r\n2. To evaluate postoperative outcomes following surgical management.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMaterials and Methods:\r\nA prospective case series was conducted on patients diagnosed with CSOM and its complications. Each patient underwent detailed clinical, audiological, and radiological evaluation, followed by appropriate surgical intervention and postoperative follow-up.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe most common complications encountered were mastoid abscess, facial nerve palsy, and intracranial extension. Most patients showed favorable postoperative recovery with surgery and antibiotics. Early recognition and timely intervention prevented permanent sequelae and reduced morbidity.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCSOM remains a prevalent and preventable cause of morbidity. Early diagnosis, proper imaging, and prompt surgical management play vital roles in preventing severe and potentially life-threatening complications.', '/public/upload/abstract/35f7e2ec56fca922349f4a56d22380e1.docx', 'A clinical profile of chronic suppurative otitis media patients with complications - A case series', 2, 1, '2025-11-05 12:12:18', '2025-11-05 12:12:21'),
(275, 'Dr SETHU MADHAVAN S', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo review the current understanding of the immunopathogenesis of chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRSwNP) and analyze the clinical implications of the EPOS 2020 guidelines in diagnosis and management.\r\n\r\nObjectives:\r\n\r\n1. To describe the immunologic mechanisms underlying CRSwNP with emphasis on type 2 inflammation.\r\n\r\n\r\n2. To outline the diagnostic criteria and classification according to EPOS 2020.\r\n\r\n\r\n3. To evaluate updated recommendations for medical and surgical management.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMethods:\r\nA comprehensive review of recent literature and the EPOS 2020 position paper was performed. Studies focusing on cytokine profiles, eosinophilic inflammation, microbiome influence, and treatment outcomes were analyzed. Management strategies were compared between traditional steroid-based therapy and newer targeted biologic approaches.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nCRSwNP is predominantly driven by type 2 immune response characterized by elevated IL-4, IL-5, IL-13, and eosinophilic infiltration. EPOS 2020 emphasizes a multidisciplinary, endotype-driven approach integrating clinical phenotype, inflammatory biomarkers, and radiologic grading (Lund-Mackay score). Topical corticosteroids remain first-line therapy, while short systemic courses are reserved for exacerbations. Endoscopic sinus surgery (ESS) is recommended for medically refractory cases, followed by postoperative intranasal therapy. Biologic agents such as dupilumab, omalizumab, and mepolizumab are advised for recurrent, severe, eosinophilic disease.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nEPOS 2020 has redefined CRSwNP as a chronic, type 2–mediated inflammatory disease requiring personalized, multidisciplinary care. Integration of immunologic profiling, optimized medical therapy, and biologic treatment has improved long-term outcomes and reduced recurrence rates. Continued research into immunomodulation and precision medicine is essential for future management.', '/public/upload/abstract/2e7c5b2345ef94a89acd0c7f0baeed6b.docx', 'Topic: Chronic Rhinosinusitis with Nasal Polyposis – Immunologic Insights and EPOS 2020 Guidelines', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-05 12:31:48', '2025-11-05 12:31:51'),
(276, 'Nikhil Jacob', 'n3niks1@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000198', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nBranchial apparatus anomalies arise from incomplete embryonic cleft involution. Among these, second branchial cleft anomalies are the most common and can present as cysts, sinuses, or fistulae. Branchial sinuses are relatively rare and often manifest as a discharging opening along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle.\r\n\r\nCase Report:\r\nA 15-year-old female presented with a history of intermittent discharge from a small opening on the lower neck for five years. Examination revealed a tiny sinus opening along the anterior border of the right sternocleidomastoid muscle, with no other associated neck abnormalities. CECT neck and CT sinogram demonstrated a blind-ending sinus tract extending from the skin to the right greater horn of the hyoid bone, measuring approximately 6.7 cm × 4 mm × 5 mm. The patient underwent surgical excision of the sinus tract using the stepladder technique, which provided excellent exposure and ensured complete tract removal. A 12 cm tract extending up to the right tonsillar fossa was excised in toto and sent for histopathological examination. The postoperative period was uneventful, and no recurrence was observed at the 3-month follow-up.\r\n\r\nDiscussion:\r\nThe branchial apparatus develops between the 3rd and 8th weeks of embryogenesis and comprises arches, pouches, and clefts. Failure of complete involution of the second branchial cleft can result in sinus or fistula formation. Surgical excision remains the gold standard of management, as incomplete removal leads to recurrence. The stepladder technique provides optimum exposure, ensuring the identification and total excision of the tract, thereby minimizing recurrence.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nBranchial sinus should be considered in the differential diagnosis of a persistent discharging neck sinus, particularly along the sternocleidomastoid. Complete excision using the stepladder technique remains the definitive management approach to prevent recurrence.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Branchial sinus, Second branchial cleft, Stepladder technique, Embryology, Neck sinus', '/public/upload/abstract/e0c27a4777a900efa18a82f62d3f1bcb.docx', NULL, 1, 1, '2025-11-05 13:04:37', '2025-11-05 13:04:37'),
(277, 'Nikhil Jacob', 'n3niks1@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000198', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\nIntroduction:\r\nBranchial apparatus anomalies arise from incomplete embryonic cleft involution. Among these, second branchial cleft anomalies are the most common and can present as cysts, sinuses, or fistulae. Branchial sinuses are relatively rare and often manifest as a discharging opening along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle.\r\nCase Report:\r\nA 15-year-old female presented with a history of intermittent discharge from a small opening on the lower neck for five years. Examination revealed a tiny sinus opening along the anterior border of the right sternocleidomastoid muscle, with no other associated neck abnormalities. CECT neck and CT sinogram demonstrated a blind-ending sinus tract extending from the skin to the right greater horn of the hyoid bone, measuring approximately 6.7 cm × 4 mm × 5 mm. The patient underwent surgical excision of the sinus tract using the stepladder technique, which provided excellent exposure and ensured complete tract removal. A 12 cm tract extending up to the right tonsillar fossa was excised in toto and sent for histopathological examination. The postoperative period was uneventful, and no recurrence was observed at the 3-month follow-up.\r\nDiscussion:\r\nThe branchial apparatus develops between the 3rd and 8th weeks of embryogenesis and comprises arches, pouches, and clefts. Failure of complete involution of the second branchial cleft can result in sinus or fistula formation. Surgical excision remains the gold standard of management, as incomplete removal leads to recurrence. The stepladder technique provides optimum exposure, ensuring the identification and total excision of the tract, thereby minimizing recurrence.\r\nConclusion:\r\nBranchial sinus should be considered in the differential diagnosis of a persistent discharging neck sinus, particularly along the sternocleidomastoid. Complete excision using the stepladder technique remains the definitive management approach to prevent recurrence.', '/public/upload/abstract/0faf7db093431bed8c75ed21316db30d.docx', 'Embryology’s Lingering Footprint – Branchial Sinus: A Case Report', 1, 1, '2025-11-05 13:15:11', '2025-11-05 13:15:11'),
(280, 'Kaviyarasi V', 'vkaviyarasi@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000474', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-06 22:21:07', '2025-11-06 22:21:10'),
(281, 'Kaviyarasi V', 'vkaviyarasi@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000474', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: “Sniffles in the Classroom: Unmasking Allergic Rhinitis in School Children”\r\nBackground: Allergic rhinitis (AR) is a common, IgE-mediated nasal inflammation causing congestion, rhinorrhea, sneezing, and itching. It affects up to 40% of children worldwide and can impair sleep, concentration, and school performance. In India, prevalence ranges from 7% to 30%, influenced by pollution and lifestyle changes. Despite its high burden, AR often remains underdiagnosed and undertreated, especially in rural settings.\r\nObjectives: 1. To determine the prevalence of AR among school-going children aged 8–14 years in Melmaruvathur.\r\n2.	To assess its impact on health-related quality of life (HRQoL).\r\nMethods:\r\nA questionnaire-based cross-sectional study was conducted among 613 children (8–14 years) from GB Public School, Melmaruvathur. Data were collected using the International Study of Asthma and Allergies in Childhood (ISAAC) questionnaire with ARIA severity grading.\r\nResults:\r\nAbout 81% of children reported worsening symptoms during certain months, and 67% had itchy-watery eyes. The prevalence of nasal symptoms was 28%, while 14% had allergic rhino-conjunctivitis. Around 15% reported interference with daily activities. ‘Blockers’ (61%) were more common than ‘sneeze-runners’ (39%). More than half (56%) had comorbidities such as asthma or eczema. Major allergens included pollens, house-dust mites, pets, molds, and certain foods.\r\nConclusion:\r\nAllergic rhinitis is prevalent among school-aged children and significantly affects their daily life and school performance. Early diagnosis, parental awareness, and timely management can help reduce morbidity and improve quality of life. Broader community-based studies are needed to better understand risk factors and prevention strategies.', '/public/upload/abstract/2f5de41434424f06670bac87dfe35875.docx', '“Sniffles in the Classroom: Unmasking Allergic Rhinitis in School Children”', 2, 1, '2025-11-06 22:55:38', '2025-11-06 22:55:42'),
(282, 'Dr Aarushi Vashist', 'aaavashist@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000524', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\nPresenting Author- Dr. Aarushi Vashist\r\nAssistant Professor ENT, Kalpana Chawla Government Medical College Karnal, Haryana\r\nIntroduction:\r\nSinonasal malignancies are rare and heterogeneous tumours of nasal cavity and paranasal\r\nsinuses which comprise only 3% of tumours of head and neck region. They arise most\r\ncommonly in the maxillary sinus but other sinuses can also be involved.\r\nPresenting symptoms:\r\nThe patients with unusual sinonasal tumours present with vague symptoms like nasal\r\nobstruction, nasal discharge, facial pain etc. which mimics benign sinonasal diseases like\r\nnasal polyps. So, the diagnosis requires high level of clinical suspicion followed by accurate\r\ndiagnosis and proper management. Here, we present a rare case series comprising of\r\neosinophilic angiocentric fibrosis, sinonasal neuro-endocrine tumour, adenoid cystic\r\ncarcinoma of nose and sinonasal myxoma. Diagnosis was done by clinical findings\r\nsupplemented by CT Scan and MRI. Biopsy was done to confirm the diagnosis. Treatment\r\nwas done by surgery and post op radiotherapy and chemotherapy depending on the diagnosis.\r\nConclusion:\r\nA proper clinical suspicion of these malignancies should be there while dealing with the\r\npatients presenting with vague sinonasal problems so that timely and effective management\r\ncan be done.', '/public/upload/abstract/3efcf69e7fedb1d93ddc35f8421861fa.docx', 'Unusual Sinonasal Tumors in a Tertiary Care Centre: Case Series.', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-07 19:08:17', '2025-11-07 19:08:20'),
(283, 'Dr.Sonali Sharma', 'Sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-07 21:54:43', '2025-11-07 21:54:46'),
(284, 'RAHUL MAURYA', 'rahul1998maurya@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000201', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE - Schwannoma of the nasolabial area : A case report\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR- Dr. Rahul Maurya\r\nABSTRACT\r\nINTRODUCTION- Schwannoma of nasolabial region are rare, here we present a case of schwannoma of nasolabial area.\r\nCASE REPORT- A 34-year-old male presented with painless and gradually enlarging right side nasolabial mass for 7 years, associated with nasal obstruction for 2 years. Examination revealed a non-tender bulge in the nasolabial area, at the level of vestibule obscuring the view of right nasal cavity with deviated nasal septum to left. FNAC was suggestive of Benign spindle cell lesion. CECT Paranasal sinus showed presence of soft tissue density mass 34*29*35mm in vestibule of right nasal cavity showing focal areas of enhancement causing mild pressure erosion and scalloping of underlying maxillary alveolar margin. The lesion was surgically excised via sublabial approach and was sent for histopathological examination which was reported as schwannoma.\r\nDISCUSSION: Schwannomas are benign, slow growing encapsulated tumors, they most frequently occur in the head and neck region, accounting for approximately 25–45% of all cases, but their occurrence within the nasolabial area is rare, representing less than 4% of head and neck schwannomas.\r\nCONCLUSION- Nasal schwannomas are rare benign peripheral nerve sheath tumors that may mimic other intranasal pathologies. Comprehensive evaluation with imaging and histopathological confirmation is essential for accurate diagnosis. Complete surgical excision remains the definitive treatment and is associated with excellent functional and cosmetic outcomes, as well as a very low likelihood of recurrence.', '/public/upload/abstract/0ab261bbf2050c6b1dfbd5954661f4a4.docx', 'Schwannoma of the nasolabial area : A case report', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 02:17:22', '2025-11-09 02:17:26'),
(285, 'Anukaran Mahajan', 'dranukaranent@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000481', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression is a valuable surgical intervention for reducing orbital pressure, restoring ocular function, and improving cosmesis in patients with diverse orbital pathologies. This video presents a case series of six patients who underwent orbital decompression. Each patient underwent tailored surgical planning based on clinical presentation, imaging findings, and anticipated functional and aesthetic outcomes. All patients experienced significant symptom relief, improved orbital volume, and satisfactory cosmetic outcomes. Postoperative follow-up at three to six months confirmed sustained improvement with no major complications. This series emphasizes the importance of transnasal endoscopic orbital decompression in managing a spectrum of orbital diseases, the importance of individualized surgical planning, and the role of precise technique in achieving optimal prognosis.', '/public/upload/abstract/6094df8d84ab4a1cf69cb5119f3dbd7e.docx', 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression: A Case Series', 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression is a valuable surgical intervention for reducing orbital pressure, restoring ocular function, and improving cosmesis in patients with diverse orbital pathologies. This video presents a case series of six patients who underwent orbital decompression. Each patient underwent tailored surgical planning based on clinical presentation, imaging findings, and anticipated functional and aesthetic outcomes. All patients experienced significant symptom relief, improved orbital volume, and satisfactory cosmetic outcomes. Postoperative follow-up at three to six months confirmed sustained improvement with no major complications. This series emphasizes the importance of transnasal endoscopic orbital decompression in managing a spectrum of orbital diseases, the importance of individualized surgical planning, and the role of precise technique in achieving optimal prognosis.', '/public/upload/abstract/6094df8d84ab4a1cf69cb5119f3dbd7e.docx', 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression: A Case Series', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 16:04:20', '2025-11-09 16:04:23'),
(286, 'Dr Shweta Chauhan', 'shwetachauhanx09@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000457', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', 'Mucormycosis', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 18:58:15', '2025-11-09 18:58:19'),
(287, 'Dr Shweta Chauhan', 'shwetachauhanx09@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000457', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'MUCORMYCOSIS \r\n                                               Presented by : Dr Shweta Chauhan     \r\n                         \r\nINTRODUCTION : Mucormycosis, also known as zygomycosis, is a rare but aggressive opportunistic fungal infection caused by fungi belonging to the order Mucorales (genera Rhizopus, Mucor, Lichtheimia, Cunninghamella, and others). It is characterized by angioinvasion, leading to vascular thrombosis, tissue necrosis, and rapid progression, often with a fulminant and fatal course if not diagnosed early and treated aggressively.\r\nAIM AND OBJECTIVE: of this poster is to present a case of Rhinomucormycosis that was treated with the help of Inferior maxillectomy and intravenous Liposomal Amphoterecin B.\r\nMETHODOLOGY:Her is a case of Atul , 41yr old male adult from Kangra , Himachal Pradesh, who was referred to us by the department of medicine with history of abnormal body movements and ulcer on the hard palate where he was being treated for Chronic liver disease with cirrhosis.On investigations we found, Hb - 9.5g/dl , TLC - 5910, Hba1c- 9 , Rbs- 220 mg/ dl . KOH mount:negative for fungal hyphae,Hrct nose+pns:b/l chronic pansinusitis with bony rarefaction, b/l blocked osteomeatal complexes,frontal & sphenoidal recesses, rightward deviated nasal septum with left inferior and middle turbinate hypertrophy and left concha bullosa.Patient was treated by  Inferior Maxillectomy Left Side Under Ga On Dated 19/04/2025 and HPE report showed hard palate, maxilla, maxillary mucosa consistent with fungal sinusitis with angioinvasion and underlying bone involvment possibly mucormycosis and was given : inj levitracetam , inj piptaz , inj pantop , inj liposomal amphotericin b ,inj insulin r 8 units tds,inj glargine 10 unit s/c od, tab aspirin , tab atorvastatin , syrup lactulose ,inj pcm , inj metro,tab dytor plus,tab carvidol,tab rifaximin , Post op MRI brain: p/o/c rhinomucormycosis with inferior maxillectomy present scan shows . residual / recurrent disease involving the left maxillary sinus with focal cerebrotis / infarct involving left frontal parasagittal lobe. The patient improved significantly.\r\nRESULT:The patients wife requested for referral and was referred to PGI chandigarh where he was started on oral Posaconazole and improved.\r\nCONCLUSION: Mucormycosis is a medical emergency requiring rapid diagnosis and aggressive management.Awareness post-COVID is essential, especially in diabetic and immunocompromised patients.Early surgical intervention and antifungal therapy improve prognosis.', '/public/upload/abstract/a11ee8b4df8219b78d2d536323f149c8.docx', 'Mucormycosis', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 19:00:50', '2025-11-09 19:00:54'),
(288, 'Dr.Sonali sharma', 'sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Rhabdomyosarcoma Masquerading as Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma\r\nPresenting Author: \r\nDr. Sonali Sharma\r\nAim: \r\nTo highlight a rare case of embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma of the nasal cavity presenting with clinical features suggestive of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA 17-year-old male presented with recurrent epistaxis, nasal obstruction, left eye proptosis, and noisy breathing. Examination revealed a reddish polypoidal mass in both nasal cavities. Provisional diagnosis of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma or esthesioneuroblastoma was made. Biopsy was performed for histopathological confirmation.\r\nResults: \r\nHistopathological examination revealed features consistent with embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma. \r\nConclusions: \r\nRhabdomyosarcoma of the nasal cavity can clinically mimic juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. This case underscores the need for tissue diagnosis in all suspected vascular nasal masses to avoid misdiagnosis and to initiate appropriate multidisciplinary treatment promptly.', '/public/upload/abstract/b973ed60aad85f5cafb1ca715e7b030a.docx', 'Rhabdomyosarcoma masquearding as juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:12:39', '2025-11-09 20:12:42'),
(289, 'Dr.Sonali sharma', 'sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension\r\nPresenting Author: \r\nProf. Dr. Jagdeep Singh Thakur\r\nDr. Sarita Negi\r\nDr. Sonali Sharma\r\nAim: \r\nTo evaluate the role and effectiveness of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration in preserving vision in patients with idiopathic intracranial hypertension.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA review of published literature and institutional experience was conducted. Data from recent meta-analyses and clinical studies organized in the ENT Department, IGMC Shimla, were analyzed to assess outcomes of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration and decompression. Parameters studied included improvement in visual acuity, visual field, and headache relief, as well as reported complications. Comparative evaluation of transnasal and transconjunctival approaches was also performed..\r\nResults: \r\nMajority of patients showed improvement in visual symptoms and headache. Transnasal endoscopic approach demonstrated good results with minimal complications like diplopia and CSF leak.\r\nConclusions: \r\nEndoscopic optic nerve fenestration is a safe and effective option for managing idiopathic intracranial hypertension. The transnasal route offers better visualization and low morbidity.', '/public/upload/abstract/6594bb44120c5a3930a610db17b9e7c0.docx', 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:16:16', '2025-11-09 20:16:19'),
(290, 'Priya', 'priyaclassxii@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000251', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of paper : Comparative Analysis of the Visual Analogue Scale (VAS) and Nasal Obstruction Symptom Evaluation (NOSE) Score in the Evaluation of Post - Septoplasty Patients.\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Priya ( Resident Dept.of ENT &HNS, GMC JAMMU )\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n\r\nAim: To compare and establish correlation between the NOSE score and VAS score in measuring symptomatic relief in patients undergoing septoplasty .\r\n\r\nMethodology : Sixty patients with deviated nasal septum who underwent septoplasty within period of 8 months were included in the study. NOSE score & VAS score (out of 100) was documented before and after surgery. Results were correlated and compared statistically.\r\n\r\nResults:  NOSE score analysis indicated that trouble breathing through the nose and nasal obstruction or blockage were the most bothersome preoperative symptoms, with mean scores of 83.60 and 80.35, respectively. Significant postoperative improvement was observed in both NOSE and VAS scores at 1- and 3-months follow-ups (Wilcoxon test, p < 0.05). Spearman’s correlation confirmed a positive relationship between the two scoring systems, though NOSE score was found to be superior.\r\n\r\nConclusion: NOSE and VAS scores were both effective tools for assessing postoperative outcomes after septoplasty ; however, NOSE score exhibited superior sensitivity in detecting symptomatic improvement and correlated more strongly with patient satisfaction.', '/public/upload/abstract/602072520cfccbd62ded84991f2f214e.docx', 'Comparative Analysis of the Visual Analogue Scale (VAS) and Nasal Obstruction Symptom Evaluation (NO', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:40:35', '2025-11-09 20:40:39'),
(291, 'Ramneet kour', 'Ramneetkour2000@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000250', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title of paper : Comparative Evaluation of Submucosal Diathermy and Coblation- Assisted Turbinate Reduction in Patients with Inferior Turbinate Hypertrophy .\r\n\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ramneet Kour ( Junior Resident Dept. of ENT &HNS , GMC JAMMU )\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n\r\nAim: To compare the efficacy and postoperative outcomes of submucosal diathermy and coblation in the reduction of hypertrophied inferior turbinates, using subjective assessments.\r\n\r\nMethods: This is a comparative study conducted in the Department of ENT & HNS at GMC Jammu over a period of 8 months .This study aimed to compare the efficacy and outcomes of submucosal diathermy (SMD) and coblation- assisted turbinate reduction in forty patients with inferior turbinate hypertrophy using subjective assessment scores.\r\n\r\nResults: According to the findings obtained in our study, both submucosal diathermy and coblation techniques resulted in significant improvement in nasal obstruction. However, the degree of symptomatic relief was greater in the patients treated with coblation. Moreover, coblation was associated with less intraoperative and postoperative pain. The difference between the two methods was statistically significant (p < 0.05).\r\n\r\nConclusion: Both techniques were effective in reducing nasal obstruction. However, Coblation produced superior symptomatic improvement and fewer postoperative complications compared to submucosal diathermy.', '/public/upload/abstract/077b843d6b6923034e236ad8c1ae9f59.docx', 'Comparative Evaluation of Submucosal Diathermy and Coblation- Assisted Turbinate Reduction in Patien', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:40:47', '2025-11-09 20:40:50'),
(292, 'Rohini Deepa I', 'Deepi.deepa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000450', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'POSTNASAL NEURECTOMY IN REFRACTORY RHINITIS\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION:\r\n\r\nPost nasal neurectomy is a surgical technique performed to treat patients with chronic refractory rhinitis, especially those unresponsive to conventional medical management. The procedure involves sectioning the posterior nasal nerve, which carries parasympathetic secretomotor fibers to the nasal mucosa. By reducing hyperactive parasympathetic input, symptoms such as rhinorrhea, nasal obstruction, and sneezing are significantly alleviated.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAIM:\r\n\r\nTo evaluate the effectiveness of postnasal neurectomy in managing patients with refractory allergic and non-allergic rhinitis.\r\n\r\nMATERIALS AND METHODS:\r\n\r\nThe study included patients presenting to ENT OPD with refractory rhinitis unresponsive to antihistamines, intranasal corticosteroids, and immunotherapy. Post nasal neurectomy was performed endoscopically. The patients were followed up postoperatively for 1 year, and outcomes were assessed using symptom scores and quality-of-life questionnaires.\r\n\r\nRESULTS:\r\n\r\nPost nasal neurectomy demonstrated significant improvement in nasal obstruction, sneezing frequency, and rhinorrhea. Complications were minimal, with only transient nasal dryness observed in a few patients. Long-term follow-up showed sustained symptom relief in the majority of patients.', '/public/upload/abstract/cebaa075c61a5ae6574b6425ba750441.docx', 'Post Nasal Neurectomy', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-09 22:33:56', '2025-11-09 22:33:59'),
(293, 'Dr. Rashmi Agarwal', 'drrashmi65@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000506', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Title- Anterior and Central Skull Base Fibrous Dysplasia: A 12 Years’ Experience\r\nPresenting Author – Dr. Rashmi Agarwal, Assistant Professor GMC, Sri Ganganagar\r\nAim – Fibrous dysplasia, specially of anterior and central skull base region, is a rare disorder. This article discusses about our experience in this pathology over last 12 years and discusses various clinic-pathological aspects of fibrous dysplasia.\r\nMethodology – A tertiary care institute based retrospective type study was conducted over a period of 12 years. Demographics, radiology, intraoperative details, pathology and follow up were taken into consideration and the data was analysed.\r\nResults – . Sixteen patients with complaints of proptosis, diplopia, nasal obstruction and/or facial deformity, underwent endoscopic sinus surgery. Subtotal resection was done in 5 patients. Ethmoid bone involvement was seen in 12 patients. Post operatively, diplopia persisted in one patient and one patient had epistaxis. All patients were followed up for 2–10 years with no other complications reported.\r\nConclusion – Anterior and central skull base involvement is rare in fibrous dysplasia. However, it can be removed effectively by endoscopic approach. Overall safety of patient has more concern rather than complete removal of disease', '/public/upload/abstract/896a5a6fb2fe223392671f8de3fc7245.docx', 'Anterior and Central Skull Base Fibrous Dysplasia: A 12 Years’ Experience', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-09 23:01:33', '2025-11-09 23:01:37'),
(294, 'santosh shivaswamy', 'drsantosh.s@gmail.com', 'RHIN000477', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Author : Dr.Santosh.Shivaswamy Senior Consultant ENT & Head & neck Surgeon , Manipal Hospital , Hebbal ,Bangalore \r\n\r\nAim : Study aimed at comparing the intra operative (blood loss, duration of surgery)\r\n and post operative results (crusting, scarring, discharge, symptoms, recurrence) \r\nbetween the two groups using Lund-Mackay scoring system and the data was \r\nstatistically analysed\r\n\r\nMethods : A study was conducted on 40 cases of nasal polypi in a tertiary care hospital. 20 cases underwent co-ablation ass FESS and 20 using the microdebrider ass FESS.  \r\n\r\nResults : There was no statistically significant difference in surgical outcome for patients with either of methods. With Coablation ass FESS the comfort of doing surgery was better,saline irrigation gave better visualization and  blood loss was less .There was no need for the usage of tranexamic acid intra /post operatively in the co-ablation group .\r\n\r\nConclusion:The use of Co-ablation in endoscopic sinus surgery has the advantage of complete clearance of disease, uneventful intra operative course and better mucosal preservation &  post operative healing when compared to microdebrider in the treatment of nasal polyps.', '/public/upload/abstract/1da70df94af2f8841db3839a37b8254c.doc', 'A Comparison of microdebrider assisted FESS  and co-ablation assisted  FESS for nasal polypi', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 09:51:58', '2025-11-10 09:52:01'),
(295, 'Sarit Negi', 'Saritasharmanegi86@gmail.com', '1177', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'AIM:\r\n\r\nTo evaluate the efficacy of various treatments of chronic rhino- sinusitis with nasal polyposis on cardiopulmonary functions.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\n\r\nA prospective, interventional, open-label, randomised study was conducted at the IGMC Shimla, involving 61 patients. Subjects were randomly assigned to either the medical or surgical group. The medical group received intranasal corticosteroids, while the surgical group underwent endoscopic sinus surgery. Cardiopulmonary parameters were assessed using spirometry and echocardiography at baseline, three months, and six months.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n\r\nBoth groups demonstrated improvements in SNOT24 scores and pulmonary function too. However, the surgical group exhibited more pronounced improvements. Endoscopic sinus surgery demonstrated superior efficacy in enhancing right ventricular functions compared to intranasal corticosteroids alone.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\n\r\nChronic rhino-sinusitis with nasal polyposis can significantly impair cardiopulmonary functions. Therefore, endoscopic sinus surgery emerges as a more effective treatment modality for alleviating cardiopulmonary dysfunction in such cases.', '/public/upload/abstract/8a34f08a23225867f38d965a093a87ce.doc', 'NASAL POLYPOSIS-INDUCED UPPER AIRWAY OBSTRUCTION: EFFECT OF TREATMENTS ON CARDIOPULMONARY FUNCTIONS', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 15:13:55', '2025-11-10 15:13:59'),
(296, 'payal verma', 'doctorwithpet@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000471', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nCerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leaks from the lateral recess (LR) of the sphenoid sinus are usually spontaneous. LR is an extension of the sphenoid pneumatization into the pterygoid process. The endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach (EETPA) includes drilling of the pterygoid base for better access but with accompanying risk of injury to the vidian nerve (VN) and maxillary nerve (V2) \r\n Aim :\r\nLong term experience with plasma ablation in treating SLR defects via EETPA and presenting the outcomes in terms of objective assessment of the surgical field achieved, postoperative complications and success. \r\nCase Series :\r\n11 patients aged 40-70 years presented with CSF rhinorrhea .Diagnosis by  HRCT 0.75-mm cuts of PNS and MR cisternography . All cases were managed surgically .\r\nDiscussion: \r\nPlasma ablation–assisted EETPA provides superior hemostasis, visualization, and access through a single nostril while minimising complications and promoting faster healing for LR CSF leaks.\r\nConclusion :\r\nPlasma ablation assisted EETPA allows for a uninostril approach to the SLR, easy accessibility, and better visualization with clearer field, which allows appropriate repair, thus minimizing complications and preventing recurrence.', '/public/upload/abstract/b5019348f62d53da4dca7b932f062d45.docx', 'Plasma Ablation Assisted Endoscopic Endonasal Transpterygoid Approach to Sphenoid Lateral Recess Cer', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 17:54:11', '2025-11-10 17:54:15'),
(297, 'DR SHEELIA OUSEPH', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction\r\nNasal meningoencephaloceles are rare condition where meninges and cranial contents herniate through congenital, traumatic or spontaneous defects in skull base into nasal cavity. Patients often present with clear nasal discharge, nasal obstruction and improper management can result in serious complications like meningitis and seizures. With advancements in endoscopic techniques minimally invasive approaches have become the preferred modality for repair.\r\n\r\nObjective\r\nThe aim of this study is to analyze our institutional experience in endoscopic management of nasal meningoencephaloceles and review our surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethods\r\nA retrospective review of six patients diagnosed with skull base meningoencephaloceles and managed endoscopically at our centre between May 2024 and February 2025 was conducted. Data regarding demographic profile, clinical presentation, anatomical site of defect, surgical approaches, graft material and postoperative outcome were analyzed.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nOf six patients , three had frontoethmoidal and three had basal types of meningoencephaloceles. All underwent successful endoscopic transnasal repair with no complications over a follow up period of 9-12 months.\r\nConclusion\r\nEndoscopic management is safe, effective and minimally invasive with meticulous multilayer reconstruction and reliable defect closure with high success rates.', '/public/upload/abstract/50eeefeee2a514fef632b24dce0d6587.docx', 'Endoscopic Approach to Skull Base Nasal Meningoencephaloceles: Review of Surgical Outcomes', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-11-10 18:20:58', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(298, 'Dr. Dhairya Malik', 'malik02dhairya@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000455', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'AIM : Maxillofacial injuries constitute a significant proportion of emergency room admissions and represent a growing public health concern, primarily due to the increasing number of road traffic accidents (RTAs) which often require multidisciplinary approaches.\r\nMETHODOLOGY : This prospective observational study was done to assess the prevalence, clinical patterns, etiology, and management strategies of maxillofacial fractures in patients presenting to a tertiary care centre in Bareilly. The parameters used were age, sex, time of incident, etiology, type of vehicle used with preventive measures, type of fractures, and treatment received. All patients underwent proper history taking, clinical examination, radiographic evaluation, and  3-D face reconstruction.\r\n RESULTS : 354 patients presented to ER, of which 104 were of maxillofacial injuries of which 63 underwent surgical corrections, and the rest were managed non-operatively. ORIF with IMF was performed for 44.4% of fractures, 38.1% of fractures were treated by ORIF + mini plate fixation.\r\nCONCLUSIONS : This study concluded that maxillofacial injuries are life-threatening in nature and  cause esthetic or functional deformities, which might lead to psychological, financial, and social costs for people. Identifying the etiology, epidemiology, and treatment plans of maxillofacial traumas is highly important. RTAs were found to be major cause of such injuries', '/public/upload/abstract/f786ea3f13ed5d6b07d9d0c62ed5126a.docx', 'MAXILLO-FACIAL TRAUMA : A STUDY OF PREVALENCE ,CLINICAL PATTERN AND ITS MANAGEMENT', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 20:47:35', '2025-11-10 20:47:39'),
(299, 'Dr.Sonali sharma', 'sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension\r\nPresenting Author: \r\nDr. Sonali Sharma\r\nAim: \r\nTo evaluate the role and effectiveness of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration in preserving vision in patients with idiopathic intracranial hypertension.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA review of published literature and institutional experience was conducted. Data from recent meta-analyses and clinical studies organized in the ENT Department, IGMC Shimla, were analyzed to assess outcomes of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration and decompression. Parameters studied included improvement in visual acuity, visual field, and headache relief, as well as reported complications. Comparative evaluation of transnasal and transconjunctival approaches was also performed..\r\nResults: \r\nMajority of patients showed improvement in visual symptoms and headache. Transnasal endoscopic approach demonstrated good results with minimal complications like diplopia and CSF leak.\r\nConclusions: \r\nEndoscopic optic nerve fenestration is a safe and effective option for managing idiopathic intracranial hypertension. The transnasal route offers better visualization and low morbidity.', '/public/upload/abstract/d9167dc8aa0f85eab36cad0362dc047c.docx', 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 20:55:47', '2025-11-10 20:55:50'),
(300, 'Disha Saini', 'disha.saini13@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000557', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Pterygopalatine Fossa Schwannoma: A Rare Case Report\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Disha Saini\r\nAim:\r\nTo report a rare case of schwannoma arising from the pterygopalatine fossa, highlighting its clinical presentation, diagnostic evaluation, surgical management, and histopathological confirmation.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 40-year-old female presented with complaints of dull, intermittent left-sided frontal headache for 1 year, without any other nasal or visual complaints. Clinical examination revealed a left deviated nasal septum with no external or ocular abnormalities. Contrast-enhanced CT scan of paranasal sinuses showed a non-enhancing soft tissue density lesion (12 × 20 × 18 mm) in the left pterygopalatine fossa, causing widening of the pterygomaxillary fissure and minimal scalloping of the posterior wall of maxillary sinus. The patient underwent endoscopic excision under general anaesthesia via endonasal approach.\r\nResults:\r\nA well-defined, firm, whitish tumour mass measuring 2×2cm was excised completely from the left pterygopalatine fossa. Histopathological examination revealed characteristic hypercellular Antoni A and hypocellular Antoni B areas with Verocay bodies, confirming the diagnosis of ancient schwannoma. Immunohistochemistry showed strong S-100 positivity. Postoperative recovery was uneventful, and there was no recurrence on follow-up.\r\nConclusion:\r\nPterygopalatine fossa schwannomas are extremely rare, with only a few cases reported in the literature. Accurate preoperative imaging aids in localisation and surgical planning. The endoscopic endonasal approach offers excellent exposure with minimal morbidity, making it the preferred technique for the complete excision of such lesions. Therefore, awareness of this rare case is essential for otorhinolaryngologists to ensure timely diagnosis and optimal management.', '/public/upload/abstract/c3fd0d08abbefd0291c1c4300e835092.docx', 'Pterygopalatine fossa schwannoma', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 21:10:36', '2025-11-10 21:10:39');
