(301, 'M.PERIYASAMY', 'Periyasamybalaji26@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000500', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE \r\n Maxillary sinus beyond mucormycosis \r\n\r\nAUTHOR \r\n DR M.PERIYASAMY \r\nOBJECTIVE \r\nTo study clinical spectrum of mucormycosis involving maxillary sinus and beyond \r\nTo evaluate treatment modalities and outcome \r\nMETHODS   \r\nPatient with symptoms suggestive of rhinoorbital mucormycosis are evaluated with dne ,koh , hpe and culture sensitivity done ,ct pns done  with mri to assess extent of disease then planned for surgery \r\nRESULTS \r\nMaxillary sinus is primary focus in all cases 75./. Had extension beyond this at the time of presentation, combined surgical and medical management has yield best outcomes \r\nCONCLUSION \r\nMucormycosis of maxillary sinus is rapidly progressive disease early diagnosis &aggressive debridement and amphotericin B is cornerstone of management \r\nAwareness and multidisciplinary approach improves survival', '/public/upload/abstract/bda0646342a2d97314a4772b2b125e23.docx', 'Maxillary sinus beyond mucormycosis', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 22:14:06', '2025-11-10 22:14:10'),
(302, 'Dr. VIJAY KUMAR', 'dr.vijay11176@aiimspatna.org', 'RHIN0000504', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Frontal Sinusotomy-DRAF 3 Video Sessions', '/public/upload/abstract/852c4559f0c0f60f82b1ab778d1c2fb2.docx', 'Frontal Sinusotomy-DRAF 3', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 22:29:18', '2025-11-10 22:29:21'),
(303, 'Sowparnika T R', 'sowbutr@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000560', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE: A RANDOMIZED CONTROL TRIAL ON THE EFFECTIVENESS OF ANTIFUNGAL AND STEROID NASAL DOUCHING IN AFRS: A CLINICAL, RADIOLOGICAL AND BIOCHEMICAL CO-RELATION\r\n\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:DR SOWPARNIKA TR\r\n\r\nAIM:TO LOOK FOR ANY ADDED ADVANTAGE OF PRE- OPERATIVE STEROID NASAL DOUCHING IN AFRS\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY:35 AFRS PATIENTS ARE RANDOMIZED INTO TWO ARMS –ARM A GIVEN STEROID AND ANTIFUNGAL, ARM B GIVEN STEROID, ANTIFUNGAL AND BUDESONIDE NASAL DOUCHES, THE RESPONSE ARE COMPARED AT BASELINE AND AT 6 WEEKS BY CLINICAL, RADIOLOGICAL AND SEROLOGICAL PARAMETERS. CLINICAL PARAMETERS INCLUDE SNOT22 AND MELTZER SCORE, RADIOLOGICAL -LUND MACKEY AND 20 POINT SCORE, SEROLOGICAL – ABSOLUTE EOSINOPHIL COUNTS, SPECIFIC AND TOTAL IGE LEVELS, SERUM AND NASAL DOUCHES GALACTOMANNAN LEVELS. PATIENTS ARE MONITORED WITH S CORTISOL AND LFT VALUES.\r\n\r\n\r\nRESULTS: TILL NOW ARM B SHOWS MORE RESPONSE COMPARED TO ARM A IN SNOT-22, MELTZER SCORE. RADIOLOGICAL SCORES WERE MORE OR LESS COMPARABLE IN BOTH ARMS POST TREATMENT. ARM B SHOWED GREATER REDUCTIONS THAN ARM A IN BIOCHEMICAL PARAMETERS.\r\n\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION: THERE IS NO ADDED ADVANTAGE OF BUDESONIDE NASAL DOUCHES IN AFRS PATIENTS IN REDUCTION OF CLINICO-RADIOLOGICAL PARAMETERS. HOWEVER PREOPERATIVE THERAPY WITH STEROID AND ANTIFUNGAL SHOWS AN OVERALL DECREASE IN DISEASE BURDEN, DURATION OF SURGERY, LESS INTRAOPERATIVE COMPLICATIONS AND BLOOD LOSS', '/public/upload/abstract/8a2b888263f84343c355898d95b84d84.docx', 'A RANDOMIZED CONTROL TRIAL ON THE EFFECTIVENESS OF ANTIFUNGAL AND STEROID NASAL DOUCHING IN AFRS: A ', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:31:18', '2025-11-10 23:31:22'),
(304, 'Payal verma', 'Doctorwithpet@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000471', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'This video demonstrates the transpterygoid approach to the lateral recess of sphenoid sinus for a CSF leak.\r\nThis approach has a higher success rate because of the head on approach and ease of instrumentation. Depending on the type of lateral recess the vidian can be sacrificed or preserved and contents of PPF lateralised.', '/public/upload/abstract/66abfd4b2af598f23efaf1a4afa98d8a.docx', 'Plasma Ablation Assisted Endoscopic Endonasal Transpterygoid Approach to Sphenoid Lateral Recess Cer', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:33:41', '2025-11-10 23:33:45'),
(305, 'Dr Ekansh Sood', 'Ekanshsood@yahoo.com', '1200', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'A CASE OF INFRATEMPORAL FOSSA SCHWANOMMA RESECTION USING MAXILLARY SWING : A NOVEL APPROACH \r\nIntroduction : The infratemporal fossa) is a deep facial space behind the zygomatic bone and the maxilla.Infratemporal fossa tumours comprise of 5% of head and neck cancers, reflecting their nature of rarity. Trigeminal schwannoma and meningioma are more common of all ITF tumours. The surgical anatomy of the infratemporal fossa (ITF) as well as the tumour resection in this region remain a challenge for head and neck surgeons due to its proximity to cranial nerves  .CASE : 40 year old female KAMLESH presented with complaint of right side nasal obstruction, and double vision since 6 months On examination: 1. Face- right eye protrusion 2.Decreased finger insinuation in right infra orbital margin   3. On A/R-mass in right nasal cavity . Investigation and Management :Radiology : -4.9 x 4.9 x 5.2 cm epicentered at pterygopalatine fossa, pterygomaxillary fissure and right masticator space.Patient was planned for surgery and Excision of infratemporal mass by maxillary swing approach was done.Post op HPE was of Shwanoma Discussion : Infratemporal fossa is area of skull base. The contents of the fossa -lateral and medial pterygoid muscles-the maxillary artery and its branches-the pterygoid venous plexus-maxillary veins -branches of the mandibular nerveSchwannomas are benign, encapsulated peripheral nerve tumours.Approximately 25 to 45% of schwannomas occur in the head and neck region.Schwannomas limited to the infratemporal fossa are rare lesions that may also involve the maxillary sinus, the orbit and the retropharyngeal spaceOnly a few cases have been reported and the reported ones presented from the 2nd to 5th decades of life with equal distribution for both sex.', '/public/upload/abstract/8c64a7d15af7bf85b5c455f4804235a5.docx', 'INFRATEMPORAL FOSSA SCHWANOMMA RESECTION USING MAXILLARY SWING : A NOVEL APPROACH', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:34:21', '2025-11-10 23:34:26'),
(306, 'Sahaj Gulati', 'sahaj.gulati99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000456', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract\r\nBackground:\r\nCellular neurofibroma is a rare benign variant of neurofibroma characterized by increased cellularity and reduced collagenous stroma. Its occurrence in the nose and paranasal sinuses (PNS) is exceedingly uncommon, and due to its cellular features, it may mimic malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumor (MPNST) both clinically and histologically. Awareness of this entity in unusual sites such as the sinonasal region is crucial to ensure correct diagnosis and management.\r\nObjective:\r\nTo describe the clinicopathologic and immunohistochemical characteristics of a cellular neurofibroma arising in the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, emphasizing its differentiation from malignant counterparts.\r\nMethods:\r\nA detailed histopathological examination of the resected specimen was performed along with immunohistochemical staining for S-100, SOX10, and CD34 to confirm Schwann cell lineage. Clinical and radiologic findings were correlated.\r\nResults:\r\nThe lesion presented as a firm, painless nasal mass causing nasal obstruction and facial fullness. CT and MRI revealed a well-circumscribed soft tissue mass involving the nasal cavity and extending into adjacent paranasal sinuses without bony destruction. Microscopically, the tumor showed densely packed spindle cells with elongated, wavy nuclei arranged in short fascicles and whorls. There was mild nuclear pleomorphism, absence of necrosis, and low mitotic activity. Immunohistochemistry demonstrated strong diffuse positivity for S-100 and SOX10, with variable CD34 expression, consistent with cellular neurofibroma.\r\nConclusion:\r\nCellular neurofibroma of the nose and PNS is a rare benign tumor that can closely resemble low-grade MPNST. Recognition of its histopathologic and immunohistochemical profile is essential for accurate diagnosis. Complete surgical excision is curative, and recurrence is rare. Early identification prevents unnecessary radical treatment and ensures excellent prognosis.\r\nKeywords: Cellular neurofibroma, nasal cavity, paranasal sinuses, benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor, S-100, SOX10', '/public/upload/abstract/af663e433b1ee716b616f27d5497f24e.docx', 'Atypical presentation of cellular neurofibroma', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:38:07', '2025-11-10 23:38:10'),
(307, 'Sowparnika T R', 'sowbutr@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000560', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'SINONASAL TERATOCARCINOSARCOMA — THE GREAT MASQUERADER OF THE NASAL CAVITY\r\n\r\n\r\nØ	52 year male presented to OPD with 4 months history of  nasal obstruction and epistaxis\r\nØ	Local examination –pale- reddish nodular mass\r\nØ	Biopsy: SMARCA 4 deficient sinonasal teratocarcinosarcoma\r\nØ	Diagnosis-SINONASAL TERATOCARCINOSARCOMA\r\nØ	Plan- ENDOSCOPIC EXCISION\r\nØ	Endoscopic excision done with margins taken all around the tumor at its site of attachment\r\nØ	Margins taken one layer additional\r\nØ	Discussion- \r\nØ	Rare, highly aggressive malignant tumour containing mixed epithelial, mesenchymal and primitive neuroepithelial elements\r\nØ	Triple malignancy\r\nØ	Poor prognosis\r\nØ	Challenges- heterogeneous morphology and high recurrence ratePredilection for anterior skull base location\r\nØ	Disease of middle age that commonly affects men\r\nØ	Conclusion-\r\nØ	Rare but distinct sinonasal malignancy requiring high index of suspicion.\r\nØ	Multidisciplinary management offers best survival advantage.', '/public/upload/abstract/aa07888421ed3adf351b40c9cd6f3aae.docx', 'Sinonasal Teratocarcinosarcoma — The Great Masquerader of the Nasal Cavity', 2, 1, '2025-11-11 00:33:03', '2025-11-11 00:33:07'),
(308, 'DR SHEELIA OUSEPH', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo share surgical experiences and challenges encountered in managing two cases of advanced (Radkowski IIIb) juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA) with dual carotid supply, emphasizing approach selection and intraoperative strategies.\r\nMethodology:\r\nBoth patients underwent preoperative digital subtraction angiography, which demonstrated tumor vascularity from external and internal carotid branches. Selective embolization of external carotid feeders was performed. One case was managed endoscopically, while the other required an open approach with endoscopic assistance for residual clearance.\r\nResults:\r\nComplete excision was achieved in both patients with smooth postoperative recovery and no recurrence on follow-up. Challenges included controlling bleeding from internal carotid feeders, accessing deep extensions, and preserving neurovascular structures. Embolization effectively reduced intraoperative blood loss and facilitated safer dissection.\r\nConclusion:\r\nRadkowski IIIb JNA with dual carotid supply pose significant surgical challenges. Individualized planning, selective embolization, and adaptable surgical approaches are key to achieving complete clearance with minimal morbidity.', '/public/upload/abstract/e96794c1f4418f0cedecb4d6b56b8603.docx', 'Surgical Challenges and Experience in Managing Cases of Radkowski Stage IIIb Juvenile Nasopharyngeal', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-11-11 07:56:40', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(309, 'Tanisha Gautam', 'tanishaaaa64@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000454', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'The current research was conducted to complete a morphometric examination of the nasal forms and evaluate the level of satisfaction in the young medical pupils in Northern India to provide reference data on anthropometry, cosmetic, and reconstructive nasal surgery. One hundred medical students (46 males and 54 females) aged 18-25 years and studying at SRMS Institute of Medical Sciences, Bareilly took part in the study. To measure nasal height (n-sn) and nasal width (acr-acr) that were used in calculating the nasal index, standard anthropometric methods were used and a digital sliding Vernier caliper was used. The findings showed a mean nasal height of 47.95 mm, mean nasal width of 30.59 mm, and mean nasal index of 63.82 with most of the sample (77%) being of leptorrhine (fine) nose type. Males were also found to have much higher nasal indices than females (67.79 vs 60.44; p = 0.0004) which was evidence of sexual dimorphism. Also, the participants who were not satisfied with the appearance of their nose had much bigger nasal indices (71.21 vs 63.82; p < 0.0001) and desired smaller noses. Comparisons with other ethnic groups revealed that there were regional differences in nasal morphology in which the Northern Indian sample exhibited comparatively narrow nasal morphology. Finally, the research points out notable sexual dimorphism in nasal anthropometry in young Northern Indians and stresses that those with wider noses complain of having lesser satisfaction with nasal appearance. The results offer important background information to practitioners in the cosmetic, reconstructive and forensic practice of nasal inspection and surgery.', '/public/upload/abstract/a60defa09aeb1ce319b6364060360850.docx', 'MORPHOMETRIC ANALYSIS AND DEGREE OF SATISFACTION OF NASAL PROFILES IN YOUNG MEDICAL STUDENTS IN NORT', 2, 1, '2025-11-11 09:33:45', '2025-11-11 09:33:48'),
(310, 'Dr.V.J.Vikram', 'dr.vjvikram@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000568', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'This video presentation is about the surgical excision of typical (Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma) and atypical  (Extra Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma arising from right nasal septum)', '/public/upload/abstract/32a8591669467969aa37317f13f6c6e9.docx', 'Typical and Atypical Angiofibroma Surgery', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-11 21:14:53', '2025-11-11 21:14:57'),
(311, 'SaranKumar', 'saranstanlean@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000584', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'A 11 year old boy presented with a episode of profuse right sided epistaxis. on evaluation, it was diagnosed to be JNA with classical ptertgo maxillary fissure widening. This video show four handed approach for endoscopic excision of JNA', '/public/upload/abstract/7cb58e67ecbacca81cea7dc6ffb9350d.docx', 'ENDOSCOPIC EXCISION OF JUVENILE NASOPHARYNGHEAL ANGIOFIBROMA', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-13 07:38:42', '2025-11-13 07:38:46'),
(312, 'SaranKumar', 'saranstanlean@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000584', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'A 11 year old boy presented with a episode of profuse right sided epistaxis. on evaluation, it was diagnosed to be JNA with classical ptertgo maxillary fissure widening. This video show four handed approach for endoscopic excision of JNA', '/public/upload/abstract/461358a1b4ff6e3579dbc0b8187acd57.docx', 'ENDOSCOPIC EXCISION OF JUVENILE NASOPHARYNGHEAL ANGIOFIBROMA', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-13 07:38:44', '2025-11-13 07:38:48'),
(313, 'Lisa Mary Cherian', 'lisamarycherian@gmail.com', 'lisamarycherian@gmail.com', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Background:\r\nEndotyping in chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS)  by structured histopathology enables targeted therapy and improving patient outcomes. Nasal cytology is a lesser invasive tests which counts the different cell types to reflect the histologic pattern. The current study analyses the nasal cytology in CRSwNP, CRSsNP patients and controls among Indian population which has not be reported previously.\r\n\r\nMaterials and methods:\r\n\r\nAn observational prospective study was conducted on CRS patients and appropriate controls to determine the nasal cytogram by middle meatal nasal brushings. Nasal cytology sampling was done under endoscopic guidance and smears studied based on a four-point grading scale.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n \r\nThe study recruited 40 patients each in control, CRSsNP and CRSwNP groups. The SNOT 22, VAS and LKS showed significantly higher score among the CRS compared to controls. The number of patients having higher grade of eosinophil count (p=0.002) and neutrophil count were significantly higher in CRS compared to control (p=0.031). \r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nThe study suggests that Indian CRS endotyping shows both eosinophilic and neutrophilic cells, and this was highest among CRSwNP. Nasal cytology a potential complementary diagnostic tool in CRS endotyping, however, requires further studies.', '/public/upload/abstract/f0125bc735c6d9b36880362b4f3765a3.docx', 'Nasal cytology in chronic rhinosinusitis endotyping.', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-13 08:55:19', '2025-11-13 08:55:22'),
(314, 'Dr. Pon kaushikan', 'kaushikaghi@gmail.com', 'kaushikaghi@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction:\r\n\r\nThe lateral craniopharyngeal canal, also known as Sternberg’s canal, is a congenital defect located in the postero-lateral wall of the sphenoid sinus. It arises from incomplete fusion of ossification centers during embryological development. Though uncommon in adults, persistence of this canal may serve as a pathway for spontaneous cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leakage, occasionally accompanied by herniation of intracranial contents.\r\n\r\nBecause of its anatomical proximity to vital neurovascular structures—including the internal carotid artery, optic nerve, and cavernous sinus—identification and surgical repair of defects in this region are technically demanding. As a result, diagnosis may be delayed, and management often requires advanced endoscopic skull-base techniques to ensure safe and effective closure.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\n\r\n4 Patients presenting with spontaneous CSF leak , one of the patients underwent prior endoscopic surgery for the csf leak with recurrent csf rhinorrhea were further evaluated clinically and radiologically. High-resolution CT and MRI of the paranasal sinuses were used to identify the site of skull-base defect, characterize encephalocele and plan the surgical approach.\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent endoscopic endonasal csf leak repair under general anaesthesia. A trans-nasal trans-sphenoid approach was performed to access the lateral sphenoid recess. In cases with limited exposure or laterally placed defects, a trans-pterygoid extension could be  utilized to improve visualization and access.\r\n\r\nOutcomes:\r\n\r\nAll  4 patients had successful closure of the CSF leak using a multilayered endoscopic repair technique. Postoperatively, no recurrence of CSF leak  was noted during follow-up. The endoscopic approach ensured minimal morbidity, no major complications, and a rapid recovery with favorable clinical outcomes\r\n\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n\r\nA total of 4  patients diagnosed to be CSF rhinorrhea originating from Sternberg’s canal were included. One patient had undergone prior endoscopic repair elsewhere and presented with recurrence.\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent endoscopic endonasal repair with multilayer closure using fat, fascia, and a naso-septal flap\r\n\r\nPostoperatively, all patients had complete resolution of CSF rhinorrhea, with no recurrence observed on follow-up. No major complications were reported, and all patients demonstrated good recovery.', '/public/upload/abstract/bcc26350a001a3c96c51d450f6749caa.docx', '“Sealing the Silent Leak”:The Rare intersection of Sternberg canal defect causing csf leaks', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-13 14:19:04', '2025-11-13 14:19:08'),
(315, 'DR.PON KAUSHIKAN', 'kaushikaghi@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000589', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'INTRODUCTION:\r\nTrephine syndrome (also called sunken skin flap syndrome) is a rare but significant complication that occurs after decompressive craniectomy. It results from atmospheric pressure being transmitted directly to the brain, causing distortion of cerebral tissue, impaired CSF dynamics, and reduced cortical perfusion. When CSF hypovolemia coexists—as in cases of persistent CSF rhinorrhea—neurological deterioration can be accelerated. Recognising CSF leak in patients with large cranial defects is essential, as it can worsen intracranial pressure gradients and delay recovery.\r\n\r\nCASE PRESENTATION:\r\nA 33-year-old male sustained a road traffic accident and was diagnosed with epidural hematoma, bilateral frontal contusions, and frontal bone fractures. He underwent bifrontal decompressive craniectomy and required 7 days of postoperative ventilatory support. On the 10th postoperative day, he developed persistent CSF rhinorrhea despite maximal medical therapy.\r\nHe was referred to our department with active CSF leak .Clinical evaluation and imaging (CT PNS and MR cisternography) demonstrated continued CSF leak with associated intracranial pressure changes. Surgical repair was performed. Postoperative endoscopic findings on days 1, 2 and 7 showed good healing and cessation of the leak.\r\n\r\nDISCUSSION:\r\nTrephine syndrome develops due to direct transmission of atmospheric pressure through the cranial defect, collapse of the subarachnoid space, turbulence of CSF flow, and reduced cortical blood perfusion. Co-existing CSF rhinorrhea further aggravates this negative pressure gradient, predisposing to neurological decline. Patients may present with headache, dizziness, cognitive changes, irritability, and motor deficits known as motor trephine syndrome.\r\nDefinitive management is early cranioplasty to restore physiological pressure dynamics. Adjunctive measures such as head-down positioning and forehead compression (“turban dressing”) may be used temporarily until surgical correction is possible.\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nPersistent CSF rhinorrhea following decompressive craniectomy requires prompt evaluation, as it can precipitate or worsen trephine syndrome. Surgical repair of the leak followed by timely cranioplasty is essential for symptom resolution and neurological recovery. Long-term follow-up is advised due to the risk of recurrent CSF leak and complications associated with large cranial defects.', '/public/upload/abstract/e3b627104c9dd505e9eab4377aa89f5f.docx', 'Cranial Defect’s Deadliest Partner- CSF Rhinorrhea With Trephine Syndrome', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 18:17:33', '2025-11-13 18:17:37'),
(316, 'thrupthi s', 'thrupthisubbanna@gmail.com', 'thrupthisubbanna@gmail.com', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract\r\nBackground: Pituitary apoplexy is an acute neuroendocrine emergency characterized by sudden hemorrhage or infarction within the pituitary gland, often in a pre-existing adenoma. Owing to its close anatomical relationship with the sphenoid sinus and optic apparatus, ENT surgeons—especially those trained in endoscopic skull-base approaches—play a vital role in timely diagnosis and management.\r\nCase Presentation: We present a case of a 39-year-old female who arrived with rapidly progressive blurring of vision in left eye for 10 days. Clinical examination revealed right temporal field defect and partial ptosis. Endocrine evaluation demonstrated hypothyroidism. MRI Brain showed a large heterogenous cystic mass lesion of size 3*2.7*2.2cm seen in sella with suprasella extension and mass effect on chiasma on left side-pituitary macroadenoma / ?pituitary apoplexy.CT PNS showed evidence of well defined iso to hypodense lesion measuring 2.3*2.6*3.3cm in the sella region with peripheral calcification- suggestive of pituitary macroadenoma with mass effect. After stabilization with high-dose intravenous corticosteroids, the patient underwent endoscopic endonasal transsphenoidal hypophysectomy performed by the ENT skull-base team. The procedure achieved effective evacuation of hemorrhagic components and decompression of the optic apparatus. Postoperatively, the patient exhibited marked visual recovery, complete pain resolution, and stable hormonal status with appropriate replacement therapy. Follow-up imaging confirmed adequate decompression and no residual mass effect.\r\nConclusion: This case underscores the crucial role of ENT surgeons in the multidisciplinary management of pituitary apoplexy, particularly through minimally invasive endoscopic skull-base approaches. Early recognition, prompt steroid administration, and timely surgical intervention significantly improve visual and endocrine outcomes. The case reinforces the evolving contribution of endoscopic transsphenoidal surgery in emergency pituitary pathology.', '/public/upload/abstract/1e039353e80b7418c02964912515d2d2.docx', 'From Crisis to Clarity: Visual Recovery After Endoscopic Management of Pituitary Apoplexy', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-11-13 19:35:09', '2025-11-22 10:15:21'),
(317, 'A. Elakiya', 'elakiyadurai98@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000571', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE\r\n“The Return of Pott”-A case report on clinical presentation and surgical management of Pott\'s puffy tumor\r\n\r\n\r\nAUTHOR NAME \r\nDr. A.Elakiya\r\n\r\nOBJECTIVE\r\nPott\'s puffy tumor refers to subperiosteal abscess of forehead, associated frontal bone osteomyelitis ,its a rare condition usually associated with ethmoidal sinusitis, forehead trauma , insect bite. The outcome of this study is to evaluate the clinical presentation , investigations and management of patients diagnosed with Potts puffy tumor \r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY \r\nThis is a case report of a 49 year old male who presented with symptoms of  swelling and pain  over frontal region  , further imaging techniques including CT angiography , MRI was done to assess the extent of infection and surgically managed with incision and drainage ,frontal trephination ,sinusotomy . Post operatively follow up done at 2nd , 4th , 6th week to look for symptomatic improvement. \r\n\r\nRESULTS \r\nThe spectrum of presentation both clinically and radiologically is studied. Radiological investigations are used to assess the extent of swelling, to look for underlying bony erosions Challenges in surgery are studied, microbiological results helps in choosing appropriate antibiotics Follow up of the patient done to look for recurrence \r\n\r\nCONCLUSION \r\nPott\'s puffy tumor is a clinical diagnosis supported by radiological imaging presents with forehead swelling and frontal headache. Definitive treatment is broad spectrum antibiotics, frontal sinusotomy and trephination.', '/public/upload/abstract/b0d0d39c2160b0cdde3d7710350fb5ef.docx', 'The Return on Pott - case study on clinical presentation and surgical management of Pott\'s Puffy tum', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 21:25:19', '2025-11-13 21:25:22'),
(318, 'H Zaiba Fathima', 'zaibafthm29@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000583', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction\r\n\r\n              Ectopic supernumerary teeth in the nasal cavity are rare, occurring with an incidence of approximately 0.1–1%.\r\n\r\n-  Case presentation\r\n\r\n             A 41-year-old male patient, with a history of facial trauma, presented with nasal obstruction and recurrent blood-stained nasal discharge.\r\n\r\n-  Physical examination showed a deviated septum and a white mass in the right nasal cavity.\r\n\r\n-  Diagnostic nasal endoscopy revealed a polypoidal, granulomatous, pyogenic mass over the caudal septum. \r\n\r\n-  CT imaging confirmed the diagnosis of an ectopic tooth in the right nasal floor, along with septal deviation and hypertrophy of the right inferior turbinate.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSurgical extraction was carried out using a modified Caldwell-Luc operation. The mass was removed successfully, minimizing complications by employing careful mucoperiosteal techniques.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n-  Outcome\r\n\r\n                   Postoperative recovery was uneventful with resolution of symptoms. The patient experienced no major complications such as septal perforation or naso-oral fistula.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n-  Discussion\r\n\r\n                 Intranasal supernumerary teeth arise from abnormal development of dental tissue, possibly due to hyperactivity of the dental lamina, trauma, infections, craniofacial anomalies (like cleft lip/palate), or genetic syndromes.\r\n\r\n-  Management\r\n\r\nEndoscopic Approach\r\n\r\n•Preferred for most intranasal supernumerary teeth. Ideal when the tooth is superficial and not deeply embedded.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nModified Caldwell-Luc Operation\r\n\r\n•Used when the tooth is located deep in the nasal floor or maxillary sinus, when associated with extensive pathology such as a cyst or chronic infection, where endoscopic access is limited.\r\n\r\nIntraoral/Nasal Combined Approach\r\n\r\n•When teeth extend from the palate or incisive canal into the nasal cavity, or are impacted partly within the maxilla. Collaboration between oral and ENT surgeons may be needed for complex cases.\r\n\r\n- Conclusion\r\n\r\nIntranasal supernumerary teeth should be considered in patients with unexplained nasal obstruction and epistaxis\r\n\r\n- Keywords\r\n\r\nEpistaxis , ectopic tooth, Modified Cadwell luc operation,', '/public/upload/abstract/113ad5b1dbc1afdb1a20448caed5052b.doc', 'CAN A GUEST IN THE NASAL CAVITY CAUSE SO MUCH HAVOC?', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 12:37:16', '2025-11-14 12:37:21'),
(319, 'Dr.Maria Amirutha', 'mariaamirutha99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000586', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Background:\r\nSinonasal malignancies are uncommon and often mimic benign or infective conditions, leading to diagnostic delays. Fungal sinusitis is a frequent differential in unilateral maxillary sinus disease, and radiological overlap can further complicate early detection. This case highlights the importance of maintaining high suspicion and performing timely histopathological evaluation when clinical progression seems atypical.\r\n\r\nCase Presentation:\r\nA 57-year-old male presented with a 20-day history of thick, yellowish, blood-stained left-sided nasal discharge and watering of the left eye. There was no history of trauma, dental infection, or visual disturbances. Clinical examination revealed thick purulent discharge in the left nasal cavity, left maxillary tenderness, and deviated nasal septum to the right, with no neck nodes or facial swelling.\r\n\r\nDiagnostic Workup:\r\nDiagnostic nasal endoscopy showed medialised uncinate process, concha bullosa, and discharge in the middle meatus. CT PNS demonstrated complete soft-tissue opacity of the left maxillary sinus, extension into the nasal cavity, widened infundibulum, and osteomeatal complex obstruction, findings initially suggestive of fungal sinusitis. No intraorbital or buccal space involvement was noted.\r\n\r\nIntervention:\r\nThe patient underwent endoscopic polypectomy under GA, during which fungal debris and polypoidal tissue were removed using a microdebrider. As the procedure progressed, a deeper fleshy mass was visualised within the left maxillary antrum. This was excised and sent for histopathology.\r\n\r\nOutcome:\r\nHistopathological examination confirmed carcinoma ex-sinonasal papilloma – squamous cell carcinoma (non-keratinising type), explaining the atypical features and persistent symptoms.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nThis case illustrates how sinonasal malignancy may masquerade as fungal or inflammatory sinusitis. Even when imaging favours a benign diagnosis, intraoperative suspicion and routine biopsy remain essential for identifying hidden malignancy and guiding appropriate management.', '/public/upload/abstract/2f4ed69efebdc1985ef3f57630d46f25.doc', '“The Fungal Sinusitis That Wasn’t: Unveiling a Silent Carcinoma”', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 12:47:27', '2025-11-14 12:47:31'),
(320, 'Dr. Pooja N kabbannavar', 'poojakolimi@gmail.com', 'RHINO00497', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title:\r\nA rare case report of Nasopharyngeal lymphoma\r\nIntroduction\r\nExtra nodal Lymphomas are very rare accounting for 25–30% of the cases. Occurrence of NHL in Waldeyer’s region is 16–43%. Most frequently affected sites are tonsils, base of tongue and nasopharynx. \r\n\r\nCase presentation\r\n48year old female presented to us with a complaint of nasal obstruction, snoring, nasal discharge since 1 year. On diagnostic nasal endoscopy (DNE) fleshy mass in nasopharynx obliterating the choana.\r\n\r\nInvestigation:\r\nCECT PNS shows well defined hypodense soft tissue lesion measuring 3.5cm ×2.8cm is seen in the posterio- superior region of Nasopharynx\r\nImmunohistochemistry (IHC) –strongly positive for CD20, CD21, CD5\r\nTreatment:\r\nPatient posted for nasal endoscopic biopsy.\r\nHPE -A diffusely scattered lymphoid cells with vesicular nuclei and scantycytoplasm.Infiltartion of Atypical cells in stroma.\r\nDiscussion:\r\nLymphomas are classified as NHL and HL (Hodgkin’s Lymphoma). NHL is usually a nodal disease [1]. Extranodal NHL diseases involving head and neck region are heterogeneous in origin. 90% lymphomas are NHL and specifically B cell type. Occurrence of NHL in Tonsillar region is 51% and in nasopharynx is 35% . Immunohistochemistry, CECT, MRI, PET-CT should be done to rule out other site of involvement. Biopsy and followed by HPE report, treatment is planned accordingly.\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasopharyngeal lymphoma although rare. Early diagnosis and treatment will help in improving prognosis and treatment outcomes of the patients.', '/public/upload/abstract/a785cb5cc5701e2205d38ab83755ad0e.docx', 'A rare case report of Nasopharyngeal lymphoma', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 17:16:17', '2025-11-14 17:16:21'),
(321, 'Dhivyanka.M', 'dhivyankamadan@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000600', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Comparative CT and Quantitative Endoscopic Evaluation of Eosinophilic and Non-Eosinophilic Chronic Rhinosinusitis: A Prospective Study\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Dhivyanka M\r\nAim: Chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS) is an inflammatory disease of the nasal and paranasal mucosa. Differentiating eosinophilic (ECRS) from non-eosinophilic CRS (NECRS) is essential due to variations in severity, recurrence, and treatment response.\r\nObjective: To compare radiological and endoscopic severity of ECRS and NECRS using Lund–Mackay and Lund–Kennedy scoring systems.\r\nMethods: A prospective cross-sectional study of 48 CRS patients was conducted, classified into ECRS and NECRS based on nasal smear eosinophilia. CT paranasal sinuses were graded by the Lund–Mackay system, and diagnostic nasal endoscopy findings were scored using the Lund–Kennedy scale.\r\nResults: ECRS showed significantly higher mean Lund–Mackay (12.67 ± 3.25) and Lund–Kennedy (7.96 ± 2.23) scores compared to NECRS (6.42 ± 2.8 and 4.42 ± 1.97, respectively; p < 0.001). Ethmoidal and osteomeatal complex opacification predominated in ECRS, while NECRS showed more maxillary involvement.\r\nConclusion: CT and endoscopic scoring reliably differentiate ECRS from NECRS. ECRS presents with greater sinus opacification and mucosal inflammation, emphasizing the role of quantitative imaging and endoscopic evaluation in CRS endotyping.', '/public/upload/abstract/acb89a6fb061ead8838ea37ab6054cb5.docx', 'Comparative CT and Quantitative Endoscopic Evaluation of Eosinophilic and Non-Eosinophilic Chronic R', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-14 20:58:44', '2025-11-14 20:58:47'),
(322, 'shaheera tarnooom', 'shaheera.siraj@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000601', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Abstract\r\nTitle\r\nThe Sinus Snare – When the Eye Becomes the Messenger\r\nPresenting Author\r\nDr. Shaheera Tarnoom.S\r\nAim\r\nTo highlight the atypical presentation, diagnostic challenges, and surgical outcomes of isolated sphenoid sinusitis presenting with visual symptoms, particularly in diabetic patients.\r\nMethodology\r\nTwo middle-aged female patients with long-standing Type 2 diabetes presented with visual disturbances such as diplopia, blurring of vision, and periorbital pain, without nasal complaints. Clinical examination, diagnostic nasal endoscopy, CT and MRI imaging were performed. Both underwent Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (FESS) after multidisciplinary evaluation. Intraoperative samples were subjected to KOH mount, culture, and histopathology.\r\nResults\r\nImaging revealed isolated sphenoid and posterior ethmoid sinus involvement in both cases. One patient demonstrated fungal elements consistent with Aspergillus. Post-operative recovery was favourable, with complete resolution of diplopia and improvement in visual acuity in both patients. No post-operative complications or recurrence were observed on follow-up.\r\nConclusions\r\nOrbital manifestations in diabetic patients may represent occult sinus disease. Early diagnosis through imaging and prompt surgical management are crucial to prevent progression to orbital apex syndrome or fulminant fungal sinusitis. The eye can indeed serve as a vital messenger for underlying sinonasal pathology.', '/public/upload/abstract/c938dbafb11ae3898efe59263df3107a.docx', 'The Sinus Snare – When the Eye Becomes the Messenger', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-14 22:45:09', '2025-11-14 22:45:12'),
(323, 'Vasamsetty revanth manohar', 'Revanthmanohar89@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000588', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\nTITLE- \r\nClinical Predictors of Symptom Improvement Following Eustachian Tube Balloon Dilation\r\n\r\nAUTHOR NAME -V.Revanth Manohar\r\n\r\nAIM- This study aims to identify clinical predictors of treatment response to Eustachian Tube Balloon Dilation (ETBD) as measured by changes in Eustachian Tube Dysfunction Questionnaire-7 (ETDQ-7) scores.\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY-  One hundred thirteen patients who underwent ETBD at an institution from 2022 to 2025 completed ETDQ-7 pre- and post-operatively. We conducted multivariable regression analyses with ETDQ-7 normalization (<2.1 post-op), minimum clinically important difference (MCID) (>0.5 pre-op - post-op), and quantitative improvement in ETDQ-7 score as outcome variables. Pre-operative ETDQ-7 score, tympanogram type, chronic otitis media, chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS), inferior turbinate hypertrophy, deviated septum, allergic rhinitis, and rhinorrhea were included as covariates. Models controlled for age, sex, ethnicity, prior ear or sinus surgery, and follow-up duration.\r\n\r\n\r\nRESULT- The mean age was 49 years old. 51% were females, and all patients had pre-operative ETDQ-7 above 2.1. After a mean follow-up period of 13 months, 77% achieved MCID and 37% had normalized. Higher pre-operative ETDQ-7 score was associated with greater ETDQ-7 score improvement (B = 0.60, 95% CI = [0.37, 0.83]) and greater odds of achieving MCID (aOR = 1.65; 95% CI = [1.06, 2.59]). A history of CRS improved chances of achieving MCID (aOR = 4.53; 95% CI = [1.11, 18.55]) and a history of chronic otitis media predicted increased odds of ETDQ-7 normalization (aOR = 2.88; 95% CI = [1.09, 7.58]).\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION- Our findings suggest that ETBD was highly effective among patients with pre-operative ETDQ-7 above 2.1. Furthermore, higher pre-operative ETDQ-7 score, CRS, and chronic otitis media predicted more favorable symptomatic benefit from ETBD. These factors may be important to consider when counseling potential candidates for this procedure.', '/public/upload/abstract/2f40ae41c42fdaff4fddb399963cb4e7.docx', 'Clinical Predictors of Symptom Improvement Following Eustachian Tube Balloon Dilation', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 07:18:04', '2025-11-15 07:18:08'),
(324, 'Dr. Revathi V', 'reva.goku@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000590', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Poster Abstract\r\nTitle \r\nUnmasking the mysteric core of benign shell\r\nRare case of malignancy inside the cyst of upper jaw \r\n\r\nAuthor \r\nDr. Revathi V \r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo study the presentation of a rare case of  a mystery  within a cystic lesion of the maxilla and to emphasize the need for thorough histopathological assessment of all jaw cysts.\r\n\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\n\r\nA 76-year-old male presented with symptoms of  giddeness 1 month for which MRI brain  taken stating that possibility  of dentigerous cyst , CT PNS  F/s/0  right fungal sinusitis.  Patient was taken up for surgery and complete excision of cyst was done . Post op microscopic and immunohistochemical analysis was done \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n\r\nHistopathology revealed malignancy .The patient underwent complete excision and is on regular follow-up with no evidence of recurrence.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\n\r\nAlthough rare, malignant transformation within dentigerous  cysts should be considered in cases with long-standing, recurrent, or rapidly enlarging lesions. Early diagnosis through meticulous histopathological examination is essential for optimal management and prognosis.', '/public/upload/abstract/89a6c7817c96c4c5f5e937e5dca0844b.docx', 'Unmasking the mysteric core of benign shell Rare case of malignancy inside the cyst of upper jaw', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 08:37:27', '2025-11-15 08:37:31'),
(325, 'Dr. Ramprasath Athikesavan', 'ramprasath1166@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000604', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Impact of Surgical Intervention on Eustachian Tube and Middle Ear Function in CRS Patients With and Without Nasal Polyps\r\nAuthor: Dr. A. RAMPRASATH, Post Graduate, M.S. ENT \r\nGuide: Dr. SARANYA CHITHRA, Department of ENT, SMMCHRI.\r\nAim: To evaluate middle ear and Eustachian tube functions in CRS patients with and without nasal polyps before and after surgical intervention.\r\nMethods: Two groups of CRS patients, those with nasal polyps (CRSwNP) and those without (CRSsNP) were evaluated for both subjective and objective measures of sinonasal and Eustachian Tube function. The Eustachian Tube Dysfunction Questionnaire (ETDQ-7) and the Sino-Nasal Outcome Test (SNOT-22) were used to assess symptom load. Tympanometry, Eustachian tube function testing, and diagnostic nasal endoscopy with standardized scoring were all part of the objective examination. All assessments were performed preoperatively and repeated postoperatively following functional endoscopic sinus surgery.\r\nResults: SNOT-22 and ETDQ-7 ratings significantly improved after surgery for both the CRSwNP and CRSsNP groups, demonstrating a decrease in sinonasal and ET-related symptoms. Better Tympanometric profiles and lower endoscopic disease scores were objective indicators of improved middle ear condition and ET function following surgery. While both groups benefited from surgical surgery, patients with nasal polyps showed higher preoperative impairment and correspondingly higher postoperative improvements, according to a comparative analysis.\r\nConclusion: Surgical management of CRS leads to significant improvement in both subjective and objective measures of Eustachian tube and middle ear function. CRS patients with nasal polyps show more pronounced impairment preoperatively but also greater functional recovery after surgery. These findings highlight the importance of evaluating ET function in CRS and support the role of sinus surgery in restoring middle ear physiology.', '/public/upload/abstract/eeadb32dc9991a2a60fd9d08b39631eb.doc', 'Impact of Surgical Intervention on Eustachian Tube and Middle Ear Function in Chronic Rhinosinusitis', NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: A Diagnostic Puzzle: Unraveling the Cause of a Nasal Mass \r\nAuthor: Dr. A. RAMPRASATH, Post Graduate, M.S. ENT\r\nGuide: Dr. L. ASOKAN, Assistant professor, Department of ENT, SMMCHRI.\r\nAim: To highlight the diagnostic challenges of a rare case of extra nodal Non-Hodgkin’s Lymphoma (NHL) of the nasal cavity with cervical lymphadenopathy.\r\nMethodology: A 48-year-old female presented with swelling on the left side of the   neck for five months, left nasal obstruction with discharge for three months. Clinical examination, USG-guided FNAC, CT-PNS, CECT-NECK and MRI neck, performed. The patient underwent endoscopic excision biopsy of the nasal mass, followed by histopathological and immunohistochemical evaluation. \r\nResults: DNE examination revealed a firm, irregular left nasal mass. CT-PNS shows   large heterogeneously mass lesion 10.2x3.9x4.2cm seen on left nasal cavity and left maxillary sinus. CECT neck – (a)largest node 3.5 x 2.9 cm in left level II, (b)node of 3.4 x 2.1cm seen in left level IX. MRI neck-T2 isointense/T1 hypointense restricted diffusion in left nasal cavity with erosion in left lateral wall of nose. T2 isointense/T1 hypointense lesion of 2.9x2.8x4.0cm in left level I B to level II, similar lesion of 2.7x2.6x3.7cm in level IX region. FNAC suggested malignancy. Histopathology revealed poorly differentiated carcinoma, immunohistochemistry suggestive of high-grade B-cell Non-Hodgkin’s Lymphoma. PET-CT showed disease involvement of the nasal cavity and cervical nodes. The patient was started on R-CHOP chemotherapy. \r\nConclusions: Sinonasal lymphomas are uncommon and often mimic epithelial malignancies.', '/public/upload/abstract/1553528edf23e64ff91b776149ea8250.doc', 'A Diagnostic Puzzle: Unraveling the Cause of a Nasal Mass', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 14:34:40', '2025-11-15 14:34:44');
INSERT INTO `rh_abstract` (`id`, `name`, `email`, `reg_id`, `catergory_id`, `note`, `file`, `title_0`, `note_1`, `file_1`, `title_1`, `note_2`, `file_2`, `title_2`, `note_3`, `file_3`, `title_3`, `note_4`, `file_4`, `title_4`, `mail_send`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(326, 'DR. V . AANANDHA PADMANATHAN', 'motog2doc@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000566', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, '“Prospective Clinicopathological Evaluation of Neutrophilic and Eosinophilic Inflammatory Endotypes in Chronic Rhinosinusitis ”\r\n\r\nPresentor :- Dr. Aanandha Padmanathan V  (Post Graduate)\r\nGuide       :- Dr. Saranya Chitra Cheruvu (Assoc Prof) Department of ENT,  \r\nDr. Lionel Rohit Mathew(Assoc Prof) Dept of Pathology.\r\n                      Sri Muthukumaran Medical College and Research Institute\r\n\r\nAbstract :\r\nBackground: \r\nChronic rhinosinusitis  is a multifactorial inflammatory disease of the paranasal sinuses involving the sinonasal mucosa characterized by persistent symptoms lasting 12 weeks or longer and confirmed by diagnostic nasal endoscopy and computed tomography. \r\nAim : \r\nThis study aimed to evaluate the predominance of neutrophilic or eosinophilic inflammation in patients with Chronic rhinosinusitis through histopathological assessment, and to explore the association between Chronic rhinosinusitis endotypes and relevant hematological parameters.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA prospective cohort study was conducted over one year duration at Sri Muthukumaran medical college and research institute, a tertiary care center among Fifty four patients diagnosed with Chronic rhinosinusitis. All patients underwent diagnostic nasal endoscopy, CT of the paranasal sinuses, complete blood count, absolute eosinophil count , erythrocyte sedimentation rate, and serum immunoglobulin E  estimation. Patients underwent functional endoscopic sinus surgery and biopsy sent for histopathological examination.\r\nResults: \r\nOverall, higher eosinophilic predominance was observed in most of the cases. A statistically significant correlation was observed between findings on diagnostic nasal endoscopy and absolute eosinophil count.\r\nConclusion: \r\nThe present study confirms that chronic rhinosinusitis is predominantly eosinophilic, although a considerable number exhibited mixed or neutrophilic inflammation. Staph. aureus biofilm and superantigen property has burdened treatment protocols for chronic rhinosinusitis worldwide. Endotypes of chronic rhinosinusitis and recalcitrant or recurrent chronic rhinosinusitis are emerging hence we recommend more studies to look into the endotypes of chronic rhinosinusitis before initiating the treatment protocols', '/public/upload/abstract/8eb21e7a5d1f3e2e668aadd038699554.docx', 'Prospective Clinicopathological Evaluation of Neutrophilic and Eosinophilic Inflammatory Endotypes i', NULL, '', NULL, '“ RULES ARE EXCEPTIONAL ”\r\n\r\nPresentor :- Dr. Aanandha Padmanathan V  (Post Graduate)\r\nGuide - Dr. Saranya(Assoc Prof),  Dr. Haribalan(Asst Prof) ,Department of ENT\r\nSri Muthukumaran Medical College and Research Institute\r\nAim : \r\nTo present the rarity of bilateral Inverted papilloma of paranasal sinuses.\r\nMethodology : \r\n	\r\n	A 36-year-old male presenting with bilateral nasal obstruction and rhinorrhea for the last two years. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy demonstrated a deviated nasal septum and multiple pale greyish, glistening masses in both the nasal cavity beyond the middle turbinate, with mucoid discharge. CT scan of  Para-nasal Sinus showed polypoidal mucosal thickening involving bilateral maxillary, ethmoidal, sphenoid, and frontal sinuses, with blockage of the osteomeatal and recess complexes.\r\nBased on the clinical and radiological findings the patient was diagnosed as bilateral sinonasal polyposis and underwent functional endoscopic sinus surgery. Biopsy was suggestive of inverted papilloma. Since the side of pathology was not indicated while sending the biopsy during subsequent followup after 1 week , biospy from polypoidal tissues from both middle meatus was sent for HPE as separate samples which revealed Inverted Papilloma on both sides. Hence patient was subjected to Bilateral Endoscopic Medial Maxillectomy. Histopathological examination confirmed  as Inverted papilloma without dysplasia or malignancy. \r\nThis patient is under followup for last 6 months without signs of recurrence.\r\nConclusion :\r\nWe would like to emphasis the importance of follow up and histopathology while treating any sino-nasal mass, since we initially came to a diagnosis as sinonasal polyposis which later turned out to be bilateral inverted papilloma. Though inverted papilloma presents as an unilateral polypoidal mass with an incidence of less than 4% of all the nasal tumours, literature reports bilateral inverted papilloma with an incidence of less than 5% among all inverted papilloma cases.', '/public/upload/abstract/84bd0091ee8a7784c73e4c8a96dabc54.docx', 'RULES ARE EXCEPTIONAL', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 14:45:02', '2025-11-15 14:45:06'),
(327, 'k.vivekraajan', 'drvivekraajanent@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000618', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo review contemporary advancements in the management of allergic rhinitis (AR) and to evaluate the clinical utility of selective posterior nasal neurectomy (PNN) in patients with refractory symptoms.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA narrative review was conducted, synthesizing recent evidence from clinical studies, anatomical investigations, and surgical outcome research related to AR and selective PNN. Particular focus was placed on anatomical variations of the posterior nasal nerve, refinements in selective neurectomy techniques, postoperative symptom improvement, and complication profiles.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nSelective PNN demonstrates consistent and significant improvement in key AR symptoms, including nasal obstruction, rhinorrhea, and sneezing in patients unresponsive to maximal medical therapy. Advances in endoscopic visualization and improved understanding of variable nerve branching patterns have enhanced surgical accuracy. Preservation of sensory branches during selective neurectomy appears to maintain mucosal function and reduces postoperative dryness and crusting. Overall, the procedure shows a favourable safety and efficacy profile, with low complication rates when anatomical variations are carefully accounted for.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nSelective PNN is an effective and valuable adjunct in the treatment of refractory allergic rhinitis. Ongoing refinement in anatomical knowledge and surgical technique continues to enhance outcomes. Further multicentre studies and long-term follow-up are needed to standardize surgical protocols and support broader global integration of this technique.', '/public/upload/abstract/3cace966e815ae0505b3abf0607e440e.docx', 'Refining the Management of Allergic Rhinitis: Clinical Insights into the Role of Selective Posterior', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 16:54:55', '2025-11-15 16:54:59'),
(328, 'Dr. Mikun M', 'mikun99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000581', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the role of early surgery in preventing vision loss  in patients with rhino-orbital -mucormycosis \r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nRhino-orbital mucormycosis (ROM) is a rapidly progressive angio-invasive fungal infection, most commonly caused by Rhizopus species.It frequently affects immunocompromised individuals and  rapidly extend from the nasal cavity  and sinuses to the orbit,  causing orbital symptoms and cranial neuropathies, vision loss, cavernous sinus thrombosis. Surgical interventions form the cornerstone of management alongside systemic antifungal therapy.\r\n\r\nMaterials and Methods\r\nA prospective observational study was conducted on 18 patients in our institute from 2023-2025 who were diagnosed with ROM, Orbital involvement was staged radiologically as Early-stage & Advanced disease.All patients received systemic liposomal amphotericin-B as first-line therapy.Early-stage patients underwent timely surgeries like endoscopic debridement and  orbital decompression through medial and inferior orbitotomy ,retrobulbar amphotericin-B injections (where indicated).Advanced-stage patients underwent wider debridement procedures. Outcomes assessed included progression of orbital disease, preservation of vision.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n Patients underwent early orbital surgery and targeted local therapy:\r\n17 patients–85% showedi mprovement in vision on follow up.\r\nOnly 3 -15% progressed to permanent vision loss due late presentation and aggressive disease\r\nPrompt and effective decompression and disease control, significantly reducing the risk of blindness. Early multidisciplinary intervention remains crucial for preserving vision and minimizing morbidity.', '/public/upload/abstract/00c0578895f9276cae685ffb7618e932.docx', 'Early Orbital Intervention in Preventing Vision Loss in Rhino-Orbital Mucormycosis', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 17:58:02', '2025-11-15 17:58:06'),
(329, 'DR HANISH S', 'hanishsk7501@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000636', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction \r\nAdult choanal atresia is rare, and postoperative restenosis or secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis poses significant management challenges. Residual adenoidal hypertrophy and progressive scarring can contribute to delayed obstruction. Coblation-assisted scar release with adjuvant Mitomycin-C is a useful strategy to reduce fibrosis during revision surgery.\r\n\r\nCase: \r\nA 41-year-old female with right-sided unilateral choanal atresia and grade 3 adenoids underwent primary endoscopic repair. Initial recovery was satisfactory, and she remained asymptomatic. After one year, she presented with gradually progressive bilateral nasal obstruction. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy and imaging demonstrated nasopharyngeal stenosis with recurrent narrowing at the right choana, suggestive of postoperative scar formation.\r\n\r\nIntervention\r\nRevision endoscopic surgery was planned. The procedure included Coblation-assisted scar tissue release, revision choanal atresia repair, bilateral functional endoscopic sinus surgery, and nasopharyngeal stenosis release. Mitomycin-C (0.4 mg/mL) was applied over raw areas for three minutes to inhibit fibroblast proliferation. Nasal packing was retained for 48 hours and removed without complications. The patient demonstrated improved airway patency during follow-up.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted revision surgery combined with Mitomycin-C application is effective in managing adult choanal atresia restenosis with secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis, offering improved long-term airway outcomes.', '/public/upload/abstract/fa483c0ee8acc200b17418a8554453b9.doc', 'Revision Adult Choanal Atresia: Coblation and Mitomycin-C in Preventing Restenosis', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 21:40:00', '2025-11-15 21:40:04'),
(330, 'DR HANISH S', 'hanishsk7501@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000636', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction \r\nAdult choanal atresia is rare, and postoperative restenosis or secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis poses significant management challenges. Residual adenoidal hypertrophy and progressive scarring can contribute to delayed obstruction. Coblation-assisted scar release with adjuvant Mitomycin-C is a useful strategy to reduce fibrosis during revision surgery.\r\n\r\nCase: \r\nA 41-year-old female with right-sided unilateral choanal atresia and grade 3 adenoids underwent primary endoscopic repair. Initial recovery was satisfactory, and she remained asymptomatic. After one year, she presented with gradually progressive bilateral nasal obstruction. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy and imaging demonstrated nasopharyngeal stenosis with recurrent narrowing at the right choana, suggestive of postoperative scar formation.\r\n\r\nIntervention\r\nRevision endoscopic surgery was planned. The procedure included Coblation-assisted scar tissue release, revision choanal atresia repair, bilateral functional endoscopic sinus surgery, and nasopharyngeal stenosis release. Mitomycin-C (0.4 mg/mL) was applied over raw areas for three minutes to inhibit fibroblast proliferation. Nasal packing was retained for 48 hours and removed without complications. The patient demonstrated improved airway patency during follow-up.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted revision surgery combined with Mitomycin-C application is effective in managing adult choanal atresia restenosis with secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis, offering improved long-term airway outcomes.', '/public/upload/abstract/b548233257a56c2f8ecd556fb391fdf9.doc', 'Mitomycin-C-Augmented Revision Repair in Adult Unilateral Choanal Atresia: A case report', NULL, '', NULL, 'Introduction \r\nAdult choanal atresia is rare, and postoperative restenosis or secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis poses significant management challenges. Residual adenoidal hypertrophy and progressive scarring can contribute to delayed obstruction. Coblation-assisted scar release with adjuvant Mitomycin-C is a useful strategy to reduce fibrosis during revision surgery.\r\n\r\nCase: \r\nA 41-year-old female with right-sided unilateral choanal atresia and grade 3 adenoids underwent primary endoscopic repair. Initial recovery was satisfactory, and she remained asymptomatic. After one year, she presented with gradually progressive bilateral nasal obstruction. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy and imaging demonstrated nasopharyngeal stenosis with recurrent narrowing at the right choana, suggestive of postoperative scar formation.\r\n\r\nIntervention\r\nRevision endoscopic surgery was planned. The procedure included Coblation-assisted scar tissue release, revision choanal atresia repair, bilateral functional endoscopic sinus surgery, and nasopharyngeal stenosis release. Mitomycin-C (0.4 mg/mL) was applied over raw areas for three minutes to inhibit fibroblast proliferation. Nasal packing was retained for 48 hours and removed without complications. The patient demonstrated improved airway patency during follow-up.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted revision surgery combined with Mitomycin-C application is effective in managing adult choanal atresia restenosis with secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis, offering improved long-term airway outcomes.', '/public/upload/abstract/70a330416a4038cbc222c240157cbbc1.doc', 'Revision Adult Choanal Atresia: Coblation and Mitomycin-C in Preventing Restenosis', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 21:49:15', '2025-11-15 21:49:19'),
(331, 'Sunishtha Attri', 'sunishtha98@gmail.com', 'sunishtha98@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Multidisciplinary Management of Advanced Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: our institutional experience \r\nPresenting authors: Dr Sunishtha  INSERT INTO `rh_abstract_old` (`id`, `name`, `email`, `reg_id`, `catergory_id`, `title_0`, `title_1`, `title_2`, `title_3`, `title_4`, `note`, `note_1`, `note_2`, `note_3`, `note_4`, `file`, `file_1`, `file_2`, `file_3`, `file_4`, `mail_send`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(6, 'DR RITU GUPTA', 'rituguptasaraf@gmail.com', 'RHIN000034', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Chronic rhino sinusitis (CRS) is a common disease. Maxillary sinusitis not cured by the medicines was addressed by the open surgical procedure namely Caldwell Luc operation. Thereafter introduction of nasal endoscopes in 1970’s led to the minimally invasive surgery FESS which preserved the physiology of the nose and sinuses. In the year 2002 balloon sinuplasty\r\nwas introduced in the western world and subsequently in India. Due to various logistics it was not performed and reintroduced in the year 2015 in India. It can be termed as micro minimally invasive surgery wherein anatomy as well as physiology of the nose and sinuses were preserved in cases of medically non responsive mild to moderate sinusitis. \r\nBalloon sinuplasty is a relatively new procedure which can be termed as micro minimally invasive surgery addressing the CRS without the traditional forms for surgery like incision, cutting or microdebriding. The principle is causing microfractures by inflating the sinus opening and thus facilitating the drainage of the sinus contents. No immediate or late post operative complications were noted. Sinus patency 6 months later was present in 90% of the cases. Balloon sinuplasty is an excellent procedure for medically nonresponsive CRS without polyposis. The success rate is spectacular matching the FESS with almost no immediate post operative and late complication. The recurrence rate of sinusitis is low. We conclude that balloon sinuplasty is a micro invasive procedure which saves operating time, time of hospital stay of the patient and delivers excellent result with almost no complications. We hope it could be incorporated as a routine surgery for mild to moderate sinusitis not responding to medicines.', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/41585bc679c434a5c2a5d6732515bde2.docx', '', 1, 1, '2025-07-04 10:12:39', '2025-07-04 10:12:39'),
(43, 'Dr Ayaz Rehman', 'drayazrehmanent@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000112', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Septorhinoplasty: Balancing Functional Restoration and Aesthetic Refinement', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Abstract\r\nBackground:\r\nSeptorhinoplasty remains the cornerstone procedure for addressing both structural nasal airway compromise and aesthetic deformities. This study aims to evaluate the functional and aesthetic outcomes of septorhinoplasty in patients with crooked nose deformities, using validated patient-reported outcome measures and comprehensive analysis of deformity-specific surgical techniques.\r\nMethods:\r\nA prospective study was conducted on 130 patients undergoing septorhinoplasty between 2019 and 2024. Patients were categorized based on nasal axis deviation into four deformity patterns: I-shaped, C-shaped, reverse C-shaped, and S-shaped. Functional outcomes were assessed using the NOSE (Nasal Obstruction Symptom Evaluation) scale, while aesthetic satisfaction was measured using the ROE (Rhinoplasty Outcome Evaluation) scale. Surgical approach was tailored per case, with the open approach used in 85.3% and the closed approach in 14.6%, primarily for isolated dorsal corrections. Osteotomies were performed in 100% of patients, with each case involving paramedian, lateral, and transverse osteotomies; intermediate osteotomies were employed in 8.4% for additional refinement. Structural cartilage grafting was performed as indicated: spreader grafts (49.2%), columellar struts (54.6%), tip grafts (32.3%), and alar batten grafts (13.8%).\r\nResults:\r\nOf the 130 patients, 48 (36.9%) had I-shaped, 30 (23.1%) C-shaped, 28 (21.5%) reverse C-shaped, and 24 (18.5%) S-shaped deformities. Significant functional improvement was observed, with mean NOSE scores decreasing from 75.3 ± 12.1 to 18.6 ± 8.9 (p < 0.001). Aesthetic outcomes demonstrated a corresponding increase in ROE scores from 38.4 ± 10.5 to 82.1 ± 9.7 (p < 0.001). Objective aesthetic refinement was achieved across multiple parameters: dorsal profile regularization (90%), nasal symmetry restoration (88%), tip projection and definition (85%), nasofrontal and nasolabial angle harmonization (86%), and radix leveling or augmentation (42%). Complications were minimal and self-limited, with transient edema in 22% and ecchymosis in 18%. No infections, septal perforations, or revision surgeries were recorded during the follow-up period.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSeptorhinoplasty, when tailored to the specific nasal deviation pattern and supported by a structured osteotomy and grafting protocol, achieves significant functional recovery and aesthetic restoration. The combination of a deformity-specific approach, precise osteotomy execution, and comprehensive grafting techniques ensures high patient satisfaction and low morbidity. These findings underscore the importance of integrating anatomical classification with outcome-based metrics for optimizing results in modern rhinoplasty.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '/public/upload/abstract/d0415bb00ba9d396c1299bfbfe2f06bd.docx', '', '', '', '', 1, 1, '2025-07-24 17:56:56', '2025-07-24 17:56:56'),
(45, 'Dr. Ritu Gupta', 'rituguptasaraf@gmail.com', 'RHIN00006', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'EFFICACY OF BALLOON SINUPLASTY VERSUS ENDOSCOPIC SINUS SURGERY FOR CHRONIC RHINOSINUSITIS WITHOUT NA', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background: Chronic rhinosinusitis without nasal polyposis (CRSsNP) significantly\r\naffects quality of life. This study aimed to compare the efficacy of Balloon\r\nSinuplasty (BSP) and Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (ESS) in managing CRSsNP.\r\nMethods: A non-randomized controlled trial was conducted including patients\r\ndiagnosed with CRSsNP. Participants underwent either BSP or ESS based on\r\nclinical suitability. Demographic data, symptom severity (SNOT-22), radiological\r\nscores (Lund-Mackay), endoscopic findings (Lund-Kennedy), and postoperative\r\ncomplications were evaluated at baseline, 1, 3, and 6 months postoperatively.\r\nResults: The BSP and ESS groups were demographically similar (mean age: 25.41\r\nvs. 24.61 years; p = 0.684; gender distribution p = 0.522). Both groups showed\r\nsignificant improvement in SNOT-22 scores. BSP provided better early symptom\r\nrelief at 1 month (p = 0.027), whereas ESS was more effective at 3 months (p &lt;\r\n0.001), with comparable outcomes at 6 months (p = 0.914). Preoperative Lund-\r\nMackay scores were higher in the ESS group (6.35 vs. 4.89; p = 0.001), indicating\r\nmore extensive disease. Postoperative scores improved significantly in both\r\ngroups, with BSP showing lower final scores (0.70 vs. 1.24; p = 0.001). Endoscopic\r\nscores improved in both groups, with BSP demonstrating superior early and\r\nsustained mucosal healing (p &lt; 0.001 and p = 0.009). Complications were fewer in\r\nBSP (21.74%) than ESS (32.61%), though not statistically significant (p = 0.349).\r\nConclusion: Both BSP and ESS are effective for CRSsNP. BSP offers faster\r\nrecovery, fewer complications, and comparable long-term outcomes, making it a\r\nviable minimally invasive alternative, particularly in cases with less extensive\r\ndisease.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/b4f1b59a80b66a80f7d90f7b0397d97d.docx', '', '', '', 1, 1, '2025-07-28 08:57:41', '2025-07-28 08:57:41'),
(59, 'Dr JITENDRA PRATAP SINGH CHAUHAN', 'chauhanbhavya36@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000116', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'POSTERIOR NASAL NERVE NEURECTOMY : A GAME CHANGER IN CHRONIC RHINITIS MANAGEMENT.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title: Posterior Nasal Nerve Neurectomy: A Game changer in chronic Rhinitis management \'\r\nPresenting Author: Dr Jitendra pratap singh chauhan\r\nAim: To evaluate the effectiveness of posterior nasal nerve neurectomy [PNNN] in reducing refractory symptoms of allergic and non -allergic rhinitis.\r\nMETHODOLOGY: Patients of intractable chronic rhinitis recruited from ENT OPD .written Consent taken for PNNN procedure along with RQLQ ,VAS, TNSS and peak nasal inflow noted . NCCT PNS and baseline investigations done \r\nPNNN done under General anaesthesia and followup done at 1 month. ,3month ,six month and 1 year and subjective and objective parameters noted.\r\nRESULTS: Significant improvement in TNSS , VAS AND RQLQ MEAN SCORES  . Improvement in chronic Rhinitis symptoms.\r\nCONCLUSIONS: PNNN is a promising alternative for refractory rhinitis. Effective in Rural and low income settings due to its cost effectiveness.. Long term relief and reduced need for medications make it an ideal solution.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '/public/upload/abstract/642d42c4ec193064bc9bb079366f4097.docx', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-08-13 07:30:09', '2025-08-13 07:30:13'),
(60, 'Dr Jobanpreet Singh', 'jobanpreetsingh007@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000130', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'The Effect of Jalneti on Patients of Allergic Rhinitis Undergoing Medical Management with Intranasal', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title: The Effect of Jalneti on Patients of Allergic Rhinitis Undergoing Medical Management with Intranasal Corticosteroids and Antihistaminics: A Randomized Controlled Trial\r\nPresenter: Dr. Jobanpreet Singh, Resident, ENT, AFMC Pune\r\nBackground:\r\nAllergic rhinitis (AR) is a common disorder caused by an exaggerated immune response to allergens, leading to sneezing, nasal blockage, and poor sleep. Though intranasal corticosteroids and antihistaminics remain standard therapy, many patients have persistent symptoms. Jalneti, a yogic saline nasal irrigation technique, is believed to improve nasal clearance and reduce inflammation, but evidence from randomized trials is limited.\r\nAim:\r\nTo assess the role of Jalneti as an adjunct to standard treatment in patients with AR.\r\nMethods:\r\nIn this randomized controlled trial, 60 patients (18–60 years) with mild-to-moderate (ARIA) AR  were divided into two groups. One received standard therapy, while the other performed Jalneti twice daily for three months along with medication. Outcomes were measured using SNOT-22 scores, nasal endoscopy, and eosinophil counts.\r\nResults:\r\nThe Jalneti group demonstrated greater symptom relief, lower eosinophil counts, and improved nasal findings compared to controls.\r\nConclusion:\r\nJalneti appears to be a safe, simple, and low-cost adjunct that can improve outcomes, reduce drug dependence, and enhance quality of life in allergic rhinitis.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/9cd3acac50f28b7f8ca2107d759b77df.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-08-22 22:47:23', '2025-09-17 14:21:43'),
(61, 'DR B GANESH RAJA', 'ganeshrajastanley@gmail.com', 'RHIN000013', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Unveiling the Rare Sinonasal Entity: A Case Report and Review', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Unveiling the Rare Sinonasal Entity: A Case Report and Review\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ganesh Raja B, Senior Resident, Department of ENT, Government Medical College Hospital, Kallakurichi\r\nObjective:\r\nTo highlight the diagnostic complexity and management of a rare sinonasal mass in a young adult female.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 22-year-old female presented to our department with complaints of left-sided nasal obstruction and intermittent episodes of epistaxis for a duration of two months. On nasal endoscopy, a polypoidal mass was visualized in the left nasal cavity. To further delineate the lesion, contrast-enhanced CT and MRI were performed, which revealed a well-defined expansile lesion occupying the left nasal cavity with extension into the left maxillary sinus. Based on these findings, the patient underwent endoscopic sinus surgery, during which the lesion was completely excised. The specimen was subsequently sent for histopathological evaluation.\r\nResults:\r\nHistopathology revealed the lesion to be a **nasal cholesteatoma**, a rare and unusual finding in this anatomical location. The postoperative period was uneventful, and the patient recovered well. She was kept under regular follow-up for six months, during which there was no evidence of recurrence either clinically or radiologically.\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasal cholesteatoma is an exceedingly rare condition, particularly when it involves the maxillary sinus. Its presentation often overlaps with that of more common benign sinonasal pathologies, such as nasal polyps or antrochoanal polyps, thereby posing diagnostic challenges. Cross-sectional imaging and histopathological confirmation remain crucial for accurate diagnosis. Complete surgical excision through endoscopic sinus surgery ensures optimal outcomes and reduces the risk of recurrence. This case emphasizes the need for clinicians to maintain a high index of suspicion for rare entities like cholesteatoma in the differential diagnosis of unilateral sinonasal masses, especially in young patients, to facilitate timely and appropriate management.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/5e7d598760b3d724f5da15e579a95159.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-01 15:11:00', '2025-09-01 15:11:05'),
(65, 'P Praveen Kumar', 'praveen19061992@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000191', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Renal Cell-Like Adenocarcinoma of Nasal Cavity: A Rare Entity Deserving Elucidation', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Sino-nasal malignancies are extremely rare accounting < 1% of all malignancies and < 3% of aero-digestive tract tumors. Their surgical pathology is extremely challenging due to the enormous heterogeneity. Few of these sino-nasal tumors may possibly present histologically as clear cell neoplasm. This mechanism is described as ‘histological mimicry’. Renal cell like adenocarcinoma (RCLA) is amongst the top contenders in that list of tumors including squamous cell carcinoma and mucoepidermoid carcinoma. RCLA affecting the nasal cavity is an extremely rare malignancy to have been reported in the literature. It was first described by Zuhr et al. in 2002 and till as recent as 2017 only 15 such cases had been reported worldwide. We present a rare case report of a 45 years old female who presented with unilateral nasal obstruction but was found harboring a histopathological surprise. We wish to highlight the diagnostic and therapeutic challenge faced in the management of this case and create awareness amongst the ORLs, pathologists and medical oncologists about this unaccustomed entity.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/fef1c007ffee619a650d88ebd8a4a38c.docx', 2, 1, '2025-09-13 16:06:12', '2025-09-13 16:06:16'),
(66, 'MAROOF SHAMUSHIHABUDHEEN', 'maroofsham5@gmail.com', 'RHIN000084', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Tuberculosis of the Sphenoid Sinus: A Rare and Elusive Diagnosis – A Case Report', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'We report a 10-year-old male presenting with progressive headache and visual loss. Imaging revealed a lytic lesion involving the sphenoid sinus with skull base extension. Initial biopsy demonstrated granulomatous inflammation, while CBNAAT confirmed Mycobacterium tuberculosis. The patient underwent endoscopic surgical debridement followed by standard anti-tubercular therapy, leading to clinical and visual improvement.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/8240b2e9750ca38a68848957688f2501.docx', 2, 1, '2025-09-13 22:29:04', '2025-09-13 22:29:08'),
(69, 'THAVAMANI', 'sewoj77250@ishense.com', 'Rhino0000537678', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, '765 video', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ytfymhj.l[:\"plkjgfxdcghjkl;jhgfcxghj', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/6d84b1ee8526bcdf13466dd0132edf51.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-15 11:03:51', '2025-09-15 11:03:55'),
(80, 'Priyasree', 'lakshmipriya662003@gmail.com', 'reg2333test', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Anoop title', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'wewe', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-17 20:20:02', '2025-09-17 20:20:06'),
(81, 'LEKHYA V', 'Lekhs1990@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000119', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Telephonic assessment of patient – reported outcomes following functional endoscopic sinus surgery: ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Presenting author – Dr Lekhya v Assistant Professor \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nObjective: To evaluate long-term patient-reported outcomes following functional endoscopic sinus surgery (FESS) using structured telephonic assessment.\r\n\r\nMethodology:  A retrospective audit of 72 patients (mean age 34.47±13.56 years, 68.1% male) who underwent FESS was conducted using validated telephonic questionnaires( modified SNOT 22, assessing five domains: nasal/sinus symptoms, sleep quality, psychological health, social/occupational functioning, and self-care management.\r\n\r\nResults:The questionnaire demonstrated acceptable internal consistency (Cronbach\'s alpha=0.793). Highest improvement was observed in nasal symptom relief (24.90±4.34) and self-care management (23.79±2.52). Composite overall score averaged 5.51±0.92, indicating favorable outcomes. Ordered logistic regression revealed nasal symptom relief (β=0.289, p=0.002) and sleep quality (β=0.532, p=0.028) as significant predictors of overall improvement. Patients aged 61-70 years showed significantly better outcomes compared to younger cohorts (β=3.427, p=0.027).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConclusion:Telephonic assessment effectively captures long-term post-FESS outcomes, with nasal symptom relief and sleep improvement being primary determinants of patient-reported success.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-19 11:58:47', '2025-09-19 11:58:51'),
(82, 'VADEPPALLY BALA KRISHNA', 'BALAKRISHNA221@GMAIL.COM', 'RHIN0000193', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Crossed Nerve Palsies in Sinonasal Mucormycosis: A Diabetic’s Facial-Hypoglossal Puzzle', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE\r\nCrossed Nerve Palsies in Sinonasal Mucormycosis: A Diabetic’s Facial-Hypoglossal Puzzle\r\nABSTRACT\r\nINTRODUCTION\r\nSinonasal mucormycosis is an acute invasive fungal infection of the nose and paranasal sinuses, which is rare, opportunistic and potentially fatal, occurring in both normal and immunocompromised individuals. Uncontrolled diabetics and immunocompromised patients are more prone to this invasive fungal infection. Sinonasal mucormycosis is approximately 1.7 cases per 1,000,000 inhabitants per year. Incidence of VII Cranial nerve palsy is 11% in these cases, and coexistence of ipsilateral Facial nerve and contralateral hypoglossal nerve is not documented in existing literature. \r\nCASE REPORT\r\n A 53-year-old woman was diagnosed with Sinonasal Mucormycosis with extension to the skull base and Infratemporal fossa with involvement of ipsilateral facial nerve palsy and contralateral hypoglossal nerve palsy, in the setting of newly diagnosed and uncontrolled diabetes mellitus. She was promptly started on Liposomal Amphotericin-B and underwent “Endoscopic trans-nasal trans-maxillary trans-pterygoid debridement”.\r\nCONCLUSION\r\nMucormycosis is a rare condition that is still fatal in the era of medical and surgical advancements. A combination of endoscopic surgical debridement followed by intravenous Amphotericin B therapy is quintessential in the management of such patients and has less morbidity compared with conventional treatment. Rare presentations like multiple cranial nerve palsy, which would otherwise raise the suspicion onwards granulomatous disease, need to be scrutinised and aspects ruled out in effective treatment of patients.\r\nKEYWORDS: \r\nSinonasal mucormycosis, Cranial nerve palsy, Amphotericin B, Transpterygoid debridement', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-19 13:50:12', '2025-09-19 13:50:16'),
(83, 'Dr Jobanpreet Singh', 'jobanpreetsingh007@gmail.com', 'RHINO000130', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Choanal Atresia Unplugged: A Journey from Blockage to Breathing', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Abstract\r\nTitle: Choanal Atresia Unplugged: A Journey from Blockage to Breathing\r\nAuthor: Dr Jobanpreet Singh, Resident ENT,AFMC Pune\r\nBackground:\r\nChoanal atresia is a rare congenital malformation characterized by complete or partial obstruction of the posterior nasal aperture, occurring in approximately 1 in 5,000–8,000 live births. It may be unilateral, typically presenting later with nasal obstruction and rhinorrhea, or bilateral, which manifests in neonates as respiratory distress relieved by crying. Nearly half of all cases are associated with other congenital anomalies, emphasizing the need for comprehensive evaluation.\r\nObjective:\r\nThis poster highlights a case series of congenital choanal atresia managed at a tertiary care center, emphasizing diagnostic approaches, surgical techniques, outcomes, and challenges in long-term follow-up.\r\nMethods:\r\nDiagnosis was initially suspected clinically by failure to pass a 6 Fr catheter through the nasal cavity and confirmed via nasal endoscopy and computed tomography (CT). All patients underwent surgical correction via an endoscopic transnasal approach, with postoperative stenting for seven days to maintain patency.\r\nResults:\r\nChoanal patency was successfully achieved in all patients. One case was complicated by mortality secondary to a severe atrioventricular septal defect (AVSD). Another patient developed postoperative restenosis on follow-up, requiring evaluation for revision atresiaplasty. Early diagnosis, airway stabilization, and timely intervention proved vital for favorable outcomes.\r\nConclusion:\r\nChoanal atresia, though rare, is a critical neonatal airway emergency, particularly in bilateral cases. A combination of high clinical suspicion, prompt imaging confirmation, and a multidisciplinary approach is essential. The endoscopic transnasal repair remains the gold standard for surgical management, offering excellent visualization and minimal morbidity. Long-term follow-up is imperative to monitor for restenosis and optimize patient outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-19 23:26:46', '2025-09-19 23:26:50'),
(86, 'Kaaviya J', 'kaaviyaj24@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000103', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic removal of esthenioneuroblastoma- a minimally Invasive procedure', NULL, 'Endoscopic Endonasal Excision of Esthesioneuroblastoma – A Minimally Invasive Approach Author:Dr.J.K', NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic Endonasal Excision of Esthesioneuroblastoma – A Minimally Invasive Approach\r\nAuthor:Dr.J.Kaaviya M.S.ENT postgraduate \r\nAbstract\r\nAim: To assess the role of endoscopic endonasal excision in the management of esthesioneuroblastoma with respect to surgical clearance, morbidity, and recovery.\r\n\r\nMethodology: Patients with histologically proven esthesioneuroblastoma (Kadish stage A–C) underwent endoscopic endonasal removal under general anesthesia. A binostril, four-handed technique with image guidance was employed. Tumor dissection from the nasal cavity, cribriform plate, and paranasal sinuses was performed with attention to preservation of critical structures. Postoperative follow-up included nasal endoscopy and imaging to detect residual or recurrent disease.\r\n\r\nDiscussion: Endoscopic surgery offers direct and magnified visualization, enabling precise tumor clearance with reduced morbidity compared to craniofacial resection. Benefits include minimal external scars, less blood loss, shorter hospital stay, and faster recovery. Limitations include technical challenges, requirement of surgical expertise, and relative difficulty in tumors with extensive orbital or intracranial spread. Long-term follow-up is crucial due to the potential for delayed recurrence.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Endoscopic endonasal excision is a safe and effective alternative for selected cases of esthesioneuroblastoma. It achieves comparable oncological outcomes to open approaches while reducing morbidity, thus representing a valuable minimally invasive strategy in modern skull base surgery', NULL, 'Endoscopic Endonasal Excision of Esthesioneuroblastoma – A Minimally Invasive Approach\r\nAuthor:Dr.J.Kaaviya M.S.ENT postgraduate \r\nAbstract\r\nAim: To assess the role of endoscopic endonasal excision in the management of esthesioneuroblastoma with respect to surgical clearance, morbidity, and recovery.\r\n\r\nMethodology: Patients with histologically proven esthesioneuroblastoma (Kadish stage A–C) underwent endoscopic endonasal removal under general anesthesia. A binostril, four-handed technique with image guidance was employed. Tumor dissection from the nasal cavity, cribriform plate, and paranasal sinuses was performed with attention to preservation of critical structures. Postoperative follow-up included nasal endoscopy and imaging to detect residual or recurrent disease.\r\n\r\nDiscussion: Endoscopic surgery offers direct and magnified visualization, enabling precise tumor clearance with reduced morbidity compared to craniofacial resection. Benefits include minimal external scars, less blood loss, shorter hospital stay, and faster recovery. Limitations include technical challenges, requirement of surgical expertise, and relative difficulty in tumors with extensive orbital or intracranial spread. Long-term follow-up is crucial due to the potential for delayed recurrence.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Endoscopic endonasal excision is a safe and effective alternative for selected cases of esthesioneuroblastoma. It achieves comparable oncological outcomes to open approaches while reducing morbidity, thus representing a valuable minimally invasive strategy in modern skull base surgery', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 20:47:12', '2025-09-23 20:47:17'),
(87, 'M Praveena', 'praveena2198@gmail.com', 'RHIN000099', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Fibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series', NULL, 'Fibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series', NULL, NULL, 'Title\r\n\r\nFibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series\r\n\r\nAuthor - Dr.M Praveena  MS ENT postgraduate\r\n\r\nAim\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this case series is to present and analyze three cases of fibrous dysplasia affecting the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, with emphasis on clinical features, diagnostic challenges, imaging findings, and surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\n\r\nThree patients presented with symptoms including  nasal obstruction, facial swelling, and intermittent epistaxis. Diagnostic evaluation with computed tomography  revealed the typical “ground-glass”  appearance consistent with fibrous dysplasia. Each case was managed uniquely based on the site and extent of involvement, with individualized treatment strategies. Preoperative planning relied on imaging to assess the anatomical extent and guide the management approach.\r\n\r\nResults\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent successful  management and had uneventful recoveries. Follow-up evaluations showed no recurrence in any case. One patient had involvement of the inferior turbinate, which added complexity to the diagnosis and management, requiring careful planning and execution.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nFibrous dysplasia involving the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses is rare but should be considered in patients presenting with osseous masses and nasal symptoms. Timely diagnosis and appropriately planned surgical intervention lead to favorable functional  outcomes.', NULL, 'Title\r\n\r\nFibrous Dysplasia of the Nasal Cavity and Paranasal Sinuses: A Case Series\r\n\r\nAuthor - Dr.M Praveena  MS ENT postgraduate\r\n\r\nAim\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this case series is to present and analyze three cases of fibrous dysplasia affecting the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, with emphasis on clinical features, diagnostic challenges, imaging findings, and surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\n\r\nThree patients presented with symptoms including  nasal obstruction, facial swelling, and intermittent epistaxis. Diagnostic evaluation with computed tomography  revealed the typical “ground-glass”  appearance consistent with fibrous dysplasia. Each case was managed uniquely based on the site and extent of involvement, with individualized treatment strategies. Preoperative planning relied on imaging to assess the anatomical extent and guide the management approach.\r\n\r\nResults\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent successful  management and had uneventful recoveries. Follow-up evaluations showed no recurrence in any case. One patient had involvement of the inferior turbinate, which added complexity to the diagnosis and management, requiring careful planning and execution.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nFibrous dysplasia involving the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses is rare but should be considered in patients presenting with osseous masses and nasal symptoms. Timely diagnosis and appropriately planned surgical intervention lead to favorable functional  outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 20:50:07', '2025-09-23 20:50:11'),
(88, 'Shreya Deshpande', 'docsharoo@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000327', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Case of Frontal Mucocele', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Case of Frontal Mucocele \r\n\r\nAuthor : Dr Shreya Deshpande ( Junior resident, Dept of ENT, SKNMC Pune) \r\nGuide : Dr Sanjana Nemade ( HOD, Dept of ENT, SKNMC Pune ) \r\n\r\nCase: A 70 years old female, presented to ENT OPD with complaints of protrusion of left eye and decrease in vision of left eye since 15 days.\r\nExamination of Orbits - Left eye : Vision CF <1 m, Extraocular movements restricted, eyeball protruding. \r\nDiagnostic Nasal endoscopy and Anterior Rhinoscopy - Polypoidal left middle turbinate, smooth bulge above and lateral to left middle turbinate, \r\nCT PNS + Orbits  - Widening of frontal sinus, thinning of sinus wall with minimal erosion of posterior wall of the frontal sinus, extension into orbital roof with erosion of orbital roof.\r\nManagement - Left FESS under GA. Under endoscopic evaluation, inferior turbinate was infractured and lateralised; Uncinectomy done; Bulge noted in the middle meatus, mucosa removed, whitish cystic growth noted in the frontal recess region. On opening, cheesy non foul smelling material suctioned out. Protrusion of left eye resolved on table.\r\nHistopathology report - left frontal sinus mucocele.\r\nStatus on discharge- Complete subsidence of left eye protrusion.\r\nOn follow up - Left eye extra ocular movements improved in all directions, vision improved.\r\nConclusion: Mucocele is epithelium lined mucus filled sac within paranasal sinuses which causes expansion and remodeling of sinus walls. Site: Frontal > Ethmoid > Maxillary > Sphenoid. Most common etiology- Sinus surgery ( 66-86%). Other causes can be post surgery(50%),  trauma ( 10-14%), spontaneously (15-17%). Two essential factors - 1.Obstructed sinus outflow tract & 2. Inflammatory process within the sinus which include cytokine IL1 and TNF causing bony erosions and thinning of sinus walls. Surgical management is wide marsupialization of sac.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-23 22:13:32', '2025-09-23 22:13:37'),
(90, 'VIKAS SHARMA', 'vicky251983@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000345', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CHOANAL ATRESIA IN ADULT- ENDOSCOPIC SURGERY AND RECONSTRUCTION', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Choanal atresia is a rare but the most common congenital anomaly of the nasal cavity. Bilateral choanal atresia in an elderly person is extremely rare. This condition occurs due to the persistence of the nasobuccal membrane, which should normally rupture around the 7th week of embryonic development. The only way the patient survives is if there is partial atresia in one of the sides as was present in our patient. Here, we present a case of a 69-year-old woman with bilateral choanal atresia, with the right choana being completely atretic and the left choana partially atretic, the patient underwent transnasal endoscope-guided bilateral choanoplasty and reconstruction using the crossover nasoseptal flap technique and stenting. Transnasal endoscopic choanoplasty is generally considered the treatment of choice for this condition. Restenosis is a common postoperative complication, but proper nasal douching and regular follow-up can help reduce the likelihood of restenosis.', NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-25 10:59:38', '2025-09-25 10:59:42'),
(91, 'RADHIKA DEVI S', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Invasive Fungal Sinusitis in Immunocompromised Patient- Case Report', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title \r\nInvasive Fungal Sinusitis in Immunocompromised Patient – Case Report\r\nAuthor \r\nDr. Radhika Devi. S\r\nSecond Year ENT PG\r\nMadras Medical College \r\nAim\r\nTo highlight the clinical presentation, diagnostic approach and management of single case of invasive fungal sinusitis with importance of early intervention.\r\nMethodology \r\nA  35 year old male occupant as driver referred from RIOGH Egmore with C/O swelling in the left eye × 1week, Nasal obstruction and discharge ×1 week.\r\nClinical examination reveals DNS to left and secretions present in left nasal cavity. Examination of eye shows, blurring of vision,  elevation, abduction and adduction restricted on left eye. MRI brain shows invasive fungal sinusitis with left eye proptosis with intra cranial extensions. Patient underwent full house FESS with endoscopic left medial orbital wall decompression with septal correction followed by systemic antifungal therapy.\r\nResults: \r\nPost operatively left eye proptosis decreased and  vision also improved . \r\nPatient restricted eye movements increased . \r\nConclusion :\r\n      \"This case emphasizes the critical role of early diagnosis and prompt combined surgical and medical management \"\r\n        \"in invasive fungal sinusitis. In high-risk patients such as those with uncontrolled diabetes, a high index of \"\r\n        \"suspicion is essential to reduce morbidity and prevent mortality.\"', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-25 22:56:28', '2025-09-25 22:56:32'),
(92, 'RADHIKA DEVI S', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', 'dr.radhikadevi@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Extra nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma- A Rare Case Presentation', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title\r\nExtra nasopharyngeal Angio fibroma: A Rare Case Presentation \r\nAuthor\r\nDr. Radhika Devi. S\r\nSecond Year Postgraduate, Department of ENT\r\nMadras Medical College, Chennai\r\nAim\r\nTo present a rare case of extranasopharyngeal angiofibroma (ENA), highlight its clinical presentation, diagnostic approach, and management, and to compare it with classical juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA).\r\nMethodology\r\nA single case report was documented involving a 16-year-old patient who presented with swelling in the right nasal cavity for past 2 weeks and epistaxis on and off for past 2 weeks. Detailed history, clinical examination, and CT were performed to assess the site, and  extent, of the lesion followed by surgical excision under general anesthesia. Histopathological examination confirmed the diagnosis. Relevant literature was reviewed to compare epidemiology, sites of origin, and treatment strategies of ENA versus JNA.\r\nResults\r\nThe patient underwent complete surgical excision without obvious blood loss. Postoperative recovery was uneventful, and no recurrence was observed during a follow-up period of six months. Histopathology correlated with a diagnosis of extranasopharyngeal angiofibroma. A review of literature revealed that ENA is extremely rare, tends to occur in older age groups, shows less aggressive behavior than JNA, and has a better surgical outcome.\r\nConclusion\r\nExtranasopharyngeal angiofibroma should be considered in the differential diagnosis of vascular nasal and paranasal masses, especially in cases not fitting the classical profile of JNA. Early imaging, preoperative planning, and surgical excision provide excellent outcomes with minimal recurrence.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-25 23:33:49', '2025-09-25 23:33:53'),
(97, 'Dr Malathi M', 'malathim91@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000115', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'NASOPHARYNGEAL CARCINOMA: DIAGNOSING THE SILENT INTRUDER', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE:“NASOPHARYNGEAL CARCINOMA: DIAGNOSING THE SILENT INTRUDER”\r\nPresenting author: Dr. Malathi M\r\nAim:\r\nTo study the clinical presentation, diagnostic methods, and treatment response of nasopharyngeal carcinoma.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective observational study was conducted on patients diagnosed with nasopharyngeal carcinoma in a tertiary care hospital. Detailed history, ENT examination, imaging, and histopathological confirmation were done. Patients were treated with radiotherapy and concurrent chemotherapy and followed up for outcome assessment.\r\nResults:\r\nMajority of patients presented with painless cervical lymph node enlargement, nasal obstruction, and epistaxis. Histopathology revealed undifferentiated carcinoma in most patients. Radiotherapy with chemotherapy was effective in early-stage disease, with good local control.\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasopharyngeal carcinoma often presents late due to its silent location and vague symptoms. Early diagnosis with imaging and biopsy, along with combined modality treatment, improves survival. Multidisciplinary care is vital for better outcomes.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:34:27', '2025-09-26 19:34:32'),
(99, 'Imon DasGupta', 'imon.crazy@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000194', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'THE VANISHING TUMOUR\r\nDr. Imon DasGupta\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION / BACKGROUND\r\nOral cancer is one of the three commonest types of cancer in India. 5- 12% of oral cavity cancers are found in the hard palate. They are usually seen in tobacco users and may be preceded by luekoplakia or erythroplakia. Surgical excision is the mainstay of the treatment, often followed by adjuvant radiotherapy.\r\nAIM		\r\nWe present an interesting case of Squamous carcinoma of the hard palate where, in spite of margin involvement in the original excision, no residual tumour was found in the final specimen.\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY\r\nA 42 year old male patient presented with an erythroplakic lesion of the right hard palate; the initial biopsy obtained elsewhere suggested dysplasia. A wide local excision was performed with local flap reconstruction. Surprisingly the specimen was reported as well differentiated squamous carcinoma involving all margins. The patient then underwent an infrastructure maxillectomy.\r\n\r\nRESULT\r\nThe final histopathology report showed no sign of any tumour. Both biopsy and final specimen slides were reviewed.\r\nCONCLUSION \r\nLocal immunity and anti tumour activity possibly cleared the remaining tumour cells resulting in a vanishing tumour.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 19:44:10', '2025-09-26 19:44:14'),
(102, 'PRASANTH L', 'ragavprash28@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000118', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Role of image-guided navigation in enhancing safety and surgical precision in Endoscopic sinonas', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '-	Aim:\r\nTo highlight the role of image-guided navigation using the Medtronic-Stealth Station FlexENT™ system in improving surgical safety, accuracy, and outcomes in endoscopic sinonasal surgeries.\r\n-	Methodology:\r\nThe video shows series of patients who underwent navigation-assisted endoscopic sinonasal surgery and includes Intraoperative parameters assessed included accuracy of anatomical localization, facilitation of dissection near vital structures, completeness of lesion clearance, and surgeon confidence. \r\n-	Results:\r\nThe image-guided navigation system provided real-time anatomical guidance with high precision, enabling safe dissection around critical areas such as the orbit, skull base, and optic nerve. Navigation proved particularly valuable in revision cases and advanced disease with distorted anatomy. Surgeons reported increased confidence, better intraoperative decision-making, and improved efficiency. Complete disease clearance was achieved in the majority of cases, with no major intraoperative complications and minimal postoperative morbidity.\r\n-	Conclusion:\r\nImage-guided navigation significantly enhances the safety and precision of endoscopic sinonasal surgeries. This system improves surgeon confidence, reduces complication risk, and ensures optimal surgical outcomes, making it a valuable adjunct in modern rhinological and skull base practice.\r\n-	Word count – 199', NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-26 21:57:25', '2025-09-26 21:57:29'),
(108, 'Dr. Mohamed Farook', 'mohammedfarooqa@yahoo.com', 'RHIN00087', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ACUTE BACTERIAL RHINOSINUSITIS MASQUERADING AS ANGIOFIBROMA :  A CASE REPORT', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nThe reported case of an 8-year-old female underscores the significant diagnostic challenges arising when common infections, such as Acute Bacterial Rhinosinusitis (ABRS), mimic rare, aggressive neoplastic conditions. While ABRS is typically straightforward, its imaging features can occasionally overlap with tumours like Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma (JNA), a benign, highly vascular tumour predominantly affecting adolescent males.\r\nCase history: \r\nThe patient presented with a 7-day history of left periorbital pain, swelling, redness, and watering of the left eye. \r\nGeneral examination: showed mild left eye proptosis. \r\nLocal examination and Diagnostic Nasal Endoscopy (DNE):  were highly suggestive of infection, revealing congested nasal mucosa, mucopurulent discharge in the left middle meatus, and an oedematous middle turbinate. Grade 4 adenoid hypertrophy was also noted.\r\nMRI Findings:  an external MRI complicated the diagnosis, suggesting a nasopharyngeal mass, likely angiofibroma, with osseous erosion of the sphenoid sinus and extension into surrounding structures, including the maxillary and frontal sinuses and the masticator space.\r\nCECT Findings: The definitive CECT provided clarity, demonstrating complete opacification of four left-sided sinuses (maxillary, ethmoid, frontal, and sphenoid) and extra-conal orbital involvement. Crucially, the CECT showed an intact left lamina papyracea. Based on clinical and CECT findings, the final diagnosis was ABRS with orbital complications (stage 2 orbital cellulitis/post septal cellulitis).\r\nManagement and Conclusion:  required a careful assessment of vision, fundus, and colour vision, followed by an aggressive 11-day course of IV Meropenem (700 mg) and Vancomycin (400 mg) thrice daily. Marked clinical improvement occurred within 48 hours, critically obviating the need for surgery. The patient was discharged with proptosis resolved, continuing oral Linezolid and Cefuroxime. This case confirms that prompt, aggressive IV antibiotics are paramount in managing stage 1 and 2 orbital cellulitis and can prevent unnecessary invasive procedures.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-27 11:44:55', '2025-09-27 11:44:59'),
(109, 'Dr.R.kamala', 'kaushikathar@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000101', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Bleeding clues : Unmasking sinonasal malignancy behind recurrent epistaxis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'BLEEDING CLUES : UNMASKING SINONASAL MALIGNANCY BEHIND  RECURRENT EPISTAXIS Dr.Kamala.R.,Postgraduate \r\nBACKGROUND :\r\nRecurrent Epistaxis as a Presenting Symptom of  Sinonasal Neoplasm: A Case Report\r\nMETHODOLOGY :\r\n A case of a 45-year-old male patient who presented with recurrent epistaxis and was found to have a nasal mass on Anterior rhino scopy examination. Patient further evaluated with Endoscopic examination and Radiological Evaluation. Biopsy and histopathology revealed a poorly differentiated Sino nasal neoplasm. The patient was  planned for radiotherapy. This case highlights the importance of considering Sino nasal malignancies in the differential diagnosis of recurrent epistaxis and the need for prompt evaluation and treatment\r\nMANAGEMENT :\r\nThe patient was planned for radiotherapy as part of a multidisciplinary treatment approach.\r\n CONCLUSION:\r\nThis case emphasizes the importance of considering sinonasal malignancies in patients with recurrent epistaxis and highlights the need for prompt evaluation and management to improve patient outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-27 15:42:24', '2025-09-27 15:42:28'),
(110, 'THAIEBA A', 'thaieba777@gmail.com', 'RHINO000100', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'SURGICAL MANAGEMENT OF RECURRENT PAEDIATRIC EPISTAXIS ( REFRACTORY TO CONSERVATIVE METHODS)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title:     SURGICAL MANAGEMENT OF RECURRENT PAEDIATRIC EPISTAXIS (REFRACTORY TO CONSERVATIVE  METHODS)\r\n\r\nPresenting Author:        Dr. Thaieba. A., ( Final year Post graduate)\r\nAim:\r\nRecurrent epistaxis in pediatric patients often presents a management challenge when conservative treatments fail. This study aims to assess the safety and effectiveness of targeted surgical management in pediatric patients with recurrent epistaxis unresponsive to conservative treatment.\r\nMethodology:\r\nSeven children aged 6–11 years with refractory epistaxis were studied. Five underwent Endoscopic Sphenopalatine artery  cauterization with bipolar cauterization of bleeding spots in septum, while two were managed with nasal septal bony spurrectomy combined with bipolar cauterization of bleeding spots in septum. All procedures were performed under general anesthesia with endoscopic guidance.\r\nResults\r\nAll patients achieved complete cessation of epistaxis postoperatively, with no recurrence or significant complications during varying periods of  follow-up from 3 to 6 months post operatively.\r\nConclusion\r\nCombined endoscopic surgical approaches, tailored to patient anatomy, are safe and effective in controlling refractory pediatric epistaxis. Early surgical intervention should be considered to provide durable relief and reduce morbidity', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-27 19:40:34', '2025-09-27 19:40:38'),
(111, 'Jyoti Ranjan Das', 'jdbegins007@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000362', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Central Giant Cell Granuloma of Maxilla with Coexisting Parathyroid Adenoma: A Rare Dual Pathology', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A 35-year-old female presented with a gradually enlarging swelling over the left cheek and nasal obstruction persisting for one year. She denied pain, nasal discharge, bleeding, sensory deficits, or visual disturbances. Her medical history was notable for renal calculi treated with lithotripsy, with no other comorbidities.\r\nClinical examination revealed a firm, non-tender swelling over the left cheek, extending superiorly to the infraorbital rim, inferiorly to the upper lip, medially to the nasomaxillary groove, and laterally to the lateral canthus. \r\nNasal endoscopy showed a bulge on the lateral nasal wall with medial displacement of the inferior and middle turbinates.  Intraoral examination revealed a non-bleeding bulge over the hard palate from the canine to second molar region, with loosened premolars.\r\nCEMRI of the nose and paranasal sinuses demonstrated a lobulated expansile lesion (4.5 × 5 × 4.7 cm) centered in the left maxillary sinus, with osseous remodeling and extension into adjacent structures including the anterior and posterior walls, orbital floor, alveolar ridge, hard palate, and nasal cavity. \r\nCBCT revealed a translucent lesion from tooth 25 to 28, with root resorption and cortical plate destruction. \r\nMSCT angiography showed a well-enhancing lesion (50 × 46 × 44 mm) within the left maxillary sinus, displacing the inferior rectus muscle and involving surrounding structures, without vascular malformation.\r\nOPD biopsy suggested central giant cell granuloma (CGCG). The lesion was excised via an extended medial maxillectomy, and a palatal obturator was placed. Histopathology confirmed CGCG.\r\nOn postoperative day 3, the patient developed abdominal pain and vomiting. Imaging revealed pancreatitis, and biochemical tests showed elevated serum parathyroid hormone, ionized calcium, and lipase, with low phosphorus—indicative of hypercalcemia-induced pancreatitis. \r\nMSCT neck identified a right inferior parathyroid adenoma (17 × 9 × 43 mm), which was surgically excised. Histopathology confirmed the adenoma, and postoperative hormone levels normalized. At 2-month follow-up, the patient remained stable with no recurrence. \r\nThis case underscores the importance of evaluating serum calcium and parathyroid hormone levels in patients with CGCG, as underlying hyperparathyroidism may coexist and influence management.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-27 23:35:02', '2025-09-27 23:35:06');
INSERT INTO `rh_abstract_old` (`id`, `name`, `email`, `reg_id`, `catergory_id`, `title_0`, `title_1`, `title_2`, `title_3`, `title_4`, `note`, `note_1`, `note_2`, `note_3`, `note_4`, `file`, `file_1`, `file_2`, `file_3`, `file_4`, `mail_send`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(112, 'Dr Raghvi Anand', 'raghvia7@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000361', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'REDEFINING SURGICAL CONTROL IN EPISTAXIS: THE EVOLVING ROLE OF TESPAL IN CONTEMPORARY RHINOLOGY', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'AIM:\r\nTo assess the effectiveness, safety, and evolving role of Transnasal Endoscopic Sphenopalatine Artery Ligation (TESPAL) in the management of refractory posterior epistaxis.\r\nMETHODOLOGY:\r\nThis prospective case series was conducted between (2023-2024) in the Department of Otorhinolaryngology. 20 patients with intractable posterior epistaxis, unresponsive to anterior/posterior nasal packing and medical measures, were included. Patients with bleeding diathesis or uncontrolled hypertension were excluded. All underwent TESPAL under general anesthesia using 0° and 30° nasal endoscopes. The sphenopalatine foramen was identified, arterial branches isolated, and hemostasis secured by clipping. Parameters studied included operative duration, intraoperative events, blood loss, complications, hospital stay, recurrence, and follow-up outcomes at 1 week, 1 month, and 3 months.\r\nRESULTS:\r\nOf the 20 patients (14 males, 6 females; mean age 52 years), complete control of bleeding was achieved in 19 (95%) after a single procedure. One patient (5%) experienced recurrence at 2 weeks, successfully managed by revision cauterization. Mean operative time was 38 minutes, with an average blood loss of 65 ml and mean hospital stay of 2.1 days. Minor complications included nasal crusting in 3 patients, which resolved conservatively. No major complications were noted.\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nTESPAL is a minimally invasive, precise, and highly effective surgical technique for refractory posterior epistaxis. This 20-patient series underscores its reliability, safety, and role as a contemporary frontline surgical strategy, redefining the paradigm of epistaxis control in modern rhinology.\r\nKeywords: TESPAL, Refractory posterior epistaxis, Endoscopic sphenopalatine artery ligation, Minimally invasive rhinology', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-28 08:48:51', '2025-09-28 08:48:56'),
(114, 'JAISE JACOB', 'jaijaisedr@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000108', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Orbital Complications of Acute Sinusitis-a retrospective analysis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '•	Title-Orbital Complications of Acute Sinusitis-a retrospective analysis \r\n•	Presenting Author-Dr.Jaise Jacob\r\n•	Aim-To review orbitalcomplications ofacute sinusitis and analyze their demography, clinical features, microbiology, radiological findings, treatment and outcome.\r\n•	Methodology-Retrospective review of medical records of patients diagnosed with acute sinusitis with orbital complicationsbetween 2010-2025.\r\n•	Results-Among the 26 patients with complications of acute sinusitis,24 (92.3%) had orbital complications. Among them 41.6% were males and 58.3%females with average age 34.9years.The orbital complications encountered were subperiosteal abscess(33.3%), orbital cellulitis(25%), cavernous-sinus thrombosis(20.8%), preseptal cellulitis(12.5%) and orbital abscess(8.3%).Predominant presenting symptoms were periorbital swelling(87.5%), nasal discharge(72%) and restricted eye movements (66.6%). Endoscopy revealed purulent discharge in 70% of patients. Bacterial culture yielded gram-positive cocci in (62.5%) and gram-negative bacilli in (20.8%). Radiologically, maxillary and ethmoid sinuses (87.5%) were commonly affected followed by sphenoid(83.3%) and frontal(66.6%). Intraorbital collection was seen in 41.6% with medial quadrant involvement. While all patients received antibiotics, 87.5% underwent sinus surgery and 25% required orbital surgery. All except two patients (91.6%) were discharged in stable condition.\r\n•	Conclusions-Orbital complications of acute sinusitis remain potentially life-threatening. Early diagnosis, aggressive medical treatment, and timely surgery enhance favorable outcome.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-29 21:45:31', '2025-09-29 21:45:35'),
(115, 'Shreya', 'shreyakovuru@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000363', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Assessment of outcomes of endonasal dacryocystorhinostomy in a tertiary referral centre', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'HEADING TITLE: “ASSESMENT OF OUTCOMES OF ENDONASAL DACROCYSTORHINOSTOMY IN A TERITIARY REFERRAL CENTRE’’- \r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR: DR KOVURU SHREYA\r\n\r\nAim: \r\n•	To document the long term outcomes in endoscopic dacryocystorhinostomy and complications\r\n•	To correlate the various risk factors with complications\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nData was retrieved from case files of patients who underwent DCR from medical record section. Data was collected in terms of immediate and delayed complications of ENDO DCR. Data was also collected at the end of one month, 3rd month and 6th month of surgery with respect to watering of eye, lacrimal sac syringing, DNE findings for assessment of stomal patency. Risk factors for developing dacryocystitis were correlated with complications of surgery.\r\nResults:\r\nPostoperative complications occurred in a minority of cases and encompassed a spectrum from transient mucosal edema and minor bleeding to granulation formation, synechiae, ostium stenosis and persistent epiphora. Early complications were predominantly self-limited and were managed conservatively, while late complications such as ostium stenosis often required endoscopic revision. Significant risk factors for adverse outcomes included history of chronic nasal inflammation, previous lacrimal surgery, and intraoperative mucosal trauma. Structured postoperative surveillance facilitated early detection of complications and targeted interventions reduced symptom persistence.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic DCR was associated with a low rate of serious postoperative complications. Most complications were manageable with  endoscopic surgeries. Attention to patient selection, meticulous surgical technique and structured postoperative care reduced complication burden and improved functional outcomes consistently.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-29 22:32:12', '2025-09-29 22:32:16'),
(116, 'DR SHRABANI SARDAR', 'shrabanisardar07@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000195', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Maxillary Antral Haemangiomata – presentation, investigation and management', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. BACKGROUND-\r\nMaxillary Haemangiomata are rare and originally described by Smith in 1959 as  an intra-osseous lesion which bled profusely at surgery. He described them as central or peripheral. Choukas in 1963 recognized two varieties: the osseous, as previously described, and the mucosal variety arising from the antral mucosa, which may be excised with minimal blood loss. \r\n2. AIM\r\nTo present our experience in the diagnosis and management of a series of mucosal maxillary antral haemangiomata.\r\n3.METHODOLOGY-\r\nIn the 12 year period from 2013 to 2025 we have encountered 5 cases of antral mucosal haemangiomata. All were adults (19 to 45 years), with 3 males and two females. All presented with intermittent epistaxis , not particularly profuse, and intermittent nasal obstruction. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy in all cases showed a mucosal bulging in the middle or inferior meatus, with a typical bluish discolouration\r\n4.RESULT-\r\nAll patients underwent Contrast enhanced CT scan of nose and paranasal sinuses, which showed a heterogenous mass , not particularly enhancing. One patient underwent excision by a lateral rhinotomy approach, all others were addressed endoscopically with minimal bleeding. Pre-operative embolization was not performed in any case. Excision was total and no recurrence has been noted', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 06:01:23', '2025-09-30 06:01:28'),
(118, 'Majid ul Islam Masoodi', 'majidmasoodi56@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000351', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Chronic Rhinosinusitis in COPD: A Case–Control Study from a Tertiary Centre in Kashmir', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim: We aimed to determine the prevalence of chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS) in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and to assess the association between these conditions. Additionally, the study evaluated differences in CRS prevalence between COPD subtypes (emphysema and chronic bronchitis).\r\nMethodology: This prospective observational case–control study was conducted at a tertiary care center (GMC Srinagar) over 1.5 years. We enrolled 200 COPD patients (cases) and 200 control subjects without COPD. COPD was diagnosed as per GOLD criteria, and CRS was identified based on EPOS guidelines through clinical evaluation and nasal endoscopy. Key symptoms (nasal discharge, nasal obstruction, postnasal drip, facial pain, anosmia) and endoscopic findings (mucopurulent discharge, edema, nasal polyps) were documented and analyzed.\r\nResults: CRS was diagnosed in 14.5% of COPD patients compared to 8.0% of controls, reflecting a significantly higher prevalence in the COPD group (OR = 1.95). Within the COPD cohort, CRS prevalence was 17.5% in the emphysema subtype and 11.3% in chronic bronchitis (OR = 2.44 and 1.47 respectively vs controls), indicating a stronger association of CRS with emphysema. The most common CRS-related symptom was nasal obstruction, followed by anosmia and facial pain; nasal discharge and postnasal drip were also frequently reported. These symptoms showed a strong correlation with CRS diagnosis (p<0.001). On nasal endoscopy, characteristic CRS findings (mucopurulent discharge, mucosal edema, and nasal polyps) were observed in CRS patients. Notably, these endoscopic abnormalities occurred at similar rates in CRS patients with and without COPD, indicating comparable sinonasal pathology in both groups.\r\nConclusions: COPD and CRS frequently co-exist as comorbid conditions. Our findings underscore the importance of recognizing CRS in COPD patients, particularly in those with the emphysema subtype. Routine screening for CRS in COPD is advisable to ensure comprehensive management of these patients.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 11:40:26', '2025-09-30 11:40:30'),
(119, 'Dr. Srinidhi V', 'srinidhivijaykumar1999@gmail.com', 'srinidhivijaykumar1999@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '\"Epistaxis unmasked : The hidden leech \"', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background:\r\nChildren aged 2–5 years often insert small objects like beads, seeds, or button batteries into their noses out of curiosity. If not detected early, these can lead to infection, bleeding, or nasal damage. Timely recognition and safe removal are crucial to prevent complications.\r\nMaterials and Methods:\r\n A 40 year old patient presented to the emergency department of tertiary care Hospital, Sullia on 1st april 2025 who is chronic alcoholic since 28 years presented with left nasal bleed since 5 days which is insidious onset, recurrent episodes, minimal amount of bleeding noticed. \r\nNo history of trauma, hypertension, cardiovascular disease, liver and kidney disorder, bleeding disorder.\r\nNo history of nasal obstruction, foul smelling nasal discharge, anosmia, fever/cough, living/working in farms, anticoagulant drug use. Patient was initially managed by trotters method and topical haemocoagulase nasal drops but intermittent nose bleed was present in view of this ENT reference was taken. \r\nOn examination - \r\n- Bilateral vestibule appears normal, no finger nail abrasion marks, anterior rhinoscopy shows mild deviated nasal septum to right. Left nasal cavity and floor bleeding present. Right nasal cavity appears clear.\r\nInvestigation -\r\nDiagnostic nasal endoscopy: A leech(alive foreign body) noted in left nasal cavity below middle turbinate. Nasopharynx, middle and superior turbinates and meatuses appears normal. Right nasal cavity appears normal. \r\nResults: \r\nLeech noted in left nasal cavity below middle turbinate.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasal foreign bodies are common in young children and can rarely be seen in adults, doctors can be faced with this problem. Early recognition and proper removal are essential to prevent infection, bleeding, or nasal damage. Prevention through supervision and education is also a key.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 12:35:29', '2025-09-30 12:35:33'),
(121, 'ASHOK BALAJI R', 'ashokbala98765@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000111', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Unmasking the Unusual: Bilateral Eustachian Tube Involvement in Recurrent Rhinosporidiosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background:\r\nRhinosporidiosis is a chronic granulomatous disease caused by Rhinosporidium seeberi, primarily affecting the nasal mucosa and nasopharynx. Involvement of the Eustachian tubes is extremely rare and poses significant diagnostic and therapeutic challenges, especially in recurrent cases.\r\n\r\nCase Presentation:\r\nA 47-year-old male with a history of recurrent rhinosporidiosis presented with epistaxis. Anterior rhinoscopy revealed a pinkish, proliferative mass with visible spores involving both nasal cavities, inferior and middle turbinates. The nasal septum was obscured. Surgical excision under general anesthesia revealed unexpected extension of the mass into both Eustachian tube openings. Complete excision was performed, followed by cauterization to reduce recurrence risk.\r\n\r\nPostoperative Course:\r\nAt one-week follow-up, the patient reported aural fullness. Impedance audiometry showed a Type C tympanogram, suggesting Eustachian tube dysfunction likely due to postoperative inflammation or fibrosis. At two months, he continued to report aural symptoms. Audiometry revealed a right Type A curve and left Type B curve, indicating persistent dysfunction on the left side.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nThis case highlights an unusual and rare involvement of bilateral Eustachian tubes in rhinosporidiosis, emphasizing the importance of careful intraoperative evaluation in recurrent cases. Postoperative Eustachian tube dysfunction is a potential complication that requires monitoring and management. Long-term follow-up is crucial due to the high recurrence rate of this condition.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 14:46:40', '2025-09-30 14:46:43'),
(144, 'Devanand K', 'devanand.kannabiran92@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000334', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'PEDIATRIC PONS, TARGETED PATHWAY: ENDOSCOPIC APPROACH FOR INFANTILE PONTINE CAVERNOMA', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction: Surgical management of brainstem cavernous malformations is challenging due to their delicate location and complex accessibility. To date, advances in endoscopic techniques have enabled the reporting of ten cases of endoscopic transnasal resection of cavernous malformations in the literature. We introduce a groundbreaking technique for resecting these lesions. \r\nCase Summary: A one-year-nine-month-old infant presented with a 3-day history of difficulty walking, difficulty swallowing, and difficulty holding objects with her right hand. She was diagnosed with acute onset right hemiparesis with involvement of cranial nerves 6, 7, 9, and 10. Three months later, she returned to the emergency room with Cheyne-stokes breathing, drowsiness and was intubated. She underwent extended endoscopic transnasal transclival excision of the pontine cavernoma. Postoperative evaluation revealed significant neurological improvement with minimal morbidity.\r\nConclusion: We selected an anteromedial endoscopic endonasal approach because the lesion had displaced white matter tracts laterally rendering an anteromedial corridor the least traumatic pathway.', NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 21:27:56', '2025-09-30 21:27:59'),
(146, 'Dr EKTA', 'ekta301097@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000357', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Impact of Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery on Sinonasal and Pulmonary Outcomes in Chronic Rhinosi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Impact of Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery on Sinonasal and Pulmonary Outcomes in Chronic Rhinosinusitis With and Without Nasal Polyposis\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ekta\r\nAim\r\nTo evaluate the effect of Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (FESS) on sinonasal symptoms and pulmonary function in patients with chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS), with and without nasal polyposis.\r\nMethodology\r\nA prospective study was conducted on 50 CRS patients at SPMC Medical College, Bikaner. Pre- and postoperative assessments included sinonasal outcome scores, visual analogue scales (VAS), and objective tests (rhinomanometry, acoustic rhinometry, nasal spirometry). Pulmonary function parameters (FEV₁, FVC, FEV₁/FVC) were recorded preoperatively, and at 1 and 3 months postoperatively.\r\nResults\r\nNasal obstruction was reported in 83–100% of patients. Following FESS, mean VAS and Likert scores decreased by over 50%. Objective measures showed significant improvement in nasal airflow and cavity volume. Pulmonary function demonstrated significant increases in FEV₁ and FVC at 1 and 3 months (p < 0.05). Improvements in pulmonary function paralleled symptomatic relief across both CRS subtypes.\r\nConclusions\r\nFESS significantly improves sinonasal and pulmonary outcomes in CRS patients, irrespective of nasal polyposis, reinforcing its role in integrated airway management.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-01 00:06:55', '2025-10-01 00:06:59'),
(147, 'Akshaya V', 'dr.ak.venkat@gmail.com', 'ME0025062', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Autologous platelet-rich plasma gel as a sole adjunct in endoscopic repair of spontaneous CSF rhinor', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction\r\nCerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhea results from an abnormal communication between the subarachnoid space and nasal cavity and predisposes patients to meningitis if untreated. Endoscopic endonasal repair is now the standard of care, with success relying on secure closure and effective adjuncts. Platelet-rich plasma (PRP), when activated with calcium chloride to form a gel, provides concentrated growth factors that accelerate healing and create an immediate watertight seal, making it a promising autologous alternative to fibrin glue.\r\n\r\nObjective:\r\nTo assess the efficacy of autologous PRP gel as an adjunct in endoscopic repair of spontaneous anterior skull base CSF leaks.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA retrospective case series was conducted at a tertiary care center in Pondicherry. Five female patients, aged 43–50 years, presented with spontaneous CSF rhinorrhea without trauma or prior surgery. CT cisternography and MRI localized the leaks, and two patients had empty sella, suggestive of idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH). Endoscopic multilayer closure with fat and fascia lata was performed, and PRP gel was made by activating with calcium chloride and was applied between graft layers and over the repair site. Postoperative care included antibiotics, acetazolamide, and lumbar drainage for IIH patients.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll five patients had successful closure with no recurrence over 6 months of follow-up. No postoperative complications such as meningitis or graft failure occurred. PRP gel provided rapid sealing and mucosal healing while avoiding the cost of commercial sealants.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nAutologous PRP gel is a safe, effective, and economical adjunct in endoscopic CSF leak repair. Larger studies are warranted to validate long-term outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-01 06:36:57', '2025-10-01 06:37:00'),
(148, 'Abarna C', 'abarnachandrasamy@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000255', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Optic Nerve Decompression in a Case of Orbital Apex Syndrome Following Functional Endoscopic Sinus S', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title\r\nOptic Nerve Decompression in a Case of Orbital Apex Syndrome Following Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery\r\nAuthor\r\nAbarna\r\nObjective\r\nTo highlight the rare complication of orbital apex syndrome following functional endoscopic sinus surgery (FESS) for sinonasal polyposis and to discuss the role of timely surgical intervention in preserving vision.\r\nMethodology\r\nA 37-year-old male presented with right-sided nasal obstruction for 5 years. Clinical examination revealed bilateral polypoidal masses. CT paranasal sinuses showed sinonasal polyposis with pansinusitis. The patient underwent FESS with polypectomy. Postoperatively, he developed right medial rectus palsy with second, third and sixth cranial nerve involvement. Endoscopic re-exploration showed clots in the right nasal cavity, which were cleared. MRI brain and orbit revealed features suggestive of right orbital apex syndrome.\r\nResult\r\nThe patient was started on intravenous voriconazole, methylprednisolone and piperacillin–tazobactam. On postoperative day 5, optic nerve decompression was performed. Intraoperatively, fungal-like mucosal debris was seen in the sphenoid sinus, along with cystic material filling the sinus. The peri-orbital area was traced posteriorly up to the orbital apex, and 180° of bone covering the optic nerve was removed. Optic nerve decompression was successfully achieved.\r\nDiscussion\r\nOrbital apex syndrome is a rare but serious complication of sinonasal disease and its surgical management. Early diagnosis with radiological imaging and prompt medical and surgical management are crucial to prevent irreversible visual loss. The use of antifungal therapy, corticosteroids, and timely optic nerve decompression can improve outcomes in select cases.\r\nConclusion\r\nOrbital apex syndrome following FESS is an uncommon but vision-threatening complication. A high index of suspicion, rapid evaluation, and timely surgical decompression of the optic nerve play a key role in patient recovery and visual prognosis.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-02 08:29:11', '2025-10-02 08:29:14'),
(149, 'Dr.Meenu PS', 'psmeenu9122@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000407', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'RETROSPECTIVE STUDY ON ETIOLOGY AND MANAGEMENT OF EPISTAXIS IN A TERTIARY CARE HOSPITAL', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ABSTRACT \r\nTITLE : RETROSPECTIVE  STUDY ON ETIOLOGY AND MANAGEMENT OF EPISTAXIS IN A TERTIARY CARE HOSPITAL \r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:DR. MEENU PS\r\nAIM: To analyze the etiological factors and evaluate the effectiveness of various management strategies for epistaxis in patients presenting to a tertiary care hospital.\r\nMETHODOLOGY: A retrospective observational study was conducted on patients diagnosed with epistaxis who presented to our hospital. Data regarding age, sex, site of bleeding, predisposing factors, clinical presentation, and treatment modalities were collected. Management approaches included conservative measures, anterior and posterior nasal packing, cauterization, medical therapy, and surgical interventions. Analysis of various etiological factors giving rise to epistaxis and effectiveness  of each modality of treatment were assessed. \r\nRESULTS: A total of 384 patients with epistaxis were included in the study. Males constituted the majority, accounting for 76.3 % (293) of cases. Trauma was the most common cause of epistaxis(60%), followed by hypertension(20%). The majority of patients (60%) were managed with anterior nasal packing. Conservative management  was effective in 26.7% of patients, while posterior nasal packing was required in 13.3%  of cases. 3 patients required blood transfusion during the course of treatment.\r\nCONCLUSIONS: Epistaxis is a multifactorial ENT emergency with trauma and hypertension as predominant causes. Most cases respond well to conservative management, while a small subset requires surgical intervention. A structured approach to etiology and stepwise management ensures effective outcomes and reduced recurrence.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-05 12:45:04', '2025-10-05 12:45:07'),
(151, 'Amandeep Singh', 'amandsingh001@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000330', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Effect of Adenoidectomy on Quality of Life in Children with Long Standing Snoring and Apnea using OS', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title of Paper:  Effect of Adenoidectomy on Quality of Life in Children with Long Standing Snoring and Apnea using OSD-6 Questionnaire- A Tertiary Care Centre Study\r\n\r\nPresenting Author: Dr Amandeep Singh\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n \r\nAim:  To evaluate the effectiveness of adenoidectomy alone in treating pediatric snoring and apnea using OSD-6 questionnaire.\r\n\r\nMethods: A prospective observational study was conducted in the Department of Otorhinolaryngology over one year (August 2024–August 2025) on a total of  90 children between the age group of 5–10 years, who underwent adenoidectomy, satisfying the inclusion and exclusion criteria adapted from the the CHAT trial. Parents/guardians of the selected children were requested to fill up the OSD-6 questionnaire preoperatively and postoperatively at third month\r\n \r\nResults: 90 patients were evaluated with a mean age of 6.20± 2.33 years with male preponderance. There was statistically significant improvement in all six parameters of OSD-6 questionnaire (physical distress, sleep and swallowing disorders, emotional stress, limitation of physical activities and caregiver’s concerns) postoperatively at 3rd month (p<0.05)\r\n\r\nConclusion: This study concludes that in carefully selected candidates, adenoidectomy in isolation can be a recommended surgical option to improve the symptoms of pediatric apnea and snoring.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-05 22:12:45', '2025-10-05 22:12:49'),
(153, 'Niharika Gupta', 'niharika.g2609@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000332', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Association of ABO Blood Groups with Susceptibility and Severity of Allergic Rhinitis: A Case–Contro', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title of Poster: Association of ABO Blood Groups with Susceptibility and Severity of Allergic Rhinitis: A Case–Control Study\r\n\r\nPresenting author: Dr. Niharika Gupta\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu \r\n\r\n\r\nAim: To explore the association of ABO and Rh blood groups with AR susceptibility and severity.\r\n\r\nMethods: A prospective study was conducted in the Department of ENT from January 2025 to August 2025 on 133 clinically diagnosed persistent AR patients (per ARIA guidelines, aged 18–55 years) and 133 age- and sex-matched healthy controls. Disease severity was assessed using the Total Nasal Symptom Score (TNSS). ABO and Rh blood groups were determined via standard serological typing.\r\n\r\nResults: The mean age of AR cases was 38.5 ± 11 years, with a female predominance. Based on TNSS, 38.3% had moderate AR, 37.6% mild, and 24.1% severe. Blood group O⁺ was significantly more frequent in AR patients compared to controls (43.6% vs. 28.6%), while AB⁺ was notably less common (3.7% vs. 15.0%) (p = 0.035).\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nBlood group O, particularly O⁺, was significantly associated with both susceptibility and severity of AR, whereas AB appeared protective. ABO typing may serve as an additional risk stratification tool for early identification and preventive strategies in allergic rhinitis.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-05 22:29:54', '2025-10-05 22:29:58'),
(154, 'Pooja Suryawanshi', 'pooja.suryawanshi.ps@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000259', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma of Maxillary Sinus masquerading as Chronic Dacryocystitis: a rare case repo', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title- Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma(ACC)  of Maxillary Sinus masquerading as Chronic Dacryocystitis(CDC): a rare case report\r\nPresenting author- Dr. Pooja Suryawanshi, Dr. Archan Naik, Dr. Vathsalya Vijay\r\nAim- To present a rare case of maxillary sinus ACC masquerading as CDC.\r\nMethodology- 36year female presented with history of watering from left eye since 2021 and left eye protrusion with left sided facial swelling for 3 months since May 2024.\r\nO/E - Left eye proptosis + vision Normal\r\nDNE- Mass in left middle meatus\r\nMRI of PNS which showed irregular heterogeneously enhancing mass causing destruction of it’s walls suggestive of neoplastic etiology \r\nBiopsy/ IHC- suggestive of ACC of left maxillary sinus\r\nPatient underwent left total maxillectomy + R1 excision of tumor extension in left orbit + temporalis flap reconstruction + insertion of palatal prosthesis under GA in oct 2024.\r\nNegative consent for orbital exenteration.\r\n\r\nResult- Histopathological diagnosis ACC with predominant cribriform pattern with perineural invasion, all margins not free.\r\nPatient underwent adjuvant radiotherapy post operatively and tolerated well.\r\nAt 11 month follow up, the patient was alive and well with no evidence of local recurrence and distant metastasis\r\n\r\nConclusion- This case highlights that ACC of the maxillary sinus can present with non-specific slow onset symptoms. The combination of surgical resection and adjuvant radiotherapy is the standard of care and vigilant follow up is essential.\r\nSecondary causes of CDC (paranasal/lacrimal sac tumors) to be kept in mind while treating cases of CDC.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-07 21:54:36', '2025-10-07 21:54:39'),
(160, 'PRIYA', 'priyaclassxii@gmail.com', 'priyaclassxii@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rhinosporidiosis of nasal cavity', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title of poster: Rhinosporidiosis of nasal cavity.\r\nType of article: Case Report\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Priya\r\nAffiliation: Department of ENT &HNS , GMC Jammu.\r\nIntroduction: Rhinosporidiosis is an infectious disease caused by an aquatic protozoan , Rhinosporidium seeberi previously considered to be a fungus . Mode of infection is transepithelial by inoculation of traumatized epithelium ( mucosa  & submucosa ) and  and with sporangiospores  on exposure to infected water (ponds, lakes) and soil.\r\n Rhinosporidiosis is an endemic disease found in tropical regions, prevalent in India (South and Central India) , Sri Lanka, and Argentina. The present report of rhinopsoridiosis constitutes the very few reported cases of rhinosporidiosis in a resident of Jammu and Kashmir , India, who has no history of travel to any of the endemic areas. \r\n Case Details: A 37 year old male presented to  ENT & HNS OPD  with complaints of  right side nasal obstruction which was gradual in onset , slowly progressive and associated with nasal discharge .\r\nLOCAL EXAMINATION  :\r\n Anterior Rhinoscopy - ‘S’ shaped deviated nasal septum. Mucopurulent discharge present in right nasal cavity . No polyp /mass visualised.\r\nOral cavity / oropharynx - WNL\r\nCECT NOSE & PNS: \r\nHeterogenously enhancing soft tissue density mass lesion measuring 22.3mm*16mm*22mm (AP*TR*CC)  is seen centred in nasopharynx more towards right side .This mass is causing obliteration of right side fossa of rossenmuller .\r\n\r\nDigital Nasal Endoscopy - A friable polypoidal mass arising from right side of choana in nasopharynx with white spots on the under surface .\r\nBiopsy was taken from the mass and sent for hpe.\r\nHISTOPATHOLOGY  EXAMINATION : Multiple sections from the submitted biopsy showed respiratory lining epithelium. Sub epithelium shows thick walled sporangia containing spores. Features were consistent with RHINOSPORIDIOSIS.\r\n \r\n Patient was planned for excision of mass using coblation under general anaesthesia  . Histopathological examination of the excised mass revealed findings consistent with rhinosporidiosis.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-08 22:02:07', '2025-10-08 22:02:11'),
(161, 'Ramneet kour', 'Ramneetkour2000@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000250', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Fibro osseous lesion left frontoethmoid recess  and left nasal cavity', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title of poster: Fibro osseous lesion left frontoethmoid recess  and left nasal cavity\r\n \r\nType of article :Case report\r\n \r\nPresenting author:Dr.Ramneet kour\r\n \r\nAffliation: Department of ENT,GMC Jammu\r\n \r\nIntroduction :Fibro-osseous lesion characterized by the replacement of normal bone with fibrous tissue containing varying amounts of mineralized material. It mostly  involve the craniofacial skeleton. In sinonasal region it is   uncommon, with the frontal and ethmoid sinuses being rare sites of involvement. Patients typically present with nasal obstruction, headache, facial swelling, or proptosis.\r\n \r\nDetails :14 year old male patient presented to ENT OPD with complain of protrusion of left eyeball since 3 months which was insidious in onset and gradually progressive .\r\n \r\nOn examination there was increase in interpupillary distance\r\n(84mm).The interpalpebral fissure height was more on left side than the right.No inflammatory changes were seen in adjacent areas  .visual acuity was 6/6 on right side and 6/18 on left side .\r\n \r\nNCCT ORBIT :\r\nill defined  heterogeneous ,predominately,hyperdense lesion measuring approximately 4.5 *2.8*2.6 cm (AP*TR*CC) seen involving left maxillary sinus, left ethmoid air cells ,left frontoethmoid recess and left nasal cavity including left middle turbinate and causing thinning and erosion of adjacent bones .\r\n \r\n• Laterally, the lesion is seen bulging into left orbit causing abutment and displacement of left medial rectus, inferior rectus and superior oblique muscle. Lateral displacement of optic nerve is seen.\r\nMild proptosis of left globe is seen.\r\n \r\n• Medially, it is seen abutting nasal septum and causing effacement and blockage of left osteomeatal complex.\r\n \r\n• Inferomedially, the lesion is seen abutting inferior orbital fissure.\r\n• Anteriorly,  it is seen involving  left nasolacrimal duct with opacification of  left frontal, ethmoid,maxillary and sphenoid sinus is seen.\r\n \r\nLikely suggestive of fibre osseous lesion.\r\n \r\nEndoscopic excision  and left orbital decompression done under GA . Histopathology revealed features of benign fibro osseous lesion suggestive of ossifying fibroma.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-08 22:08:59', '2025-10-08 22:09:03'),
(162, 'Dr.Shaileja S. Chopdekar', 'chopdekarshaileja1996@gmail.com', 'chopdekarshaileja1996@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Indications for open approach septorhinoplasty: case series', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title \r\nIndications for open approach septorhinoplasty: case series\r\n\r\nPresenting Authors\r\nDr. Shaileja S. Chopdekar , Dr.Markandeya Tiwari.\r\n\r\nAim\r\nTo identify and analyze the functional and aesthetic indications for selecting the open approach in septorhinoplasty at a tertiary care center.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nThis was a prospective observational study conducted over 18 months in the Department of ENT , Goa Medical College .\r\nPatients undergoing open approach septorhinoplasty were included regardless of age or gender .\r\nDemographic data ,preoperative diagnosis and surgical indications were recorded.\r\nSurgical indications were categorised into \r\n•	Post traumatic nasal deformity\r\n•	Severe septal deviation or S- shaped deformity\r\n•	Tip deformity\r\n•	Saddle nose\r\n•	Combined functional and aesthetic corrections\r\n•	Binders nose\r\nFunctional outcomes were assessed using the NOSE SCORE, and patient satisfaction was measured with a VISUAL ANALOG SCALE (VAS) .\r\nResults\r\nAmong 20 patients ( 12 males and 8 females, mean age 28.4 ± 6.7 years), the leading indication was post traumatic deformity followed by severe septal deviation, tip deformity, saddle nose correction .\r\n\r\nConclusion \r\nOpen approach septorhinoplasty is predominantly indicated for post traumatic deformities and severe septal deviations. It provides superior anatomical exposure , enabling precise correction and high patient satisfaction , making it the preferred technique for complex functional and aesthetic nasal reconstructions.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-11 23:38:23', '2025-10-11 23:38:27'),
(164, 'Thomas George', 'thomasgk97@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000415', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Expanded Endoscopic Anterior Skull Base Surgeries for Extradural Pathologies', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Presenting Author:\r\nDr Thomas George\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nEndoscopic skull base surgery has shown promise as a minimally invasive alternative to traditional open approaches. This presentation highlights the safety, efficacy, and surgical advantages of the expanded endoscopic approach in extradural lesions.\r\n\r\nMethods:\r\nThis presentation includes 12 challenging cases of extradural anterior skull base lesions managed at our department in a tertiary care hospital. Each patient underwent detailed prospective clinical and radiological evaluation followed by endoscopic resection/repair using expanded endonasal approaches. The focus was on demonstrating surgical feasibility, expanding the margins of possible endoscopic resection, intraoperative safety, and postoperative outcomes.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll patients underwent successful endoscopic resection of their respective lesions with no major intraoperative or postoperative complications. The procedures had minimal blood loss, excellent visualization of anatomical structures, and satisfactory clearance of disease. All patients are currently under regular follow-up and remain asymptomatic, with no evidence of recurrence or postoperative morbidity.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nExpanded endoscopic approaches to the anterior skull base provide a safe and effective alternative for managing extradural pathologies. The enhanced visualization, reduced morbidity, and good cosmetic outcomes (owing to the lack of external incisions) make it a valuable tool in the skull base surgeon’s armamentarium. With growing experience and refinement of techniques, surgeons are pushing the envelope and expanding the surgical corridors of extradural endoscopic endonasal surgery, and these techniques are poised to become the new standard of care for the management of extradural pathologies of the anterior skull base.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-12 09:55:20', '2025-10-12 09:55:23'),
(167, 'KIRUBAKARAN K', 'kkirubakaran93@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000418', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic Management of Lateral Sphenoid Recess CSF Leak: Technical Considerations and Clinical Ins', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title:\r\nEndoscopic Management of Lateral Sphenoid Recess CSF Leak: Technical Considerations and Clinical Insights from a Complex Case\r\nAuthors: Dr Kirubakaran K, Dr Mainak Dutta, Dr Henna M, Dr Vijay Sankar\r\nBackground:\r\nSpontaneous cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhea originating from the lateral recess of the sphenoid sinus is rare and challenging to manage due to the lateral location and complex anatomy. It is frequently associated with elevated intracranial pressure and idiopathic intracranial hypertension. Traditional transsphenoidal approaches offer limited instrumentation access, making the endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid route an important alternative.\r\nObjectives:\r\nTo present a complex case of spontaneous type IV lateral recess CSF leak managed by the endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach, emphasizing technical challenges, surgical strategies, and lessons from a revision procedure.\r\nCase Report\r\nA 40-year-old male with spontaneous CSF rhinorrhea confirmed by beta-2 transferrin assay underwent endoscopic repair via a transpterygoid approach. Imaging showed a 7mm x 5mm bony defect with meningoencephalocele in the postero-superior lateral recess. Multilayer repair was performed with fat, cartilage, fascia, and fibrin glue. Recurrence prompted revision surgery with widened exposure, further drilling for access, and lumbar drain placement.\r\nDiscussion points:\r\nInitial repair was complicated by mucosalization between fascia and bone causing a recurrent CSF tract. Revision surgery facilitated improved access and successful multilayer closure. The patient had no CSF leak on long-term follow-up and was managed medically for elevated intracranial pressure. This case highlights the importance of addressing CSF pressure and achieving optimal surgical exposure before attempting to repair\r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach enables direct access and effective repair of lateral recess CSF leaks. Adequate exposure, multilayer closure, and consideration of CSF dynamics are critical for success. Multidisciplinary management including ICP control is essential to prevent recurrence in this complex anatomical region.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-12 20:19:58', '2025-10-12 20:20:01'),
(170, 'JAIMANTI BAKSHI', 'drjayabakshi@ymail.com', 'drjayabakshi@ymail.com', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Endoscopic Management of Sinonasal Tumors: Experience from a Tertiary Care Hospital', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim\r\nTo evaluate the spectrum, surgical outcomes, and role of adjuvant therapy in sinonasal cancers managed endoscopically at a tertiary care hospital.\r\nMethodology\r\nA retrospective review conducted on 21 patients with sinonasal tumors treated by endoscopic surgery. Demographic details, surgical outcomes, recurrence and use of adjuvant modalities were analyzed. Patients previously managed by open surgery were excluded.\r\nResults\r\nThe cohort comprised 21 patients (mean age 45 years; 11 females, 10 males).\r\nThe histology was as follows-\r\n•	Adenocarcinoma – 7\r\n•	Adenoid cystic carcinoma – 2\r\n•	Glomangiopericytoma/Hemangiopericytoma – 3\r\n•	Solitary fibrous tumor – 1\r\n•	Plasmacytoma – 1\r\n•	Osteosarcoma – 1\r\n•	Others/Inflammatory (Rosai-Dorfman, GPA, inverted papilloma ) – 6\r\n Complete endoscopic excision was feasible in most patients with minimal complications. Adjuvant radiotherapy was administered in high-risk cases with aggressive histologies and positive or close margins. Selected patients also received chemoradiation. Early follow-up indicates favorable disease control, though recurrences were noted in a few adenocarcinoma and hemangiopericytoma cases.\r\nConclusions\r\nEndoscopic surgery is effective primary modality for sinonasal cancers, with reduced morbidity. Integration of adjuvant radiotherapy and multimodal therapy is essential for optimizing oncological outcomes . Careful selection and multidisciplinary management remain key.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-13 09:16:58', '2025-10-13 09:17:01'),
(172, 'Dr Lekhaa Mohanraj', 'lekhaamraj@gmail.com', 'RHIN000073', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Rare Case of Congenital Nasolacrimal Sac Mucocele', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim and Background\r\nMucoceles are benign expansive cystic formations, composed of a mucus-secreting epithelium. Dacryocystocele or congenital mucocele of nasolacrimal duct is a relatively rare variant of NLDO, representing 0.1% of children with congenital obstruction, and results from the coexistence of a distal and a proximal obstruction. Nasolacrimal duct mucocele typically presents as a bulging in the lower medial canthus of the eye and epiphora. \r\nCase Description \r\nThe patient was a 8-year-old boy a history of watering of right eye for 4 months. Computed tomography (CT) showed a cystic expansion in the right lacrimal sac topography and dilatation of the bony canal of the nasolacrimal duct. Nasal endoscopy showed medialization of lateral wall. He had endoscopic dacryocystorhinostomy. The lacrimal sac was opened with drainage of thick purulent secretion. \r\nResults\r\nThe patient remains asymptomatic and without clinical signs 1 year and 8 months after surgery.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nNasolacrimal duct mucocele is a rare occurrence; however, it carries a risk of complications such as local infection and cellulitis. Dacrocystorhinostomy is considered as the definitive treatment  having good outcomes.', NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-13 15:35:48', '2025-10-13 15:35:52'),
(174, 'Nikhil Solomon Sundara Raj', 'nikhilssr@hotmail.com', 'RHIN0000261', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The sensitvity and resistance pattern of pathogens isolated from Skull Base Osteomyelitis (SBO).', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background\r\nSkull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is a severe infection primarily affecting individuals with compromised immune systems, complicated by the rise of pan-resistant organisms. Effective management relies on prolonged, culture-directed, broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy tailored to microbiological results. The increasing prevalence of pan-resistant pathogens necessitates exploring alternative treatment options.\r\nTimely diagnosis, culture-directed therapy, and an interdisciplinary approach are crucial to reducing morbidity and mortality associated with SBO.\r\n\r\nAim\r\nThe study aimed to assess resistance patterns in central and lateral skull base osteomyelitis due to specific pathogens and to explore the importance of antibiotic stewardship in effectively managing these conditions.\r\n\r\nObjectives\r\nWe aim to explore the prevalent pathogens associated with central and lateral skull base osteomyelitis, focusing on their resistance patterns and the antibiotics utilised for effective treatment.\r\n\r\nMaterials and Methods\r\nThis comprehensive study thoughtfully evaluates 139 patients who visited the ENT outpatient department with symptoms indicative of skull base osteomyelitis. The demographic data and the diabetic status were assessed. Clinical and radiological findings made the diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nIn our comprehensive study of 139 patients, 46 % were diagnosed with central skull base osteomyelitis (CSBO) 13% with lateral skull base osteomyelitis (LSBO), 59% demonstrated maixed-type skull base osteomyelitis. The mean age was 59.8 years. There was a male preponderance, 112 patients accounting for 82.4% of the total skull base osteomyelitis patients. Diabetes Mellitus was a common factor for most patients. The mean HbA1C was 9.8.\r\nMonomicrobial infections constitute approximately 57.25% of the cases, and polymicrobial infections constitute 42.75%. The most common isolated organisms are Pseudomonas (52 cases), CONS (Coagulase-Negative Staphylococci, 27 cases), Staphylococcus Aureus (22 cases), and Aspergillus Flavus (21 cases), among others.\r\nRegarding antibiotic therapy, about 22.57% of cases are susceptible to treatment, while 77.43% show resistance to antibiotic therapy based on the susceptibility data.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nSkull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is a severe infection primarily affecting individuals with compromised immune systems, complicated by the rise of pan-resistant organisms. Effective management relies on culture-directed, broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy tailored to microbiological results. The increasing prevalence of pan-resistant pathogens necessitates exploring antibiotic stewardship and alternative treatment options.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-13 21:22:39', '2025-10-13 21:22:42');
