(180, 'SUSHMA SAMPATHKUMAR', 'dr.sushmasampathkumar.2025@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000422', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, '“Endoscopic Management of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Retrospective Cross-Sectional Stud', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE :\r\n“Endoscopic Management of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Retrospective Cross-Sectional Study”\r\n\r\nPresenting Author – Dr Sushma Sampathkumar \r\n\r\n Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical presentation, surgical approach, intraoperative techniques, and outcomes of patients with Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma (JNA) managed by endoscopic excision at a tertiary care centre. \r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nThis retrospective cross-sectional study analysed hospital records of patients diagnosed with JNA from 2015 to 2025. Data were collected on demographic details, presenting complaints, radiological and endoscopic findings, surgical methods ,   arterial involvement and postoperative outcomes. \r\n\r\nResults:\r\nAll patients were males aged 12–21 years (mean age 19.1 years). The most common presenting complaints were nasal obstruction   and recurrent epistaxis. Radiological evaluation commonly demonstrated vascular masses arising from the sphenopalatine region with extension.. All patients underwent endoscopic JNA excision using   cautery or ligaclip  for hemostasis. The vascular supply was universal  by sphenopalatine artery; internal maxillary contributed in 57% of the cases . Complete excision was achieved in 60% of cases, while 40% required piecemeal removal due to bleeding or extension. Only one case (14%) showed recurrence at 1 year follow-up. \r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic management of JNA provides excellent visualization, effective hemostasis, and favourable postoperative outcomes. Early diagnosis and meticulous endoscopic excision significantly reduce morbidity and recurrence rates.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-14 21:38:38', '2025-10-14 21:38:42'),
(181, 'P. Naga Vikasini', 'vikasini1996@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000421', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, 'The Hidden Malignancy Behind a Chronic Nasal Discharge: A Rare Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma', NULL, 'Hard as Stone – Unveiling the Cemento-Ossifying Fibroma of the Nose (A Rare Case Report)', NULL, NULL, 'The Hidden Malignancy Behind a Chronic Nasal Discharge: A Rare Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma\r\nAim:\r\nTo report a rare case of sinonasal adenocarcinoma of the intestinal type (ITAC) managed successfully with endoscopic resection and skull base reconstruction, highlighting its clinical presentation, surgical approach, and outcome.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 51-year-old male with a 20-year history of intermittent left-sided nasal discharge, recently blood-stained, was evaluated. Clinical examination and contrast-enhanced MRI revealed a heterogeneously enhancing lobulated mass over the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone with cribriform plate erosion (T3). Endoscopic biopsy confirmed sinonasal adenocarcinoma of the intestinal type. The patient underwent coblator and microdebrider-assisted endoscopic excision of the tumor with bilayered anterior skull base reconstruction using fascia lata, Surgicel, and fibrin glue to prevent CSF leak.\r\nResults:\r\nThe postoperative course was uneventful with good symptomatic improvement. Histopathology confirmed intestinal-type sinonasal adenocarcinoma with chronic inflammation. The patient was advised nasal care and regular follow-up to monitor recurrence. No postoperative complications or CSF leak were observed.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSinonasal adenocarcinoma, though uncommon, should be considered in patients with chronic unilateral nasal symptoms. Early diagnosis and complete endoscopic excision with meticulous skull base reconstruction can provide favorable functional and oncological outcomes.', NULL, 'Hard as Stone – Unveiling the Cemento-Ossifying Fibroma of the Nose (A Rare Case Report)\r\nAim:\r\nTo report a rare case of cemento-ossifying fibroma arising from the nasal septum and to emphasize the importance of early diagnosis and management.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 61-year-old female presented with progressive bilateral nasal obstruction for one year. Nasal endoscopy revealed a hard, pinkish mass arising from the septum. CT scan showed a high-attenuation lesion involving the nasal septum with extension to the ethmoid sinuses. The patient underwent transnasal endoscopic excision, and the specimen was subjected to histopathological evaluation.\r\nResults:\r\nIntraoperatively, a firm, well-defined mass was excised completely. Histopathology demonstrated lamellar bone with cementum-like calcifications and acellular lobulated areas, confirming cemento-ossifying fibroma. Postoperative recovery was uneventful with no recurrence noted on follow-up.\r\nConclusions:\r\nCemento-ossifying fibroma, though benign, can present aggressively when involving the sinonasal tract. Accurate diagnosis and complete surgical excision are crucial to prevent recurrence and ensure favorable outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-14 21:54:59', '2025-10-14 21:55:03'),
(182, 'Varun Gupta', 'varungupta815@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000423', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'ORBITAL COMPLICATIONS OF SINUSITIS – A REVIEW OF 10 YEARS IN TERTIARY CARE CENTRE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ORBITAL COMPLICATIONS OF SINUSITIS – A REVIEW OF 10 YEARS IN TERTIARY CARE CENTRE\r\n\r\nIntroduction - Orbital complications of sinusitis are serious vision threatening infections that spread from the sinuses into the eye socket that can lead to orbital cellulitis, subperiosteal abscess and orbital abscess. \r\n\r\nAim – To analyze patients who were treated for these complications in the last decade.\r\n\r\nMethodology – Retrospective analysis of 27 patients treated with orbital complications of  sinusitis, between the years 2015 to 2025. The diagnosis was determined based on clinical examination, DNE, CT scans and MRI scans. In all cases, intensive treatment was initiated with FESS with or without Orbital abscess drainage / orbital decompression / optic nerve decompression with IV antibiotics\r\n\r\nResults – In our study, we had 27 cases of orbital complications with an average patients age of 35 years (28days – 70 years). The most common complications were palpebral inflammatory oedema, orbital cellulitis, orbital abscess, optic nerve compression. The average time patient stayed in hospital was 5-7 days.  \r\n\r\nConclusion – Orbital complications of acute rhinosinusitis are common in pediatric age group and in adult its rare. Surgical intervention and aggressive medical management remain the standard to achieve a good prognosis and visual outcome. \r\n\r\nDr. Varun Gupta\r\nRHIN0000423', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-14 22:05:09', '2025-10-14 22:05:13'),
(183, 'KARTHIKA G', 'karthig1994@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000424', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Endoscopic Repair of CSF Rhinorrhoea – A Review of Its Efficacy and Success Rate', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the efficacy and outcomes of endoscopic repair in patients with cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhoea of various aetiologies.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA retrospective review was conducted on 22 patients who underwent endoscopic repair for CSF rhinorrhoea. The study analysed demographic distribution, aetiology, site, and size of the leak. Conservative management was attempted in selected cases prior to surgical intervention. All patients underwent defect closure using multi-layered grafting techniques, with postoperative management focused on reducing intracranial pressure and preventing recurrence.\r\nResults:\r\nAmong 22 patients studied, traumatic and iatrogenic aetiologies accounted for most cases, while idiopathic leaks were less common. The ethmoid and sphenoid regions were frequent sites of leakage. Endoscopic multilayer repair achieved a primary success rate of 90%, with no major postoperative complications or recurrence. The middle turbinate was preserved intact in all cases, maintaining normal nasal anatomy and function. Use of cartilage, fat, fascia, tissue glue, vascularized flaps, including the Hadad flap, provided robust closure in larger defects.\r\nConclusion:\r\nEndoscopic repair is a safe, minimally invasive with intact middle turbinate, and highly effective technique for managing CSF rhinorrhoea. It offers superior visualization, reduced morbidity, and high success rates, making it the preferred method for most skull base leaks.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 00:21:10', '2025-10-15 00:21:14'),
(187, 'Dr Monica J', 'mons.jawa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000254', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Ocular manifestations as key to sinus diagnosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'OCULAR MANIFESTATIONS AS KEY TO SINUS DIAGNOSIS\r\n \r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:\r\nDR. MONICA. J\r\nPOST GRADUATE\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nGUIDE:\r\nPROF. DR. M.K. RAJASEKAR  \r\nPROFESSOR AND HEAD OF DEPARTMENT OF ENT\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n \r\nAIM:\r\nTo highlight the importance of early recognition and prompt management of sinusitis in uncontrolled diabetic patients, emphasizing the risk of silent orbital complications and potential progression to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\n \r\nMETHODOLOGY:\r\nStudy Design: Descriptive case-based presentation of two diabetic patients with sinusitis and orbital complications.\r\nPatient Selection: Uncontrolled diabetic patients presenting with orbital signs and minimal or no nasal symptoms.\r\nClinical Evaluation: Detailed history taking and ophthalmological/ENT examination.\r\nInvestigations: Imaging with CT and MRI of paranasal sinuses and orbit to identify extent of disease.\r\nManagement Approach: Referral from ophthalmology to ENT, medical optimization of diabetes, and appropriate antifungal/antibacterial therapy with surgical intervention where indicated.\r\nOutcome Assessment: Observation of clinical response and complications during hospital stay and follow-up.\r\nRESULTS:  \r\nEarly ENT intervention and glycemic control led to stabilization of orbital findings and prevention of acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nUncontrolled diabetic patients with sinusitis, when not treated promptly, often develop orbital complications despite having no nasal symptoms. Diagnosis is usually established only after CT or MRI imaging. Both patients were referred to the ENT department from ophthalmology based on CT and MRI findings.\r\nThe underlying cause is typically sinusitis affecting the posterior group of sinuses. It is not always invasive fungal sinusitis; non-invasive fungal or bacterial sinusitis can also be responsible. In diabetic patients, even a minor orbital syndrome can rapidly progress to acute fulminant fungal sinusitis.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 06:22:06', '2025-10-15 06:22:09'),
(190, 'AJJAI A', 'ajjaiamudhan@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000245', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Missed the Bus: An Unexpected Turnaround in a Case of Hidden Nasopharyngeal Malignancy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim To highlight a rare presentation of nasopharyngeal carcinoma (NPC) as isolated otologic symptoms, emphasizing the necessity of complete nasopharyngeal evaluation in adults with persistent unilateral ear complaints.\r\n\r\nMethodology A 50-year-old male presented with six months of right ear pain and fullness. Previous evaluations at multiple centers revealed only a minimal bulge in the tympanic membrane, and mastoidectomy was planned. At our institute, CT imaging identified a soft-tissue mass in the right fossa of Rosenmüller. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy confirmed a bulge in the nasopharynx. The patient underwent coblation-assisted biopsy under general anesthesia, along with grommet insertion for middle ear ventilation.\r\n\r\nResults Histopathology revealed non-keratinizing nasopharyngeal carcinoma. The patient received postoperative chemoradiotherapy. At follow-up, otologic symptoms resolved, and the patient remains clinically well.\r\n\r\nConclusion Persistent unilateral otalgia or middle ear effusion in adults, even without nasal symptoms, should prompt thorough nasopharyngeal evaluation. Early detection of occult NPC prevents misdiagnosis, avoids unnecessary surgery, and ensures timely oncological management. This case reinforces the principle: in ENT, the ear may be the first sign of a hidden nasopharyngeal malignancy.\r\n\r\nKeywords: Nasopharyngeal carcinoma, Otalgia, Fossa of Rosenmüller, Middle ear effusion, Diagnostic nasal endoscopy', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 10:42:21', '2025-10-15 10:42:24'),
(194, 'DR ARYA V', 'aryaachutham@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000417', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, 'BEYOND THE USUAL EPISTAXIS: SEPTAL LOBULAR CAPILLARY HEMANGIOMA IN A CHILD', NULL, 'TITLE : “POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE', NULL, NULL, 'TITLE :BEYOND THE USUAL EPISTAXIS: SEPTAL LOBULAR CAPILLARY HEMANGIOMA IN A CHILD\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR : DR ARYA V\r\nABSTRACT\r\nAIM: Lobular capillary hemangioma (LCH) is a benign proliferative vascular tumor originating from the skin and mucosal membranes with the tendency to bleed. In head and neck region LCH is commonly located in oral cavity but rarely found in the nasal cavity. The study is aimed to know in detail the rare case presentation \r\nMETHODOLOGY :We present a case of 7 year old girl with LCH of the nasal cavity presenting with nasal obstruction and epistaxis. Examination through anterior rhinoscopy revealed polypoidal mass occupying the left side of nasal cavity on the septum which was red in colour. The patient successfully underwent surgical excision without pre-operative embolization \r\nRESULT : Child underwent endonasal endoscopic excision of polypoidal mass under short general anesthesia. The entire mass was resected and the apparent pedicle was cauterised with bipolar diathermy (figure 3a and 3b). Mass was later sent for histopathological examination. Anterior nasal packing was done for 24 hours and later removed and discharged the child.Histological examination revealed findings typical of LCH\r\nCONCLUSION: Lobular capillary hemangioma (LCH) of the nasal cavity is a rare, benign vascular lesion that should be considered in the differential diagnosis of intranasal masses, especially in children. In literature, only nine cases of hemangioma of nasal cavities have been reported in children since 1985.', NULL, 'Dr.Arya V,aryaachutham@gmail.com,Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session,Registration Number : RHIN0000417\r\nTITLE : “POLYP-A DIAGNOSTIC DILEMMA” -ONCOCYTIC PAPPILOMA OF THE NOSE\r\nBACKGROUND: Oncocytic papilloma is a rare, benign tumor originating from the Schneiderian membrane (lining) of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses.This is rarest form of sinonasal papilloma with an incidence of 0.5 to 1.5 cases per 100,000 people per year.\r\nCASE REPORT:A 63 year old male with no relevant past medical history presented to otorhinolaryngology clinic with 5 years history of  bilateral nasal obstruction and snoring and 2 months history of recurrent episodes of nasal bleeds. Anterior rhinoscopy showed multiple pale polypoidal glistening masses with probe passed all around, non tender, not bleed on touch in right nasal cavity and posterior rhinoscopy showed -Pale glistening polypoidal mass noted covering both choana posteriorly extending upto the oropharynx.NCCT PNS was showing diffuse extensive mucosal thickening and near total soft tissue opacification of the right maxillary sinus and the ethmoid complexes on both sides ,that appears merging with the nasal turbinates with near total obliteration of the nasal cavity ,widening the right maxillary ostium ,the soft tissue density is also seen extending to the left choana ,obliteration of right osteomeatal complex -features suggestive of sino-nasal polyposis.Under General anesthesia FESS + Septoplasty was done and specimen was send for Histopathological evaluation.HPE shown features suggestive of sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type (ICD 10 CODE D14.0)\r\nCONCLUSION: Sinonasal pappiloma -oncocytic type extremely rare condition. Accurate diagnosis and appropriate surgical management are crucial for favorable outcome in such cases. Complete surgical excision through endoscopic surgery or open radical procedure is the treatment of choice; lateral rhinotomy and medial maxillectomy may be required.  Histopathological investigations play a pivotal role to arrive at the final diagnosis and exclude malignancy.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 11:39:07', '2025-10-15 11:39:10'),
(199, 'Akshay Singh', 'akshaysinghheer@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000120', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title: Sinonasal Myxoma: A rare entity in a common space\r\n\r\nPresenting author : Dr. Akshay Singh\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe a rare case of sinonasal myxoma in an adult male, outlining the clinical features, radiological findings, histopathological confirmation, and management, while emphasizing the importance of early recognition and complete excision in such uncommon lesions.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 46-year-old male farmer presented with complaints of nasal obstruction and reduced sense of smell for seven months, which began on the right side and gradually involved the left. He also reported foul-smelling, nasal discharge, loss of taste, and bilateral aural fullness. On examination, there was a left-sided deviated nasal septum and a right-sided nasal mass. CECT of the paranasal sinuses showed a heterogeneously enhancing soft tissue lesion measuring 60 × 27 × 45 mm in the right nasal cavity, extending into the nasopharynx. The mass caused erosion of the nasal septum and medial wall of the right maxillary sinus with mild invasion, while the cribriform plate remained intact and no intracranial extension was seen. The lesion was completely excised endoscopically. Histopathological examination revealed abundant myxoid stroma containing scattered spindle-shaped cells without atypia, confirming the diagnosis of sinonasal myxoma. The postoperative course was uneventful, and no recurrence was noted on follow-up. \r\nResults:\r\nA 46-year-old male presented with progressive nasal obstruction and hyposmia. Imaging revealed a right nasal cavity mass with septal and turbinate erosion. Endoscopic excision confirmed sinonasal myxoma; management and recovery was uneventful.\r\nConclusion:\r\nSinonasal myxoma is an extremely rare benign tumor that can mimic other nasal masses. Despite its benign nature, it may be locally invasive. Accurate diagnosis and complete surgical removal are essential for preventing recurrence and ensuring good long-term outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 12:19:15', '2025-10-15 12:19:18'),
(200, 'Dr RIMJHIM SHARMA', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Trends in Allergen Sensitization Among Patients with Allergic Rhinitis in Our Region', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim: To identify the predominant allergens responsible for sensitization in patients with allergic rhinitis in our region.\r\n\r\nMethodology: A prospective 12-month study was conducted among patients with clinical features of allergic rhinitis at Shri Mata Vaishno Devi institute of medical excellence, kakryal. Proper informed consent was taken from all the participants. Participants received counselling on allergic rhinitis and the skin prick test (SPT) procedure. Standardized allergen extracts were applied at 2 cm intervals using a 1 mm lancet. A positive response was defined as a wheal at least 3 mm larger than the saline control.\r\n\r\nResults: A total of 215 patients underwent skin prick testing, comprising 64.65%(n=139) males and 35.35%(n=76) females. Patients mostly belonged to age group between 20 and 40 years of age. Sensitization was most frequently observed to dust mites (78.6%, n=169), followed by pollens (49.77%, n=107), insects (46.05%, n=99), moulds (40%, n=86), food allergens (6.51%, n=14), and animal dander (2.32%, n=5).\r\n\r\nConclusion: The distribution of allergen sensitization varies across regions. In our study, dust mite sensitization was predominant, likely due to local climatic conditions that promote the use of carpets and room heaters, creating an environment conducive to dust mite proliferation.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 13:00:24', '2025-10-15 13:00:28'),
(204, 'DR.AYUSHI', 'ayushiashu655@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000128', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Effectiveness of oral saline gargling in postnasal drip syndrome (upper airway cough syndrome).', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title of paper: Effectiveness of Oral Saline Gargling in Postnasal Drip Syndrome ( upper airway cough syndrome).\r\n\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ayushi\r\n\r\nAffiliation: Department of ENT, GMC, Jammu\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the correlation between endoscopic findings and symptom severity in patients with postnasal drip syndrome (PNDS) without cough, and to assess the effectiveness of oral saline gargling as a therapeutic option.\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION: \r\nPostnasal drip syndrome (PNDS) is among the most common yet often misunderstood rhinological complaints. It presents as a persistent sensation of mucus trickling into the throat, sometimes causing irritation or globus feeling without any cough or evident sinonasal disease. Although traditionally linked to rhinosinus disorders and upper airway cough syndrome, PNDS can occur independently when symptom severity does not correlate with endoscopic findings. Abnormal mucus viscosity, altered mucociliary clearance, and sensory hypersensitivity may contribute to this condition. This study aimed to evaluate the association between endoscopic findings and symptom scores and to assess the role of oral saline gargling as a simple therapeutic option.\r\n\r\nMethods:\r\nA retrospective observational study was conducted on patients presenting with isolated postnasal discharge and no associated cough or sinonasal disease. All participants performed isotonic saline oral gargling for twelve weeks. The Sino-Nasal Outcome Test-22 (SNOT-22) and Postnasal Drip Symptom Score (PNDSS) were recorded pre- and post-treatment to assess improvement. Endoscopic examination was also done. \r\nResults:\r\nBoth SNOT-22 and PNDSS scores showed significant reduction following twelve weeks of therapy (p < 0.001). Endoscopic findings demonstrated mild improvement, though no consistent correlation was observed between mucosal appearance and symptom severity.\r\nConclusion:\r\nOral saline gargling is a safe, inexpensive, and effective measure for symptomatic relief in PNDS. The study supports redefining PNDS as a distinct clinical entity characterized by postnasal discharge without cough or active sinonasal pathology.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 14:10:37', '2025-10-15 14:10:40'),
(206, 'PRASHANTH.N', 'prasi39@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000426', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Orbital complications ignited by propagating Sinusitis – a clinical case series.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nChandler et al was instrumental in describing the pathogenesis of complications occurring secondary to acute sinusitis. In the elaborate account, he divided the complications into five following groups – Inflammatory edema, orbital cellulitis, sub periosteal abscess, orbital abscess, and cavernous sinus thrombosis. We present to you a series of  6 patients ( 5 pediatric and 1 adult ) presenting with different orbital complications following sinusitis in our tertiary care medical college and hospital.\r\nMethodology, Procedure and Results :\r\nWe have had 6 patients of which 5 patients were Pediatric age group and 1 elderly male with Type 2 Diabetes. Of which 4 patients of pediatric age group had stage 3-4 chandlers ( orbital and pre septal abscess), 1 child had only orbital cellulitis (pre septal –stage 2), and 1 adult patient presented with bilateral vision loss and stage 5 (cavernous sinus thrombosis). . \r\nIn our series, conservative management with IV antibiotic and supportive management was initiated but a final call for surgery was taken after no improvement was observed. On the other hand, in cases where vision is threatened, frank abscess is apparent clinically or radiologically, a wait and watch policy is strongly discouraged.\r\nAll the patients have undergone Endoscopic sinus surgery, Chandlers stage 3,4 patients required additional external Incision and drainage. Cavernous thrombosis patient required anticoagulants, high end antibiotics after surgery. All the patients successfully discharged within 4-5 days except cavernous thrombosis patient where he had to stay for 10 days for his recovery.\r\nConclusion:\r\nOrbital complications resulting secondary to sinus pathology have serious implications and therefore, require prompt intervention. The decision for conservative or surgical management should be based on the symptomatology at the time of presentation and stage of complication assessed after complete clinic-radiological investigations. Early diagnosis and swift treatment is needed in these cases to prevent complete loss of vision and even death of a patient.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 15:27:26', '2025-10-15 15:27:29'),
(207, 'Dr Hamsini Sudhakar', 'hams2000.ms@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000244', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Title: Coblation-Assisted Excision of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Case Report', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'PRESENTOR ; \r\nDr Hamsini Sudhakar \r\nJunior Resident , Sree balaji medical college and hospital \r\nPhone no : 9677011701 \r\nEmail :hams2000.ms@gmail.com \r\n\r\nGuide :\r\nDr MK Rajasekar \r\nProfessor and head of department \r\nSree balaji medical college and hospital \r\n\r\nTitle: Coblation-Assisted Excision of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: A Case Report\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe the surgical management of a case of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA) using coblation-assisted excision and highlight its effectiveness in reducing intraoperative bleeding and improving surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA male adolescent patient presented with recurrent nasal obstruction and epistaxis. Clinical examination, nasal endoscopy, and imaging confirmed the diagnosis of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. The patient underwent coblation-assisted excision of the tumor under general anesthesia. Intraoperative technique involved careful dissection of the tumor with coblation technology to minimize blood loss and preserve surrounding structures.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe coblation-assisted approach allowed precise removal of the tumor with significantly reduced intraoperative bleeding compared to conventional techniques. The postoperative course was uneventful, with no major complications or residual disease noted on follow-up endoscopic evaluation. The patient experienced rapid recovery, minimal postoperative pain, and no recurrence during the follow-up period.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted excision of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma is a safe and effective technique. It provides excellent hemostasis, enhances surgical precision, and reduces morbidity. This method can be considered a valuable alternative to conventional surgical approaches in the management of JNA.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 15:41:36', '2025-10-15 15:41:40'),
(208, 'Vishwanath Sivasubramanian', 'Vishwanathsiva@yahoo.com', 'RHIN0000253', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Hypoohysectomy in Pituitary macroadenomas', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'PRESENTOR: \r\nDr Vishwanath Sivasubramanian \r\nJUNIOR RESIDENT, SREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\nPHONE-9677258642, \r\nEMAIL- Vishwanathsiva@yahoo.com\r\nGUIDE: \r\nProf Dr. M.K.Rajasekar\r\nProfessor and Head of Department\r\nSREE BALAJI MEDICAL COLLEGE AND HOSPITAL\r\n\r\n\r\nBackground: Pituitary macroadenomas are benign adenohypophyseal tumors larger than 10 mm, often presenting with visual disturbances, endocrine dysfunction, or features of raised intracranial pressure. Surgical management, primarily via hypophysectomy, remains the cornerstone of treatment for symptomatic lesions.\r\n\r\nObjective: To evaluate the clinical presentation, surgical management, and postoperative outcomes of a patient with pituitary macroadenoma treated with hypophysectomy.\r\n\r\nMethods: A patient diagnosed with pituitary macroadenoma based on clinical, radiological, and endocrine evaluation underwent hypophysectomy. Detailed assessment of presenting symptoms, imaging characteristics, operative findings, and perioperative management was carried out. Postoperative follow-up included clinical evaluation, visual field assessment, hormonal profile, and neuroimaging.\r\n\r\nResults: The patient presented with progressive headache, visual field defects, and features suggestive of hypopituitarism. MRI revealed a sellar-suprasellar mass consistent with pituitary macroadenoma. Hypophysectomy was performed via a trans-sphenoidal approach, achieving near-total excision. Postoperatively, there was significant improvement in visual symptoms, with normalization of intracranial pressure-related features. Hormonal replacement therapy was initiated as required.\r\n\r\nConclusion: Hypophysectomy remains an effective and safe procedure for pituitary macroadenomas, offering significant relief of compressive symptoms and improved quality of life. Early diagnosis, meticulous surgical technique, and vigilant postoperative endocrine monitoring are crucial for optimal outcomes.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 15:42:05', '2025-10-15 15:42:09'),
(211, 'GAYATHRI BHASKARAN', 'gayathri.tilapu@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000206', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Carotid Quell…..A Case Report', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background:Skull base osteomyelitis (SBO) is an uncommon yet potentially fatal infection, commonly affecting immunocompromised individuals, particularly those with diabetes mellitus. Mucormycosis, an equally dangerous infection, affects a similar patient population. Despite advances in antimicrobial therapy and surgical techniques, management of both conditions remain complex, and life-threatening complications can ensue. Among these, hemorrhagic events secondary to vascular involvement are exceedingly rare. We  present a case of a diabetic patient who developed a catastrophic hemorrhage, likely due to a ruptured pseudoaneurysm, following surgical debridement for Rhino-orbital mucormycosis and Left SBO.\r\nCase Presentation:A 55-year-old male with Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus presented with clinical and radiological features consistent with Rhino-orbital mucormycosis . He underwent surgical exploration with Denkers’s approach with globe sparing left orbital debridement. He was on long-term antifungal treatment. After disease stabilisation, he was discharged and was on regular followup with disease control. After 6 months, he presented with intractable headache and left ear pain and was diagnosed with left skull base osteomyelitis. He underwent comprehensive medical management with prolonged intravenous antibiotics and multidisciplinary care and surgical intervention including a left subtotal petrosectomy. Postoperatively patient recovery was good. On POD 17, he experienced two minor episodes of nasal bleeding before developing a sudden, massive nasal and oral hemorrhage associated with a precipitous drop in oxygen saturation to 86%, profuse diaphoresis, and altered consciousness, necessitating emergency intensive care support. The clinical course and background strongly suggested rupture of a pseudoaneurysm—an uncommon but devastating vascular complication of SBO.\r\nConclusion:This case highlights the critical need for vigilance regarding vascular complications, particularly pseudoaneurysm formation, in patients with Rhinoorbital mucormycosis and skull base osteomyelitis, especially those with diabetes mellitus. The dual insult of angioinvasive infection, potentially of fungal etiology and surgical manipulation may predispose to vessel wall compromise and subsequent hemorrhage. Early recognition of sentinel bleeding as a possible harbinger of vascular injury, coupled with prompt vascular imaging and intervention, is paramount to preventing fatal outcomes in such high-risk patients.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 16:00:15', '2025-10-15 16:00:19'),
(214, 'Tanisha Goel', 'tanisha287@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000427', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Comparative Study of the Role of Oral Steroids with Itraconazole and Antibiotics in Allergic Fungal ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Comparative Study of the Role of Oral Steroids with Itraconazole and Antibiotics in Allergic Fungal Rhinosinusitis\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Tanisha Goel\r\nAim: To compare the efficacy of oral itraconazole plus steroids versus oral antibiotics plus steroids in AFRS, using objective and subjective outcome measures.\r\nMethodology: A prospective randomized clinical trial was conducted on 100 AFRS patients diagnosed via NCCT of the nose and paranasal sinuses. Participants were divided into two groups: Group A received oral prednisolone (tapering dose) with antibiotics, and Group B received oral prednisolone with itraconazole for two weeks. Pre- and post-treatment assessments included Lund-Mackay CT scores, Kupferberg and modified Lund-Kennedy endoscopic scores, serum total IgE, SNOT-22, and VAS scores.\r\nResults: Both groups showed significant improvement in all parameters post-treatment. The mean SNOT-22 scores decreased from 41.96 to 23.08 in Group A and from 48.62 to 26.86 in Group B. VAS scores improved by 3.36 and 3.74 points, respectively. Endoscopic and CT scores also demonstrated comparable reductions. However, no statistically significant differences were observed.\r\nConclusion: Both treatment regimens—oral steroids with itraconazole and oral steroids with antibiotics—are equally effective for preoperative disease control in AFRS. Further studies are needed to validate these findings and explore long-term outcomes.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 19:42:40', '2025-10-15 19:42:44'),
(215, 'KUNE SAPHI PYRBOT', 'drkunesaphi@gmail.com', 'RHIN000083', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Clinicopathological Spectrum and Long-Term Outcomes of Sinonasal Masses at a Tertiary Care Centre in', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background: Sinonasal masses include benign and malignant lesions of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, presenting commonly with nasal obstruction, epistaxis and facial swelling. Early diagnosis and management are crucial to reduce complications and recurrence.\r\nObjective: To evaluate the clinical features, pathology, treatment, and outcomes of sinonasal masses over five years.\r\nMethods: A retrospective study from 2019 to 2024 included 33 patients (15 males, 18 females; age 10–86 years, mean 48 years). Patients with nasal polyposis, allergic fungal rhinosinusitis and granulomatous diseases were excluded. Data on presentation, histology, treatment and follow-up were analysed.\r\nResults: Of 33 cases, 27 (82%) were benign and 6 (18%) malignant. Benign lesions included rhinosporidiosis (11), inverted papilloma (7), juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (6), fibromatosis(1), dermoid cyst(1), and schwannoma (1). Malignant tumors included squamous cell carcinoma (2), esthesioneuroblastoma (2), lymphoma(1), and hyalinising clear cell carcinoma (1).\r\nAll benign cases had complete surgical excision; malignant cases received surgery followed by radiotherapy. Recurrence occurred in 12 patients (36%), with 2 malignant (33%) and 10 benign (37%). Mean follow-up was 48 months.\r\nConclusion: Sinonasal masses show varied pathology and age distribution. Surgery is key for benign tumours; while malignant tumours require multimodal management. The notable recurrence rate, particularly in benign lesions, emphasizes the importance of long-term follow-up.\r\nKeywords: Sinonasal mass, Rhinosporidiosis, Inverted papilloma, Esthesioneuroblastoma, Demographics, Tamil Nadu, Surgical outcomes, Recurrence.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 20:25:19', '2025-10-15 20:25:23'),
(217, 'Rachit Pahwa', 'drrachitpahwa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000126', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Association Between Biomarkers, Cough, and Asthma in Chronic Rhinosinusitis Patients', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title:Association Between Biomarkers, Cough, and Asthma in Chronic Rhinosinusitis Patients\r\nPresenting Author:Dr.RachitPahwa, Department of ENT, SMGS Hospital, Government Medical College, Jammu\r\nAim:To assess the relationship between inflammatory biomarkers and lower airway involvement among patients diagnosed with chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS), in the context of the unified airway hypothesis.\r\nMethodology:A prospective observational study was conducted in the ENT department of SMGS Hospital over 18 months. 121 adult patients with CRS underwent spirometry (FEV₁, FEV₁/FVC), fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO), absolute eosinophil count (AEC), serum IgE evaluation, and SNOT-22 scoring. Patients meeting ≥2 of the following thresholds—AEC ≥0.3×10³/µL, IgE ≥150 kU/L, FeNO>25 ppb, or FEV₁ <2.0 L—were analyzed for airway inflammation patterns. Statistical analysis included correlation and multivariate regression.\r\nResults:FeNO was positively associated with SNOT-22 scores (ρ=0.23). FEV₁ showed significant associations with AEC (p=0.048) and SNOT-22 (p=0.009). FeNO levels were significantly predicted by AEC (p=0.038), IgE (p=0.041), SNOT-22 (p=0.027), and age (p=0.015).\r\nConclusions:CRS patients frequently exhibited biomarker patterns suggestive of subclinical lower airway involvement. Inflammatory markers such as AEC, FeNO, and IgE may offer useful insights into unified airway pathology.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 20:48:16', '2025-10-15 20:48:20'),
(218, 'Rajendran Dinesh Kumar', 'dinuraj1186@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000419', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Assessment of the Distance between the Uncinate Process and Nasolacrimal Duct to Enhance Safety duri', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background:\r\n\r\nUncinectomy is a critical first step in Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (FESS), where injury to the nasolacrimal duct (NLD) can lead to postoperative epiphora. Limited literature defines a safe anatomical distance between the uncinate process and NLD. This study aimed to quantify this distance in patients with normal sinonasal anatomy, using radiological and intraoperative data, to enhance surgical safety.\r\n\r\nMaterials & Methods:\r\nA prospective observational study was conducted on 102 patients (≥18 years) undergoing FESS for chronic rhinosinusitis. High-resolution preoperative CT scans measured the shortest uncinate–NLD distance bilaterally. Intraoperative findings and postoperative complications were recorded. Data were analyzed for side-to-side variation, gender differences, and safety classification based on instrument sizes.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nMean distance was 8.14 ± 1.50 mm (right) and 7.93 ± 1.70 mm (left), with no significant side-to-side difference (p=0.189). Males had a slightly greater right-side distance (p=0.039). Distances ranged from 4.6–14.4 mm. Safety analysis showed a 4 mm instrument head or bite was safe in almost all patients, while 6 mm jaws increased risk, particularly in minimal-distance cases. No postoperative epiphora occurred over 3 months.\r\n\r\nConclusions:\r\nAverage uncinate–NLD distance is ~8 mm, generally symmetrical. Preoperative CT is essential to identify high-risk patients. A jaw size ≤4 mm is safest; larger jaws require greater caution. Findings apply to normal anatomy—craniofacial anomalies or pediatric cases may differ significantly.\r\n\r\nKeywords: FESS, Uncinate Process, Nasolacrimal Duct, Safety.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 20:51:05', '2025-10-15 20:51:10'),
(238, 'SHARMILA S', 'drssharmilambbs@gmail.com', 'RHINO000350', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Left Sinonasal inverted papilloma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim\r\nTo highlight the clinical presentation, diagnostic approach and management of single case of Left Sino nasal inverted papilloma with importance of early diagnosis and effective surgical intervention.\r\nMethodology \r\nA  52 year old male, farmer by occupation presented with C/O left side Nasal obstruction and left side nasal discharge ×1 week. C/O 1 episode of nose bleed.\r\nClinical examination reveals DNS to right. Left nasal cavity – proliferative pinkish friable mass extending from inferior turbinate to middle turbinate. CT PNS shows large polypoidal mucosal thickening noted in left maxillary sinus with complete opacification of the left maxillary sinus extending into the left sided nasal cavity involving middle and inferior turbinate. DNE and biopsy done.  Histopathological examination shows sinonasal papilloma (oncocytic type). Patient underwent endoscopic debridement with left medial maxillectomy.\r\nResults: \r\nPost operatively patient improved symptomatically and good surgical outcome\r\nConclusion :\r\n      This case emphasizes the role of early diagnosis and effective surgical approach to remove the tumor origin completely, to achieve low recurrence rate, minimizing morbidity, preserving anatomy and maintaining normal nasal function. It also provides excellent access for followup.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 21:48:37', '2025-10-15 21:48:45'),
(244, 'Nicole Stephen', 'nicolestephen99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000260', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Use of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypert', NULL, 'Use of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypert', NULL, NULL, 'Title\r\nUse of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypertension\r\n\r\nPresenting Author\r\nDr Nicole Stephen\r\n\r\nAim\r\nTo assess the specific changes in Optical coherence tomography in patients with spontaneous CSF leak\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nThis retrospective study includes 20 patients including male and female between the age 18-65years. A thorough history, including history of headache, tinnitus, rhinorrhea, nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances. OCT was taken at the time of diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nAmong the 20 patients included in the study, 18 were females. The most common clinical presentation is watery nasal discharge, followed by headache, seen in 10 patients. Two patients had history of recurrent meningitis. The average retinal nerve fibre layer thickness in right eye is 106.2m and left eye is 105.9m with symmetry of 85%.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nIdiopathic intracranial hypertension is predominantly seen in females with a history of long-standing headache and visual disturbances in the form of scotoma, diplopia and reduced visual acuity. They can present as CSF leak in patients with a long-standing history, as chronic elevation of CSF pressure can erode the skull base. Once CSF leak ensues, the intracranial pressure normalises, hence showing near-normal or higher end of normal range of RNFL thickness', NULL, 'Title\r\nUse of non-invasive techniques in identifying CSF opening pressure in Idiopathic intracranial hypertension\r\n\r\nPresenting Author\r\nDr Nicole Stephen\r\n\r\nAim\r\nTo assess the specific changes in Optical coherence tomography in patients with spontaneous CSF leak\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nThis retrospective study includes 20 patients including male and female between the age 18-65years. A thorough history, including history of headache, tinnitus, rhinorrhea, nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances. OCT was taken at the time of diagnosis.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nAmong the 20 patients included in the study, 18 were females. The most common clinical presentation is watery nasal discharge, followed by headache, seen in 10 patients. Two patients had history of recurrent meningitis. The average retinal nerve fibre layer thickness in right eye is 106.2m and left eye is 105.9m with symmetry of 85%.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nIdiopathic intracranial hypertension is predominantly seen in females with a history of long-standing headache and visual disturbances in the form of scotoma, diplopia and reduced visual acuity. They can present as CSF leak in patients with a long-standing history, as chronic elevation of CSF pressure can erode the skull base. Once CSF leak ensues, the intracranial pressure normalises, hence showing near-normal or higher end of normal range of RNFL thickness', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 22:28:02', '2025-10-15 22:28:06'),
(247, 'Dr J. JANANI', 'jjanani25395@gmail.com', 'RHIN000047', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Comparative study between Navigation guided and conventional Endoscopic Trans-nasal trans-sphenoidal', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'AIM- To compare the surgical outcomes, complications and recurrence rates in patients undergoing endoscopic trans-nasal trans-sphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas with and without intraoperative navigation guidance.\r\nMETHODOLOGY- A retrospective comparative study was conducted on 45 patients who underwent endoscopic trans-nasal transsphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas over a 5year period. The patients were divided into two groups: Group A underwent conventional endoscopic excision without navigation and Group B underwent navigation guided excision. Pre operative MRI and hormonal evaluation were done. Parameters assessed included demographics, extent of resection, complications, and recurrence in follow op imaging. \r\nRESULTS- Among the 45 patients, 57.7 were female with a mean age of 48.8 years. Most had Macroadenoma with headache and visual symptoms. 42% underwent navigation guided excision while 57.7 underwent convention excision. Navigation guided surgery had better result with fewer recurrences and complications.\r\nCONCLUSION- Navigation guided endoscopic trans-nasal transsphenoidal excision of pituitary adenomas significantly improves surgical accuracy, lowers recurrence rates compared to conventional surgery. The use of intraoperative navigation is recommended as a standard adjunct for safe and effective tumour excision.\r\nKey Words- Pituitary adenoma, Navigation guided', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 22:56:18', '2025-10-15 22:56:21'),
(248, 'Dheeneshwar S', 'dheeneshwar98@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000429', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Pott’s Puffy Tumor Without Sinus Symptoms: A Rare Presentation and Multimodal Management', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Pott’s Puffy Tumor Without Sinus Symptoms: A Rare Presentation and Multimodal Management\r\nPott’s puffy tumor is a rare complication of frontal sinusitis involving subperiosteal abscess and frontal bone osteomyelitis. We report an unusual case presenting with history of vague headache without any other sinus symptoms.\r\nA 27-year-old female with no comorbidities presented with a rapidly progressive, tender forehead swelling (4×3 cm) over 15 days, preceded by intermittent headache for one year. NCCT revealed complete frontal sinus opacification with anterior wall defect and subgaleal extension, with bilateral maxillary sinus involvement. Multiple aspirations and intravenous antibiotics were initially attempted, but recurrence occurred. Definitive management was performed via a combined endoscopic and bicoronal flap frontal osteoplastic surgery and Draf III (modified Lothrop) procedure. Intraoperatively, inflamed tissue and fungal mucin were identified; histopathology showed chronic inflammation without fungal elements.\r\nPostoperative recovery was uneventful. Minimal recurrence in the form a mild swelling at two months resolved with antibiotics and topical therapy. Follow-up computed tomography at three months showed expected healing changes without cosmetic deformity.\r\nEarly recognition and multidisciplinary surgical management are key to preventing intracranial complications and achieving excellent functional and cosmetic outcomes in atypical pott’s puffy tumor presentations.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 23:26:00', '2025-10-15 23:26:04');
INSERT INTO `rh_abstract_old` (`id`, `name`, `email`, `reg_id`, `catergory_id`, `title_0`, `title_1`, `title_2`, `title_3`, `title_4`, `note`, `note_1`, `note_2`, `note_3`, `note_4`, `file`, `file_1`, `file_2`, `file_3`, `file_4`, `mail_send`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(249, 'Dr Sonam Snehil', 'sonam522544@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000430', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Tale of Two Sides: Synchronous Nasal and Contralateral Infraorbital Neurofibromas in a Young Male', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Tale of Two Sides: Synchronous Nasal and Contralateral Infraorbital Neurofibromas in a Young Male\r\n\r\nBackground\r\nNeurofibromas are benign peripheral nerve sheath tumors that usually occur in the context of neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1). Solitary or localized neurofibromas involving the nasal cavity or orbit are extremely rare, and synchronous lesions in distinct craniofacial sites without systemic NF1 features are uncommon.\r\n\r\nCase Presentation\r\nA 19-year-old male presented with progressive right-sided nasal obstruction and a lobulated mass protruding externally from the right nasal vestibule for last 5yrs , accompanied by a gradually enlarging, painless swelling over the left infraorbital (lower-lid) region. There was no history of epistaxis, visual disturbance, or hearing loss.\r\n\r\nInvestigations\r\nMRI face (CEMRI) demonstrated a heterogeneously enhancing lesion involving the right lateral nasal wall measuring 29 × 26 × 29 mm and another soft-tissue lesion in the left infraorbital region, both showing T2 hyperintensity and T1 hypointensity, suggestive of neurogenic origin. \r\nSections examined from right nasal cavity shows epidermis and dermis with an ill-circumscribed spindle cell tumor arranged in vague fascicles with collagen deposits resembling shredded carrots and myxoidy changes in the background. No significant atypia, mitosis or necrosis noted,suggestive of Neurofibroma. Biopsy from the infraorbital swelling confirmed neurofibroma. \r\nManagement\r\nThe patient underwent complete excision of the nasal mass , with preservation of nasal architecture. Vision and cranial nerve function remained normal post-operatively.\r\n\r\nDiscussion\r\nMultiple neurofibromas occurring without features of neurofibromatosis type 1 are rare and usually appear as isolated, slow-growing swellings. Because their imaging features can resemble other benign nasal tumors and they can affect facial appearance, careful evaluation and planned surgery are essential.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nSynchronous neurofibromas of the nasal and infraorbital regions are exceedingly uncommon. High suspicion, imaging correlation, and histopathological confirmation are essential for diagnosis, and complete excision ensures favorable functional and cosmetic outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 23:45:59', '2025-10-15 23:46:03'),
(250, 'SIVASUBRAMANIAM NAGARAJAN', 'sivan020393@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000428', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'CSF Leak unmasking the forgotten Trauma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE\r\nCSF Leak unmasking the forgotten Trauma\r\n\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR\r\nSivasubramaniam Nagarajan\r\n\r\nAIM\r\nTailoring the management of Traumatic CSF Leaks based on its clinical presentation\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY\r\nCross sectional study\r\nCase series of patients with Cerebrospinal Fluid Leak with past history of trauma.\r\n\r\nRESULTS\r\nAscertaining the cause for every patient with subsequent surgical repair of the CSF leak is necessary for successful management of this condition.\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION\r\nSurgical management of Traumatic CSF Leaks should be considered. Timely intervention is essential wherever necessary.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-15 23:50:29', '2025-10-15 23:50:32'),
(254, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Outcomes of Extracorporeal Septorhinoplasty', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo evaluate the functional and aesthetic outcomes of extracorporeal septorhinoplasty in patients with severe septal deviation and nasal obstruction.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is performed under general anaesthesia for severe septal deviation. The mucoperichondrial flaps are elevated through an open or hemitransfixation incision, and the deviated septal cartilage is completely removed. The cartilage is reshaped extracorporeally on a flat surface by scoring, trimming, and suturing to achieve a straight and stable framework. The reconstructed septum is reimplanted in the midline, with the caudal end fixed to the anterior nasal spine and dorsal support reattached to the upper lateral cartilages. Mucosal flaps are repositioned and sutured, followed by nasal splints or packing to maintain alignment and ensure optimal postoperative airway function.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe mean age of the patients was 31.7 ± 8.2 years. The mean preoperative NOSE score significantly decreased at three months post-surgery (p < 0.001). Marked improvement in nasal airflow and patient-reported satisfaction was observed. Postoperative complications were minimal, including mild dorsal irregularity and transient nasal tip edema, both of which resolved with conservative management. No cases of septal perforation or saddle nose deformity were reported.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nExtracorporeal septorhinoplasty is a highly effective surgical technique for correcting complex septal deformities. It provides excellent functional and aesthetic outcomes by restoring nasal symmetry and airway patency. The procedure ensures stable septal support with minimal complications, making it a preferred approach in cases of severe deviation or post-traumatic nasal deformity.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 11:03:37', '2025-10-16 11:03:40'),
(257, 'Dr Rimjhim Sharma', 'sharma.jiya2012@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000416', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Clinical Experience with Intratympanic Dexamethasone in Sensorineural Hearing and Vestibular Disorde', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr. Rimjhim Sharma\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo assess the efficacy and safety of intratympanic dexamethasone injections in improving hearing thresholds and reducing vertigo/tinnitus in patients unresponsive to conventional therapy.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA prospective observational study was carried out on 35 patients between January 2022 and December 2023. Conditions included idiopathic sudden sensorineural hearing loss (ISSNHL) (n=20), refractory Menière’s disease (n=10), and persistent tinnitus (n=5) after at least four weeks of standard medical management. Intratympanic dexamethasone (4 mg/mL, 0.5 mL) was administered weekly for three consecutive weeks. Pure tone audiometry, vertigo frequency, and tinnitus handicap inventory scores were recorded pre-treatment, at one month, and at three months post-treatment.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nIn ISSNHL patients, 65% (13/20) demonstrated ≥25 dB improvement in pure tone average (PTA) at three months (mean gain 28 ± 7 dB). Among those with Menière’s disease, 8 out of 10 patients (80%) reported a >50% reduction in monthly vertigo attacks (average from 6.4 to 2.1 episodes/month). Tinnitus scores improved significantly in 3 of 5 patients (60%) at one month, though partial relapse was seen by three months. No major adverse effects occurred; transient ear discomfort was most common.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nIntratympanic dexamethasone is a safe and effective adjunct treatment for patients with ISSNHL, refractory Menière’s disease, and chronic tinnitus who have not responded to standard therapy. It yields significant improvements in hearing outcomes and vertigo control, with moderate benefit for tinnitus. Controlled trials with larger samples are recommended to optimize dose, frequency, and patient selection.', '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-16 11:51:11', '2025-10-16 11:51:14'),
(259, 'Dr Suji P.S', 'ps.sujips.suji@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000435', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\",\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '“Minimally Invasive Mastery: Our Experience with the Endoscopic Transnasal Transsphenoidal Approach ', NULL, '“Combined Supraorbital and Endoscopic Approach for Lateral Frontoorbital Mucocele Excision.”', NULL, NULL, 'Aim: To present our surgical experience in the management of various intracranial lesions using ETNTS approach.\r\nMethodology: This retrospective review analyzed patients who underwent the ETNTS approach for sellar or parasellar lesions at our center. Preoperative imaging, surgical technique, intraoperative navigation, and postoperative management were assessed, with focus on resection extent, hospital stay, recovery, and complications. Special attention was given to preventing cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leaks and preserving neurovascular structures.\r\nResults: Six patients (aged 27-60) underwent ETNTS, primarily for pituitary adenomas. Complete resection was achieved in all cases. The average hospital stay was 7 days, and most patients reported mild postoperative discomfort. Complications included CSF leaks and sinus issues in 33% of cases each, managed conservatively or with minor interventions. Patients showed significant improvement in neurological symptoms.\r\nConclusion: The ETNTS approach provided effective tumor resection with minimal complications, shorter recovery, and reduced discomfort. While CSF leakage remains a challenge, the ETNTS technique proves valuable for selected intracranial lesions. A multidisciplinary approach is essential for maximizing patient safety and outcomes.', NULL, 'Abstract: Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\r\nTitle: Combined Supraorbital and Endoscopic Approach for Lateral Fronto-orbital Mucocele Excision.\r\n                                                                                  Presenting Author: Dr Suji P.S\r\nLateral frontoorbital mucoceles are rare entities that present a surgical challenge due to their deep, lateral location and proximity to the orbit and anterior cranial fossa. While endoscopic sinus surgery has become the preferred approach for most frontal mucoceles, access to the lateral recess remains limited. We present a case of a lateral frontoorbital mucocele successfully excised using a combined supraorbital and endoscopic approach.\r\nA middle-aged patient presented with progressive right supraorbital swelling and dull frontal headache. CT and MRI scans revealed a well-defined, expansile lesion occupying the lateral frontal sinus and extending toward the orbital roof. A limited supraorbital incision provided direct access to the lateral component, while endoscopic transnasal access facilitated drainage and marsupialization of the medial extension. The mucocele was completely excised with preservation of orbital and neurovascular structures.\r\nThe combined approach offered excellent visualization and complete clearance of the lesion with minimal morbidity and a superior cosmetic outcome. This hybrid technique effectively overcomes the limitations of purely endoscopic or external approaches and represents a safe and cosmetically acceptable option for the management of laterally placed frontoorbital mucoceles.', NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-21 06:41:07', '2025-10-21 06:41:10'),
(260, 'Pritansh Kumar Nikhar', 'pritanshkumar@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000124', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'ENDOSCOPE IS MIGHTIER THAN SCALPEL: A PARADIGM SHIFT IN MANAGEMENT OF JUVENILE NASOPHARYNGEAL ANGIOF', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'AIM- To present outcome of excision of Juvenile nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma via endoscopic approach.\r\nMETHODOLOGY- Retrospective case series review of five cases of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma who presented to Department of ENT, IPGMER and SSKM Hospital, Kolkata. All patients underwent endoscopic excision preceded by embolization.\r\nRESULTS- All patients were Indian males, presenting with chief complaints of progressive unilateral nasal obstruction, spontaneous profuse epistaxsis, hyopsmia, sleep disturbance and unilateral heaviness in ear. The patient presentation comprised of Radkowski Ib to IIc stages, with one recurrence case. Internal Maxillary artery and Ascending Pharyngeal artery were the main blood supply to the lesion. surgical approach applied was endoscopic four- handed technique of excision. All patients were discharged well with no major complications nor cases of recurrence.\r\nCONCLUSION- Endoscopic approach is possible for various stages of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma. Preoperative angiographic embolization has minimalized blood loss intraoperatively. The endoscopic approach is a better and advanced treatment modality for excision of Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma which has reduced post operative morbidity.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-21 19:17:29', '2025-10-21 19:17:32'),
(268, 'Apoorv Srivastava', 'apoorvsrivastava85@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000347', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'RARE PRESENTATION OF EWING’S SARCOMA IN MAXILLA', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'INTRODUCTION-Ewing\'s sarcoma are small round cell tumors belonging to Ewing\'s family of tumors and the second most common bone tumour seen in children. Primary arising in head and neck region is uncommon and maxillary Ewing\'s sarcoma is rarely seen. Histologically it is one of many small round cell tumors found in children and therefore immunohistochemical and occasionally molecular studies are required to establish the diagnosis. CASE REPORT-A 22‐year‐old female patient reported with a chief complaint of swelling on right side of face, gradually increasing in size. Swelling was insidious in onset. On physical appearance there was gross facial asymmetry with a well-circumscribed swelling measuring about 5 × 5 cm, on the right cheek. Movements of the eye was present. Acuity of vision was not altered. On palpation the swelling was non tender, bony hard in consistency. It was non-pulsatile and noncompressible. Anterior rhinoscopy reveals pinkish mass in right nasal cavity. INVESTIGATION AND MANAGEMENT-MRI shows large circumscribed mixed signal intensity soft tissue mass epicentre in right maxillary sinus, extending into right nasal cavity, right orbit, ethmoid sinus and premaxillary sinus, causing destruction of all walls of right maxillary sinus, right maxillary bone, inferomedial wall and floor of right orbit. A maxillectomy was performed including hard palate till midline.  Three weeks, postoperatively, the patient was referred for radiation and chemotherapy. Where 24 cycles of radiotherapy were done.  DISCUSSION- After osteosarcoma, Ewing’s Sarcoma is the second most frequent primary malignant tumor occurring in bone. However, it is rare for Ewing Sarcoma to be found in the head and neck region. Approximately 4% of Ewing’s sarcoma cases have arisen in the bones of head and neck with 1% occurring in the jaws. When the jaws are involved it frequently involves the mandible than maxilla. A painful swelling was the most common presentation. The majority of patients had a average tumour size of 6 × 4 cm. The lesion is predominantly seen in children and young adults. Ewing’s sarcoma is a radiosensitive tumour. Multimodality therapy consisting of an initial biopsy, aggressive combination of surgery, chemotherapy and localized radiotherapy is the treatment of choice for Ewing’s sarcoma of the head andneck region and may result in long-term survival.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/371d63a45a97e92b13dd0e30857cf8ed.docx', 2, 1, '2025-10-28 00:39:25', '2025-10-28 00:39:28'),
(269, 'Dr Swati Tewari', 'swatitwr4@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000472', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Outcomes of septal perforation repair using an Anterior ethmoidal artery flap and Collagen Matrix', NULL, 'ENTOMOPHTHOROMYCOSIS – THE TROPICAL FUNGAL INFILTRATOR', NULL, NULL, 'TITLE: Outcomes of septal perforation repair using an Anterior ethmoidal artery flap and Collagen Matrix \r\nPresenting Author: Dr Swati Tewari,\r\nCo-authors Prof Satyawati Mohindra, Prof Ramandeep Singh Virk \r\nAIM: -To evaluate the efficacy and safety of endoscopic nasal septal perforation (NSP) repair using an anterior ethmoidal artery (AEA) flap combined with a collagen matrix inlay and assess its impact on quality of life.\r\nMETHODOLOGY: - This prospective case series included five patients with symptomatic anterior NSPs who underwent endoscopic repair using an AEA pedicled flap reinforced with a collagen matrix graft. Patients were followed postoperatively on day 21 and day 90. Primary outcomes assessed were anatomical closure and mucosalization, while secondary outcomes included complication rates and quality-of-life improvements using the Septal Perforation Quality of Life (SEPEQOL) questionnaire.\r\nRESULTS: - Complete closure of the perforation was achieved in 60% of patients, with contralateral mucosalization in 80% at postoperative day (POD) 21 and 60% at POD 90. Only one patient (20%) experienced postoperative crusting. SEPEQOL scores showed statistically significant improvement in nasal congestion (2.6→0.4, p=0.01), nasal blockage (1.8→0.2, p=0.01), and air hunger (1.6→0.1, p=0.009). No major complications or graft failures were observed.\r\nCONCLUSION: - Endoscopic NSP repair using an anterior ethmoidal artery flap with a collagen matrix is a safe, effective technique for small to medium-sized anterior perforations. It provides high closure rates, promotes mucosal healing, and significantly enhances patient quality of life. Further large-scale studies are recommended to validate these findings.', NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nEntomophthoromycosis is a rare, chronic fungal infection predominantly affecting immunocompetent individuals in tropical and subtropical regions. Caused by Conidiobolus and Basidiobolus species, it primarily involves nasal and facial subcutaneous tissues, often mimicking other granulomatous\r\n Aim:\r\nTo present a short case series highlighting the clinical spectrum, diagnostic approach, and successful management of rhino-facial Entomophthoromycosis in immunocompetent patients.\r\nCase Report:\r\nFour male patients aged 2–19 years presented with nasal obstruction and facial swelling of 3–9 months duration. Diagnosis was confirmed through clinico-histopathological correlation demonstrating granulomatous inflammation with the Splendore-Hoeppli phenomenon. All cases were managed surgically through biopsy followed by medical therapy using liposomal amphotericin B, supersaturated potassium iodide (SSKI), and itraconazole. Patients showed complete recovery and remained disease-free during 1–13 years of follow-up.\r\nDiscussion:\r\nDue to its indolent course and clinical resemblance to other granulomatous diseases, Entomophthoromycosis often faces delayed diagnosis. Histopathology remains crucial, while combination antifungal therapy offers optimal results.\r\nConclusion:\r\nEarly recognition, prompt histological confirmation, and combined antifungal therapy ensure favorable outcomes in rhino-facial Entomophthoromycosis. Heightened clinician awareness in endemic areas can prevent morbidity and facial disfigurement.', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/ba3abb00d7779cd98891f677b8cca8b8.docx', '', '/public/upload/abstract/7c8ef469ef063c7bdb807ba2fff122f0.docx', 2, 1, '2025-10-29 22:17:32', '2025-10-29 22:17:35'),
(270, 'MOHANRAJ S', 'mohanraj1757@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000488', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'An Anomalous Tooth Masquerading as Chronic Maxillary Sinusitis: A Rare Case Report', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo present a rare case of an ectopic maxillary tooth presenting as chronic sinusitis and to emphasize the value of a combined surgical approach for successful management.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 30-year-old male presented with unilateral nasal obstruction, purulent nasal discharge, and facial heaviness unresponsive to medical therapy. Nasal endoscopy showed mucopurulent discharge from the right middle meatus. CT paranasal sinuses revealed a radiodense tooth-like structure within the right maxillary sinus. The patient underwent a combined Caldwell-Luc and endoscopic middle meatal antrostomy for removal of the ectopic tooth and sinus clearance.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe tooth was removed completely without complications. Postoperatively, the patient had complete relief of symptoms, and follow-up imaging showed a healthy, aerated maxillary sinus. Histopathology confirmed chronic inflammatory changes consistent with sinusitis.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nEctopic tooth in the maxillary sinus, though rare, should be considered in unilateral, refractory sinusitis. A combined Caldwell-Luc and endoscopic approach offers excellent visualization, complete removal, and long-term disease resolution with minimal morbidity.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/4d787e372f3b725195d795900b7a3e99.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-10-30 12:17:03', '2025-10-30 12:17:08'),
(271, 'Balakumar Y', 'bala2343@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000499', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Isolated Third Cranial Nerve Palsy Secondary to Allergic Fungal Rhinosinusitis (AFRS)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Objective\r\nTo highlight an uncommon presentation of isolated third cranial nerve palsy as a complication of allergic fungal rhinosinusitis (AFRS), and to emphasize the importance of early recognition and management to prevent long-term neurological deficits.\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\nA 64-year-old female presented with gradual-onset right-sided ptosis and diplopia over 3 weeks, associated with nasal obstruction and intermittent headache. On examination, there was complete right-sided ptosis with impaired ocular movements consistent with isolated third cranial nerve palsy. Pupillary reaction was sluggish. Nasal endoscopy was completely normal. CT paranasal sinuses showed hyperdense areas within the right sphenoid sinus suggestive of allergic fungal rhinosinusitis with extension to cavernous sinus and orbit. \r\n\r\nResult\r\nThe patient underwent functional endoscopic sinus surgery (FESS) with debridement of allergic mucin and fungal debris. Histopathological examination confirmed allergic fungal rhinosinusitis. Postoperatively, the patient was managed with systemic corticosteroids. At 4-week follow-up, there was partial improvement in ptosis and ocular motility, indicating early recovery of third nerve function.\r\n\r\nDiscussion\r\nIsolated third cranial nerve palsy as a manifestation of allergic fungal rhinosinusitis is extremely rare. The mechanism involves compressive or inflammatory neuropathy due to fungal-induced sinus expansion or inflammation extending to the orbital apex. Early surgical intervention combined with medical management can result in favorable outcomes. Radiological evaluation plays a crucial role in detecting disease extension and differentiating it from other causes such as neoplasms or vascular lesions.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nAFRS can rarely present with isolated third cranial nerve palsy due to involvement of the orbital apex. Prompt recognition, imaging, and combined medical-surgical management are essential to prevent irreversible neurological damage and optimize recovery.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/f60a7db3df20752f022616f4bc43dba5.docx', 2, 1, '2025-10-31 16:50:01', '2025-10-31 16:50:05'),
(272, 'Dr Hafees Abdullah Perumbally', 'drhafeesabdullah@gmail.com', 'ME002501203', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic Draf III for a Fronto-orbital Mucocele Presenting with Isolated Ptosis in an adolescent f', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title: Endoscopic Draf III for a Fronto-orbital Mucocele Presenting with Isolated Ptosis in an adolescent female: Case Description and Video Demonstration.\r\nCase Report: A 16-year-old female with no comorbidities presented with progressive left-eye ptosis of 15 days duration. Clinical examination showed isolated partial ptosis without ophthalmoplegia or vision loss. CT imaging revealed a left frontal sinus mucocele with erosive bony changes of the frontal sinus posterior wall and floor. After multidisciplinary discussion she underwent endoscopic frontal sinus drainage via a Draf III (endoscopic modified Lothrop) approach. The procedure was video-recorded for demonstration. Intra-operative findings included frank mucocele contents and sclerotic frontal sinus walls. The postoperative course was uneventful; ptosis improved over days to weeks and the patient remains well on follow up with a patent frontal neo-ostium on endoscopic inspection.\r\nDiscussion & Conclusion: Endoscopic Draf III provided safe, definitive drainage and decompression of the frontal mucocele causing orbital symptoms in this adolescent patient, avoiding open external approaches. Early endoscopic management can result in rapid symptomatic recovery and good ostial patency. This case is accompanied by an intra-operative video illustrating key technical steps when frontal sinus walls are eroded and orbit is at risk.', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/d505b94e4e851fea883ad4b8c730c789.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-02 22:57:24', '2025-11-02 22:57:27'),
(274, 'Dr SETHU MADHAVAN S', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A clinical profile of chronic suppurative otitis media patients with complications - A case series', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Abstract\r\n\r\nBackground:\r\nChronic Suppurative Otitis Media (CSOM) is a persistent infection of the middle ear and mastoid cavity, characterized by ear discharge and tympanic membrane perforation. It continues to be a significant cause of morbidity, especially in developing countries. Complications may arise due to bone erosion or venous thrombophlebitis, leading to extracranial or intracranial spread.\r\n\r\nAims and Objectives:\r\n\r\n1. To assess and analyze patients presenting with complications of CSOM.\r\n\r\n\r\n2. To evaluate postoperative outcomes following surgical management.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMaterials and Methods:\r\nA prospective case series was conducted on patients diagnosed with CSOM and its complications. Each patient underwent detailed clinical, audiological, and radiological evaluation, followed by appropriate surgical intervention and postoperative follow-up.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nThe most common complications encountered were mastoid abscess, facial nerve palsy, and intracranial extension. Most patients showed favorable postoperative recovery with surgery and antibiotics. Early recognition and timely intervention prevented permanent sequelae and reduced morbidity.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCSOM remains a prevalent and preventable cause of morbidity. Early diagnosis, proper imaging, and prompt surgical management play vital roles in preventing severe and potentially life-threatening complications.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/35f7e2ec56fca922349f4a56d22380e1.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-05 12:12:18', '2025-11-05 12:12:21'),
(275, 'Dr SETHU MADHAVAN S', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', 'sethusethu91@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Topic: Chronic Rhinosinusitis with Nasal Polyposis – Immunologic Insights and EPOS 2020 Guidelines', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Abstract\r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo review the current understanding of the immunopathogenesis of chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyposis (CRSwNP) and analyze the clinical implications of the EPOS 2020 guidelines in diagnosis and management.\r\n\r\nObjectives:\r\n\r\n1. To describe the immunologic mechanisms underlying CRSwNP with emphasis on type 2 inflammation.\r\n\r\n\r\n2. To outline the diagnostic criteria and classification according to EPOS 2020.\r\n\r\n\r\n3. To evaluate updated recommendations for medical and surgical management.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMethods:\r\nA comprehensive review of recent literature and the EPOS 2020 position paper was performed. Studies focusing on cytokine profiles, eosinophilic inflammation, microbiome influence, and treatment outcomes were analyzed. Management strategies were compared between traditional steroid-based therapy and newer targeted biologic approaches.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nCRSwNP is predominantly driven by type 2 immune response characterized by elevated IL-4, IL-5, IL-13, and eosinophilic infiltration. EPOS 2020 emphasizes a multidisciplinary, endotype-driven approach integrating clinical phenotype, inflammatory biomarkers, and radiologic grading (Lund-Mackay score). Topical corticosteroids remain first-line therapy, while short systemic courses are reserved for exacerbations. Endoscopic sinus surgery (ESS) is recommended for medically refractory cases, followed by postoperative intranasal therapy. Biologic agents such as dupilumab, omalizumab, and mepolizumab are advised for recurrent, severe, eosinophilic disease.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nEPOS 2020 has redefined CRSwNP as a chronic, type 2–mediated inflammatory disease requiring personalized, multidisciplinary care. Integration of immunologic profiling, optimized medical therapy, and biologic treatment has improved long-term outcomes and reduced recurrence rates. Continued research into immunomodulation and precision medicine is essential for future management.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/2e7c5b2345ef94a89acd0c7f0baeed6b.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-05 12:31:48', '2025-11-05 12:31:51'),
(277, 'Nikhil Jacob', 'n3niks1@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000198', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Embryology’s Lingering Footprint – Branchial Sinus: A Case Report', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\nIntroduction:\r\nBranchial apparatus anomalies arise from incomplete embryonic cleft involution. Among these, second branchial cleft anomalies are the most common and can present as cysts, sinuses, or fistulae. Branchial sinuses are relatively rare and often manifest as a discharging opening along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle.\r\nCase Report:\r\nA 15-year-old female presented with a history of intermittent discharge from a small opening on the lower neck for five years. Examination revealed a tiny sinus opening along the anterior border of the right sternocleidomastoid muscle, with no other associated neck abnormalities. CECT neck and CT sinogram demonstrated a blind-ending sinus tract extending from the skin to the right greater horn of the hyoid bone, measuring approximately 6.7 cm × 4 mm × 5 mm. The patient underwent surgical excision of the sinus tract using the stepladder technique, which provided excellent exposure and ensured complete tract removal. A 12 cm tract extending up to the right tonsillar fossa was excised in toto and sent for histopathological examination. The postoperative period was uneventful, and no recurrence was observed at the 3-month follow-up.\r\nDiscussion:\r\nThe branchial apparatus develops between the 3rd and 8th weeks of embryogenesis and comprises arches, pouches, and clefts. Failure of complete involution of the second branchial cleft can result in sinus or fistula formation. Surgical excision remains the gold standard of management, as incomplete removal leads to recurrence. The stepladder technique provides optimum exposure, ensuring the identification and total excision of the tract, thereby minimizing recurrence.\r\nConclusion:\r\nBranchial sinus should be considered in the differential diagnosis of a persistent discharging neck sinus, particularly along the sternocleidomastoid. Complete excision using the stepladder technique remains the definitive management approach to prevent recurrence.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/0faf7db093431bed8c75ed21316db30d.docx', 1, 1, '2025-11-05 13:15:11', '2025-11-05 13:15:11'),
(280, 'Kaviyarasi V', 'vkaviyarasi@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000474', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-06 22:21:07', '2025-11-06 22:21:10'),
(281, 'Kaviyarasi V', 'vkaviyarasi@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000474', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '“Sniffles in the Classroom: Unmasking Allergic Rhinitis in School Children”', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title: “Sniffles in the Classroom: Unmasking Allergic Rhinitis in School Children”\r\nBackground: Allergic rhinitis (AR) is a common, IgE-mediated nasal inflammation causing congestion, rhinorrhea, sneezing, and itching. It affects up to 40% of children worldwide and can impair sleep, concentration, and school performance. In India, prevalence ranges from 7% to 30%, influenced by pollution and lifestyle changes. Despite its high burden, AR often remains underdiagnosed and undertreated, especially in rural settings.\r\nObjectives: 1. To determine the prevalence of AR among school-going children aged 8–14 years in Melmaruvathur.\r\n2.	To assess its impact on health-related quality of life (HRQoL).\r\nMethods:\r\nA questionnaire-based cross-sectional study was conducted among 613 children (8–14 years) from GB Public School, Melmaruvathur. Data were collected using the International Study of Asthma and Allergies in Childhood (ISAAC) questionnaire with ARIA severity grading.\r\nResults:\r\nAbout 81% of children reported worsening symptoms during certain months, and 67% had itchy-watery eyes. The prevalence of nasal symptoms was 28%, while 14% had allergic rhino-conjunctivitis. Around 15% reported interference with daily activities. ‘Blockers’ (61%) were more common than ‘sneeze-runners’ (39%). More than half (56%) had comorbidities such as asthma or eczema. Major allergens included pollens, house-dust mites, pets, molds, and certain foods.\r\nConclusion:\r\nAllergic rhinitis is prevalent among school-aged children and significantly affects their daily life and school performance. Early diagnosis, parental awareness, and timely management can help reduce morbidity and improve quality of life. Broader community-based studies are needed to better understand risk factors and prevention strategies.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/2f5de41434424f06670bac87dfe35875.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-06 22:55:38', '2025-11-06 22:55:42'),
(282, 'Dr Aarushi Vashist', 'aaavashist@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000524', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Unusual Sinonasal Tumors in a Tertiary Care Centre: Case Series.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\nPresenting Author- Dr. Aarushi Vashist\r\nAssistant Professor ENT, Kalpana Chawla Government Medical College Karnal, Haryana\r\nIntroduction:\r\nSinonasal malignancies are rare and heterogeneous tumours of nasal cavity and paranasal\r\nsinuses which comprise only 3% of tumours of head and neck region. They arise most\r\ncommonly in the maxillary sinus but other sinuses can also be involved.\r\nPresenting symptoms:\r\nThe patients with unusual sinonasal tumours present with vague symptoms like nasal\r\nobstruction, nasal discharge, facial pain etc. which mimics benign sinonasal diseases like\r\nnasal polyps. So, the diagnosis requires high level of clinical suspicion followed by accurate\r\ndiagnosis and proper management. Here, we present a rare case series comprising of\r\neosinophilic angiocentric fibrosis, sinonasal neuro-endocrine tumour, adenoid cystic\r\ncarcinoma of nose and sinonasal myxoma. Diagnosis was done by clinical findings\r\nsupplemented by CT Scan and MRI. Biopsy was done to confirm the diagnosis. Treatment\r\nwas done by surgery and post op radiotherapy and chemotherapy depending on the diagnosis.\r\nConclusion:\r\nA proper clinical suspicion of these malignancies should be there while dealing with the\r\npatients presenting with vague sinonasal problems so that timely and effective management\r\ncan be done.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/3efcf69e7fedb1d93ddc35f8421861fa.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-07 19:08:17', '2025-11-07 19:08:20'),
(283, 'Dr.Sonali Sharma', 'Sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-07 21:54:43', '2025-11-07 21:54:46'),
(284, 'RAHUL MAURYA', 'rahul1998maurya@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000201', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Schwannoma of the nasolabial area : A case report', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE - Schwannoma of the nasolabial area : A case report\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR- Dr. Rahul Maurya\r\nABSTRACT\r\nINTRODUCTION- Schwannoma of nasolabial region are rare, here we present a case of schwannoma of nasolabial area.\r\nCASE REPORT- A 34-year-old male presented with painless and gradually enlarging right side nasolabial mass for 7 years, associated with nasal obstruction for 2 years. Examination revealed a non-tender bulge in the nasolabial area, at the level of vestibule obscuring the view of right nasal cavity with deviated nasal septum to left. FNAC was suggestive of Benign spindle cell lesion. CECT Paranasal sinus showed presence of soft tissue density mass 34*29*35mm in vestibule of right nasal cavity showing focal areas of enhancement causing mild pressure erosion and scalloping of underlying maxillary alveolar margin. The lesion was surgically excised via sublabial approach and was sent for histopathological examination which was reported as schwannoma.\r\nDISCUSSION: Schwannomas are benign, slow growing encapsulated tumors, they most frequently occur in the head and neck region, accounting for approximately 25–45% of all cases, but their occurrence within the nasolabial area is rare, representing less than 4% of head and neck schwannomas.\r\nCONCLUSION- Nasal schwannomas are rare benign peripheral nerve sheath tumors that may mimic other intranasal pathologies. Comprehensive evaluation with imaging and histopathological confirmation is essential for accurate diagnosis. Complete surgical excision remains the definitive treatment and is associated with excellent functional and cosmetic outcomes, as well as a very low likelihood of recurrence.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/0ab261bbf2050c6b1dfbd5954661f4a4.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 02:17:22', '2025-11-09 02:17:26'),
(285, 'Anukaran Mahajan', 'dranukaranent@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000481', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression: A Case Series', 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression: A Case Series', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression is a valuable surgical intervention for reducing orbital pressure, restoring ocular function, and improving cosmesis in patients with diverse orbital pathologies. This video presents a case series of six patients who underwent orbital decompression. Each patient underwent tailored surgical planning based on clinical presentation, imaging findings, and anticipated functional and aesthetic outcomes. All patients experienced significant symptom relief, improved orbital volume, and satisfactory cosmetic outcomes. Postoperative follow-up at three to six months confirmed sustained improvement with no major complications. This series emphasizes the importance of transnasal endoscopic orbital decompression in managing a spectrum of orbital diseases, the importance of individualized surgical planning, and the role of precise technique in achieving optimal prognosis.', 'Transnasal Endoscopic Orbital Decompression is a valuable surgical intervention for reducing orbital pressure, restoring ocular function, and improving cosmesis in patients with diverse orbital pathologies. This video presents a case series of six patients who underwent orbital decompression. Each patient underwent tailored surgical planning based on clinical presentation, imaging findings, and anticipated functional and aesthetic outcomes. All patients experienced significant symptom relief, improved orbital volume, and satisfactory cosmetic outcomes. Postoperative follow-up at three to six months confirmed sustained improvement with no major complications. This series emphasizes the importance of transnasal endoscopic orbital decompression in managing a spectrum of orbital diseases, the importance of individualized surgical planning, and the role of precise technique in achieving optimal prognosis.', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/6094df8d84ab4a1cf69cb5119f3dbd7e.docx', '/public/upload/abstract/6094df8d84ab4a1cf69cb5119f3dbd7e.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 16:04:20', '2025-11-09 16:04:23'),
(286, 'Dr Shweta Chauhan', 'shwetachauhanx09@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000457', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Mucormycosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 18:58:15', '2025-11-09 18:58:19'),
(287, 'Dr Shweta Chauhan', 'shwetachauhanx09@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000457', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Mucormycosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'MUCORMYCOSIS \r\n                                               Presented by : Dr Shweta Chauhan     \r\n                         \r\nINTRODUCTION : Mucormycosis, also known as zygomycosis, is a rare but aggressive opportunistic fungal infection caused by fungi belonging to the order Mucorales (genera Rhizopus, Mucor, Lichtheimia, Cunninghamella, and others). It is characterized by angioinvasion, leading to vascular thrombosis, tissue necrosis, and rapid progression, often with a fulminant and fatal course if not diagnosed early and treated aggressively.\r\nAIM AND OBJECTIVE: of this poster is to present a case of Rhinomucormycosis that was treated with the help of Inferior maxillectomy and intravenous Liposomal Amphoterecin B.\r\nMETHODOLOGY:Her is a case of Atul , 41yr old male adult from Kangra , Himachal Pradesh, who was referred to us by the department of medicine with history of abnormal body movements and ulcer on the hard palate where he was being treated for Chronic liver disease with cirrhosis.On investigations we found, Hb - 9.5g/dl , TLC - 5910, Hba1c- 9 , Rbs- 220 mg/ dl . KOH mount:negative for fungal hyphae,Hrct nose+pns:b/l chronic pansinusitis with bony rarefaction, b/l blocked osteomeatal complexes,frontal & sphenoidal recesses, rightward deviated nasal septum with left inferior and middle turbinate hypertrophy and left concha bullosa.Patient was treated by  Inferior Maxillectomy Left Side Under Ga On Dated 19/04/2025 and HPE report showed hard palate, maxilla, maxillary mucosa consistent with fungal sinusitis with angioinvasion and underlying bone involvment possibly mucormycosis and was given : inj levitracetam , inj piptaz , inj pantop , inj liposomal amphotericin b ,inj insulin r 8 units tds,inj glargine 10 unit s/c od, tab aspirin , tab atorvastatin , syrup lactulose ,inj pcm , inj metro,tab dytor plus,tab carvidol,tab rifaximin , Post op MRI brain: p/o/c rhinomucormycosis with inferior maxillectomy present scan shows . residual / recurrent disease involving the left maxillary sinus with focal cerebrotis / infarct involving left frontal parasagittal lobe. The patient improved significantly.\r\nRESULT:The patients wife requested for referral and was referred to PGI chandigarh where he was started on oral Posaconazole and improved.\r\nCONCLUSION: Mucormycosis is a medical emergency requiring rapid diagnosis and aggressive management.Awareness post-COVID is essential, especially in diabetic and immunocompromised patients.Early surgical intervention and antifungal therapy improve prognosis.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/a11ee8b4df8219b78d2d536323f149c8.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 19:00:50', '2025-11-09 19:00:54'),
(288, 'Dr.Sonali sharma', 'sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rhabdomyosarcoma masquearding as juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rhabdomyosarcoma Masquerading as Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma\r\nPresenting Author: \r\nDr. Sonali Sharma\r\nAim: \r\nTo highlight a rare case of embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma of the nasal cavity presenting with clinical features suggestive of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA 17-year-old male presented with recurrent epistaxis, nasal obstruction, left eye proptosis, and noisy breathing. Examination revealed a reddish polypoidal mass in both nasal cavities. Provisional diagnosis of juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma or esthesioneuroblastoma was made. Biopsy was performed for histopathological confirmation.\r\nResults: \r\nHistopathological examination revealed features consistent with embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma. \r\nConclusions: \r\nRhabdomyosarcoma of the nasal cavity can clinically mimic juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma. This case underscores the need for tissue diagnosis in all suspected vascular nasal masses to avoid misdiagnosis and to initiate appropriate multidisciplinary treatment promptly.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/b973ed60aad85f5cafb1ca715e7b030a.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:12:39', '2025-11-09 20:12:42'),
(289, 'Dr.Sonali sharma', 'sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension\r\nPresenting Author: \r\nProf. Dr. Jagdeep Singh Thakur\r\nDr. Sarita Negi\r\nDr. Sonali Sharma\r\nAim: \r\nTo evaluate the role and effectiveness of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration in preserving vision in patients with idiopathic intracranial hypertension.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA review of published literature and institutional experience was conducted. Data from recent meta-analyses and clinical studies organized in the ENT Department, IGMC Shimla, were analyzed to assess outcomes of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration and decompression. Parameters studied included improvement in visual acuity, visual field, and headache relief, as well as reported complications. Comparative evaluation of transnasal and transconjunctival approaches was also performed..\r\nResults: \r\nMajority of patients showed improvement in visual symptoms and headache. Transnasal endoscopic approach demonstrated good results with minimal complications like diplopia and CSF leak.\r\nConclusions: \r\nEndoscopic optic nerve fenestration is a safe and effective option for managing idiopathic intracranial hypertension. The transnasal route offers better visualization and low morbidity.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/6594bb44120c5a3930a610db17b9e7c0.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:16:16', '2025-11-09 20:16:19'),
(290, 'Priya', 'priyaclassxii@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000251', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Comparative Analysis of the Visual Analogue Scale (VAS) and Nasal Obstruction Symptom Evaluation (NO', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title of paper : Comparative Analysis of the Visual Analogue Scale (VAS) and Nasal Obstruction Symptom Evaluation (NOSE) Score in the Evaluation of Post - Septoplasty Patients.\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Priya ( Resident Dept.of ENT &HNS, GMC JAMMU )\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n\r\nAim: To compare and establish correlation between the NOSE score and VAS score in measuring symptomatic relief in patients undergoing septoplasty .\r\n\r\nMethodology : Sixty patients with deviated nasal septum who underwent septoplasty within period of 8 months were included in the study. NOSE score & VAS score (out of 100) was documented before and after surgery. Results were correlated and compared statistically.\r\n\r\nResults:  NOSE score analysis indicated that trouble breathing through the nose and nasal obstruction or blockage were the most bothersome preoperative symptoms, with mean scores of 83.60 and 80.35, respectively. Significant postoperative improvement was observed in both NOSE and VAS scores at 1- and 3-months follow-ups (Wilcoxon test, p < 0.05). Spearman’s correlation confirmed a positive relationship between the two scoring systems, though NOSE score was found to be superior.\r\n\r\nConclusion: NOSE and VAS scores were both effective tools for assessing postoperative outcomes after septoplasty ; however, NOSE score exhibited superior sensitivity in detecting symptomatic improvement and correlated more strongly with patient satisfaction.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/602072520cfccbd62ded84991f2f214e.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:40:35', '2025-11-09 20:40:39');
