(291, 'Ramneet kour', 'Ramneetkour2000@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000250', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Comparative Evaluation of Submucosal Diathermy and Coblation- Assisted Turbinate Reduction in Patien', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title of paper : Comparative Evaluation of Submucosal Diathermy and Coblation- Assisted Turbinate Reduction in Patients with Inferior Turbinate Hypertrophy .\r\n\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Ramneet Kour ( Junior Resident Dept. of ENT &HNS , GMC JAMMU )\r\n\r\nAffiliation: GMC Jammu\r\n\r\nAim: To compare the efficacy and postoperative outcomes of submucosal diathermy and coblation in the reduction of hypertrophied inferior turbinates, using subjective assessments.\r\n\r\nMethods: This is a comparative study conducted in the Department of ENT & HNS at GMC Jammu over a period of 8 months .This study aimed to compare the efficacy and outcomes of submucosal diathermy (SMD) and coblation- assisted turbinate reduction in forty patients with inferior turbinate hypertrophy using subjective assessment scores.\r\n\r\nResults: According to the findings obtained in our study, both submucosal diathermy and coblation techniques resulted in significant improvement in nasal obstruction. However, the degree of symptomatic relief was greater in the patients treated with coblation. Moreover, coblation was associated with less intraoperative and postoperative pain. The difference between the two methods was statistically significant (p < 0.05).\r\n\r\nConclusion: Both techniques were effective in reducing nasal obstruction. However, Coblation produced superior symptomatic improvement and fewer postoperative complications compared to submucosal diathermy.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/077b843d6b6923034e236ad8c1ae9f59.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 20:40:47', '2025-11-09 20:40:50'),
(292, 'Rohini Deepa I', 'Deepi.deepa@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000450', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Post Nasal Neurectomy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'POSTNASAL NEURECTOMY IN REFRACTORY RHINITIS\r\n\r\nINTRODUCTION:\r\n\r\nPost nasal neurectomy is a surgical technique performed to treat patients with chronic refractory rhinitis, especially those unresponsive to conventional medical management. The procedure involves sectioning the posterior nasal nerve, which carries parasympathetic secretomotor fibers to the nasal mucosa. By reducing hyperactive parasympathetic input, symptoms such as rhinorrhea, nasal obstruction, and sneezing are significantly alleviated.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAIM:\r\n\r\nTo evaluate the effectiveness of postnasal neurectomy in managing patients with refractory allergic and non-allergic rhinitis.\r\n\r\nMATERIALS AND METHODS:\r\n\r\nThe study included patients presenting to ENT OPD with refractory rhinitis unresponsive to antihistamines, intranasal corticosteroids, and immunotherapy. Post nasal neurectomy was performed endoscopically. The patients were followed up postoperatively for 1 year, and outcomes were assessed using symptom scores and quality-of-life questionnaires.\r\n\r\nRESULTS:\r\n\r\nPost nasal neurectomy demonstrated significant improvement in nasal obstruction, sneezing frequency, and rhinorrhea. Complications were minimal, with only transient nasal dryness observed in a few patients. Long-term follow-up showed sustained symptom relief in the majority of patients.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/cebaa075c61a5ae6574b6425ba750441.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 22:33:56', '2025-11-09 22:33:59'),
(293, 'Dr. Rashmi Agarwal', 'drrashmi65@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000506', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Anterior and Central Skull Base Fibrous Dysplasia: A 12 Years’ Experience', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title- Anterior and Central Skull Base Fibrous Dysplasia: A 12 Years’ Experience\r\nPresenting Author – Dr. Rashmi Agarwal, Assistant Professor GMC, Sri Ganganagar\r\nAim – Fibrous dysplasia, specially of anterior and central skull base region, is a rare disorder. This article discusses about our experience in this pathology over last 12 years and discusses various clinic-pathological aspects of fibrous dysplasia.\r\nMethodology – A tertiary care institute based retrospective type study was conducted over a period of 12 years. Demographics, radiology, intraoperative details, pathology and follow up were taken into consideration and the data was analysed.\r\nResults – . Sixteen patients with complaints of proptosis, diplopia, nasal obstruction and/or facial deformity, underwent endoscopic sinus surgery. Subtotal resection was done in 5 patients. Ethmoid bone involvement was seen in 12 patients. Post operatively, diplopia persisted in one patient and one patient had epistaxis. All patients were followed up for 2–10 years with no other complications reported.\r\nConclusion – Anterior and central skull base involvement is rare in fibrous dysplasia. However, it can be removed effectively by endoscopic approach. Overall safety of patient has more concern rather than complete removal of disease', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/896a5a6fb2fe223392671f8de3fc7245.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-09 23:01:33', '2025-11-09 23:01:37'),
(294, 'santosh shivaswamy', 'drsantosh.s@gmail.com', 'RHIN000477', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'A Comparison of microdebrider assisted FESS  and co-ablation assisted  FESS for nasal polypi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Author : Dr.Santosh.Shivaswamy Senior Consultant ENT & Head & neck Surgeon , Manipal Hospital , Hebbal ,Bangalore \r\n\r\nAim : Study aimed at comparing the intra operative (blood loss, duration of surgery)\r\n and post operative results (crusting, scarring, discharge, symptoms, recurrence) \r\nbetween the two groups using Lund-Mackay scoring system and the data was \r\nstatistically analysed\r\n\r\nMethods : A study was conducted on 40 cases of nasal polypi in a tertiary care hospital. 20 cases underwent co-ablation ass FESS and 20 using the microdebrider ass FESS.  \r\n\r\nResults : There was no statistically significant difference in surgical outcome for patients with either of methods. With Coablation ass FESS the comfort of doing surgery was better,saline irrigation gave better visualization and  blood loss was less .There was no need for the usage of tranexamic acid intra /post operatively in the co-ablation group .\r\n\r\nConclusion:The use of Co-ablation in endoscopic sinus surgery has the advantage of complete clearance of disease, uneventful intra operative course and better mucosal preservation &  post operative healing when compared to microdebrider in the treatment of nasal polyps.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '/public/upload/abstract/1da70df94af2f8841db3839a37b8254c.doc', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 09:51:58', '2025-11-10 09:52:01'),
(295, 'Sarit Negi', 'Saritasharmanegi86@gmail.com', '1177', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'NASAL POLYPOSIS-INDUCED UPPER AIRWAY OBSTRUCTION: EFFECT OF TREATMENTS ON CARDIOPULMONARY FUNCTIONS', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'AIM:\r\n\r\nTo evaluate the efficacy of various treatments of chronic rhino- sinusitis with nasal polyposis on cardiopulmonary functions.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\n\r\nA prospective, interventional, open-label, randomised study was conducted at the IGMC Shimla, involving 61 patients. Subjects were randomly assigned to either the medical or surgical group. The medical group received intranasal corticosteroids, while the surgical group underwent endoscopic sinus surgery. Cardiopulmonary parameters were assessed using spirometry and echocardiography at baseline, three months, and six months.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n\r\nBoth groups demonstrated improvements in SNOT24 scores and pulmonary function too. However, the surgical group exhibited more pronounced improvements. Endoscopic sinus surgery demonstrated superior efficacy in enhancing right ventricular functions compared to intranasal corticosteroids alone.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\n\r\nChronic rhino-sinusitis with nasal polyposis can significantly impair cardiopulmonary functions. Therefore, endoscopic sinus surgery emerges as a more effective treatment modality for alleviating cardiopulmonary dysfunction in such cases.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/8a34f08a23225867f38d965a093a87ce.doc', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 15:13:55', '2025-11-10 15:13:59'),
(296, 'payal verma', 'doctorwithpet@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000471', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Plasma Ablation Assisted Endoscopic Endonasal Transpterygoid Approach to Sphenoid Lateral Recess Cer', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction:\r\nCerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leaks from the lateral recess (LR) of the sphenoid sinus are usually spontaneous. LR is an extension of the sphenoid pneumatization into the pterygoid process. The endoscopic endonasal transpterygoid approach (EETPA) includes drilling of the pterygoid base for better access but with accompanying risk of injury to the vidian nerve (VN) and maxillary nerve (V2) \r\n Aim :\r\nLong term experience with plasma ablation in treating SLR defects via EETPA and presenting the outcomes in terms of objective assessment of the surgical field achieved, postoperative complications and success. \r\nCase Series :\r\n11 patients aged 40-70 years presented with CSF rhinorrhea .Diagnosis by  HRCT 0.75-mm cuts of PNS and MR cisternography . All cases were managed surgically .\r\nDiscussion: \r\nPlasma ablation–assisted EETPA provides superior hemostasis, visualization, and access through a single nostril while minimising complications and promoting faster healing for LR CSF leaks.\r\nConclusion :\r\nPlasma ablation assisted EETPA allows for a uninostril approach to the SLR, easy accessibility, and better visualization with clearer field, which allows appropriate repair, thus minimizing complications and preventing recurrence.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/b5019348f62d53da4dca7b932f062d45.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 17:54:11', '2025-11-10 17:54:15'),
(297, 'DR SHEELIA OUSEPH', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Endoscopic Approach to Skull Base Nasal Meningoencephaloceles: Review of Surgical Outcomes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction\r\nNasal meningoencephaloceles are rare condition where meninges and cranial contents herniate through congenital, traumatic or spontaneous defects in skull base into nasal cavity. Patients often present with clear nasal discharge, nasal obstruction and improper management can result in serious complications like meningitis and seizures. With advancements in endoscopic techniques minimally invasive approaches have become the preferred modality for repair.\r\n\r\nObjective\r\nThe aim of this study is to analyze our institutional experience in endoscopic management of nasal meningoencephaloceles and review our surgical outcomes.\r\n\r\nMethods\r\nA retrospective review of six patients diagnosed with skull base meningoencephaloceles and managed endoscopically at our centre between May 2024 and February 2025 was conducted. Data regarding demographic profile, clinical presentation, anatomical site of defect, surgical approaches, graft material and postoperative outcome were analyzed.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nOf six patients , three had frontoethmoidal and three had basal types of meningoencephaloceles. All underwent successful endoscopic transnasal repair with no complications over a follow up period of 9-12 months.\r\nConclusion\r\nEndoscopic management is safe, effective and minimally invasive with meticulous multilayer reconstruction and reliable defect closure with high success rates.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/50eeefeee2a514fef632b24dce0d6587.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 18:20:58', '2025-11-10 18:21:01'),
(298, 'Dr. Dhairya Malik', 'malik02dhairya@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000455', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'MAXILLO-FACIAL TRAUMA : A STUDY OF PREVALENCE ,CLINICAL PATTERN AND ITS MANAGEMENT', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'AIM : Maxillofacial injuries constitute a significant proportion of emergency room admissions and represent a growing public health concern, primarily due to the increasing number of road traffic accidents (RTAs) which often require multidisciplinary approaches.\r\nMETHODOLOGY : This prospective observational study was done to assess the prevalence, clinical patterns, etiology, and management strategies of maxillofacial fractures in patients presenting to a tertiary care centre in Bareilly. The parameters used were age, sex, time of incident, etiology, type of vehicle used with preventive measures, type of fractures, and treatment received. All patients underwent proper history taking, clinical examination, radiographic evaluation, and  3-D face reconstruction.\r\n RESULTS : 354 patients presented to ER, of which 104 were of maxillofacial injuries of which 63 underwent surgical corrections, and the rest were managed non-operatively. ORIF with IMF was performed for 44.4% of fractures, 38.1% of fractures were treated by ORIF + mini plate fixation.\r\nCONCLUSIONS : This study concluded that maxillofacial injuries are life-threatening in nature and  cause esthetic or functional deformities, which might lead to psychological, financial, and social costs for people. Identifying the etiology, epidemiology, and treatment plans of maxillofacial traumas is highly important. RTAs were found to be major cause of such injuries', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/f786ea3f13ed5d6b07d9d0c62ed5126a.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 20:47:35', '2025-11-10 20:47:39'),
(299, 'Dr.Sonali sharma', 'sonalisharma3720@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000494', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Endoscopic Optic Nerve Fenestration in Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension\r\nPresenting Author: \r\nDr. Sonali Sharma\r\nAim: \r\nTo evaluate the role and effectiveness of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration in preserving vision in patients with idiopathic intracranial hypertension.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA review of published literature and institutional experience was conducted. Data from recent meta-analyses and clinical studies organized in the ENT Department, IGMC Shimla, were analyzed to assess outcomes of endoscopic optic nerve fenestration and decompression. Parameters studied included improvement in visual acuity, visual field, and headache relief, as well as reported complications. Comparative evaluation of transnasal and transconjunctival approaches was also performed..\r\nResults: \r\nMajority of patients showed improvement in visual symptoms and headache. Transnasal endoscopic approach demonstrated good results with minimal complications like diplopia and CSF leak.\r\nConclusions: \r\nEndoscopic optic nerve fenestration is a safe and effective option for managing idiopathic intracranial hypertension. The transnasal route offers better visualization and low morbidity.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/d9167dc8aa0f85eab36cad0362dc047c.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 20:55:47', '2025-11-10 20:55:50'),
(300, 'Disha Saini', 'disha.saini13@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000557', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Pterygopalatine fossa schwannoma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Pterygopalatine Fossa Schwannoma: A Rare Case Report\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Disha Saini\r\nAim:\r\nTo report a rare case of schwannoma arising from the pterygopalatine fossa, highlighting its clinical presentation, diagnostic evaluation, surgical management, and histopathological confirmation.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA 40-year-old female presented with complaints of dull, intermittent left-sided frontal headache for 1 year, without any other nasal or visual complaints. Clinical examination revealed a left deviated nasal septum with no external or ocular abnormalities. Contrast-enhanced CT scan of paranasal sinuses showed a non-enhancing soft tissue density lesion (12 × 20 × 18 mm) in the left pterygopalatine fossa, causing widening of the pterygomaxillary fissure and minimal scalloping of the posterior wall of maxillary sinus. The patient underwent endoscopic excision under general anaesthesia via endonasal approach.\r\nResults:\r\nA well-defined, firm, whitish tumour mass measuring 2×2cm was excised completely from the left pterygopalatine fossa. Histopathological examination revealed characteristic hypercellular Antoni A and hypocellular Antoni B areas with Verocay bodies, confirming the diagnosis of ancient schwannoma. Immunohistochemistry showed strong S-100 positivity. Postoperative recovery was uneventful, and there was no recurrence on follow-up.\r\nConclusion:\r\nPterygopalatine fossa schwannomas are extremely rare, with only a few cases reported in the literature. Accurate preoperative imaging aids in localisation and surgical planning. The endoscopic endonasal approach offers excellent exposure with minimal morbidity, making it the preferred technique for the complete excision of such lesions. Therefore, awareness of this rare case is essential for otorhinolaryngologists to ensure timely diagnosis and optimal management.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/c3fd0d08abbefd0291c1c4300e835092.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 21:10:36', '2025-11-10 21:10:39'),
(301, 'M.PERIYASAMY', 'Periyasamybalaji26@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000500', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Maxillary sinus beyond mucormycosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE \r\n Maxillary sinus beyond mucormycosis \r\n\r\nAUTHOR \r\n DR M.PERIYASAMY \r\nOBJECTIVE \r\nTo study clinical spectrum of mucormycosis involving maxillary sinus and beyond \r\nTo evaluate treatment modalities and outcome \r\nMETHODS   \r\nPatient with symptoms suggestive of rhinoorbital mucormycosis are evaluated with dne ,koh , hpe and culture sensitivity done ,ct pns done  with mri to assess extent of disease then planned for surgery \r\nRESULTS \r\nMaxillary sinus is primary focus in all cases 75./. Had extension beyond this at the time of presentation, combined surgical and medical management has yield best outcomes \r\nCONCLUSION \r\nMucormycosis of maxillary sinus is rapidly progressive disease early diagnosis &aggressive debridement and amphotericin B is cornerstone of management \r\nAwareness and multidisciplinary approach improves survival', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/bda0646342a2d97314a4772b2b125e23.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 22:14:06', '2025-11-10 22:14:10'),
(302, 'Dr. VIJAY KUMAR', 'dr.vijay11176@aiimspatna.org', 'RHIN0000504', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Frontal Sinusotomy-DRAF 3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Frontal Sinusotomy-DRAF 3 Video Sessions', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/852c4559f0c0f60f82b1ab778d1c2fb2.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 22:29:18', '2025-11-10 22:29:21'),
(303, 'Sowparnika T R', 'sowbutr@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000560', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'A RANDOMIZED CONTROL TRIAL ON THE EFFECTIVENESS OF ANTIFUNGAL AND STEROID NASAL DOUCHING IN AFRS: A ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE: A RANDOMIZED CONTROL TRIAL ON THE EFFECTIVENESS OF ANTIFUNGAL AND STEROID NASAL DOUCHING IN AFRS: A CLINICAL, RADIOLOGICAL AND BIOCHEMICAL CO-RELATION\r\n\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR:DR SOWPARNIKA TR\r\n\r\nAIM:TO LOOK FOR ANY ADDED ADVANTAGE OF PRE- OPERATIVE STEROID NASAL DOUCHING IN AFRS\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY:35 AFRS PATIENTS ARE RANDOMIZED INTO TWO ARMS –ARM A GIVEN STEROID AND ANTIFUNGAL, ARM B GIVEN STEROID, ANTIFUNGAL AND BUDESONIDE NASAL DOUCHES, THE RESPONSE ARE COMPARED AT BASELINE AND AT 6 WEEKS BY CLINICAL, RADIOLOGICAL AND SEROLOGICAL PARAMETERS. CLINICAL PARAMETERS INCLUDE SNOT22 AND MELTZER SCORE, RADIOLOGICAL -LUND MACKEY AND 20 POINT SCORE, SEROLOGICAL – ABSOLUTE EOSINOPHIL COUNTS, SPECIFIC AND TOTAL IGE LEVELS, SERUM AND NASAL DOUCHES GALACTOMANNAN LEVELS. PATIENTS ARE MONITORED WITH S CORTISOL AND LFT VALUES.\r\n\r\n\r\nRESULTS: TILL NOW ARM B SHOWS MORE RESPONSE COMPARED TO ARM A IN SNOT-22, MELTZER SCORE. RADIOLOGICAL SCORES WERE MORE OR LESS COMPARABLE IN BOTH ARMS POST TREATMENT. ARM B SHOWED GREATER REDUCTIONS THAN ARM A IN BIOCHEMICAL PARAMETERS.\r\n\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION: THERE IS NO ADDED ADVANTAGE OF BUDESONIDE NASAL DOUCHES IN AFRS PATIENTS IN REDUCTION OF CLINICO-RADIOLOGICAL PARAMETERS. HOWEVER PREOPERATIVE THERAPY WITH STEROID AND ANTIFUNGAL SHOWS AN OVERALL DECREASE IN DISEASE BURDEN, DURATION OF SURGERY, LESS INTRAOPERATIVE COMPLICATIONS AND BLOOD LOSS', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/8a2b888263f84343c355898d95b84d84.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:31:18', '2025-11-10 23:31:22'),
(304, 'Payal verma', 'Doctorwithpet@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000471', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Plasma Ablation Assisted Endoscopic Endonasal Transpterygoid Approach to Sphenoid Lateral Recess Cer', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'This video demonstrates the transpterygoid approach to the lateral recess of sphenoid sinus for a CSF leak.\r\nThis approach has a higher success rate because of the head on approach and ease of instrumentation. Depending on the type of lateral recess the vidian can be sacrificed or preserved and contents of PPF lateralised.', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/66abfd4b2af598f23efaf1a4afa98d8a.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:33:41', '2025-11-10 23:33:45'),
(305, 'Dr Ekansh Sood', 'Ekanshsood@yahoo.com', '1200', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'INFRATEMPORAL FOSSA SCHWANOMMA RESECTION USING MAXILLARY SWING : A NOVEL APPROACH', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A CASE OF INFRATEMPORAL FOSSA SCHWANOMMA RESECTION USING MAXILLARY SWING : A NOVEL APPROACH \r\nIntroduction : The infratemporal fossa) is a deep facial space behind the zygomatic bone and the maxilla.Infratemporal fossa tumours comprise of 5% of head and neck cancers, reflecting their nature of rarity. Trigeminal schwannoma and meningioma are more common of all ITF tumours. The surgical anatomy of the infratemporal fossa (ITF) as well as the tumour resection in this region remain a challenge for head and neck surgeons due to its proximity to cranial nerves  .CASE : 40 year old female KAMLESH presented with complaint of right side nasal obstruction, and double vision since 6 months On examination: 1. Face- right eye protrusion 2.Decreased finger insinuation in right infra orbital margin   3. On A/R-mass in right nasal cavity . Investigation and Management :Radiology : -4.9 x 4.9 x 5.2 cm epicentered at pterygopalatine fossa, pterygomaxillary fissure and right masticator space.Patient was planned for surgery and Excision of infratemporal mass by maxillary swing approach was done.Post op HPE was of Shwanoma Discussion : Infratemporal fossa is area of skull base. The contents of the fossa -lateral and medial pterygoid muscles-the maxillary artery and its branches-the pterygoid venous plexus-maxillary veins -branches of the mandibular nerveSchwannomas are benign, encapsulated peripheral nerve tumours.Approximately 25 to 45% of schwannomas occur in the head and neck region.Schwannomas limited to the infratemporal fossa are rare lesions that may also involve the maxillary sinus, the orbit and the retropharyngeal spaceOnly a few cases have been reported and the reported ones presented from the 2nd to 5th decades of life with equal distribution for both sex.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/8c64a7d15af7bf85b5c455f4804235a5.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:34:21', '2025-11-10 23:34:26'),
(306, 'Sahaj Gulati', 'sahaj.gulati99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000456', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Atypical presentation of cellular neurofibroma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Abstract\r\nBackground:\r\nCellular neurofibroma is a rare benign variant of neurofibroma characterized by increased cellularity and reduced collagenous stroma. Its occurrence in the nose and paranasal sinuses (PNS) is exceedingly uncommon, and due to its cellular features, it may mimic malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumor (MPNST) both clinically and histologically. Awareness of this entity in unusual sites such as the sinonasal region is crucial to ensure correct diagnosis and management.\r\nObjective:\r\nTo describe the clinicopathologic and immunohistochemical characteristics of a cellular neurofibroma arising in the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses, emphasizing its differentiation from malignant counterparts.\r\nMethods:\r\nA detailed histopathological examination of the resected specimen was performed along with immunohistochemical staining for S-100, SOX10, and CD34 to confirm Schwann cell lineage. Clinical and radiologic findings were correlated.\r\nResults:\r\nThe lesion presented as a firm, painless nasal mass causing nasal obstruction and facial fullness. CT and MRI revealed a well-circumscribed soft tissue mass involving the nasal cavity and extending into adjacent paranasal sinuses without bony destruction. Microscopically, the tumor showed densely packed spindle cells with elongated, wavy nuclei arranged in short fascicles and whorls. There was mild nuclear pleomorphism, absence of necrosis, and low mitotic activity. Immunohistochemistry demonstrated strong diffuse positivity for S-100 and SOX10, with variable CD34 expression, consistent with cellular neurofibroma.\r\nConclusion:\r\nCellular neurofibroma of the nose and PNS is a rare benign tumor that can closely resemble low-grade MPNST. Recognition of its histopathologic and immunohistochemical profile is essential for accurate diagnosis. Complete surgical excision is curative, and recurrence is rare. Early identification prevents unnecessary radical treatment and ensures excellent prognosis.\r\nKeywords: Cellular neurofibroma, nasal cavity, paranasal sinuses, benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor, S-100, SOX10', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/af663e433b1ee716b616f27d5497f24e.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-10 23:38:07', '2025-11-10 23:38:10'),
(307, 'Sowparnika T R', 'sowbutr@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000560', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Sinonasal Teratocarcinosarcoma — The Great Masquerader of the Nasal Cavity', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SINONASAL TERATOCARCINOSARCOMA — THE GREAT MASQUERADER OF THE NASAL CAVITY\r\n\r\n\r\nØ	52 year male presented to OPD with 4 months history of  nasal obstruction and epistaxis\r\nØ	Local examination –pale- reddish nodular mass\r\nØ	Biopsy: SMARCA 4 deficient sinonasal teratocarcinosarcoma\r\nØ	Diagnosis-SINONASAL TERATOCARCINOSARCOMA\r\nØ	Plan- ENDOSCOPIC EXCISION\r\nØ	Endoscopic excision done with margins taken all around the tumor at its site of attachment\r\nØ	Margins taken one layer additional\r\nØ	Discussion- \r\nØ	Rare, highly aggressive malignant tumour containing mixed epithelial, mesenchymal and primitive neuroepithelial elements\r\nØ	Triple malignancy\r\nØ	Poor prognosis\r\nØ	Challenges- heterogeneous morphology and high recurrence ratePredilection for anterior skull base location\r\nØ	Disease of middle age that commonly affects men\r\nØ	Conclusion-\r\nØ	Rare but distinct sinonasal malignancy requiring high index of suspicion.\r\nØ	Multidisciplinary management offers best survival advantage.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/aa07888421ed3adf351b40c9cd6f3aae.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-11 00:33:03', '2025-11-11 00:33:07'),
(308, 'DR SHEELIA OUSEPH', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', 'sheelia.ouseph@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Surgical Challenges and Experience in Managing Cases of Radkowski Stage IIIb Juvenile Nasopharyngeal', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo share surgical experiences and challenges encountered in managing two cases of advanced (Radkowski IIIb) juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma (JNA) with dual carotid supply, emphasizing approach selection and intraoperative strategies.\r\nMethodology:\r\nBoth patients underwent preoperative digital subtraction angiography, which demonstrated tumor vascularity from external and internal carotid branches. Selective embolization of external carotid feeders was performed. One case was managed endoscopically, while the other required an open approach with endoscopic assistance for residual clearance.\r\nResults:\r\nComplete excision was achieved in both patients with smooth postoperative recovery and no recurrence on follow-up. Challenges included controlling bleeding from internal carotid feeders, accessing deep extensions, and preserving neurovascular structures. Embolization effectively reduced intraoperative blood loss and facilitated safer dissection.\r\nConclusion:\r\nRadkowski IIIb JNA with dual carotid supply pose significant surgical challenges. Individualized planning, selective embolization, and adaptable surgical approaches are key to achieving complete clearance with minimal morbidity.', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/e96794c1f4418f0cedecb4d6b56b8603.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-11 07:56:40', '2025-11-11 07:56:44'),
(309, 'Tanisha Gautam', 'tanishaaaa64@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000454', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'MORPHOMETRIC ANALYSIS AND DEGREE OF SATISFACTION OF NASAL PROFILES IN YOUNG MEDICAL STUDENTS IN NORT', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The current research was conducted to complete a morphometric examination of the nasal forms and evaluate the level of satisfaction in the young medical pupils in Northern India to provide reference data on anthropometry, cosmetic, and reconstructive nasal surgery. One hundred medical students (46 males and 54 females) aged 18-25 years and studying at SRMS Institute of Medical Sciences, Bareilly took part in the study. To measure nasal height (n-sn) and nasal width (acr-acr) that were used in calculating the nasal index, standard anthropometric methods were used and a digital sliding Vernier caliper was used. The findings showed a mean nasal height of 47.95 mm, mean nasal width of 30.59 mm, and mean nasal index of 63.82 with most of the sample (77%) being of leptorrhine (fine) nose type. Males were also found to have much higher nasal indices than females (67.79 vs 60.44; p = 0.0004) which was evidence of sexual dimorphism. Also, the participants who were not satisfied with the appearance of their nose had much bigger nasal indices (71.21 vs 63.82; p < 0.0001) and desired smaller noses. Comparisons with other ethnic groups revealed that there were regional differences in nasal morphology in which the Northern Indian sample exhibited comparatively narrow nasal morphology. Finally, the research points out notable sexual dimorphism in nasal anthropometry in young Northern Indians and stresses that those with wider noses complain of having lesser satisfaction with nasal appearance. The results offer important background information to practitioners in the cosmetic, reconstructive and forensic practice of nasal inspection and surgery.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/a60defa09aeb1ce319b6364060360850.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-11 09:33:45', '2025-11-11 09:33:48'),
(310, 'Dr.V.J.Vikram', 'dr.vjvikram@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000568', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Typical and Atypical Angiofibroma Surgery', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'This video presentation is about the surgical excision of typical (Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma) and atypical  (Extra Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma arising from right nasal septum)', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/32a8591669467969aa37317f13f6c6e9.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-11 21:14:53', '2025-11-11 21:14:57'),
(311, 'SaranKumar', 'saranstanlean@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000584', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ENDOSCOPIC EXCISION OF JUVENILE NASOPHARYNGHEAL ANGIOFIBROMA', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A 11 year old boy presented with a episode of profuse right sided epistaxis. on evaluation, it was diagnosed to be JNA with classical ptertgo maxillary fissure widening. This video show four handed approach for endoscopic excision of JNA', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/7cb58e67ecbacca81cea7dc6ffb9350d.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 07:38:42', '2025-11-13 07:38:46'),
(312, 'SaranKumar', 'saranstanlean@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000584', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ENDOSCOPIC EXCISION OF JUVENILE NASOPHARYNGHEAL ANGIOFIBROMA', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A 11 year old boy presented with a episode of profuse right sided epistaxis. on evaluation, it was diagnosed to be JNA with classical ptertgo maxillary fissure widening. This video show four handed approach for endoscopic excision of JNA', NULL, '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/461358a1b4ff6e3579dbc0b8187acd57.docx', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 07:38:44', '2025-11-13 07:38:48'),
(313, 'Lisa Mary Cherian', 'lisamarycherian@gmail.com', 'lisamarycherian@gmail.com', '[\"Dr.I.S.Gupta Award presentation for Senior Consultant\"]', 'Nasal cytology in chronic rhinosinusitis endotyping.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background:\r\nEndotyping in chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS)  by structured histopathology enables targeted therapy and improving patient outcomes. Nasal cytology is a lesser invasive tests which counts the different cell types to reflect the histologic pattern. The current study analyses the nasal cytology in CRSwNP, CRSsNP patients and controls among Indian population which has not be reported previously.\r\n\r\nMaterials and methods:\r\n\r\nAn observational prospective study was conducted on CRS patients and appropriate controls to determine the nasal cytogram by middle meatal nasal brushings. Nasal cytology sampling was done under endoscopic guidance and smears studied based on a four-point grading scale.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n \r\nThe study recruited 40 patients each in control, CRSsNP and CRSwNP groups. The SNOT 22, VAS and LKS showed significantly higher score among the CRS compared to controls. The number of patients having higher grade of eosinophil count (p=0.002) and neutrophil count were significantly higher in CRS compared to control (p=0.031). \r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nThe study suggests that Indian CRS endotyping shows both eosinophilic and neutrophilic cells, and this was highest among CRSwNP. Nasal cytology a potential complementary diagnostic tool in CRS endotyping, however, requires further studies.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '/public/upload/abstract/f0125bc735c6d9b36880362b4f3765a3.docx', '', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 08:55:19', '2025-11-13 08:55:22'),
(314, 'Dr. Pon kaushikan', 'kaushikaghi@gmail.com', 'kaushikaghi@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, '“Sealing the Silent Leak”:The Rare intersection of Sternberg canal defect causing csf leaks', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction:\r\n\r\nThe lateral craniopharyngeal canal, also known as Sternberg’s canal, is a congenital defect located in the postero-lateral wall of the sphenoid sinus. It arises from incomplete fusion of ossification centers during embryological development. Though uncommon in adults, persistence of this canal may serve as a pathway for spontaneous cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leakage, occasionally accompanied by herniation of intracranial contents.\r\n\r\nBecause of its anatomical proximity to vital neurovascular structures—including the internal carotid artery, optic nerve, and cavernous sinus—identification and surgical repair of defects in this region are technically demanding. As a result, diagnosis may be delayed, and management often requires advanced endoscopic skull-base techniques to ensure safe and effective closure.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\n\r\n4 Patients presenting with spontaneous CSF leak , one of the patients underwent prior endoscopic surgery for the csf leak with recurrent csf rhinorrhea were further evaluated clinically and radiologically. High-resolution CT and MRI of the paranasal sinuses were used to identify the site of skull-base defect, characterize encephalocele and plan the surgical approach.\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent endoscopic endonasal csf leak repair under general anaesthesia. A trans-nasal trans-sphenoid approach was performed to access the lateral sphenoid recess. In cases with limited exposure or laterally placed defects, a trans-pterygoid extension could be  utilized to improve visualization and access.\r\n\r\nOutcomes:\r\n\r\nAll  4 patients had successful closure of the CSF leak using a multilayered endoscopic repair technique. Postoperatively, no recurrence of CSF leak  was noted during follow-up. The endoscopic approach ensured minimal morbidity, no major complications, and a rapid recovery with favorable clinical outcomes\r\n\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n\r\nA total of 4  patients diagnosed to be CSF rhinorrhea originating from Sternberg’s canal were included. One patient had undergone prior endoscopic repair elsewhere and presented with recurrence.\r\n\r\nAll patients underwent endoscopic endonasal repair with multilayer closure using fat, fascia, and a naso-septal flap\r\n\r\nPostoperatively, all patients had complete resolution of CSF rhinorrhea, with no recurrence observed on follow-up. No major complications were reported, and all patients demonstrated good recovery.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/bcc26350a001a3c96c51d450f6749caa.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 14:19:04', '2025-11-13 14:19:08'),
(315, 'DR.PON KAUSHIKAN', 'kaushikaghi@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000589', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cranial Defect’s Deadliest Partner- CSF Rhinorrhea With Trephine Syndrome', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'INTRODUCTION:\r\nTrephine syndrome (also called sunken skin flap syndrome) is a rare but significant complication that occurs after decompressive craniectomy. It results from atmospheric pressure being transmitted directly to the brain, causing distortion of cerebral tissue, impaired CSF dynamics, and reduced cortical perfusion. When CSF hypovolemia coexists—as in cases of persistent CSF rhinorrhea—neurological deterioration can be accelerated. Recognising CSF leak in patients with large cranial defects is essential, as it can worsen intracranial pressure gradients and delay recovery.\r\n\r\nCASE PRESENTATION:\r\nA 33-year-old male sustained a road traffic accident and was diagnosed with epidural hematoma, bilateral frontal contusions, and frontal bone fractures. He underwent bifrontal decompressive craniectomy and required 7 days of postoperative ventilatory support. On the 10th postoperative day, he developed persistent CSF rhinorrhea despite maximal medical therapy.\r\nHe was referred to our department with active CSF leak .Clinical evaluation and imaging (CT PNS and MR cisternography) demonstrated continued CSF leak with associated intracranial pressure changes. Surgical repair was performed. Postoperative endoscopic findings on days 1, 2 and 7 showed good healing and cessation of the leak.\r\n\r\nDISCUSSION:\r\nTrephine syndrome develops due to direct transmission of atmospheric pressure through the cranial defect, collapse of the subarachnoid space, turbulence of CSF flow, and reduced cortical blood perfusion. Co-existing CSF rhinorrhea further aggravates this negative pressure gradient, predisposing to neurological decline. Patients may present with headache, dizziness, cognitive changes, irritability, and motor deficits known as motor trephine syndrome.\r\nDefinitive management is early cranioplasty to restore physiological pressure dynamics. Adjunctive measures such as head-down positioning and forehead compression (“turban dressing”) may be used temporarily until surgical correction is possible.\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nPersistent CSF rhinorrhea following decompressive craniectomy requires prompt evaluation, as it can precipitate or worsen trephine syndrome. Surgical repair of the leak followed by timely cranioplasty is essential for symptom resolution and neurological recovery. Long-term follow-up is advised due to the risk of recurrent CSF leak and complications associated with large cranial defects.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/e3b627104c9dd505e9eab4377aa89f5f.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 18:17:33', '2025-11-13 18:17:37'),
(316, 'thrupthi s', 'thrupthisubbanna@gmail.com', 'thrupthisubbanna@gmail.com', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'From Crisis to Clarity: Visual Recovery After Endoscopic Management of Pituitary Apoplexy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Abstract\r\nBackground: Pituitary apoplexy is an acute neuroendocrine emergency characterized by sudden hemorrhage or infarction within the pituitary gland, often in a pre-existing adenoma. Owing to its close anatomical relationship with the sphenoid sinus and optic apparatus, ENT surgeons—especially those trained in endoscopic skull-base approaches—play a vital role in timely diagnosis and management.\r\nCase Presentation: We present a case of a 39-year-old female who arrived with rapidly progressive blurring of vision in left eye for 10 days. Clinical examination revealed right temporal field defect and partial ptosis. Endocrine evaluation demonstrated hypothyroidism. MRI Brain showed a large heterogenous cystic mass lesion of size 3*2.7*2.2cm seen in sella with suprasella extension and mass effect on chiasma on left side-pituitary macroadenoma / ?pituitary apoplexy.CT PNS showed evidence of well defined iso to hypodense lesion measuring 2.3*2.6*3.3cm in the sella region with peripheral calcification- suggestive of pituitary macroadenoma with mass effect. After stabilization with high-dose intravenous corticosteroids, the patient underwent endoscopic endonasal transsphenoidal hypophysectomy performed by the ENT skull-base team. The procedure achieved effective evacuation of hemorrhagic components and decompression of the optic apparatus. Postoperatively, the patient exhibited marked visual recovery, complete pain resolution, and stable hormonal status with appropriate replacement therapy. Follow-up imaging confirmed adequate decompression and no residual mass effect.\r\nConclusion: This case underscores the crucial role of ENT surgeons in the multidisciplinary management of pituitary apoplexy, particularly through minimally invasive endoscopic skull-base approaches. Early recognition, prompt steroid administration, and timely surgical intervention significantly improve visual and endocrine outcomes. The case reinforces the evolving contribution of endoscopic transsphenoidal surgery in emergency pituitary pathology.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/1e039353e80b7418c02964912515d2d2.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 19:35:09', '2025-11-13 19:35:13'),
(317, 'A. Elakiya', 'elakiyadurai98@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000571', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Return on Pott - case study on clinical presentation and surgical management of Pott\'s Puffy tum', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TITLE\r\n“The Return of Pott”-A case report on clinical presentation and surgical management of Pott\'s puffy tumor\r\n\r\n\r\nAUTHOR NAME \r\nDr. A.Elakiya\r\n\r\nOBJECTIVE\r\nPott\'s puffy tumor refers to subperiosteal abscess of forehead, associated frontal bone osteomyelitis ,its a rare condition usually associated with ethmoidal sinusitis, forehead trauma , insect bite. The outcome of this study is to evaluate the clinical presentation , investigations and management of patients diagnosed with Potts puffy tumor \r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY \r\nThis is a case report of a 49 year old male who presented with symptoms of  swelling and pain  over frontal region  , further imaging techniques including CT angiography , MRI was done to assess the extent of infection and surgically managed with incision and drainage ,frontal trephination ,sinusotomy . Post operatively follow up done at 2nd , 4th , 6th week to look for symptomatic improvement. \r\n\r\nRESULTS \r\nThe spectrum of presentation both clinically and radiologically is studied. Radiological investigations are used to assess the extent of swelling, to look for underlying bony erosions Challenges in surgery are studied, microbiological results helps in choosing appropriate antibiotics Follow up of the patient done to look for recurrence \r\n\r\nCONCLUSION \r\nPott\'s puffy tumor is a clinical diagnosis supported by radiological imaging presents with forehead swelling and frontal headache. Definitive treatment is broad spectrum antibiotics, frontal sinusotomy and trephination.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/b0d0d39c2160b0cdde3d7710350fb5ef.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-13 21:25:19', '2025-11-13 21:25:22'),
(318, 'H Zaiba Fathima', 'zaibafthm29@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000583', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CAN A GUEST IN THE NASAL CAVITY CAUSE SO MUCH HAVOC?', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction\r\n\r\n              Ectopic supernumerary teeth in the nasal cavity are rare, occurring with an incidence of approximately 0.1–1%.\r\n\r\n-  Case presentation\r\n\r\n             A 41-year-old male patient, with a history of facial trauma, presented with nasal obstruction and recurrent blood-stained nasal discharge.\r\n\r\n-  Physical examination showed a deviated septum and a white mass in the right nasal cavity.\r\n\r\n-  Diagnostic nasal endoscopy revealed a polypoidal, granulomatous, pyogenic mass over the caudal septum. \r\n\r\n-  CT imaging confirmed the diagnosis of an ectopic tooth in the right nasal floor, along with septal deviation and hypertrophy of the right inferior turbinate.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSurgical extraction was carried out using a modified Caldwell-Luc operation. The mass was removed successfully, minimizing complications by employing careful mucoperiosteal techniques.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n-  Outcome\r\n\r\n                   Postoperative recovery was uneventful with resolution of symptoms. The patient experienced no major complications such as septal perforation or naso-oral fistula.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n-  Discussion\r\n\r\n                 Intranasal supernumerary teeth arise from abnormal development of dental tissue, possibly due to hyperactivity of the dental lamina, trauma, infections, craniofacial anomalies (like cleft lip/palate), or genetic syndromes.\r\n\r\n-  Management\r\n\r\nEndoscopic Approach\r\n\r\n•Preferred for most intranasal supernumerary teeth. Ideal when the tooth is superficial and not deeply embedded.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nModified Caldwell-Luc Operation\r\n\r\n•Used when the tooth is located deep in the nasal floor or maxillary sinus, when associated with extensive pathology such as a cyst or chronic infection, where endoscopic access is limited.\r\n\r\nIntraoral/Nasal Combined Approach\r\n\r\n•When teeth extend from the palate or incisive canal into the nasal cavity, or are impacted partly within the maxilla. Collaboration between oral and ENT surgeons may be needed for complex cases.\r\n\r\n- Conclusion\r\n\r\nIntranasal supernumerary teeth should be considered in patients with unexplained nasal obstruction and epistaxis\r\n\r\n- Keywords\r\n\r\nEpistaxis , ectopic tooth, Modified Cadwell luc operation,', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/113ad5b1dbc1afdb1a20448caed5052b.doc', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 12:37:16', '2025-11-14 12:37:21');
INSERT INTO `rh_abstract_old` (`id`, `name`, `email`, `reg_id`, `catergory_id`, `title_0`, `title_1`, `title_2`, `title_3`, `title_4`, `note`, `note_1`, `note_2`, `note_3`, `note_4`, `file`, `file_1`, `file_2`, `file_3`, `file_4`, `mail_send`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(319, 'Dr.Maria Amirutha', 'mariaamirutha99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000586', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '“The Fungal Sinusitis That Wasn’t: Unveiling a Silent Carcinoma”', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Background:\r\nSinonasal malignancies are uncommon and often mimic benign or infective conditions, leading to diagnostic delays. Fungal sinusitis is a frequent differential in unilateral maxillary sinus disease, and radiological overlap can further complicate early detection. This case highlights the importance of maintaining high suspicion and performing timely histopathological evaluation when clinical progression seems atypical.\r\n\r\nCase Presentation:\r\nA 57-year-old male presented with a 20-day history of thick, yellowish, blood-stained left-sided nasal discharge and watering of the left eye. There was no history of trauma, dental infection, or visual disturbances. Clinical examination revealed thick purulent discharge in the left nasal cavity, left maxillary tenderness, and deviated nasal septum to the right, with no neck nodes or facial swelling.\r\n\r\nDiagnostic Workup:\r\nDiagnostic nasal endoscopy showed medialised uncinate process, concha bullosa, and discharge in the middle meatus. CT PNS demonstrated complete soft-tissue opacity of the left maxillary sinus, extension into the nasal cavity, widened infundibulum, and osteomeatal complex obstruction, findings initially suggestive of fungal sinusitis. No intraorbital or buccal space involvement was noted.\r\n\r\nIntervention:\r\nThe patient underwent endoscopic polypectomy under GA, during which fungal debris and polypoidal tissue were removed using a microdebrider. As the procedure progressed, a deeper fleshy mass was visualised within the left maxillary antrum. This was excised and sent for histopathology.\r\n\r\nOutcome:\r\nHistopathological examination confirmed carcinoma ex-sinonasal papilloma – squamous cell carcinoma (non-keratinising type), explaining the atypical features and persistent symptoms.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nThis case illustrates how sinonasal malignancy may masquerade as fungal or inflammatory sinusitis. Even when imaging favours a benign diagnosis, intraoperative suspicion and routine biopsy remain essential for identifying hidden malignancy and guiding appropriate management.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/2f4ed69efebdc1985ef3f57630d46f25.doc', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 12:47:27', '2025-11-14 12:47:31'),
(320, 'Dr. Pooja N kabbannavar', 'poojakolimi@gmail.com', 'RHINO00497', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A rare case report of Nasopharyngeal lymphoma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Title:\r\nA rare case report of Nasopharyngeal lymphoma\r\nIntroduction\r\nExtra nodal Lymphomas are very rare accounting for 25–30% of the cases. Occurrence of NHL in Waldeyer’s region is 16–43%. Most frequently affected sites are tonsils, base of tongue and nasopharynx. \r\n\r\nCase presentation\r\n48year old female presented to us with a complaint of nasal obstruction, snoring, nasal discharge since 1 year. On diagnostic nasal endoscopy (DNE) fleshy mass in nasopharynx obliterating the choana.\r\n\r\nInvestigation:\r\nCECT PNS shows well defined hypodense soft tissue lesion measuring 3.5cm ×2.8cm is seen in the posterio- superior region of Nasopharynx\r\nImmunohistochemistry (IHC) –strongly positive for CD20, CD21, CD5\r\nTreatment:\r\nPatient posted for nasal endoscopic biopsy.\r\nHPE -A diffusely scattered lymphoid cells with vesicular nuclei and scantycytoplasm.Infiltartion of Atypical cells in stroma.\r\nDiscussion:\r\nLymphomas are classified as NHL and HL (Hodgkin’s Lymphoma). NHL is usually a nodal disease [1]. Extranodal NHL diseases involving head and neck region are heterogeneous in origin. 90% lymphomas are NHL and specifically B cell type. Occurrence of NHL in Tonsillar region is 51% and in nasopharynx is 35% . Immunohistochemistry, CECT, MRI, PET-CT should be done to rule out other site of involvement. Biopsy and followed by HPE report, treatment is planned accordingly.\r\nConclusion:\r\nNasopharyngeal lymphoma although rare. Early diagnosis and treatment will help in improving prognosis and treatment outcomes of the patients.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/a785cb5cc5701e2205d38ab83755ad0e.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 17:16:17', '2025-11-14 17:16:21'),
(321, 'Dhivyanka.M', 'dhivyankamadan@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000600', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Comparative CT and Quantitative Endoscopic Evaluation of Eosinophilic and Non-Eosinophilic Chronic R', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Comparative CT and Quantitative Endoscopic Evaluation of Eosinophilic and Non-Eosinophilic Chronic Rhinosinusitis: A Prospective Study\r\nPresenting Author: Dr. Dhivyanka M\r\nAim: Chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS) is an inflammatory disease of the nasal and paranasal mucosa. Differentiating eosinophilic (ECRS) from non-eosinophilic CRS (NECRS) is essential due to variations in severity, recurrence, and treatment response.\r\nObjective: To compare radiological and endoscopic severity of ECRS and NECRS using Lund–Mackay and Lund–Kennedy scoring systems.\r\nMethods: A prospective cross-sectional study of 48 CRS patients was conducted, classified into ECRS and NECRS based on nasal smear eosinophilia. CT paranasal sinuses were graded by the Lund–Mackay system, and diagnostic nasal endoscopy findings were scored using the Lund–Kennedy scale.\r\nResults: ECRS showed significantly higher mean Lund–Mackay (12.67 ± 3.25) and Lund–Kennedy (7.96 ± 2.23) scores compared to NECRS (6.42 ± 2.8 and 4.42 ± 1.97, respectively; p < 0.001). Ethmoidal and osteomeatal complex opacification predominated in ECRS, while NECRS showed more maxillary involvement.\r\nConclusion: CT and endoscopic scoring reliably differentiate ECRS from NECRS. ECRS presents with greater sinus opacification and mucosal inflammation, emphasizing the role of quantitative imaging and endoscopic evaluation in CRS endotyping.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/acb89a6fb061ead8838ea37ab6054cb5.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 20:58:44', '2025-11-14 20:58:47'),
(322, 'shaheera tarnooom', 'shaheera.siraj@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000601', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'The Sinus Snare – When the Eye Becomes the Messenger', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Abstract\r\nTitle\r\nThe Sinus Snare – When the Eye Becomes the Messenger\r\nPresenting Author\r\nDr. Shaheera Tarnoom.S\r\nAim\r\nTo highlight the atypical presentation, diagnostic challenges, and surgical outcomes of isolated sphenoid sinusitis presenting with visual symptoms, particularly in diabetic patients.\r\nMethodology\r\nTwo middle-aged female patients with long-standing Type 2 diabetes presented with visual disturbances such as diplopia, blurring of vision, and periorbital pain, without nasal complaints. Clinical examination, diagnostic nasal endoscopy, CT and MRI imaging were performed. Both underwent Functional Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (FESS) after multidisciplinary evaluation. Intraoperative samples were subjected to KOH mount, culture, and histopathology.\r\nResults\r\nImaging revealed isolated sphenoid and posterior ethmoid sinus involvement in both cases. One patient demonstrated fungal elements consistent with Aspergillus. Post-operative recovery was favourable, with complete resolution of diplopia and improvement in visual acuity in both patients. No post-operative complications or recurrence were observed on follow-up.\r\nConclusions\r\nOrbital manifestations in diabetic patients may represent occult sinus disease. Early diagnosis through imaging and prompt surgical management are crucial to prevent progression to orbital apex syndrome or fulminant fungal sinusitis. The eye can indeed serve as a vital messenger for underlying sinonasal pathology.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/c938dbafb11ae3898efe59263df3107a.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-14 22:45:09', '2025-11-14 22:45:12'),
(323, 'Vasamsetty revanth manohar', 'Revanthmanohar89@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000588', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Clinical Predictors of Symptom Improvement Following Eustachian Tube Balloon Dilation', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ABSTRACT\r\nTITLE- \r\nClinical Predictors of Symptom Improvement Following Eustachian Tube Balloon Dilation\r\n\r\nAUTHOR NAME -V.Revanth Manohar\r\n\r\nAIM- This study aims to identify clinical predictors of treatment response to Eustachian Tube Balloon Dilation (ETBD) as measured by changes in Eustachian Tube Dysfunction Questionnaire-7 (ETDQ-7) scores.\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY-  One hundred thirteen patients who underwent ETBD at an institution from 2022 to 2025 completed ETDQ-7 pre- and post-operatively. We conducted multivariable regression analyses with ETDQ-7 normalization (<2.1 post-op), minimum clinically important difference (MCID) (>0.5 pre-op - post-op), and quantitative improvement in ETDQ-7 score as outcome variables. Pre-operative ETDQ-7 score, tympanogram type, chronic otitis media, chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS), inferior turbinate hypertrophy, deviated septum, allergic rhinitis, and rhinorrhea were included as covariates. Models controlled for age, sex, ethnicity, prior ear or sinus surgery, and follow-up duration.\r\n\r\n\r\nRESULT- The mean age was 49 years old. 51% were females, and all patients had pre-operative ETDQ-7 above 2.1. After a mean follow-up period of 13 months, 77% achieved MCID and 37% had normalized. Higher pre-operative ETDQ-7 score was associated with greater ETDQ-7 score improvement (B = 0.60, 95% CI = [0.37, 0.83]) and greater odds of achieving MCID (aOR = 1.65; 95% CI = [1.06, 2.59]). A history of CRS improved chances of achieving MCID (aOR = 4.53; 95% CI = [1.11, 18.55]) and a history of chronic otitis media predicted increased odds of ETDQ-7 normalization (aOR = 2.88; 95% CI = [1.09, 7.58]).\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION- Our findings suggest that ETBD was highly effective among patients with pre-operative ETDQ-7 above 2.1. Furthermore, higher pre-operative ETDQ-7 score, CRS, and chronic otitis media predicted more favorable symptomatic benefit from ETBD. These factors may be important to consider when counseling potential candidates for this procedure.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/2f40ae41c42fdaff4fddb399963cb4e7.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 07:18:04', '2025-11-15 07:18:08'),
(324, 'Dr. Revathi V', 'reva.goku@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000590', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Unmasking the mysteric core of benign shell Rare case of malignancy inside the cyst of upper jaw', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Poster Abstract\r\nTitle \r\nUnmasking the mysteric core of benign shell\r\nRare case of malignancy inside the cyst of upper jaw \r\n\r\nAuthor \r\nDr. Revathi V \r\n\r\nAim:\r\nTo study the presentation of a rare case of  a mystery  within a cystic lesion of the maxilla and to emphasize the need for thorough histopathological assessment of all jaw cysts.\r\n\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\n\r\nA 76-year-old male presented with symptoms of  giddeness 1 month for which MRI brain  taken stating that possibility  of dentigerous cyst , CT PNS  F/s/0  right fungal sinusitis.  Patient was taken up for surgery and complete excision of cyst was done . Post op microscopic and immunohistochemical analysis was done \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n\r\nHistopathology revealed malignancy .The patient underwent complete excision and is on regular follow-up with no evidence of recurrence.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\n\r\nAlthough rare, malignant transformation within dentigerous  cysts should be considered in cases with long-standing, recurrent, or rapidly enlarging lesions. Early diagnosis through meticulous histopathological examination is essential for optimal management and prognosis.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/89a6c7817c96c4c5f5e937e5dca0844b.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 08:37:27', '2025-11-15 08:37:31'),
(325, 'Dr. Ramprasath Athikesavan', 'ramprasath1166@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000604', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Impact of Surgical Intervention on Eustachian Tube and Middle Ear Function in Chronic Rhinosinusitis', NULL, 'A Diagnostic Puzzle: Unraveling the Cause of a Nasal Mass', NULL, NULL, 'Title: Impact of Surgical Intervention on Eustachian Tube and Middle Ear Function in CRS Patients With and Without Nasal Polyps\r\nAuthor: Dr. A. RAMPRASATH, Post Graduate, M.S. ENT \r\nGuide: Dr. SARANYA CHITHRA, Department of ENT, SMMCHRI.\r\nAim: To evaluate middle ear and Eustachian tube functions in CRS patients with and without nasal polyps before and after surgical intervention.\r\nMethods: Two groups of CRS patients, those with nasal polyps (CRSwNP) and those without (CRSsNP) were evaluated for both subjective and objective measures of sinonasal and Eustachian Tube function. The Eustachian Tube Dysfunction Questionnaire (ETDQ-7) and the Sino-Nasal Outcome Test (SNOT-22) were used to assess symptom load. Tympanometry, Eustachian tube function testing, and diagnostic nasal endoscopy with standardized scoring were all part of the objective examination. All assessments were performed preoperatively and repeated postoperatively following functional endoscopic sinus surgery.\r\nResults: SNOT-22 and ETDQ-7 ratings significantly improved after surgery for both the CRSwNP and CRSsNP groups, demonstrating a decrease in sinonasal and ET-related symptoms. Better Tympanometric profiles and lower endoscopic disease scores were objective indicators of improved middle ear condition and ET function following surgery. While both groups benefited from surgical surgery, patients with nasal polyps showed higher preoperative impairment and correspondingly higher postoperative improvements, according to a comparative analysis.\r\nConclusion: Surgical management of CRS leads to significant improvement in both subjective and objective measures of Eustachian tube and middle ear function. CRS patients with nasal polyps show more pronounced impairment preoperatively but also greater functional recovery after surgery. These findings highlight the importance of evaluating ET function in CRS and support the role of sinus surgery in restoring middle ear physiology.', NULL, 'Title: A Diagnostic Puzzle: Unraveling the Cause of a Nasal Mass \r\nAuthor: Dr. A. RAMPRASATH, Post Graduate, M.S. ENT\r\nGuide: Dr. L. ASOKAN, Assistant professor, Department of ENT, SMMCHRI.\r\nAim: To highlight the diagnostic challenges of a rare case of extra nodal Non-Hodgkin’s Lymphoma (NHL) of the nasal cavity with cervical lymphadenopathy.\r\nMethodology: A 48-year-old female presented with swelling on the left side of the   neck for five months, left nasal obstruction with discharge for three months. Clinical examination, USG-guided FNAC, CT-PNS, CECT-NECK and MRI neck, performed. The patient underwent endoscopic excision biopsy of the nasal mass, followed by histopathological and immunohistochemical evaluation. \r\nResults: DNE examination revealed a firm, irregular left nasal mass. CT-PNS shows   large heterogeneously mass lesion 10.2x3.9x4.2cm seen on left nasal cavity and left maxillary sinus. CECT neck – (a)largest node 3.5 x 2.9 cm in left level II, (b)node of 3.4 x 2.1cm seen in left level IX. MRI neck-T2 isointense/T1 hypointense restricted diffusion in left nasal cavity with erosion in left lateral wall of nose. T2 isointense/T1 hypointense lesion of 2.9x2.8x4.0cm in left level I B to level II, similar lesion of 2.7x2.6x3.7cm in level IX region. FNAC suggested malignancy. Histopathology revealed poorly differentiated carcinoma, immunohistochemistry suggestive of high-grade B-cell Non-Hodgkin’s Lymphoma. PET-CT showed disease involvement of the nasal cavity and cervical nodes. The patient was started on R-CHOP chemotherapy. \r\nConclusions: Sinonasal lymphomas are uncommon and often mimic epithelial malignancies.', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/eeadb32dc9991a2a60fd9d08b39631eb.doc', '', '/public/upload/abstract/1553528edf23e64ff91b776149ea8250.doc', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 14:34:40', '2025-11-15 14:34:44'),
(326, 'DR. V . AANANDHA PADMANATHAN', 'motog2doc@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000566', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Prospective Clinicopathological Evaluation of Neutrophilic and Eosinophilic Inflammatory Endotypes i', NULL, 'RULES ARE EXCEPTIONAL', NULL, NULL, '“Prospective Clinicopathological Evaluation of Neutrophilic and Eosinophilic Inflammatory Endotypes in Chronic Rhinosinusitis ”\r\n\r\nPresentor :- Dr. Aanandha Padmanathan V  (Post Graduate)\r\nGuide       :- Dr. Saranya Chitra Cheruvu (Assoc Prof) Department of ENT,  \r\nDr. Lionel Rohit Mathew(Assoc Prof) Dept of Pathology.\r\n                      Sri Muthukumaran Medical College and Research Institute\r\n\r\nAbstract :\r\nBackground: \r\nChronic rhinosinusitis  is a multifactorial inflammatory disease of the paranasal sinuses involving the sinonasal mucosa characterized by persistent symptoms lasting 12 weeks or longer and confirmed by diagnostic nasal endoscopy and computed tomography. \r\nAim : \r\nThis study aimed to evaluate the predominance of neutrophilic or eosinophilic inflammation in patients with Chronic rhinosinusitis through histopathological assessment, and to explore the association between Chronic rhinosinusitis endotypes and relevant hematological parameters.\r\nMethodology: \r\nA prospective cohort study was conducted over one year duration at Sri Muthukumaran medical college and research institute, a tertiary care center among Fifty four patients diagnosed with Chronic rhinosinusitis. All patients underwent diagnostic nasal endoscopy, CT of the paranasal sinuses, complete blood count, absolute eosinophil count , erythrocyte sedimentation rate, and serum immunoglobulin E  estimation. Patients underwent functional endoscopic sinus surgery and biopsy sent for histopathological examination.\r\nResults: \r\nOverall, higher eosinophilic predominance was observed in most of the cases. A statistically significant correlation was observed between findings on diagnostic nasal endoscopy and absolute eosinophil count.\r\nConclusion: \r\nThe present study confirms that chronic rhinosinusitis is predominantly eosinophilic, although a considerable number exhibited mixed or neutrophilic inflammation. Staph. aureus biofilm and superantigen property has burdened treatment protocols for chronic rhinosinusitis worldwide. Endotypes of chronic rhinosinusitis and recalcitrant or recurrent chronic rhinosinusitis are emerging hence we recommend more studies to look into the endotypes of chronic rhinosinusitis before initiating the treatment protocols', NULL, '“ RULES ARE EXCEPTIONAL ”\r\n\r\nPresentor :- Dr. Aanandha Padmanathan V  (Post Graduate)\r\nGuide - Dr. Saranya(Assoc Prof),  Dr. Haribalan(Asst Prof) ,Department of ENT\r\nSri Muthukumaran Medical College and Research Institute\r\nAim : \r\nTo present the rarity of bilateral Inverted papilloma of paranasal sinuses.\r\nMethodology : \r\n	\r\n	A 36-year-old male presenting with bilateral nasal obstruction and rhinorrhea for the last two years. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy demonstrated a deviated nasal septum and multiple pale greyish, glistening masses in both the nasal cavity beyond the middle turbinate, with mucoid discharge. CT scan of  Para-nasal Sinus showed polypoidal mucosal thickening involving bilateral maxillary, ethmoidal, sphenoid, and frontal sinuses, with blockage of the osteomeatal and recess complexes.\r\nBased on the clinical and radiological findings the patient was diagnosed as bilateral sinonasal polyposis and underwent functional endoscopic sinus surgery. Biopsy was suggestive of inverted papilloma. Since the side of pathology was not indicated while sending the biopsy during subsequent followup after 1 week , biospy from polypoidal tissues from both middle meatus was sent for HPE as separate samples which revealed Inverted Papilloma on both sides. Hence patient was subjected to Bilateral Endoscopic Medial Maxillectomy. Histopathological examination confirmed  as Inverted papilloma without dysplasia or malignancy. \r\nThis patient is under followup for last 6 months without signs of recurrence.\r\nConclusion :\r\nWe would like to emphasis the importance of follow up and histopathology while treating any sino-nasal mass, since we initially came to a diagnosis as sinonasal polyposis which later turned out to be bilateral inverted papilloma. Though inverted papilloma presents as an unilateral polypoidal mass with an incidence of less than 4% of all the nasal tumours, literature reports bilateral inverted papilloma with an incidence of less than 5% among all inverted papilloma cases.', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/8eb21e7a5d1f3e2e668aadd038699554.docx', '', '/public/upload/abstract/84bd0091ee8a7784c73e4c8a96dabc54.docx', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 14:45:02', '2025-11-15 14:45:06'),
(327, 'k.vivekraajan', 'drvivekraajanent@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000618', '[\"Mrs.Neena Saharia Award presentation for Junior Consultant\"]', NULL, 'Refining the Management of Allergic Rhinitis: Clinical Insights into the Role of Selective Posterior', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo review contemporary advancements in the management of allergic rhinitis (AR) and to evaluate the clinical utility of selective posterior nasal neurectomy (PNN) in patients with refractory symptoms.\r\n\r\nMethodology:\r\nA narrative review was conducted, synthesizing recent evidence from clinical studies, anatomical investigations, and surgical outcome research related to AR and selective PNN. Particular focus was placed on anatomical variations of the posterior nasal nerve, refinements in selective neurectomy techniques, postoperative symptom improvement, and complication profiles.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\nSelective PNN demonstrates consistent and significant improvement in key AR symptoms, including nasal obstruction, rhinorrhea, and sneezing in patients unresponsive to maximal medical therapy. Advances in endoscopic visualization and improved understanding of variable nerve branching patterns have enhanced surgical accuracy. Preservation of sensory branches during selective neurectomy appears to maintain mucosal function and reduces postoperative dryness and crusting. Overall, the procedure shows a favourable safety and efficacy profile, with low complication rates when anatomical variations are carefully accounted for.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nSelective PNN is an effective and valuable adjunct in the treatment of refractory allergic rhinitis. Ongoing refinement in anatomical knowledge and surgical technique continues to enhance outcomes. Further multicentre studies and long-term follow-up are needed to standardize surgical protocols and support broader global integration of this technique.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '/public/upload/abstract/3cace966e815ae0505b3abf0607e440e.docx', '', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 16:54:55', '2025-11-15 16:54:59'),
(328, 'Dr. Mikun M', 'mikun99@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000581', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Early Orbital Intervention in Preventing Vision Loss in Rhino-Orbital Mucormycosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Aim:\r\nTo evaluate the role of early surgery in preventing vision loss  in patients with rhino-orbital -mucormycosis \r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nRhino-orbital mucormycosis (ROM) is a rapidly progressive angio-invasive fungal infection, most commonly caused by Rhizopus species.It frequently affects immunocompromised individuals and  rapidly extend from the nasal cavity  and sinuses to the orbit,  causing orbital symptoms and cranial neuropathies, vision loss, cavernous sinus thrombosis. Surgical interventions form the cornerstone of management alongside systemic antifungal therapy.\r\n\r\nMaterials and Methods\r\nA prospective observational study was conducted on 18 patients in our institute from 2023-2025 who were diagnosed with ROM, Orbital involvement was staged radiologically as Early-stage & Advanced disease.All patients received systemic liposomal amphotericin-B as first-line therapy.Early-stage patients underwent timely surgeries like endoscopic debridement and  orbital decompression through medial and inferior orbitotomy ,retrobulbar amphotericin-B injections (where indicated).Advanced-stage patients underwent wider debridement procedures. Outcomes assessed included progression of orbital disease, preservation of vision.\r\n\r\nResults:\r\n Patients underwent early orbital surgery and targeted local therapy:\r\n17 patients–85% showedi mprovement in vision on follow up.\r\nOnly 3 -15% progressed to permanent vision loss due late presentation and aggressive disease\r\nPrompt and effective decompression and disease control, significantly reducing the risk of blindness. Early multidisciplinary intervention remains crucial for preserving vision and minimizing morbidity.', NULL, NULL, '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/00c0578895f9276cae685ffb7618e932.docx', '', '', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 17:58:02', '2025-11-15 17:58:06'),
(329, 'DR HANISH S', 'hanishsk7501@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000636', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Revision Adult Choanal Atresia: Coblation and Mitomycin-C in Preventing Restenosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Introduction \r\nAdult choanal atresia is rare, and postoperative restenosis or secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis poses significant management challenges. Residual adenoidal hypertrophy and progressive scarring can contribute to delayed obstruction. Coblation-assisted scar release with adjuvant Mitomycin-C is a useful strategy to reduce fibrosis during revision surgery.\r\n\r\nCase: \r\nA 41-year-old female with right-sided unilateral choanal atresia and grade 3 adenoids underwent primary endoscopic repair. Initial recovery was satisfactory, and she remained asymptomatic. After one year, she presented with gradually progressive bilateral nasal obstruction. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy and imaging demonstrated nasopharyngeal stenosis with recurrent narrowing at the right choana, suggestive of postoperative scar formation.\r\n\r\nIntervention\r\nRevision endoscopic surgery was planned. The procedure included Coblation-assisted scar tissue release, revision choanal atresia repair, bilateral functional endoscopic sinus surgery, and nasopharyngeal stenosis release. Mitomycin-C (0.4 mg/mL) was applied over raw areas for three minutes to inhibit fibroblast proliferation. Nasal packing was retained for 48 hours and removed without complications. The patient demonstrated improved airway patency during follow-up.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted revision surgery combined with Mitomycin-C application is effective in managing adult choanal atresia restenosis with secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis, offering improved long-term airway outcomes.', '', '', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/fa483c0ee8acc200b17418a8554453b9.doc', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 21:40:00', '2025-11-15 21:40:04'),
(330, 'DR HANISH S', 'hanishsk7501@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000636', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\",\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Mitomycin-C-Augmented Revision Repair in Adult Unilateral Choanal Atresia: A case report', NULL, 'Revision Adult Choanal Atresia: Coblation and Mitomycin-C in Preventing Restenosis', NULL, NULL, 'Introduction \r\nAdult choanal atresia is rare, and postoperative restenosis or secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis poses significant management challenges. Residual adenoidal hypertrophy and progressive scarring can contribute to delayed obstruction. Coblation-assisted scar release with adjuvant Mitomycin-C is a useful strategy to reduce fibrosis during revision surgery.\r\n\r\nCase: \r\nA 41-year-old female with right-sided unilateral choanal atresia and grade 3 adenoids underwent primary endoscopic repair. Initial recovery was satisfactory, and she remained asymptomatic. After one year, she presented with gradually progressive bilateral nasal obstruction. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy and imaging demonstrated nasopharyngeal stenosis with recurrent narrowing at the right choana, suggestive of postoperative scar formation.\r\n\r\nIntervention\r\nRevision endoscopic surgery was planned. The procedure included Coblation-assisted scar tissue release, revision choanal atresia repair, bilateral functional endoscopic sinus surgery, and nasopharyngeal stenosis release. Mitomycin-C (0.4 mg/mL) was applied over raw areas for three minutes to inhibit fibroblast proliferation. Nasal packing was retained for 48 hours and removed without complications. The patient demonstrated improved airway patency during follow-up.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted revision surgery combined with Mitomycin-C application is effective in managing adult choanal atresia restenosis with secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis, offering improved long-term airway outcomes.', NULL, 'Introduction \r\nAdult choanal atresia is rare, and postoperative restenosis or secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis poses significant management challenges. Residual adenoidal hypertrophy and progressive scarring can contribute to delayed obstruction. Coblation-assisted scar release with adjuvant Mitomycin-C is a useful strategy to reduce fibrosis during revision surgery.\r\n\r\nCase: \r\nA 41-year-old female with right-sided unilateral choanal atresia and grade 3 adenoids underwent primary endoscopic repair. Initial recovery was satisfactory, and she remained asymptomatic. After one year, she presented with gradually progressive bilateral nasal obstruction. Diagnostic nasal endoscopy and imaging demonstrated nasopharyngeal stenosis with recurrent narrowing at the right choana, suggestive of postoperative scar formation.\r\n\r\nIntervention\r\nRevision endoscopic surgery was planned. The procedure included Coblation-assisted scar tissue release, revision choanal atresia repair, bilateral functional endoscopic sinus surgery, and nasopharyngeal stenosis release. Mitomycin-C (0.4 mg/mL) was applied over raw areas for three minutes to inhibit fibroblast proliferation. Nasal packing was retained for 48 hours and removed without complications. The patient demonstrated improved airway patency during follow-up.\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nCoblation-assisted revision surgery combined with Mitomycin-C application is effective in managing adult choanal atresia restenosis with secondary nasopharyngeal stenosis, offering improved long-term airway outcomes.', '', '', '/public/upload/abstract/b548233257a56c2f8ecd556fb391fdf9.doc', '', '/public/upload/abstract/70a330416a4038cbc222c240157cbbc1.doc', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 21:49:15', '2025-11-15 21:49:19'),
(331, 'Sunishtha Attri', 'sunishtha98@gmail.com', 'sunishtha98@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, NULL, 'Multidisciplinary Management of Advanced Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: our institutional exp', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Multidisciplinary Management of Advanced Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: our institutional experience \r\nPresenting authors: Dr Sunishtha  INSERT INTO `rh_additional_package` (`id`, `member_id`, `order_id`, `payment_id`, `payment_message`, `payment_status`, `gala_dinner`, `gala_dinner_price`, `gala_dinner_tax`, `room_tarrif_id`, `room_tarrif`, `room_tarrif_price`, `room_tarrif_tax`, `no_of_days`, `room_dates`, `person`, `training`, `total`, `mail_send`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
