\r\nAIM:  To highlight the evolving roles, coordination strategies, and clinical impact of a multidisciplinary approach in optimizing outcomes for patients with advanced JNA.\r\nMethods: A comprehensive review of current clinical practices was conducted, focusing on key components of multidisciplinary care: advanced imaging, endovascular embolization, endoscopic and combined surgical approaches, intraoperative navigation, blood-loss reduction strategies, and the selective use of adjuvant radiotherapy. Case examples from our  institutional experience are used to illustrate decision-making processes.\r\nResults: Multidisciplinary planning enhances preoperative characterization of tumor extent, enabling tailored surgical corridors and reducing intraoperative risk. Preoperative embolization performed 24–48 hours before surgery consistently reduces intraoperative blood loss and operative time. Collaborative endoscopic–open hybrid approaches permit safer access to tumors with intracranial or infratemporal fossa involvement. Radiation therapy is effective as an adjunct for unresectable residual disease or recurrence, particularly near critical neurovascular structures. Overall, multidisciplinary management is associated with improved tumor control, reduced complications, shorter hospital stays, and better functional outcomes.\r\nConclusion: A multidisciplinary strategy is essential in the management of advanced JNA, facilitating precise diagnosis, safer resection, and personalized adjuvant therapy. This collaborative approach not only improves oncologic control but also minimizes morbidity in this young patient population. Continued integration of advanced imaging, endovascular techniques, and minimally invasive skull‐base surgery will further refine outcomes for complex JNA cases.', '/public/upload/abstract/77d9a7d24f4ee6d11ba6cf6c13d8f5b2.docx', 'Multidisciplinary Management of Advanced Juvenile Nasopharyngeal Angiofibroma: our institutional exp', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 0, '2025-11-15 21:56:14', '2025-11-22 10:08:37'),
(332, 'Dr Nitika Gupta', 'nitikagupta5949@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000630', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', 'Modified Denkers', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 22:08:55', '2025-11-15 22:08:59'),
(333, 'HARI VALLIAPPAN A', 'harivalliappan17@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000576', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TITLE: INVERTED PAPILLOMA – OUR EXPERIENCE\r\n\r\nPRESENTING AUTHOR: Dr. Hari Valliappan.A\r\n\r\nAIM:\r\nTo evaluate the clinical presentation, diagnostic challenges, and treatment outcomes of patients with nasal inverted papilloma, with emphasis on recurrence rates and the effectiveness of endoscopic surgical management.\r\n\r\nMETHODOLOGY:\r\nIt is a case series on patients diagnosed with inverted papilloma of the nose at our institution over a defined study period. Clinical symptoms, radiological findings, endoscopic evaluations, and histopathological reports were reviewed. All patients underwent endoscopic surgical excision, and postoperative outcomes—including recurrence and complications—were assessed during follow-up visits.\r\n\r\nRESULTS:\r\nMost patients presented with unilateral nasal obstruction, nasal mass, and epistaxis. CT and MRI proved essential in identifying tumor extent . Endoscopic excision allowed complete removal with good visualization and minimal morbidity. The recurrence rate was low, No major intraoperative or postoperative complications were noted.\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nNasal inverted papilloma remains a benign but locally aggressive tumor with significant potential for recurrence. Early diagnosis supported by high-quality imaging and meticulous endoscopic surgical excision yields excellent outcomes. Long-term follow-up is crucial to detect late recurrences and ensure optimal patient prognosis', '/public/upload/abstract/38ae370fe8531a124993e99faad55aef.docx', 'INVERTED PAPILLOMA OUR EXPERIENCE', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 22:28:44', '2025-11-15 22:28:47'),
(334, 'Dr Nitika Gupta', 'nitikagupta5949@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000630', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'A 44-year-old male presented with a history of unilateral left-sided nasal blockage persisting for the past two years. Clinical evaluation was carried out, and contrast-enhanced CT (CECT) of the nose and paranasal sinuses (PNS) revealed focal hyperostosis. A biopsy was taken, and histopathology was consistent with inverted papilloma.\r\n\r\nAn endoscopic modified Denker\'s procedure was performed. The nasal part of the tumor was excised using a microdebrider, with representative tissue sent for histopathological examination. Utilizing a coblator, an incision was made at the pyriform aperture while preserving the alar cartilages. Dissection was performed to elevate the tissue from the anterolateral wall of the maxilla up to the infraorbital nerve.\r\n\r\nSuperior and inferior incisions in the maxillary wall were made using a drill, and the LUCS forceps was employed to remove the maxillary wall, thereby gaining access to the maxillary sinus. All diseased tissue was meticulously debrided, and the area of the tumor attachment was drilled for complete removal.\r\n\r\nThe nasolacrimal duct was transected flush to the level of the lacrimal sac, minimizing the risk of future fibrosis and epiphora. Upon completion of the procedure, the surgical cavity was packed with medicated packs.', '/public/upload/abstract/a895d73fcf07d3e81830971164aefe2e.docx', 'Modified Denkers Inverted Papilloma', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 22:40:01', '2025-11-15 22:40:05'),
(335, 'Dr Nitika Gupta', 'nitikagupta5949@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000630', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', 'Multilayer endoscopic CSF leak repair', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 23:13:44', '2025-11-15 23:13:48'),
(336, 'Dr Nitika Gupta', 'nitikagupta5949@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000630', '[\"Dr. Arvind Soni Award - Video Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, '62 years old female presented with unilateral watery nasal discharge, Preoperative Preparation\r\n- High-resolution CT abnd CT cisternography confirmed diagnosis of CSF rhinorrhoea and site of leak was lateral lamella of cribriform plate.\r\n\r\nPatient was taken up for repair and following steps were taken for repair.\r\n-1.Patient is positioned supine with the head elevated (reverse Trendelenburg) to decrease venous return; general anesthesia is administered.\r\n\r\n2. Nasal Cavity Preparation and Exposure\r\n- Achieve decongestion of the nasal cavity using topical vasoconstrictors.\r\n- Gently lateralize the middle turbinate to expose the cribriform plate and defect site; superior turbinate may be lateralized if needed.\r\n- Use a 0-degree, 4mm rigid endoscope and high-definition camera for visualization.\r\n\r\n3. Defect Identification and Preparation\r\n- Carefully identify the leak site endoscopically.\r\n- Circumferentially cauterize and denude the mucosa around the defect using bipolar cautery to create a raw bed and promote graft adherence.\r\n\r\n4. Multi-Layer Repair\r\n- High flow leak flow was there hence packing with autologous fat harvested from the thigh or abdomen.\r\n\r\nFascia Lata placed over this layer of fat plug, ensuring full coverage.\r\nMini hadad flap placed over this layer of the grafts and further packing was done with a hemostatic agent, such as Surgicel; fibrin glue and nasal packing was done\r\n6. Final Stabilization\r\n- Medialization of the middle turbinate done and sutured with 3-0 Vicryl to the nasal septum to support the graft and maintain scaffold stability (quilting stitch).\r\n- No fibrin glue is used in the standard approach.\r\n\r\nPostoperative Care\r\n- Patients are discharged by the 2nd or 3rd day postoperatively.\r\n- Advise avoidance of actions that increase intracranial pressure (nose blowing, heavy lifting) for at least two weeks for optimal healing.', '/public/upload/abstract/757ad7a490bac8f210281c718968035d.docx', 'Multilayer endoscopic CSF repair', NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 23:15:54', '2025-11-15 23:15:57'),
(337, 'RASIKAPRIYA K', 'gkrasikapriya@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000473', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title: Sniffles on Duty: Allergic Rhinitis Among Healthcare Workers\r\nPresenting Author\r\nK. Rasikapriya\r\nAim\r\nTo assess the prevalence of allergic rhinitis among healthcare workers (HCWs) in a tertiary care centre in Tamil Nadu and evaluate its impact on work performance.\r\nMethodology\r\nA cross-sectional study was conducted among doctors, nurses, technicians, and support staff using a validated ARIA-based questionnaire. Information on symptom frequency, severity, triggers, ocular involvement, medication use, absenteeism, and perceived work impairment was collected. Descriptive statistics were used to determine prevalence, and the relationship between symptom severity and work impact was analysed.\r\nResults\r\nA high prevalence of allergic rhinitis was observed among HCWs. Common symptoms included sneezing, rhinorrhea, nasal obstruction, and itching. Frequently reported workplace triggers were chemical disinfectants, dust exposure, and temperature variations. AR affected work efficiency by reducing concentration and productivity, with occasional absenteeism noted. Participants with moderate-to-severe AR reported greater work impairment and required more frequent medication. Many HCWs had not sought medical evaluation, indicating under-recognition of the condition.\r\nConclusions\r\nAllergic rhinitis is common among healthcare workers and significantly impacts workplace performance. Improved recognition, appropriate treatment, and measures to reduce occupational triggers are essential to enhance HCW well-being and productivity.', '/public/upload/abstract/ae76a1dd6300dde6448e5786d02b9b50.docx', 'Sniffles on Duty: Allergic Rhinitis Among Healthcare workers\"', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 23:22:18', '2025-11-15 23:22:22'),
(338, 'RASIKAPRIYA K', 'gkrasikapriya@gmail.com', 'RHIN0000473', '[\"Dr. Anoop Raj Award - Poster Session\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Title\r\nWhen the Nose Speaks, the Lungs Listen: Understanding the AR–Asthma Link\r\nPresenting Author\r\nK. Rasikapriya\r\nAim\r\nTo describe the relationship between allergic rhinitis (AR) and asthma based on the unified airway concept and to summarize the epidemiological, pathophysiological, and clinical connections as outlined in standard otolaryngology references including Scott-Brown.\r\nMethodology\r\nA narrative review approach was used, compiling evidence from Scott-Brown’s Otorhinolaryngology and ARIA guidelines. Key concepts regarding shared airway anatomy, immunological mechanisms, epidemiology, and treatment implications were synthesized. Emphasis was placed on mechanisms linking AR with asthma, including systemic inflammation, neural reflex pathways, nasal obstruction, and postnasal drip.\r\nResults\r\nAllergic rhinitis and asthma share common inflammatory pathways and represent manifestations of a single airway disease. Epidemiologically, 20–40% of patients with AR have asthma, and up to 80% of asthmatics exhibit nasal symptoms. Nasal allergen exposure can trigger lower airway inflammation, bronchoconstriction via nasobronchial reflexes, and increased bronchial hyperresponsiveness due to mouth breathing. Uncontrolled rhinitis correlates with poorer asthma control and more frequent exacerbations. Treatment of AR—particularly with intranasal corticosteroids, antihistamines, and leukotriene receptor antagonists—has been shown to improve asthma outcomes.\r\nConclusions\r\nAllergic rhinitis significantly influences asthma through shared airway physiology and inflammatory mechanisms. Integrated assessment and treatment following ARIA recommendations are essential to achieve optimal control of both conditions.', '/public/upload/abstract/f0757a0f7f459c95bb5323996aef5f13.docx', 'When the Nose Speaks, the Lungs Listen: Understanding the Allergic Rhinitis–Asthma Link', 2, 1, '2025-11-15 23:30:57', '2025-11-15 23:31:01'),
(339, 'Dr Kartik kumar', 'kartiksharma2770@yahoo.in', '1484', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'Presenting Author: Dr Kartik kumar\r\nAim:\r\nTo describe the clinical presentation, diagnostic evaluation, and successful endovascular management of a post-traumatic cavernous internal carotid artery (ICA) pseudoaneurysm presenting with massive epistaxis.\r\nMethodology:\r\nA single-patient case report was compiled from clinical records, imaging findings and interventional radiology documentation. The patient’s presentation, investigative pathway including NCCT and CT angiography, and therapeutic intervention using digital subtraction angiography (DSA) with coil embolization were analyzed in detail.\r\nResults:\r\nA 42-year-old man presented with sudden massive epistaxis following remote head trauma. NCCT revealed sphenoid sinus roof erosion with soft-tissue protrusion. CT angiography demonstrated a right cavernous ICA pseudoaneurysm projecting into the sphenoid sinus through a traumatic bony defect. DSA confirmed the lesion. Endovascular detachable coil embolization was performed with preservation of carotid flow, achieving immediate hemorrhage control. The patient recovered without neurological complications and remained asymptomatic at one-year follow-up.\r\nConclusions:\r\nPost-traumatic cavernous ICA pseudoaneurysm is rare but potentially fatal, often presenting with delayed massive epistaxis. High suspicion in post-trauma patients, rapid imaging with CT angiography, and early endovascular intervention are crucial to prevent mortality. The case underscores the importance of multidisciplinary coordination in achieving successful outcomes.', '/public/upload/abstract/a7d3a3f5ce156509f5bea421ddc01993.docx', 'Acute Onset of Massive Epistaxis Due to Post-Traumatic Cavernous Internal Carotid Artery Pseudoaneur', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-15 23:39:45', '2025-11-15 23:39:48'),
(340, 'Dr.Ooviya .V', 'ooviyaveeramani606@gmail.com', 'ooviyaveeramani606@gmail.com', '[\"Dr. Adesh Saxena and Dr.Mita Saxena Award presentation for Post Graduate\"]', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 'TOPIC : \r\n\"ANALYSIS ON VARIOUS APPROACHES OF SPHENOID SINUS SURGERY \"\r\n\r\nAUTHOR: \r\n DR . OOVIYA.V\r\n\r\nAIM:\r\nTo analyze the different surgical approaches to the sphenoid sinus with respect to their anatomical basis, indications, advantages, limitations, and potential complications.\r\n\r\nMETHODS:\r\nA comprehensive study  to evaluate the transnasal, transethmoidal, transseptal, transoral, and external (transantral and transcranial) approaches. Comparative analysis was based on accessibility, exposure, operative safety, and postoperative morbidity.\r\n\r\nRESULTS:\r\nThe endoscopic transnasal approach emerged as the most commonly preferred method owing to its minimally invasive nature, direct access, and improved visualization. Transethmoidal and transseptal approaches offer alternative routes depending on anatomical variations or concurrent pathology. External approaches are reserved for extensive lesions with lateral or superior extension not reachable endoscopically. Advances in image-guided navigation have further enhanced the precision and safety of endoscopic techniques.\r\n\r\nCONCLUSION:\r\nAn in-depth understanding of sphenoid sinus anatomy and careful selection of the surgical approach are key determinants of successful outcomes. The endoscopic transnasal route remains the gold standard for most pathologies, while other approaches retain significance in selected complex or recurrent cases.', '/public/upload/abstract/697fc6e6ae03951e17c19330d7686d1a.docx', '\"ANALYSIS ON VARIOUS APPROACHES OF SPHENOID SINUS SURGERY \"', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, 2, 1, '2025-11-16 15:16:35', '2025-11-16 15:16:38');

